<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAVE A KOBE _ AND A SMILE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif _ It's not his scar-less, tireless, tightly
coiled legs that will make Kobe Bryant the go-to shooter if the Los
Angeles Lakers' first must-win game of 1999 is close in the final
minute today.
</P>
<P>
   It's not his clear, sharp eyes. It's not his long fingers. It's
not his feet, though they're quick as a shell game.
</P>
<P>
   It's definitely not the shoes.
</P>
<P>
   It's his teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Did you see them, displayed in an oddly timed smile, as Bryant
walked to the Lakers' bench in San Antonio on Wednesday night after
he missed two free throws that could have clinched a game the Spurs
went on to win?
</P>
<P>
   A smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know exactly what he was saying,'' Spurs reserve guard Steve
Kerr said Friday. ``He was saying, `I don't believe I missed those
free throws.' You have to laugh it off _ and he did.''
</P>
<P>
   A smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It says, `(That's) life ... I know I'm going to get another
opportunity,''' Lakers guard Derek Fisher said. ```Probably in this
game.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant didn't get another opportunity in that game. After Tim
Duncan gave the Spurs a one-point lead with a jump hook, Bryant's
in-bounds pass to Fisher was stolen with six seconds left, and free
throws gave San Antonio a 79-76 victory and a 2-0 lead in the
best-of-seven playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   Now Bryant wants another chance this afternoon. He doesn't think
he'll miss again.
</P>
<P>
   And if he gets it, bet on smiles all over the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   With Shaquille O'Neal bottled up by San Antonio's three-headed
defensive monster and his own predictability, and with Glen Rice
still waiting for a screen or two or three, the Lakers might have
to rely again on Kobe to create points out of thin air.
</P>
<P>
   Fine with him.
</P>
<P>
   Undaunted, the 20-year-old charges into the most dangerous
moment of the season today, leading again with his incisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fearless? That's probably an understatement,'' Fisher said,
adding with a needless-to-say expression, ``We aren't overly
concerned about his confidence being shaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe's accepted that type of responsibility since he's been in
the league. I really can't think of a time where he didn't want to
be in a pressure situation, want to have the ball in his hands with
a game on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Lakers possessions before the missed free throws, Bryant
sank the 3-pointer that gave them their last lead with :46 on the
clock.
</P>
<P>
   The shot from deep in the right corner also gave Bryant his
playoff career-high 28th point of the night. All of his averages in
the playoffs this year (20.3 points, 7.2 rebounds, 5.5 assists, 1.8
steals, 1.5 blocks) are up from the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   If Kobe came to the NBA with an all-style-no-substance rap and
provided skeptics were early confirmation with his airballs in the
dying seconds of the '96 playoff series against the Utah Jazz, he
is acquitting himself this month, win or lose.
</P>
<P>
   He stole the ball from Scottie Pippen and made the deciding free
throws in Game 1 of the opening series against the Houston Rockets.
He dominated Pippen in Game 2. He scored 13 straight Lakers points
in the first half of Game 4 when Rice was injured and out. He's the
leading Lakers scorer in the two games against the Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Start worrying now? Why?
</P>
<P>
   Because they're down 0-2? ``This is small potatoes,'' Bryant
said _ smiling _ ``compared to what we were going through during
the regular season.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the sloppy Lakers play at the start of Game 2? ``It's
good to get it out of your system,'' Bryant said _ smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Because of those lost free throws at the end of Game 2? ``I
slept well, actually,'' Bryant said _ smiling.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers veterans, impatient for a championship, might prefer to
see a little more anguish on his face, instead of that
live-and-learn grin.
</P>
<P>
   But who'd want to take away that youthful bravado?
</P>
<P>
   Would any Laker trade places with Sean Elliott, the Spur
assigned to guard Bryant?
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants (the ball). You have to admire that,'' said Elliott,
who's 10 years his senior. ``A lot of guys in this league will run
from the ball at the end of the game. He's one of the rare guys who
run to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``(He'll) take responsibility for being the hero or the goat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's impressive,'' Kerr said. ``For anybody, let alone a
20-year-old.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody asked Bryant Friday how much he would have bet he'd
sink those free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have lost the house,'' he said. ``It was ... strange.
I didn't expect to miss.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``I would love to be in the same position (today).''
</P>
<P>
   Lucky for the Lakers if he is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
