<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ORIOLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPUTED THIRD-STRIKE CALL SINKS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Oriole Park at Camden Yards' most-productive hitter
would be the best card the Rangers could play.
</P>
<P>
   Baltimore's Charles Johnson and Sidney Ponson trumped it, and
so, too, did plate umpire Dale Scott, according to Rangers
designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro, the productive hitter in
question.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's three-run, seventh-inning home run and Ponson's
120-pitch complete game _ one that included a controversial called
third strike during Palmeiro's ninth-inning at-bat _ propelled the
Orioles to a 3-2 victory last night.
</P>
<P>
   That ruined what appeared would be Palmeiro's triumphant return
to Baltimore's Inner Harbor, which witnessed his exploits with the
bat while playing for the Orioles the previous five seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro greeted the Orioles with memories from that past with
his second-inning solo home run on a first-pitch, 95-mph fastball
from Ponson. Camden Yards' 25-foot high scoreboard in right field
could not stop it.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson and Ponson, though, prevented it from becoming
memorable.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro, who received a mixed reaction from the 45,867 fans
upon being introduced before his second-inning at-bat, received a
standing ovation from some of the fans soon after rounding third
base.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-throwing Ponson drew the louder ovation with his
ninth-inning strikeout of Palmeiro with a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was that far outside,'' said Palmeiro, who claimed the
pitch was at least a foot off the plate. ``\RThe umpire\S saw it as
a strike, period. He called a strike, and I just walked away. If
\RPonson\S throws it over the plate, I hit it. I was geared for his
fastball, but it was out of my reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponson, who surrendered only six hits, to emerge victorious in
his duel with Rangers right-hander Rick Helling, threw Palmeiro six
consecutive sliders before unleashing a 99-mph fastball on his
117th pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the second inning, I made a bad pitch, and Palmeiro hit it
out,'' Ponson said. ``I have confidence in myself, though, and I
said to myself, `If he's going to beat me, he's going to beat me
with my best stuff.' So, I threw him a 3-2 fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers entered the ninth trailing, 3-1, before Mark
McLemore drew a leadoff walk and advanced to third on a double by
Rusty Greer.
</P>
<P>
   McLemore scored on a run-scoring ground ball from Juan Gonzalez,
but Ponson retired Palmeiro and induced a game-ending flyball from
catcher Ivan Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Helling (4-5), emerged as the evening's hard-luck case by being
saddled with a loss, despite delivering the Rangers' first complete
game since Sept. 7. Helling also pitched that game, and the
Rangers' complete game before that. This, though, would be the
Rangers' first defeat in 10 games this season when receiving a
quality start from their rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a game I didn't deserve to lose, but he didn't deserve
to lose, either,'' Helling said of Ponson (4-3). ``Somebody's got
to lose, and I came up on the short end.''
</P>
<P>
   Helling entered the seventh inning with a four-hit shutout, but
the Orioles' Cal Ripken led off with a single and advanced to
second on a single by Delino DeShields.
</P>
<P>
   Helling threw the first two pitches for strikes and then
followed the Rangers' scouting report on DeShields by throwing
three consecutive curveballs out of the strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw him three breaking balls in the dirt, and he didn't
swing any of them,'' Helling said. ``I made a good pitch on that
3-2 fastball, and he hit a 47-hopper through the hole'' and into
right field.
</P>
<P>
   Orioles shortstop Mike Bordick advanced the runners with a
sacrifice bunt before Johnson belted an 0-1 belt-high curveball
into the left-field seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I overthrew it, and it spun out of my hand and stayed up,''
Helling said. ``I made one bad mistake to CJ, and it cost me the
game.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
