<HEADLINE>
10 ARRESTED IN PHOENIX-BASED IMMIGRANT SMUGGLING RING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal authorities on Friday claimed a major victory in the
battle against illegal immigration with the dismantling of a
Phoenix-based ring that smuggled immigrants into Arizona then sent
them on to destinations across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The officials also announced indictments against 17 people, 10
of whom have already been arrested.
</P>
<P>
   According to an official of the Immigration and Naturalization
Service, undercover investi gators infiltrated the ring's
operations in Honduras, Guatemala and and El Salvador, where local
brokers recruited a steady flow of illegals.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of the trip ranged from $5,000 to $9,000 per person,
officials said. Half of the cost was normally paid in advance,
while the remainder was due once the illegals reached Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investigation provided us insight into the detailed
mechanics of the smuggling trade, which will be invaluable to us in
the future,'' said Johnny Williams, western regional director for
the INS.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Fickett, deputy director of the INS Phoenix office that
conducted the investigation, said its techniques would be taught to
investigators across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have learned that by following the movement of money, you
can get at the corporate structure of these operations and do an
awful lot of damage to them,'' Fickett said.
</P>
<P>
   The smuggling ring took in enormous sums of money, officials
said. They said the it often moved 200 Central Americans per week.
</P>
<P>
   The route typically took them by bus across Mexico to the U.S.
border at Douglas, then by vans to Phoenix. Many of the illegals
were driven to Los Angeles and then flown to their final
destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing at a news conference with Williams, U.S. Attorney Jose
de Jesus Rivera said seven of the 10 people arrested so far were
part of the ring's operations in Phoenix. One of those arrested in
Phoenix, Ymer Adid Aguilar-Yoc, was identified by officials as a
leader.
</P>
<P>
   Others were arrested in Los Angeles and Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   Once the illegals had reached Phoenix, they were locked in
``safe houses'' until the smuggling fees were paid in full.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment charges the alleged ring members not only with
smuggling illegal immigrants, but also with holding them hostage
and laundering the proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the illegals were typically held in the safe
houses until relatives wired the final payment to the ring through
a Western Union office in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Some $200,000 has been seized from the operation, officials
said, along with several vehicles. The investigation is ongoing and
more arrests are expected.
</P>
<P>
   INS spokeswoman Virginia Kice said immigrant smuggling has
become a multibillion-dollar business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's more money in it than ever before, and it has become a
lot more sophisticated in terms of organization,'' Kice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we use the money laundering laws, that not only helps us
to get at the profit motive, but the penalties for money laundering
are stiffer than for some of the more traditional charges related
to smuggling itself.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
