<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-SOFTBALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME RUN SINKS NORTHRIDGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Tara Glaister watched the ball leave UCLA's Easton
Stadium, then got philosophical.
</P>
<P>
   She could do little else, especially after her 13-strikeout
performance turned into just another stellar effort in a losing
cause.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota edged the Matadors 2-1 Friday in an NCAA regional game
on a seventh-inning home run by Dana Ballard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It happens,'' Glaister said. ``It's frustrating, but it's part
of the game. You make the pitch or you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Golden Gophers (48-18) advanced to today's 10 a.m. winners'
bracket game against UCLA. Northridge (30-23) drops to the
elimination bracket and plays Missouri at 12:30 p.m. The Matadors
beat the Tigers 7-3 in Thursday's opener. A victory sends CSUN into
a 3:30 p.m. game against the Minnesota-UCLA loser; a loss ends the
Matadors season.
</P>
<P>
   Glaister did just about everything right. She recorded the first
seven outs by strikeout (although Minnesota scored an unearned run
in between) and finished with a five-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Her only miscue was Ballard's homer to left, Ballard's first in
more than a year and the fourth of the junior's career. But Ballard
has been the clutch hitter of late, having driven in two
seventh-inning, game-winning runs in the Big Ten tournament against
Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Glaister (21-14) wanted the pitch inside, but the ball went over
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, I missed a spot at the wrong time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge couldn't muster enough offense despite chasing
Minnesota starter Steph Klaviter in the third inning, when the
Matadors scored their run. Catcher Jamie Moore singled off the
fence to score Jill Passafiume.
</P>
<P>
   Northridge managed just two hits off reliever Michelle Harrison
(10-7) over the final 42/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA 14, Creighton 0: Julie Adams hit two home runs, including a
grand slam, and drove in six to lead a 21-hit attack, and the
Bruins (57-6) eliminated the Blue Jays (31-28).
</P>
<P>
   Adams continued her torrid hitting in the regional, following
Thursday's two-homer, five-RBI effort against Alabama with a slam
to right field off Shelli Mellegaard (13-14) in the fifth inning.
She added a solo shot off Mellegaard to lead off the seventh inning
and later in the inning singled in another.
</P>
<P>
   The grand slam gave UCLA needed cushion because before that,
Amanda Freed (25-4) clung to a 1-0 lead. She stranded three
Creighton runners in scoring position through four innings and
finished with a four-hitter with 11 strikeouts and two walks for
her 14th shutout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
