A7067 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-BIGSKY-LADN     05-22 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-BIGSKY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE WOMEN GET JUMP ON FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ LaTanya Collier finally got a fair jump in the
long jump in the Big Sky Conference Championships on Friday at Cal
State Northridge.
</P>
<P>
   The Northridge junior, who has had a history of trouble on the
board and fouled out of the conference indoor championships the
last two seasons, hit her mark on Friday to sail to victory in a
career-best 19 feet, 11} inches.
</P>
<P>
   Collier's triumph added to LaShaunda Fowler's fourth at 19-1{
and Brandi Prieto and Anicia Rimm's fifth and sixth with wind-aided
18-9\ and 18-8{ marks gave the Matadors 22 points and a convincing
jump toward their second outdoor conference championship in three
years.
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors are in first with 68 points after six events in the
four-day meet that concludes today. Northern Arizona is second with
43 and Idaho State is third with 34.
</P>
<P>
   The Weber State men lead after seven events with 61 points;
Northridge is fifth with 29.
</P>
<P>
   The Northridge women picked up 23 points in the pole vault,
placing four among the top five with Allyson Crosby, Monica Tobin,
Jennifer Capehart (each at 11-8) and Lisa Rugenstein (11-1{)
finishing second through fifth. Marisol Barajas added a fourth
place in the 10,000 in 36:01.84.
</P>
<P>
   Collier's performance in the long jump exceeded her
personal-best of 19-7{ set in April and was 11 inches farther than
her best in her freshman season when she finished fourth in the
outdoor conference finals. Collier, who competes in the triple jump
today, had four jumps of 19-2 or better and two fouls well over 20
feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get too emotional, too excited and too pumped up when I am
on the runway,'' Collier said. ``Everybody is crossing their
fingers and really tense because I can blow real good opportunities
by fouling. There are too many times I have walked away from a
competition knowing that I did not win because of some mistake that
I made.''
</P>
<P>
   With the loss of sprinter Genia Seymore to a stress fracture,
Collier's points in the long jump might be the boost the Matadors
need to dethrone defending champion Weber State.
</P>
<P>
   Prieto and Fowler, who finished first and second in the
heptathlon, advanced in the 100-meter hurdles in 14.14 and 14.1,
and Rimm qualified for the 100 with a heat victory in 12.09.
</P>
<P>
   Krystal Harris qualified with the fastest time in the 100 with a
wind-aided 11.78 and Annetta Wells moved up to the 400 to post the
No.1 preliminary mark of 54.4 1 to crush her previous lifetime best
of 55.71.
</P>
</TEXT>
