<HEADER>
A7079 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NET-STOCK-LADN     05-22 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-STOCK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET'S GREAT RIDE AT AN END?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DEBORAH ADAMSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- What goes up, must come down.
</P>
<P>
   This time-worn adage has proved true for high-flying Internet
stocks, especially during the past month. After spectacular
run-ups, they've floated back down to earth.
</P>
<P>
   For proof, just look at the Hambrecht &AMP; Quist Internet Index,
one of the leading indicators of the online sector. In the past
month, it's down 19 percent. In the past (ITAL) month (END ITAL).
Over the same period, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 4.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say it's a combination of factors that have taken the
steam out of the sector: The threat of higher interest rates, a
shift among institutional investors to cyclical and industrial
stocks, profit-taking by Net investors and renewed concerns about
valuation.
</P>
<P>
   Already, some mutual funds have been unloading Internet stocks
-- and, to a lesser extent, their cousins, the technology stocks --
since the beginning of the year and contributing to the weakness,
said Patrick Dorsey, technology analyst at fund-rating firm
Morningstar in Chicago. Dorsey said Fidelity Magellan, the nation's
largest fund, and Legg Mason Value Trust were two of the most
well-known mutual funds selling off Net shares.
</P>
<P>
   Why? After two years of spectacular growth, investors apparently
finally think that Internet stocks are overvalued, analysts said.
And this week's announcement by a key Federal Reserve committee
that it's leaning toward raising interest rates because of signs of
inflation additionally spooked the markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The focus -- with the Fed's move -- will be on earnings now,''
said Chris Orndorff, head of equity investments at Payden &AMP; Rygel,
a $27 billion money management firm based in Los Angeles. ``That
will bring some sanity to Internet stocks'' since only a handful of
these companies have earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Why are interest rates so important to Internet stocks? The most
common gauge investors use to judge whether a stock is expensive --
and needs to be sold -- is the price-to-earnings ratio, or P/E. The
ratio compares the price of one share of the company to the amount
of money it earns for that one share.
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks have high P/E ratios because, until recently,
there have been more people wanting to buy them than sell them.
Thus, the share prices have gone up.
</P>
<P>
   In a low-interest environment, investors are willing to pay more
for a stock because they believe economic factors will stimulate
business. The price they are paying now bets that future earnings
will be good enough to justify it. But if interest rates rise,
business will slow down because it will cost more to borrow.
Consumers will spend less as well. In addition, a rise in inflation
makes future earnings worth less.
</P>
<P>
   ``People fear a rise in interest rates,'' Dorsey said. ``High
interest rates are death to high price-to-earnings stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet stocks are expected to weaken further in the near
future as the flight to other investments continues, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't mean that the bull market is ending. Despite its
volatility, the overall market isn't turning bearish, analysts
believe.
</P>
<P>
   One good sign is that breadth -- the number of stocks rising vs.
declining -- has broadened as more companies enjoy an increase in
their stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big positive. The bull will continue,'' Orndorff said.
``In the last 60 days, breadth has really increased. Mid- and
small-caps had gains.''
</P>
<P>
   How should Internet investors play this market?
</P>
<P>
   Look for bargains in solid companies that will survive the
coming shakeout, advised Dorsey, the Morningstar technology
analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL, Yahoo! and Amazon.com will probably be higher'' in the
long run, he said. ``They will probably be around.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, he has less confidence in stocks like theglobe.com,
which perhaps does not have the same staying power as an America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey compared the current Internet marketplace to the
automobile industry of the early 20th century. Like the Internet,
the invention of cars changed people's lives. In the beginning,
there were dozens of American car companies. But only a handful
remain today. The same cycle will befall Internet companies, Dorsey
predicted.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be a lot fewer Internet companies two years
from now,'' he predicted.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
