<P>
   NATIONAL _ GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `w' category)
</P>
<P>
   TRIE-DONATE (Washington) _ Charlie Trie, Little Rock
restaurateur and longtime friend of Clinton, whose donations to
Democrats were returned, pleads guilty to obstruction and campaign
related offenses and agrees to cooperate with federal authorities.
By David Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   TRIE-DONATE-HUGHES (Washington) _ The Justice Department has
obtained a note from the Little Rock office of Yah Lin Trie, a
Democratic fund-raiser, that suggests he was aware of a bribery
problem. By Jeff Gerth.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-MARIJUANA (Washington) _ In an effort to promote research
into the medical benefits of marijuana, the Clinton administration
has decided to begin selling government-grown marijuana to
scientists who want to study the drug but who have previously been
unable to do so because they lacked the required relationship with
the National Institutes of Health. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-FINANCE (Washington) _ In his first confrontation with
Republican moderates, House Speaker Dennis Hastert has spurned
their request for an early vote on campaign finance legislation. By
Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ Fresh from their victory on gun
control in the Senate, Democrats trained their attention and
oratory on the House, calling for a gun-control vote within the
next week and lambasting Republican leaders for laying out a less
immediate course. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS-CLELAND (Washington) _ As someone who once had to
carry an assault rifle, losing three limbs when he was in Vietnam,
Sen. Max Cleland has always thought deeply about guns. He tended to
view the issue in Second Amendment terms. But the school shootings
in the last year and a half led him to change his mind and become
the crucial vote in the Senate. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VACATION (Washington) _ A White House memo the politics
of vacation planning. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   LOTTERY-IMPACT (Orange, N.J.) _ With lottery machines as
prevalent as cash registers in 38 states and $35 billion bet on
them each year, the most prevalent purveyors of gambling are now
state governments. It is in communities like Orange where the
lottery is a dominant force and many poor and modest wage earners
are devoted to an endless search for winning numbers. By Brett
Pulley. WITH PHOTOS and GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS-IMPACT (Boston) _ A handful of relatively little
noticed provisions in the crime bill passed by the Senate on
Thursday may do as much or more to curb the flow of illegal guns to
criminals and juveniles than the much debated measures that require
child safety locks and background checks at gun shows, senior
Treasury officials say. By Fox Butterfield.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-COMMUNITY (Littleton, Colo.) _ As Columbine High
School approaches the end of the school year, the community finds
itself struggling not only with its tragedy, but also with how to
reclaim its privacy. What it's like to live at the center of a news
event. By Sara Rimer. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-PROBE (Denver) _ One month after the Columbine High
School massacre, 80 law enforcement investigators are planning to
labor through the summer trying to determine if any friends of the
two school gunmen aided them or knew about the attack beforehand.
By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-GENOME-PROJECT (Cold Spring Harbor, N.Y.) _ The publicly
financed effort to decode the human genome, the 3 billion units of
DNA at the heart of every human cell, is now 10 percent complete
and is on track to meet its goal of finishing a first draft of the
genome a year from now, said the NIH. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   NY-SCHOOLS-RELIGION (White Plains, N.Y.) _ A school district
violated First Amendment rights of its students by allowing schools
to conduct religious-oriented activities, including the
construction of a Hindu god's likeness by third-graders and new-age
prayer recitals at a high-school Earth Day celebration, a federal
district court judge ruled.
</P>
<P>
   GA-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Conyers, Ga.) _ Thomas Solomon, the
15-year-old accused in the shooting of six students at a suburban
high school, broke into his stepfather's locked gun cabinet to get
two weapons, then carried them aboard a school bus, authorities
said. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Boy Scouts and the Universalists
battle over the meaning of faith. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   NY-LOUIMA-TRIAL (New York) _ Developments on the trial of police
officers charged with brutalizing Abner Louima, a Hatian immigrant,
while he was in custody. By Joseph P. Fried.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Washington) _ The Clinton administration announced
that the U.S. would press its allies to move quickly to deploy what
was described as a peacekeeping force of about 50,000 troops on the
borders of Kosovo. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLICY (Washington) _ Between the two options that
President Clinton has declared unacceptable _ doing nothing or
all-out war _ the White House has devised a new kind of warfare for
Yugoslavia. It is a calibrated war, enabled by high-tech weaponry,
shaped by the flickering light of opinion polls and shackled by
fear that a few American combat deaths could turn the public
against any military intervention. By Blaine Harden and John
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Yugoslavia insisted that it must
play a central role in negotiations within the United Nations to
end the war and bring a political settlement to Kosovo, and that
Belgrade would not simply let NATO dictate a solution. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Tirana, Albania) _ The Kosovo rebel group, the
KLA, which says that Russians are fighting in Kosovo, announces
that it has killed one and shows his body, according to Russian TV.
By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Washington) _ NATO warplanes attacking a
military compound in northwestern Kosovo struck what Yugoslavia's
official news agency described as a prison, killing at least 19
inmates and guards. The strike came as NATO faced mounting concerns
about its targeting, even from within the alliance. NATO's attacks
nevertheless resumed a furious pace Friday after intermittently bad
weather severely hampered strikes. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   SMALLPOX (United Nations) _ Prompted by fears of a new outbreak
of one of the world's deadliest scourges, the World Health Assembly
in Geneva effectively decided to defer eradicating the world's
known remaining stocks of the smallpox virus until at least 2002.
By Judith Miller and Lawrence K. Altman.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-IMMIG (Berlin) _ Acknowledging what a mixed society it
has become, Germany adopted a new immigration law that will make it
easier for many of the country's 7 million residents of foreign
origin to become citizens. After a fiercely contested passage
through Parliament, the the new legislation was approved by the
upper house. It goes into effect Jan. 1 and represents a
significant shift in the country's view of itself. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-BIZARRE-TV (Sao Paulo) _ Even in Brazil's permissive
climate there are limits on sex, violence and the bizarre _ and the
newly minted TV stars Auntie and Little Rat have set off a national
controversy by exceeding them. Public outrage at their behavior has
become so intense that the government is intervening on
human-rights grounds. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-TERROR (Rome) _ Italians scoured their newspapers Friday
with a sickening sense of deja-vu: blaring headlines about the
assassination of a government official, blurry photographs of the
widow leaving the police station, and a five-pointed star that
terrified Italy for two decades, the emblem of the Red Brigades. By
Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   BOMB-SUSPECTS (New York) _ Under cloak of secrecy, the
government has taken another suspect into custody in the
investigation of Osama bin Laden, the Saudi exile charged in the
bombings of the U.S. Embassies in East Africa last year, according
to several people knowledgeable about the case. By Benjamin Weiser.
</P>
