<BODY>
 PM-NYT-BUDGET-2NDTAKE-NYT  
 UNDATED: Alessandra Stanley . 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSINESS DAY
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `f' category)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-COLA (Newark, N.J.) _ Marketing consultant Dan DeRose was
busy doing the math for his new client, the Newark Public Schools.
How much money could the district make if it signed an exclusive
contract with a soft-drink company? The answer, DeRose said: a lot
more than it gets now. DeRose and his company, DD Marketing, are
storming a once-quiet backwater in the soft-drink business. Schools
regard him as a font of information. Soft-drink companies, which
used to make low-key deals on their terms with local school
districts, hate him with a passion. By Constance L. Hays. WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   TELECOM-ITALIA (Rome) _ In Europe's biggest hostile takeover
ever, Olivetti, the midsized Italian telephone company, grabbed
control of the nation's largest phone company, Telecom Italia,
successfully concluding a bitter three-month corporate battle. By
John Tagliabue. WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   PROTEST-SHIP (Vladivostok, Russia) _ A freighter owned by a
union of sailors, truckers, longshoremen and others is making an
round-the-world voyage to fight the registration of ships under
`flags of convenience' _ countries other than the place of
ownership. Of the world's 85,500 self-propelled cargo vessels of
100 gross tons or greater, some 16,000 are registered in the 27
countries that the union lists as flags of convenience. The union
says such vessels have poor safety records, frequently do not pay
employees, and sometimes abandon sailors in distant ports when
aging ships get too expensive to run. By Russell Working. WITH
GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   TINA-BRITTANIA-BOOKDEAL (Undated) _ Historian Simon Schama has
signed a deal to publish his next work of nonfiction with Talk
Miramax Books, a division of Talk Media, which is owned by Miramax
Films. The book, titled `Brittania,' will be a history of Britain
from the time before the Roman invasion to the year 2000, and it
will accompany a 12-part BBC series, directed by Schama, that ABC
will broadcast in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   VITAMIN-ROCHE (Basel) _ One day after admitting that some senior
executives were ringleaders in a nine-year price-fixing cartel for
vitamins, the chairman and the chief executive of Roche Holding AG
pronounced themselves blameless and clueless. By Edmund L. Andrews.
WITH GRAPHIC.
</P>
<P>
   TWA-LABOR (Undated) _ TWA and its machinists union agree that
the airline, which has continued to lose money in the midst of an
industry boom, cannot afford a strike. Both sides worry that even
the current threat of a walkout could severely damage the carrier
because more passengers will stop making reservations as the strike
deadline nears. By Lawrence Zuckerman.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-AOL (Washington) _ AOL chief Steve Case is deposed in
the Microsoft antitrust trial. Microsoft lawyers tried to argue
that some of America Online's plans threaten parts of Microsoft's
business. This was intended to bolster Microsoft's argument that
AOL's purchase of Netscape undermined the government's case by
demonstrating a robust competitive environment in the personal
computer industry. By Joel Brinkley. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-BANKS (Tokyo) _ Japan's giant banks report record losses
for the latest fiscal year. The poor performance stems largely from
the banks' efforts to clean their books by writing off bad loans,
but the losses were still larger than expected as regulators force
banks to follow stricter rules for evaluating bad loans and to
create a deeper cushion of reserves. By Sheryl WuDunn.
</P>
<P>
   SEC-ACCOUNTING (Undated) _ The nation's largest group of
