<SLUG> BC-BKN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS LOOK LIKE YELLOWBRICK ROADKILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's quiz: What do the Los Angeles Lakers have in common with
key characters in the film ``The Wizard of Oz?''
</P>
<P>
   Answer: No heart, no brains, no courage.
</P>
<P>
   This may be a rather harsh assessment of our dysfunctional NBA
team, but the time has definitely come to stop coddling these young
men. The free pass has expired. Excuses will no longer be accepted
for their collective youth and inexperience.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' last two efforts against the San Antonio Spurs,
leaving them down 0-2 in their second-round playoff series heading
into Game 3 today at the Forum, were identical to their playoff
efforts against Utah the last two seasons, absolutely lacking in
the essentials that separate teams that win from those who only
talk about winning.
</P>
<P>
   They blew leads. They bungled opportunities. They didn't listen
to their coaches. They changed plays on the fly. They preened with
time still left on the clock. They reverted to individual play when
team play was needed most. They waited for someone else to step up
while they stood in place.
</P>
<P>
   They made excuses. They blamed the officials. And they said the
next game would be different, words that have been used so often
that they've totally lost their meaning.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' biggest sin is that they have fulfilled the scouting
report every team has on them, the one that says The Lakers will
will find a way to screw up if you give them the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Pick a player, any player.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice, the shooter the Lakers felt they needed to offset
Shaquille O'Neal's inside game, has proven to be very streaky. That
in itself is not a problem. It becomes a problem, though, when Rice
continues to shoot when he's iced up. Plus, he's lousy defensively.
Getting Rice made sense, but not at the cost of the team's best
defender, Eddie Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, the prodigy, is nearing the moment when his mind
gets in sync with his talent. But he is not ready to take on the
entire responsibility of winning like Michael Jordan did six times.
The more he finds himself cast in that role prematurely, the more
likely he is to become a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Fisher, the Lakers' point guard, hustles like a maniac and
has nothing but good intentions. But the major prerequisites of a
point guard are to be smarter than everyone else, to know what play
to run or change, and have the respect of his teammates, so that
they'll look to him for guidance. Fisher doesn't have that.
</P>
<P>
   All of the forwards asked to fill the power spot have been
unsuitable and uninspired to the task. Be it against widebody
Charles Barkley or the thin Tim Duncan, they have yet to keep
anybody from their appointments in the post. Did you ever think the
day would come when the Lakers would miss Elden Campbell? Well,
it's here.
</P>
<P>
   The most dependable trait of Robert Horry and Rick Fox is that
they are undependable. They may have a popup sensational evening
from time to time, but they never have back-to-back good efforts.
That Fox has been filling the role of statesman on this team is
glaring insight into how little character fills the Lakers locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to Shaquille O'Neal. In his three years as a
Laker, he has impressed everyone with a superb work ethic and a
real desire to be successful. He wants to be the man to carry the
team on his back.
</P>
<P>
   But desire doesn't make it so. Shaq occasionally gets exposed
defensively in one-on-one situations, and he could use a few weeks
of intense study on the value of the blocked shot. If he had as
much passion on the defensive end that he has on offense, we might
not be worrying about anyone else's liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   What he needs to do most is to stop trying to fill the role of
big brother or big daddy on this team, or some kind of general
manager in shorts suggesting help in the form of Dennis Rodman and
Glen Rice. If he wants to kick some ass, he might consider starting
in his own locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons are often odious, but they're also often
unavoidable. When you look at this Lakers team, you do not see the
passion to win that made Magic Johnson's Lakers special.
</P>
<P>
   You do not see anyone sublimating their game for the good of the
team as James Worthy and Byron Scott.
</P>
<P>
   You do not see players like Michael Cooper and Kurt Rambis
filling their roles to perfection.
</P>
<P>
   And while Kareem Abdul-Jabbar was never a personal favorite, I
never had to worry about his focus or his desire to win. Kareem
didn't need a Superman tattoo to announce his arrival, and he
understood the game had two baskets that needed attending, not just
one. And once Kareem got a taste of success, too, he wanted more.
</P>
<P>
   Could this all have been avoided? I'd like to think so. If the
Lakers had fired Del Harris in 1997, when the Del-Nick Van Exel war
escalated, maybe the team goes in another direction.
</P>
<P>
   With Nick, the Lakers have an on-court leader and an outside
shooter. Maybe Kobe doesn't have to become a go-to guy before he's
ready. Maybe the Lakers put their personnel emphasis on a true
power forward and forget about trading Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they have a coach in his second year with the team,
undoubtedly someone with more experience than Kurt Rambis.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot of what-ifs. But clearly, any Laker fantasy is much
better than their current reality, which is on the yellow brick
road to another lousy postseason.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
