<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
M'S WIN BIG WITH `LITTLE BALL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Russ Davis was not surprised when he got the
sign, because he had the same idea himself.
</P>
<P>
   It was the top of the eighth inning at Kauffman Stadium, and the
Mariners had a three-run lead over the Kansas City Royals. John
Mabry led off with a single, and up came Davis _ nine homers on the
year, and fresh off a run-scoring double _ to bunt. Mabry went to
second on the sacrifice, and scored the Mariners' final run when
David Bell singled two batters later.
</P>
<P>
   It's standard baseball, if not standard M's baseball. The
Mariners had just four sacrifices coming into Friday night, one
fewer than the Royals' Carlos Febles. No team has more homers than
Seattle, but only three have fewer sacrifices.
</P>
<P>
   So when Davis got the bunt down, it made a fitting symbol for
the Mariners' 5-2 win, their first this year in a game in which
they did not homer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always good to get a win like that, because this is a big
power-hitting team, and we live and die by the long ball,'' Davis
said. ``But to be successful, you've got to do the little things,
too. We showed that we can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   A win tonight would put the Mariners at .500, where they haven't
been in 34 games. If they do so, the M's would be following the
lead of starter Jamie Moyer, who worked six strong innings to even
his record at 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   Moyer allowed seven hits and one run Friday night, mastering a
Royals team that hadn't lost since he blanked them for eight
innings last Sunday. He did it with exceptional command; for the
first time in his 10 starts, he issued no walks.
</P>
<P>
   That's crucial against the Royals, who can sustain rallies and
have scored 57 runs in their last five games _ excluding the two
started by Moyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these guys, you've got to be around the plate, but you
can't get too much of the plate, because they put the ball in play
and move the ball around,'' Moyer said. ``To make them score runs,
you've got to make them manufacture them. That's what we did
tonight. Fortunately, they only got two, but they're tough _ one
pitch, they get a single, the next pitch, they steal second. They
can put runs up like it's playground baseball _ running and running
and running.''
</P>
<P>
   Running and running for the Mariners was Ken Griffey, Jr., who
legged out a double and stole two bases. With nine steals, he
stands first on the team and is among the AL leaders.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning, Griffey slid hard into third for his
second steal, two innings after Alex Rodriguez had done the same
advancing from first on a Griffey single. The bag came loose, the
stake noticeably bent, and Griffey left the game in the ninth with
cramps.
</P>
<P>
   No big deal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Alex slid, it bent, and when I slid, it just came out,''
Griffey said. ``Those were two rough slides going into third. But
it's just cramps, that's all. I was a little dehydrated, too. I'm
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder John Mabry had the most eventful day. He made a
diving catch in the first inning, then battled the fading sun _
and, he said, the new see-through backstop behind home plate _ for
another catch.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, with a runner on third and the Mariners leading
4-1, he dove again to catch a sinking fly ball by Joe Randa, ending
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mabry was on base four times, each time figuring in a run. He
singled home the M's first run in the second, beat out an infield
hit to sustain a two-run rally in the fourth, walked and scored in
the sixth and finished with the leadoff single in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The former Cardinal has hit safely in six of his last eight
games, raising his average 53 points, to .272. Asked afterward by a
St. Louis reporter if he still was a .300 hitter, Mabry had a quick
reply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, certainly,'' he said. ``Definitely. Through the course of
500 at-bats, I think it'll work out that I can hit .300 again.
You've got to believe in yourself, that's the No. 1 thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mabry, who hit between .284 and .307 his first four years before
tailing off last year, said he's feeling more and more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been working on it, trying to get the mechanics right and
putting myself in a better position to hit,'' he said. ``Transfer
the weight and get the timing down. It usually comes after that,
but you have to get the basics first.''
</P>
<P>
   The basics? Seemed to be the the theme of the evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit the ball behind the runner a few times, which is good
to see,'' said manager Lou Piniella. ``Sacrificed a runner over,
got a two-out hit to give us that cushion. Those are things you'd
like to see us do with consistency, and let the home runs come when
they come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
