<HEADER>
A7105 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-CARDINALS     05-22 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CARDINALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS FALL TO CARDINALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Inconsistent: not consistent; lacking agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Also see, Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   They will look like the $80 million ballclub of destruction on
one night. They will self-destruct and give the impression of being
one of the more thrifty ballclubs on another night.
</P>
<P>
   There is no rhyme. No reason. No explanation and no way to know
which is coming.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers suffered their fifth loss in six games, dropping a
10-6 decision to the St. Louis Cardinals before a sellout crowd of
53,683 Friday at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers left fielder Gary Sheffield had two homers and three
RBI. So did St. Louis' Ray Lankford.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers trailed 6-1 in the sixth inning before rallying to
pull within a run. The most significant thing the Dodgers offense
did was get St. Louis starter Juan Acevedo to his pitch count by
the end of the fifth inning. He left after throwing 78 pitches (48
strikes).
</P>
<P>
   In came Mike Mohler, though only for a brief, ineffective spell,
as the Dodgers tried to come back. Switch-hitting catcher Todd
Hundley got his first hit from the right side this season in 10
at-bats to score Eric Young and move Beltre to third. Eric Karros
singled in Beltre and Devon White looped a single to center to
score Hundley and make it 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   Mohler gave way to Rick Croushore, who got Mark Grudzielanek to
line to center on his first pitch to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   But the momentum gained for the three-run inning was abruptly
lost in the seventh when Fernando Tatis hit Masaoka's 2-1 pitch
over the right field fence for his 12th homer of the season and a
7-4 St. Louis lead.
</P>
<P>
   Croushore allowed a one-out walk to Eric Young. Two batters
later Sheffield hit a two-run homer just inside the left field foul
pole to make it 7-6. It was the third time this season Sheffield
has hit two homers in a game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cardinals' inability to hold a big lead also rubbed off
on the Dodgers' bullpen's inability to keep it close, or vice
versa.
</P>
<P>
   Newly acquired reliever Doug Bochtler gave the two runs back in
the eighth when Lankford hit a two-run homer to right-center to
push the Cardinals' lead to 9-6.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals added a run in the top of the ninth on Joe
McEwing's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals had beaten the Dodgers four times in the six
previous meetings this season, and did it without the aid of Mark
McGwire's long ball. McGwire still hadn't homered at Chavez Ravine,
but it matters not when the rest of the Cardinals are battering
Dodgers pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the worst sign of the night, though, was when the crowd
vehemently booed the Dodgers. Not because they committed four
errors in the first seven innings _ three by third baseman Adrian
Beltre _ or because their play was lackluster once again.
</P>
<P>
   No, the jeers came when reliever Onan Masaoka intentionally
walked McGwire in the sixth with runners on second and third and
two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Lost in the glitz and glamour and anticipation of a McGwire home
run is that the Dodgers were shutdown by a stopgap starter who was
pummeled in two innings in his last start _ against the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Acevedo, who allowed four runs on five hits in two innings last
Sunday in St. Louis, allowed one hit in five innings. It was a
Sheffield home run to left that gave the Dodgers a glimmer of hope
in the fourth inning as they pulled to within 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   While Acevedo was dazzling, Dodgers right-hander Ismael Valdes
was dreadful in what turned out to be his shortest outing of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes allowed six runs on six hits in 41/3 innings. He also
walked two and was hurt by three errors that led to a pair of
unearned runs.
</P>
<P>
   But after Sheffield's homer, the Cardinals came right back with
two runs in the top of the fifth, knocking Valdes out in the
process. Darren Bragg and Edgar Renteria began the inning with
singles and McGwire scored Bragg with a sacrifice fly to center.
Valdes hit Lankford, who hit his first homer earlier, with a pitch
and walked Tatis to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers manager Davey Johnson saw enough and pulled Valdes for
Mike Maddux, who walked Eric Davis to force in a run and put the
Cardinals ahead 6-1. Maddux got out of the inning with a double
play.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' rally was necessitated by Valdes' ineffectiveness
early on. It began when Lankford, who homered off closer Jeff Shaw
in Sunday's win in the Midwest, led off the second with a solo
homer.
</P>
<P>
   Tatis singled, Beltre committed his first error on Davis'
grounder and Eli Marrero singled to load the bases. McEwing's
sacrifice fly gave the Cardinals a 2-0 lead and with two outs Bragg
singled to right to score two as St. Louis went ahead 4-0.
</P>
</TEXT>
