<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KRIEGER WINS GRAND AMERICAN RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Ron Nava's Chevrolet slammed into the first
turn coming off lap three in Friday's NASCAR Grand American
Modified's race at Irwindale Speedway, causing a 15-minute delay in
front of the brave 2,742 on a chilly night.
</P>
<P>
   It only got worse from there, Rip Michels' Chevrolet blew a tire
after the second turn of lap five. He turned onto the infield, but
hit a parked ambulance, causing a second caution and extra delay.
</P>
<P>
   After the ambulance was towed away, Larry Krieger assumed the
lead following lap six and pulled away in his Chevrolet to win the
Grand American race, well ahead of second place finisher Rod
Johnson in the delay-shortened 25-lap race on the 1/2 mile track.
</P>
<P>
   Krieger, who led Johnson in the NASCAR point standings heading
in, increased his lead to 284-258 over Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson looked like he would challenge Krieger in laps nine
through 12, trying each time to pass Krieger on the inside of turn
four, but Krieger held him off each time.
</P>
<P>
   TK Karvasek captured the Super Stock race, winning the other
delayed-shortened feature over second place finisher John Vitale in
the 25 lap race, originally scheduled for 40 laps.
</P>
<P>
   In the Legends division, Escondido's Seth Hicks tried to squeeze
by leader Mike Cass in the final lap (25), but Hicks knocked Cass
into John occasions's car, causing Cass and occasions to slam into
the wall coming off turn three.
</P>
<P>
   Hicks, who led most of the race before being passed by Cass in
lap 22, was moved to last for causing the accident, allowing
Riverside's Ron Anderson to capture the Legends race. Covina's
Jimmy White finished second, 1.682 behind Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   White, who started in fourth position, took a quick lead coming
off turn four of the opening lap, passing Cass. He held that lead
for the next couple laps, holding off Cass on two occassions, but
Cass finally reclaimed the lead in lap six as White dropped to
fourth. White maintained that position throughout before being
moved to second after the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Both Cass and occasions appeared to come out of the accident in
good shape.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-lap Mini Stock race around the 1/3 mile track was
captured by Thousand Oak's Lee Ladd, who started in fourth
position. Ladd trailed second place finisher Scott Porter heading
into lap seven -- but that's where the race changed for good.
</P>
<P>
   Bellflower's Terry Limberopoulous tried to pass both Ladd and
Porter in lap seven coming off the fourth turn and entering the
front straight, but Limberopoulous spun out, clearing the way for
Ladd to sneak pass Porter to take the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Ladd was never challenged since, finishing in a time of
6:06.064. Porter finished .872 behind Ladd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
