<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7152 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNDS-SHRINK-BOSTON &LR;      05-22 1170
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-SHRINK-BOSTON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEYDAY OF STOCK MUTUAL FUNDS MAY BE IN JEOPARDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- For a decade, mutual funds have been the nation's
hottest investing trend. Invented in Boston more than 70 years ago
and enshrined in the 1990s as America's investment of choice, funds
have created wealth for everyone from ordinary citizens to
corporate money giants such as Fidelity Investments.
</P>
<P>
   But the product that brought investing to the masses and helped
Americans save for college and retirement faces new challenges. In
part beguiled by on-line trading and the fresh allure of individual
stocks, in part annoyed by a volatile Wall Street whose highs have
rewarded only the happy few, investors have been putting less money
into stock mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   After years of unimpeded expansion, the fund industry is bracing
for a slower rate of growth and stiffer competition. In Boston,
where one-quarter of the country's $5.5 trillion fund business is
concentrated and money management is a bulwark of the Massachusetts
economy, the changes have special resonance.
</P>
<P>
   If recent slower sales trends persist, ``it's going to slow down
growth in a very fast-growing industry,'' said Kevin McIntyre, a
senior economist at RFA/Dismal Sciences, a market research firm in
West Chester, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   The recent shift in investor habits suggests at least in part a
rejection of the principle of professional money management, a
foundation of the traditional fund industry. The change also
recalls an era when stocks were America's favorite investment,
before mutual funds took off in the 1980s. And it underscores the
spread of a transaction mentality _ the hallmark of traditional and
cyber brokerages _ across a nation of investors formed under an
ethos of long-term investing.
</P>
<P>
   One might argue that the fund industry has become a victim of
its own success. Investors who made money off mutual funds in
recent years now have so much extra cash they are pursuing the next
hottest thing _ shares in Internet companies. Jeremiah Potts,
director of marketing and communications at MFS Investment
Management of Boston, called the straying from funds and fresh
focus on Web-related stocks ``the result of a market peaking and
simple greed kicking in.''
</P>
<P>
   Or one could argue that the industry has faltered amid more
enticing, if riskier, investments. Many funds have not kept pace
with the broader market's returns, mostly because only a handful of
stocks _ generally blue chips or high-flying technology shares _
have performed well. That gap has led some irritated investors to
refrain from putting new cash into stock funds and instead try
on-line stock trading.
</P>
<P>
   Investors put a net $48.8 billion into equity funds so far this
year through May 20, nearly 40 percent less than a year ago,
according to Robert Adler of AMG Data Services, a firm in Arcata,
Calif., that tracks fund flows.
</P>
<P>
   The figure, which represents the amount investors put into stock
funds of all types minus the sums they pulled out, is still large
by historic standards. And the industry's total assets under
management are still increasing.
</P>
<P>
   But that growth has been caused mainly because of a rising stock
market, not new sales. Against that backdrop, the recent sales
numbers tell a complex tale of shifts in investor habits.
</P>
<P>
   While concerned about a recent drop in new cash coming into
stock funds, the workhouse of the mutual fund industry, most fund
executives are not quaking in their wingtips. Money management
firms earn the most from collecting fees for assets they oversee,
not selling new funds. So even when sales or stock markets slow
down, they still make money.
</P>
<P>
   While investors have put less cash into stock funds as a whole,
they have lavished money on a few types of funds. This year through
May 20, investors put a net $56.8 billion into large-company stock
funds, more than twice as much as in the year-ago period, according
to AMG. They sent $24 billion to funds that mimic indexes, a rise
of 70 percent from a year ago. And they poured cash into technology
funds _ $6.8 billion compared with net withdrawals of $400 million
a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Those figures are larger than the net $48.8 billion that equity
funds of all types scored because investors also withdrew tens of
billions of dollars from small-company, international, and other
funds. In fact, 297 domestic stock funds suffered net redemptions,
or withdrawals, last quarter, an increase of nearly 30 percent on
1998, according to Financial Research Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts point to a plethora of factors _ many of them
contradictory _ behind the overall slowdown in stock fund sales.
</P>
<P>
   Some think the nation's 73 million fund investors are more
afraid of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Others, pointing out the stampede to Internet issues, see
investors as less afraid of the stock market and more willing to
take risks _ especially with the Dow Jones industrial average up 18
percent so far this year and near the 11,000 range.
</P>
<P>
   Some view investors as irritated by the underperformance of
mutual funds, whose managers have found it increasingly tough to
beat the broad market.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another theory says fund investors have been seduced by
on-line brokerages, which now number 9 million accounts and are
home to more than one-third of all retail stock trades, or
transactions made by individual investors, according to Gomez
Advisers Inc., a consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Potts said up to 15 percent of all investors who use financial
planners now think they can beat professional portfolio managers
with a do-it-yourself strategy of picking stocks _ especially those
whose names end in ``dot com.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason behind the slowdown in fund sales growth,
funds ``have clearly become more of a mature business,'' Potts
said, citing the industry's success this decade in reaching more
than one in three American households.
</P>
<P>
   That natural slowdown in growth, coupled with changing investor
habits, could affect the asset management industry in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Volatile cash flows from sales make it tougher for fund firms to
plan their businesses. McIntyre of RFA/Dismal Sciences forecast
jobs growth in the securities industry, which is predominantly
composed of fund firms, slowing to 7 1/2 percent this year and just
2 percent in 2000, after expansion of 8 percent and 9 percent in
the previous two years. While securities industry employees total
1.5 percent of the Boston area's work force, they account for 4
percent of the earnings, and thus spend more dollars in the local
economy.
</P>
<P>
   Like many fund executives, AMG's Adler sees investors eventually
coming back en masse to mutual funds as a broad investment
category. Like stock markets, he said, fund sales are cyclical.
``When a correction comes _ and it will,'' Adler said, ``people
will return to mutual funds for the purpose for which they were
created _ to have a professional manage your money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1002EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 11:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7175 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DULL-POLITICS-REVIEW-     05-22 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DULL-POLITICS-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DULL CAN CUT BOTH WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(dw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Poor Al Gore. As if President Clinton's keening
that his loyal No. 2 needs to unbend were not enough, now the
Republicans have made Gore a punch line.
</P>
<P>
   Even Steve Forbes, a Republican presidential candidate not known
for flair, gets big laughs cracking wise about Gore's lack of
flair. ``Concerning Gore, I won't be giving him any advice today,''
Forbes deadpanned last week. ``He seems to be getting enough from
the White House.'' He then referred to the vice president's ``rigor
mortis.'' Both lines drew more cheers than anything Forbes said
about his new Social Security proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Nixon used to advise his proteges not to worry if they
were loved or despised. ``The worst sin in politics,'' he once
said, ``is being boring.''
</P>
<P>
   From money to the entire White House infrastructure to
on-the-job experience, Gore has more advantages than any candidate
for president today. Yet polls show that his support in the
primaries is less than enthusiastic, and that he would get
clobbered in a general election by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas or
Elizabeth Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Why? The vice president is boring. The American people, in
polls, say so. Leno and Letterman say so. Even his mentor, Clinton,
says so. Gore tried to turn his weakness into a strength, by making
self-deprecating jokes, but the boring schtick was boring.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's fate will depend on a question that is as yet
unanswerable. After the vertiginous, long-running Clinton sitcom,
will Americans want more presidential high jinks? Or will they want
a respite from it all? Will voters want a leader focusing intensely
on them, or will they just want to be left alone to play the stock
market? No one, after all, is more gratifyingly boring than Alan
Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Podesta, a Democratic strategist, said that after sampling
years with Clinton, voters may want calm. ``People go to amusement
parks and like roller coasters,'' he said. ``At the same time, they
appreciate the straight and narrow.''
</P>
<P>
   If America wants bland, Al Gore is the man. Many of the hottest
politicians these days are the coldest. The appropriately named
Gray Davis chastised reporters last year for wanting a candidate
``who could be a replacement for Jay Leno.'' Three months later,
Davis, a Democrat, was elected governor of California. Now he calls
himself Gore's ``charisma adviser.''
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, the determinedly dull governor of New York,
George Pataki, who invites critics to compare him with his
predecessor, Mario Cuomo, the compelling Democratic orator.
``There's a big difference between glitz and substance and rhetoric
and reality,'' Pataki said. ``If you look at my predecessor, there
was nobody who was better able to give a speech. But he was not as
able to change a government.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's friends still respond, perhaps reflexively, to queries
about the very vertical vice president with a query of their own:
``When were you last out with him? He's changed.'' They insist that
the dullness quotient is way overstated. They say Gore can be
surprisingly engaging, even robust, in small settings when the
cameras aren't around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why don't Al Gore's people understand?'' asked Mandy Grunwald,
a media consultant who is advising Hillary Rodham Clinton.
``Instead of bemoaning the fact that he's not Clinton, celebrate
it. People want the substance of the Clinton-Gore years without the
soap opera.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Gore's advisers are beginning to agree. ``Boring is good
because it means reliable,'' said Marla Romash, a Gore adviser who
for years has defended Gore's campaign skills. ``It means someone
who's going to get the job done. It means someone who's going to
stay focused.'' Gore's advisers argue that he has been so
overshadowed by the president that people have not had a chance to
get to know him.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, blandness comes in as many flavors as Ben &AMP; Jerry's.
In Gore's case, it means a candidate who is uninspiring and
sometimes awkward with voters (a telltale sign _ he doesn't know
quite what to do with a baby.) His lone rival, former Sen. Bill
Bradley, has some provocative ideas, but can be prone to deliver
them in a lifeless monotone. He almost seems to dislike
interruptions for applause.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the mix of fizz and bland policies is a winning
combination. One explanation for why Bush is the early favorite for
the Republican nomination may be that he knows how to charm voters.
(A recent Washington Post/ABC News Poll found 56 percent of voters
viewed Gore as somewhat or very boring; only 23 percent said that
of Bush.) But on policy matters, Bush has tried to sit on his lead
and appeal to the widest electorate possible by being
nonprovocative.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, despite Clinton's piquant reputation, some of his
best points came when he tried to make politics and ideology as
bland as possible, as when he pressed for school uniforms in the
1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``People used to say to me _ I'm not sure to my face _ that I
was kind of dull,'' said Michael Dukakis, the Democratic
presidential nominee in 1988 and three-term governor of
Massachusetts, who sympathizes with Gore. ``I would say, `You don't
get re-elected three times because you're dull.'''
</P>
<P>
   Noting the extraordinary oratorical skills of Presidents Reagan
and Clinton, he added, ``If you're going to judge the rest of us by
these two guys, then we'll all be in sad shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes blandness comes in cycles. In New York, voters picked
the peppery Ed Koch as mayor. Then they opted for David Dinkins
(bland) and then Rudolph Giuliani (highly spiced).
</P>
<P>
   Despite the rise of politicians like Pataki and Davis, there
still is some appetite for sizzle. In the contest for Minnesota
governor last year, the professional wrestler Jesse ``the Body''
Ventura defeated Hubert Humphrey III who, unlike his father, is
hardly a live wire.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over personality is important because voters often
look to politicians, specifically presidents, to inspire and to
lead. This is the television age, after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Straightforward is OK but boring is never in,'' said Patrick
Caddell, a pollster for President Jimmy Carter. ``We're talking
about the presidency. They don't want Bill Clinton back, this wild,
out-of-control thing. But to say if you're a wooden Indian that's
OK, that's overstating it.''
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview in Austin, Texas, Bush, who has the
raffish charm of Bill Clinton, declined to discuss Gore's political
skills. Yet he made the case for a president who connects with
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to know you care,'' he said. ``People want to know
you relate. People want to see you in action. That's really
important, particularly in early states where retail politics can
affect the outcome of the election. People know if you're
uncomfortable around them. People know if you don't like them.
People are smart.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Even if Gore buys the idea that bland is beautiful, he should
not expect it to carry him to the White House. Sen. Richard Lugar,
R-Ind., who was considered so bland that he was passed over for Dan
Quayle as George Bush's running mate in 1988, tried to turn his
seriousness into an asset in the 1996 presidential primaries.
</P>
<P>
   In one of his commercials, Lugar spoke earnestly as a photograph
of Clinton, Gore and Jim Belushi, in sunglasses and fedoras,
mugging as the Blues Brothers, flashed on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presidency is serious business,'' Lugar said, very
seriously. ``The president is not entertainment. The president is
commander in chief.''
</P>
<P>
   Voters, however, did not take Lugar seriously at all. He was
soon out of the race, saying he had no interest in ``competing
endlessly with no prospects.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1116EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4483 &Cx1f; var-z
