<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 11:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7177 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-BLAIR-REVIEW-     05-22 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-BLAIR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO ISN'T JUST AN AIR WAR; IT'S A BLAIR WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
 (DW)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ What was a British prime minister doing dressed down in
an open-neck shirt and short sleeves and sitting cross-legged and
shoeless in a refugee tent in Albania? And why was this leader of a
spent imperial power passing as much time this month in places like
Aachen, Bonn, Brussels, Bucharest, Chicago, Mons, Sofia, Skopje,
Tirana and Washington as in London?
</P>
<P>
   Through a combination of passion, stamina and focus, Prime
Minister Tony Blair has turned his look of concern into NATO's most
familiar face, and his sermonizing speech into the alliance's most
insistent voice, articulating in emotive language a moral
justification for the conflict over Kosovo and a demand for an
uncompromising solution to it.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, he is projecting a belligerent British view
across the English Channel onto a continent that Britain has long
treated warily, and across the Atlantic to a continent that it is
used to addressing more modestly.
</P>
<P>
   So far Blair's aggressiveness enjoys considerable support in
Britain, but it has provoked some strong opinions abroad. Most
notably, his lobbying last week for an augmented ground force that
would be prepared to enter Kosovo before any peace settlement
brought annoyed retorts from two allied leaders.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton told the prime minister during a 90-minute
trans-Atlantic phone call that Britain was fostering a dangerous
appearance of disunity between London and Washington, and Gerhard
Schroeder, the German chancellor, said flatly that Germany was
against the introduction of ground forces and would veto it in
NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder added a line that left no doubt who he thought was out
of line: he described the alliance's disagreement as ``this
specifically British debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Is Blair's combative campaign a case of the old British Lion
getting its lusty roar back? Or does it reflect a wholly new
British assertiveness, from a self-described young modernizer
interested now in remodeling Britain's global role in the
attention-getting way that he has been reshaping its politics at
home? Or is it a bit of both, the old noble beast turned out in
eye-catching trappings from New Labor stylists?
</P>
<P>
   To Kenneth Minogue, professor emeritus of government at the
London School of Economics, Blair's campaign represents ``a
remarkably high level of personal diplomacy for us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Diana syndrome,'' he continued, ``a policy made by
image, the image of miserable refugees, not one made in terms of
long years of development.'' He said the 46-year-old leader's
tactics had put the British into ``a position of having to put up
or shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And the problem is we can't put up, and we won't shut up,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   John Keegan, the military historian, said he thought Blair's
populist brand of politics was no way to fight a war. ``Master
politician that he is,'' he said, ``he has no experience of
conducting the diplomatic or military side of war. He is running
terrible risks. Polls show that he has a majority of public
support, but it is the support of tabloid readers. The
well-informed feel uninformed, are anxious and racked by doubt.
Those who cheer him on do so in the spirit of football
supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   But Anthony King, professor of government at the University of
Essex, sees Blair's current conduct as squarely in the British
tradition. ``Certainly Churchill during World War II made it a very
personal affair and went in for great personal symbolism,'' he
said. ``He was much given to posing with a tommy gun and a bowler
hat, he went to bomb sites, walked the decks of warships. I've no
idea whether Blair has that analogy in mind, but I think he's just
doing what comes naturally.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Blair trying to muscle his friend Bill Clinton, ``British
prime ministers have been in the business of trying to influence
American presidents for a large part of this century,'' King said.
``Churchill regarded wooing and winning over Franklin Roosevelt as
a prime mission of his life, Attlee was always busy with Truman,
and Thatcher made it her business to work on both Reagan and
Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair's repeated calls for total victory (``no compromise, no
fudge, no half-baked deals''), his reliance on graphic accounts of
refugee miseries and his description of the war as a ``just'' one
based on moral principles have resonances in British political
history for Vernon Bogdanor, professor of government at Oxford
University.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gladstone talked of Bulgarian horrors and Turkish atrocities
in the late 1870s, and it's in the British tradition of the liberal
left to believe that one intervenes to define certain values,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Its proven military capability and willingness to use it has
always given Britain international influence, and Blair has
exploited the current NATO mission to emphasize his desire to
repair relations with the continent after the years of
Conservative-sponsored estrangement. In Aachen, Germany, this
month, he said he insisted that Britain resolve ``once and for all
its ambivalence towards Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to end the uncertainty, the lack of confidence, the
Europhobia,'' he continued.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's present popularity at home remains the highest of any
prime minister in British history, and the Conservative opposition
is fractured and ineffectual. Debate on Britain's war policy filled
little more than half the seats in the House of Commons last
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the risk of sounding naive,'' said King, ``one thing to
bear in mind is that Blair is a creature of calculation, but also a
creature of instinct. His sense of outrage at what the Serbs are
doing is both profound and completely genuine. I don't think he's
grandstanding, and he's a proven risk taker, led to his convictions
by his gut and his passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the failure of his view to prevail may not pose that high a
risk for him. If NATO settles for less than its declared
objectives, Blair will not be the one faulted. Prompted by winks
and hints from 10 Downing St., British public opinion and the
British press have already laid the charge of going for an
indecisive conclusion at the door of Clinton, and that is where it
will continue to reside.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Marr, a columnist for The Observer, wrote last week that
Blair's role as the aggressive young war leader at first struck him
as ``a crazy gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added that even as NATO bombing mistakes mount and the
war's aims seem more remote, he found himself moving toward a
different conclusion. ``Every political instinct I have,'' Marr
wrote, ``tells me that Blair is going to emerge from this war with
Kosovo back in NATO hands and a position of European leadership no
British leader has enjoyed since 1945.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
