<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, May 23:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ Even with the Clinton
administration's decision to push for 50,000 NATO troops on
Kosovo's border, the alliance will still face a decision within the
few weeks about whether its wants to begin preparations for a
larger, more powerful force that could fight its way into Kosovo.
By Eric Schmitt and Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS (Undated) _ Military and Balkans experts say they
believe that ground troops are essential to resolving the conflict.
By Neil MacFarquhar.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Kukes, Albania) _ More than 300,000 refugees
have already trudged through Kukes on their way to more secure
shelter farther from the border with Yugoslavia. But about 100,000
remain here, and among them are a large number from Prizren, who
have stubbornly refused to be uprooted again. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-HUMAN-RIGHTS (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ Much of the time in
Belgrade, it feels as if nothing is happening in Kosovo. People
complain endlessly about the NATO bombing, but there is a large
hole in the conversation. Barely anyone mentions Kosovo, let alone
the horrors that are occurring there. Natasa Kandic is one rare
exception. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-WELFARE-REFORM (London) _ Through a two-pronged program
that aims both to put the unemployed back to work and to rein in
the country's $158.9 billion dollar-a-year welfare bill, Prime
Minister Tony Blair has pledged nothing less than an end to what he
calls the ``something-for-nothing welfare state.'' It sounds
reasonable, but it is a tall order. Aspects of the welfare reform
program have infuriated legislators on Labor's left wing and
interest groups representing the sick and disabled, who say that
some of the proposed cuts will take benefits away from some of the
neediest people. By Sarah Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   GLACIER-WAR (Siachen Glacier, in the Western Himalayas) _ For 15
blustery, shivering years, the Indian and Pakistani armies have
been fighting a war along the frigid peaks of the western Himalayas
_ in an area named for the Siachen Glacier and known as the
battleground on the roof of the world. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   JORDAN-ABDULLAH (Washington) _ Three months after he ascended
the throne, 37-year-old King Abdullah of Jordan came to Washington
for serious work and a bit of fun. On the weighty side, he paid the
kinds of visits expected of a head of state: to the White House and
Capitol Hill. On the business side, he was guest of honor at a
lunch at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. On the fun side, Abdullah
went to the movies. He chose ``The Matrix,'' a cyber-age action
film. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-NUKE (Washington) _ Inside Room H407, a tightly guarded
chamber of the Capitol, Rep. Christopher Cox, R-Calif., listened
last October as Donald Rumsfeld, a former Secretary of Defense,
talked about China's missiles. Then Cox asked a crucial question:
How had the Chinese managed to modernize their nuclear weapons
program? By Jeff Gerth and Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-POLITICS-ASSESS (Mexico City) _ The politicians gathered
at the conference of the governing Institutional Revolutionary
Party have voted to switch to a primary election system. But
Mexicans are not sure whether the party was truly embracing
democracy or simply freshening up democratic appearances, which
have been crucial throughout its 70-year domination of Mexican
politics. A news analysis. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-LABOR (Paris) _ French workers appear to be particularly
skilled in timing their strikes to cause the most irritation. Last
summer, just as France prepared to welcome tens of thousands of
foreign soccer fans here for the World Cup finals, Air France
pilots went on strike. This year, with warm weather announcing the
start of the tourist season, it is now the staff of
government-owned museums and historic chateaus that are out on
strike. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
<P>
   OLIVETTI (Rome) _ In seizing control of stumbling Telecom
Italia, Olivetti, the former typewriter manufacturer that has
become a powerful European phone company, has embarked on a risky
business gamble that will reshuffle the European phone landscape.
By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   LANDMARK-FARMSTEAD (Monroe County, Ill.) _ In the week of her
95th birthday, Emma Buck weeded her century-old rosebushes with a
120-year-old German sickle and fetched water in the well house. To
historians, Emma Buck's farm, which has never seen a tractor, is
``a remarkable survival of pioneer days in Illinois.'' The
farmstead that Miss Buck still tends, knees willing, with equal
parts frugality, conservatism and gumption, is a rare remnant of
America's rural agricultural heritage. By Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BUSH-AGENDA (Houston) _ The Texas legislative session is
entering its final full week, and the two centerpieces of Gov.
George W. Bush's legislative agenda, a major tax cut and additional
spending on education, are moving to the center of the debate.
Exactly how much money will go to tax cuts and how much to
education will be hammered out in the session's final days. And
that result will ride the legacy that Bush carries into next year's
presidential race. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   JOBS-BLACK-MEN (Undated) _ For nearly three decades, in good
times and in bad, young black men with little education and few
skills lost ground. Facing high unemployment, falling pay and
persistent discrimination, a depressingly large number never really
joined the work force or drifted out of it, getting by on handouts,
hustling or crime. But now the nation's job boom is drawing many of
these young men _ perhaps the most economically disadvantaged,
socially alienated group in America _ back into the economic
mainstream. By Sylvia Nasar with Kirsten B. Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   MORMON-MISSIONARIES (Provo, Utah) _ Since 1989, Mormon
missionaries have converted about 300,000 people annually. This
year, the church expects to have 60,000 missionaries at work in 163
nations, up from fewer than 30,000 men and women in 95 countries in
1986. No other North American church has built so large a
missionary force, nor one so focused on proselytism. By Gustav
Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPUS-ARRESTS (Washington) _ Drug arrests rose by 7 percent and
alcohol arrests by more than 3 percent on college campuses in 1997,
according to a survey being released on Monday by The Chronicle of
Higher Education, a national newspaper that covers education and
academic life.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   UNINSURED (Washington) _ Health insurance companies are
proposing new federal programs and tax breaks to subsidize
insurance for millions of people without coverage. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   SEATBELT-CRACKDOWN (Washington) _ Police agencies are planning
another highly publicized enforcement blitz to encourage people to
wear seat belts during the Memorial Day weekend, as safety experts
have concluded that the twice-yearly crackdowns are causing lasting
increases in the numbers of people who buckle up. By Matthew L.
Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ It's a mad, mad, mad, mad capital. By
Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN (New York) _ Pre-race jockeying in New York. By
Bob Herbert.
</P>
