<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-HARTLEY-AVALANCHE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AVALANCHE COACH HARTLEY COOL UNDER FIRE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When Jerry Jones hired Barry Switzer, the Cowboys owner
said the new coach's lack of NFL experience was not a problem. Any
of 500 coaches could take that talented team to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing could apply to the Colorado Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   When Marc Crawford, who led the team to the Stanley Cup in
1995-96, abruptly resigned after last season, Avalanche president
and general manager Pierre Lacroix turned to someone without any
NHL experience.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hartley, a 38-year-old native of Hawkesbury, Ontario, was a
successful minor-level coach when he was hired, but it's a long way
from the Hershey Bears of the American Hockey League to the
Avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Cowboys, the Avalanche was considered a cinch to
coach. Send Joe Sakic, Peter Forsberg, Adam Deadmarsh, Claude
Lemieux, Valeri Kamensky and Sandis Ozolinsh out for regular
shifts, and keep Patrick Roy in goal. Easy.
</P>
<P>
   It would appear so. The Avalanche is in the Western Conference
finals against the Stars, with Game 1 scheduled for 6:30 tonight at
Reunion Arena. Win four more games, and the team can take its
rookie coach to the Stanley Cup Finals.
</P>
<P>
   Only, it's not that easy.
</P>
<P>
   The coach gives the credit to his talented team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We trusted our players all year,'' he said. ``I have
absolutely no doubts about my players. They'll be ready.''
</P>
<P>
   But without a coach who learned when to push and when to pull
back, and who learned the right things to say and when to say them,
the Avalanche probably wouldn't be here today.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche got off to a rough start in the regular season,
winning just once in the first seven games.
</P>
<P>
   There was discontent in the locker room. The players grumbled
about Hartley's changing line combinations. They thought there was
a double standard for left winger Eric Lacroix, the son of the GM.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time when a young, rookie coach could have lost control
of his team.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he toned down his inflexible style. He held a team
meeting to let the players air their feelings about Lacroix, and
then engineered a trade.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly, he didn't panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just his patience,'' Sakic said. ``Obviously, we had
the tough start, but he had a lot of patience with us, and
everybody believed in the system and we just went with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartley showed patience when Roy trashed his office in Anaheim,
Calif., after being pulled from a game and not getting credit for
the victory. Hartley kept his cool, and earned more respect.
</P>
<P>
   The Avalanche improved, and had the third-best record in the
Western Conference in the regular season. They beat the San Jose
Sharks in the first round of the playoffs, but then had to play the
two-time defending Stanley Cup champion Detroit Red Wings.
</P>
<P>
   The teams were similar in talent, but the Red Wings appeared to
have a big edge behind the bench. Hartley was matched with Scotty
Bowman, the winningest coach in NHL history.
</P>
<P>
   Bowman not only knows how to win on the ice, he knows how to do
it away from the rink. He's a master at gamesmanship, and tries to
draw the other coach into verbal skirmishes to take pressure off
his players.
</P>
<P>
   It worked in the past against Crawford, but Hartley refused to
be drawn in. He remained calm, even when his team lost the first
two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the first two games, he stayed calm and relaxed, and so
were all the guys,'' Sakic said. ``Our one goal was just to try and
win one game and get some confidence, and that's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Hartley told his team to stop taking stupid penalties, and
instituted a neutral-zone trap. That, and some well-chosen words by
defenseman Aaron Miller, did the trick. The Avalanche won the next
four.
</P>
<P>
   The players make it look easy. The coach wouldn't have it any
other way.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
