<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7194 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEWSHOWS-REVIEW-NY     05-22 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NEWSHOWS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOW! A NEW SITCOM ABOUT FIVE SINGLES! 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(dw) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Help! Is there anyone at the television networks
interested in shows for viewers over 35? Is there a world beyond
20-something angst in which roommates in improbably fancy
apartments are obsessed with two quite boring issues, the boys
worried about commitment, the girls looking for Mr. Perfect? Do
viewers really crave more than one show with a happy gay roommate
(a trend since the success of ``Will and Grace,'' a series about a
woman and her gay roommate)?
</P>
<P>
   Are viewers eager to rush to the television this fall and turn
to new sitcoms involving a 34-year-old woman who falls for a
24-year-old room-service waiter or a rich woman who falls for her
super or a 14-year-old boy who is surrounded by his mom, aunt and
three sisters?
</P>
<P>
   Within the last few days in New York City the television
networks have shown snippets of prime-time shows to advertisers and
unveiled their fall schedules. For an outsider wandering in, the
message was unmistakable: Anyone over 35 should forget network
television (with some exceptions, including several new edgy shows
on Fox) and switch to old movies. Or beg HBO to rerun ``The
Sopranos,'' its hit drama about a Mafia don on Prozac, five nights
a week.
</P>
<P>
   What made the annual rite of spring so bleak was the degree of
cynicism and self-satisfaction among television executives and
writer-producers who proudly showed off their newest sitcoms and
seemed in denial over just how terrible they were.
</P>
<P>
   The faint scent of doom in the air _ that of the major networks
watching their audiences erode with the growth of the Internet and
cable _ failed to dampen the strange euphoria among executives at
the fancy parties following each screening.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more bizarre moments in the process of selling
prime-time programming was the odd juxtaposition of news and sitcom
stars. At the ABC event at the New Amsterdam Theater, the
Disney-owned home of ``The Lion King'' (Disney owns ABC), Barbara
Walters, Diane Sawyer and other news personalities were trotted out
and asked about the highlights of their careers. They could have
been the cast of the network's ``Two Guys, a Girl and a Pizza
Place.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly enjoying center stage, Donaldson intoned, ``I was
tear-gassed in the best places.'' He spoke about John Hinckley's
assassination attempt against President Reagan. ``I hoped he wasn't
shooting at me,'' he said with a shrug. The audience didn't know
whether to laugh or applaud in a Felliniesque moment that fused
journalism with show biz.
</P>
<P>
   No network executives or writer-directors quite matched those at
the WB Network, which prides itself as the only one set up to
appeal entirely to ``12- to 34-year-olds and that's it,'' according
to Jamie Kellner, the WB president. But because the network has
been successful with ``Seventh Heaven'' (which appeals to
families), ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' and ``Dawson's Creek,''
there was a heavy dose of preening. One network executive described
WB as ``hip, exciting, cool and fresh,'' adding: ``We know who we
are. We think we know what you need.''
</P>
<P>
   Another WB network executive actually told the crowd of
advertisers and executives of local affiliates to watch WB to find
out how to deal with their children. ``Look at it this way,'' he
said, ``For those of you who can't talk to your kids, at least you
can watch TV'' to find out how to do it.
</P>
<P>
   A writer, Joss Whedon, who created ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer,''
which chronicles the adventures of student vampires, was in dead
earnest when he said, ``Buffy is a symbol of empowerment around the
country and beyond.'' How was left unsaid. But Whedon said he
realized ``that there was another story that needed telling.''
</P>
<P>
   That story is ``Angel,'' a new show about a vampire with a
conscience who comes to Los Angeles. `` `Angel' is about
redemption,'' said David Greenwald, the show's executive producer,
using the most popular word in Hollywood among writers and
producers to give meaning to a work that is quite often
meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Also about redemption is yet another WB show, ``Popular,'' which
brings together a popular high school cheerleader (blonde, like all
her friends) and an unpopular girl (dark-haired, like all of her
friends) when their single parents become engaged. The show could
have been made by MGM in the 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   WB seems to be succeeding on this kind of fare. The other
networks are struggling. What was surprising about the sitcoms of
the other networks was not only the tepid quality of so many of
them, but their derivative nature. The success of ``Friends'' (see
above about 20-somethings obsessed with boring issues), has touched
off a tidal wave of other shows about more or less the same people.
</P>
<P>
   There's WB's ``D.C.,'' about five 22-year-olds in Washington
(``In this town no dream comes without a price''); there's ABC's
``Wasteland'' (six friends in the New York dating scene); there's
NBC's ``Cold Feet'' (three young couples) and there's WB's ``Jack &AMP;
Jill'' (``quirky and amusing look at six 20-somethings living in
New York'').
</P>
<P>
   Isn't there a world beyond fake 20-something angst?
</P>
<P>
   Help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1228EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 12:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4502 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-NEWSHOWS-REVIEW-NY     05-22 0932
