<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0082 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7202 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOAD-TRANSMITTER-LADN     05-22 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOAD-TRANSMITTER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOAD TRANSMITTERS TO AID PARK IN SCHEDULING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG BOTONIS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELES NATIONAL FOREST, Calif. _ After months of debate about
the closure of 3,000 acres of the Angeles National Forest because
of an endangered toad, U.S. Forest Service biologists have taken a
new step to better understand the creature's habits and habitat.
</P>
<P>
   Six southwestern arroyo toads were captured May 14 and fitted
with dime-size radio transmitters weighing about two grams each,
and 10 more toads will be fitted within the next several days.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best way we know of to study them,'' said Bill
Brown, a U.S. Forest Service biologist. ``The more we know about
the critters, the greater opportunity we have to make informed
opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   The transmitters will let biologists track the Little Rock Creek
Canyon toad population and gather data about the toads' habits,
including how far they roam from streams, which are breeding
grounds in spring and summer, and what time of the year they move
into the adjoining mountain terraces.
</P>
<P>
   Such information will let forest officials decide whether to
open parts of the closed area, which runs from Littlerock Reservoir
back into the San Gabriel Mountains almost to Angeles Crest
Highway. The closure has particularly angered off-road vehicle
enthusiasts, because it forced them out of a popular off-roading
area near the reservoir and closed two vehicle trails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we figure out their habits, we can then do seasonal
closures in the areas they inhabit,'' Brown said. ``If they move up
to the terraces in the winter then we know we can open the rest of
the area during that period.''
</P>
<P>
   The transmitter packs, which are strapped onto the two- to
three-inch long toads with a tiny belt, cost about $30 each.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists track them using hand-held receivers, hooked to
antennas like a rooftop television aerial. The receiver beeps when
it detects a transmitter: the closer the transmitter, the quicker
the beeps.
</P>
<P>
   The biologists return periodically to check where the toads are
living, carrying the receivers along Little Rock Creek but
otherwise leaving the toads alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to hike through all the inhabited areas, but just
tracking them,'' Brown said. ``The less we handle them the better.
Our job is to aid and protect the endangered species but we also
want the OHVers (off-highway vehicle users) to be able to use the
area.''
</P>
<P>
   The arroyo toad, Bufo microscaphus californicus, was declared
endangered in 1994. Experts say the toad is near extinction because
Southern California has dammed or paved nearly all the streams
where it lived, except for far upstream stretches like Little Rock
Creek in the San Gabriel Mountains or Piru Creek in Ventura County.
</P>
<P>
   Before getting the transmitters onto the toads, biologists tried
to locate the creatures by going out at night with a flashlight and
listening for toad calls.
</P>
<P>
   If a biologist heard a toad, he'd shine a flashlight in the
direction of the call. That makes the toad's eyes shine.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists will track the transmitter-wearing toads for at least
three years. They have to catch them every six weeks to replace the
batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Although the transmitters have been used in field studies
before, Brown says it is hard to know how they will affect the
toads wearing them. The tiny device was designed to allow the
creature as much freedom as possible, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing a thin antenna longer than the toad who wears it, the
device itself is covered in a pliable tubing that protects it from
water and from the sand into which the toad burrows.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things were designed to hold up in the toad's natural
environment,'' said district ranger Mike Wickman. ``They're a great
help in our studies.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
