<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 13:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7206 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORMON-MISSIONARIES-A     05-22 0985
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORMON-MISSIONARIES-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORMAN MISSIONARY ENGINE FUELED BY OPTIMISM OF THE YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Texas, Idaho, Wyo., Brazil, Ecuador, Nova Scota, The
Phillipines)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVO, Utah _ With its utilitarian appearance and youthful
population, the cluster of low-rise buildings in the shadow of the
Wasatch Mountains here resembles a small state college. But its
hallways are decorated with religious art, the campus bookstore
does a brisk business in language textbooks and white button-down
shirts, and the student body is turning over all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Every Wednesday, more than 200 young people arrive, bid goodbye
to their parents, and settle in for four to 11 weeks. They are
taught how to speak to a stranger about faith and salvation and to
do it in any of 47 languages ranging from Albanian to Vietnamese,
before they are dispatched for two years to locations far from
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Missionary Training Center of the Mormon church, an
efficient religious engine that has helped propel the Church of
Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints beyond its historic Rocky
Mountain base into a global faith, 10.4 million strong.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1989, Mormon missionaries have converted about 300,000
people annually. This year, the church expects to have 60,000
missionaries at work in 163 nations, up from fewer than 30,000 men
and women in 95 countries in 1986. No other North American church
has built so large a missionary force, nor one so focused on
proselytism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The single biggest factor in the Mormon Church's conversion
rate is the size of the missionary force,'' said Gary Shepherd, a
professor of sociology at Oakland University in Rochester, Mich.,
and the co-author of a book on Mormon missionary activity. Shepherd
estimated that, based on church records, a missionary converts an
average of four to seven people a year.
</P>
<P>
   As Mormons have increased their missionary ranks, larger shifts
have been taking place in the broader picture of missionary work.
The number of paid career missionaries sent out by mainline
Protestant churches in North America has declined since the late
1960s to fewer than 4,000, from more than 10,000, according to a
study by Robert T. Coote, assistant to the director at the Overseas
Ministries Study Center in New Haven, Conn. Many of those people
serve as teachers, medical workers or other specialists, as do many
of the 4,200 Roman Catholic missionaries from the United States who
work overseas, according to the U.S. Catholic Mission Association.
</P>
<P>
   But foreign mission activity remains highly competitive. Coote
found that the number of missionaries fielded by conservative,
evangelical churches had grown substantially since World War II. So
too have the number of short-term volunteers like the Mormons.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there has been an increase in the number of
missionaries sent by emerging churches outside the United States,
in such nations as India and Nigeria. Protestant churches in South
Korea have 5,000 missionaries working worldwide, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Here at the training center, the hallways are decorated with
photos of missionaries at work and reproductions of paintings like
one of Joseph Smith, Mormonism's first prophet, kneeling in a grove
of trees in Palmyra, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The male missionaries-in-training wear newly purchased white
button-downs, the customary dress. The women have more range in
terms of color, but must wear modest dresses with a hemline at
midcalf.
</P>
<P>
   In conversations, they speak with a friendly intensity. In the
center's cafeteria, Michael Nelson, 19, a Texan headed for Brazil,
said that while he was nervous about using his newly acquired
Portuguese, ``I'm not nervous about the faith; I know the Lord will
help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing her Spanish skills on a computer upstairs, Maryella
Wolford, 21, from Ogden, Utah, said that among the first things
missionaries discussed with serious inquirers into Mormon beliefs
was how to pray. ``We first tell them to address Heavenly Father,
and to give thanks for what they have, to ask for the things they
need and to close in the name of Jesus Christ,'' said Miss Wolford,
who will serve in Ecuador.
</P>
<P>
   Among those studying here, men outnumber women about 4-to-1, a
proportion similar to missionaries in the field. Elder Earl C.
Tingey, a member of the Presidency of the Seventy, one of the
highest levels of church leadership, said, ``We teach that every
young man should prepare himself to be worthy to be called as a
missionary.''
</P>
<P>
   The response, while proportionally high, seems to depend on the
historical depth of Mormon culture in an area. Tingey, who is also
executive director of the church's missionary department, said
about one of every two young Mormon men in Utah volunteered for
missionary work. In other parts of the United States, he said, it
is about one in three, while overseas, where a majority of the
church's membership now lives, it is close to one in six. Church
officials say the lower ratio outside the United States may stem
from financial factors; in some nations relatively few young men
have money to contribute to their mission.
</P>
<P>
   Men must be at least 19 to go on a mission; women must be 21.
They are asked to be financially self-sufficient, and either they
or their families must pay $375 a month into a church fund that
supports the missionary work. In a church that vests authority in
men, missionary service is regarded as purely optional for women.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the girls, it's a choice,'' said Eve Speer, 21, of
Tremonton, Utah, bound for mission work in Dallas. ``You do a lot
of prayer and a lot of talking to sister missionaries.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   After they arrive at the center, the missionaries are assigned
to a district, a group of eight to 12 young people who take classes
together and lend one another emotional support and religious
encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   Miss Speer's district was studying ``The Doctrine and
Covenants,'' divine revelations Smith said he received about the
church's structure and theology.
</P>
<P>
   Within her group was Lincoln Young, 25, bound for Halifax, Nova
Scotia, who had been converted eight years ago by missionaries who
went to his family's home in Guyana.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the image of Mormon missionaries as door-knockers,
conversions like Young's are not typical. Sitting in the center's
cafeteria, half a dozen young men said their teachers had told them
that cold calls on strangers' doors were the least effective way to
make converts. It works far better, they said, to have a church
member invite friends or relatives over to meet and talk to
missionaries.
</P>
<P>
   The men in the cafeteria were scheduled to leave soon for
Brazil, for a month of training at a newly opened center in Sao
Paulo, one of 16 smaller training centers that the church has
recently opened around the world.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials say Brazil and other parts of Latin America are
hot growth areas for Mormonism, in contrast to Europe, where
conversions come slowly. The situation has historical antecedents
in the 1830s and 1840s, when the Mormons, then based in the
Midwest, ran their first international missions to the industrial
cities of western England. Then and now, Mormon missionaries have
done best in growing urban areas (like Latin America's cities), to
which people have moved from rural settings, leaving behind
traditional social and religious ties, while still seeking
structure and community.
</P>
<P>
   Missionaries are advised to avoid the hostile and those who
simply want to engage in theological debate. A few missionaries
drop out, and when they do, it is often because of physical or
emotional problems, or family emergencies, Tingey said. He said he
did not know how many such cases occurred, but thought them to be a
small number.
</P>
<P>
   The eight young men who gathered for instruction in Tagalog, the
main Filipino language, were all upbeat. They listened and watched
as the instructor, Daniel Nabrotzky, 26, once a missionary in the
Philippines, ran a hand through his hair as he recited the verb for
comb, then touched his chin as he gave the word for shave.
</P>
<P>
   During a pause, Chad Schiess, 19, said he had grown up in
Victor, Idaho, near the Wyoming border, and had never been farther
away from home than northern Utah. He will soon be living in Quezon
City, a suburb of Metropolitan Manila.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to learn a language,'' he said. ``I'd never heard of
Tagalog until now, but it's pretty awesome.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
