<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0098 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7258 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANDMARK-FARMSTEAD-AR     05-22 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDMARK-FARMSTEAD-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RURAL ILLINOIS, A FARM THAT TIME FORGOT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By PATRICIA LEIGH BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROE COUNTY, Ill. _ In the week of her 95th birthday, Emma
Buck weeded her century-old rosebushes with a 120-year-old German
sickle and fetched water from a wood bucket in the well house _
cool, clean spring water bearing the slight taste of oak.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a skirt, always a skirt, and two coarse woolen coats
stitched together, she sharpened scythes on a foot-operated
grinding wheel, her life's patterns and surroundings little changed
from the 1840s, when her great-grandfather came from Germany to
this fertile land along the Mississippi River and, unaccustomed to
the midday heat, cradled wheat in the moonlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ja, well,'' Miss Buck, slight as a hummingbird, likes to say
in heavily accented English, leaning on canes or a tilling shovel
as she slowly walks around her family farm, past the blacksmith's
shop, the smokehouse, the butchering shed, the threshing barn and
the outdoor bake oven, thought to be the only surviving one in the
state. ``I've seen it all before. It's nothing new to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But to historians, Emma Buck's farm, which has never seen a
tractor, is ``a remarkable survival of pioneer days in Illinois,''
in the words of the Landmarks Preservation Council of Illinois,
which declared it one of the state's 10 most endangered sites last
year. The farmstead that Miss Buck _ who never married _ still
tends, knees willing, with equal parts frugality, conservatism and
gumption, is a rare remnant of America's rural agricultural
heritage.
</P>
<P>
   As farmland and buildings disappear, so do their mute
testimonies of the times, still vivid in Ms. Buck's sickle-sharp
memory, when horses threshed wheat around a stone pivot and soap
was made at home from suet, ashes and lye.
</P>
<P>
   Hers is one of those places where one can still encounter wood
butter churns, a horse-drawn surrey, a rope bed with a corn shuck
mattress, hobnail boots and hoops for a Conestoga wagon in the
rafters.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been little written on the ordinary lives of
ordinary farm people, who knew a world completely different than
our own,'' said Lowell Soike, a historian with the State Historical
Society of Iowa. He points out that the preservation movement has
largely focused on cities and towns, not rural landmarks. Family
farmsteads as intact as Emma Buck's ``are rare windows onto those
earlier lives and the way farms are changing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What the Buck farm represents to Annie Rieken, director of the
Heritage Foundation of Monroe County, ``is the history of what's
lost,'' Ms. Rieken said. ``She's the last of the last of the
last.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no official mechanism for historic preservation of
privately-owned farms, and the Buck farm's fate is unknown. Miss
Buck has lived alone on the farm, about 35 miles south of St.
Louis, since her sister Anna died seven years ago. Its future is in
the hands of Miss Buck's 93-year-old brother, Albert, who inherited
it as the only son. He now lives in a Chicago retirement home and
is ill.
</P>
<P>
   The farm is threatened by suburban sprawl, including a new
17-hole golf course that opened less than a mile away. The
population of Monroe County is expected to double in 20 years.
There were 804 farms in 1982; by 1997, the number had dropped to
556, according to census data.
</P>
<P>
   To spend some time with Miss Buck, who still lacks indoor
plumbing (though neighbors gave her a freezer and an electric stove
a few years ago), is to feel the evocative power of a place whose
doors have closed in on history.
</P>
<P>
   In the cellar, redware and salt-glazed crocks line the shelves,
as if waiting to be replenished with pickles and sauerkraut. In the
smokehouse, a heavy trough, to scald the fur off carcasses, still
hangs from a pulley, and the rafters are filled with copper kettles
for making sausages and apple butter.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was German business,'' she said. ``What would you do with
all these things? Throw them out?''
</P>
<P>
   The horse-drawn sleigh is there. So is the Civil War coat with
silver buttons, the one children wrapped around their feet to keep
warm. ``We didn't go away very much, except to church,'' she
recalled. ``If there was a heavy coat of snow, you just glided
along. We didn't follow the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Her maternal great-grandparents, Christian and Christina Henke,
farmers from East Friesland, came by boat from New Orleans and
settled on 80 acres in 1841. They were among the many Germans who
flocked to this corner of Illinois, where restaurants still serve
pickled beets and dumplings and the landscape is dotted with
European-style stone bridges and churches.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandparents built the log cabin that Miss Buck lives in.
Her grandmother described how German settlers, hearing there was
sickness aboard her immigrant ship from Germany, rowed into the
harbor and tossed oranges onto the deck. ``Life is like that
ship,'' Miss Buck said now. ``Sometimes it blows forward, sometimes
back. And just when you think all is lost, someone throws an orange
on your deck.''
</P>
<P>
   As was the custom among German immigrants in this area, Emma and
Anna Buck worked side-by-side with their father, Fred, an ingenious
toolmaker who died in 1963 after a long illness. (Her mother died
much earlier.) As a girl Emma walked three miles across the fields
to sell eggs at the general store, where double-wide trailers now
stand. An ``outdoors person,'' she often shot groundhogs with a
shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Amish, also of German origin, who shun modern
technology for religious reasons, the Buck family stuck to the old
ways, from horse-drawn harvesters to butter churns, out of
conservatism and stubborn resolve. Her father's token effort at
modernization was ``the light factory,'' as Miss Buck called it, an
acetylene plant that generated gas for lighting and tended to blow
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did it the way we wanted to _ Father's way _ that was
all,'' said Miss Buck. . ``I never wanted new things. If I had
them, they probably wouldn't serve me the way the old things did.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But she remains clear-eyed about the past, even the dismal job
of raking soot from the cast-iron stove with a corncob. Her
brother, Albert, in contrast, was a scholarly man who left the farm
to become a minister and who played the mandolin. Her girlhood
dreams reveal themselves more privately in scores of gentle,
colored-pencil drawings of bluebirds fishing in dewdrops, based on
1920s magazine advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   She says she never regretted not marrying or having children.
``I had what I wanted here,'' said Miss Buck, for whom
introspection is a luxury. ``We were never the patting kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven years ago, after reading about Annie Rieken's local
preservation efforts, she wrote her a letter. ``You are probably
surprised to get this little note,'' the letter read. ``My
great-grandfather came from Germany and settled here ... when John
Tyler was president. There are many antiques here that were used
then. Sincerely, Emma Buck.''
</P>
<P>
   As the farm's lone curator, Miss Buck does what she can,
weeding, pruning trees, fixing the split-rail fences with her
father's hand tools and, until recently, repairing roofs and
greasing the hubs of the old McCormick sidebinder. She tends to the
garden but doesn't farm herself, renting the fields to a neighbor.
Beneath her knee socks and bloomers, her left leg is still swollen
where she accidentally cut herself two years ago with the sickle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen old places where the doors flop open,'' she said of
the nearby farms going to seed. ``The places look deserted. I just
stayed here and did the work that had to be done. What else would I
do?''
</P>
<P>
   But with each season, more knots fall out of planks in the barn
and cellar shelves collapse from rot.
</P>
<P>
   Money must be raised ``to stabilize and restore the buildings,''
Ms. Rieken said, and she estimated the cost at about $300,000. A
more immediate concern, she said, is ``recording the stories Emma
has on the tip of her tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   Soike says some family farms have been saved when county
historical societies took them under their wing, with the owners'
or heirs' blessing. State and local preservationists would like to
avoid the now-common spectacle of antique dealers with bulging
wallets swooping in for the butter churns and blacksmithing
bellows.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things deserve to be preserved the way they are,'' said
Otto Faulbaum, a local lawyer and preservationist. ``Not everything
needs to be sanitized.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking for Buck, who was too ill to be interviewed, the Rev.
Robert L. Randall, a minister in Elmhurst, Ill., and trustee for
Albert Buck's estate, said that the Buck farm ``is not going to be
sold off to developers or realtors.''
</P>
<P>
   One idea is to turn it into a museum that would tell the story
of Emma Buck's family and the German farming heritage of the
region. Such ``living history farms,'' which now number over 500
across the country, are growing, as are antique farm-implement
shows and threshing bees.
</P>
<P>
   As farms are sold off or consolidated, nostalgia for the rural
past grows, whether for country landmarks or old-time equipment,
said John Walter, senior editor of Successful Farming Magazine,
which sponsors a barn preservation program with the National Trust
for Historic Preservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more financial stress among farmers,'' he said, ``the more
there seems to be a need to hold on to the things that have made
rural life what it's been.''
</P>
<P>
   For Miss Buck, though, holding on to the old ways is
increasingly difficult. Age can be unkind both to people and
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   She is reminded of this whenever her knees stiffen up in the
rain, or whenever she eats store-bought bread. ``It all tastes like
dough to me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In her outdoor bake oven, its bricks collapsed from weather and
time, she used to bake the dark, crusty bread according to her
great-grandmother's recipe. Its decrepit condition has sorely
tested her patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 100 years,'' she said, ``things just don't work
anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
