<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7260 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2TAKES-NY     05-22 0977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME RUNNING OUT FOR NATO TO PLAN A KOSOVO INVASION
</HEADLINE>
   (mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT and MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Even with the Clinton administration's
decision to push for 50,000 NATO troops on Kosovo's border, the
alliance will still face a choice within three weeks about whether
to begin preparations for a larger and more powerful force that
could fight its way into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The 50,000 troops that the United States wants NATO to send
would be used as peacekeepers in the event of a settlement with
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   They would include thousands of combat engineers, military
police and civil affairs troops that would be used to help rebuild
the shattered province of Kosovo and maintain order there.
</P>
<P>
   The troops would not have the armored punch of an invasion
force, which NATO officials said could number over 150,000 if the
initial contingent of peacekeepers and support troops are included.
</P>
<P>
   Marshaling such a potent force would be a mammoth undertaking,
which would include identifying the units that would be sent,
mobilizing reserves and shipping tons of armor and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the alliance has much to do and very little time to do
it if it wants to keep open the option of deploying an invasion
force to bring the war to an end before winter sets in. Further,
there is still intense opposition from Germany and some other NATO
members to using ground troops in a combat role.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the next two to three weeks, we need a political
breakthrough on a peace resolution,'' said a veteran NATO diplomat.
``If not, some tough choices on ground forces will have to be
made.''
</P>
<P>
   The urgency over making a decision on ground troops is being
driven now mainly by NATO's goal to return 850,000 refugees outside
the country and 580,000 displaced persons inside Kosovo to their
homes before subfreezing temperatures return to the Balkans in
October.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with a dozen senior diplomats and other top officials
at NATO headquarters here suggest that the facade of public
optimism among the allies is tempered by private fears. With each
passing day, they say, concern grows that public opinion, the
ability to hold the alliance together, and the dispersal of Kosovar
Albanian refugees are working against them.
</P>
<P>
   Even deploying the more modest 50,000-troop peacekeeping force
may not be easy. The alliance's political body, the North Atlantic
Council, will meet as early as Tuesday to consider the plan.
</P>
<P>
   But there are plenty of thorny issues. Allied ambassadors have
to identify which nations would contribute the troops and
equipment. Since combat engineers and military police are generally
in the military reserves, NATO nations would have to make the
politically difficult decision about whether to mobilize them.
</P>
<P>
   Further, some NATO nations may be nervous about authorizing the
deployment of ground troops _ even peacekeeping ones _ at a time
when diplomats are trying to explore a solution.
</P>
<P>
   NATO nations would have to make a separate decision to actually
send the force. Milosevic will be closely monitoring the alliance's
moves to see if NATO has the determination to end the war on its
terms.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gen. Wesley Clark, NATO's military commander, who pressed
the allies to deploy the 50,000-soldier peacekeeping force to the
borders of Kosovo as quickly as possible. He wanted the force to be
ready in case of a peace settlement, but also to place added
pressure on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington last week, Clark gave Defense Secretary William
Cohen and Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of
Staff, the same warning he has already delivered to NATO
ambassadors: Time is running to plan a ground campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration approved the proposal, seeking in
part to deflect the political pressure it has been under to declare
its hand on the use of combat troops.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve NATO's goal, Britain last week revived the idea of
sending combat troops but not until the Yugoslav troops had been
weakened by months more or air attacks. If the air war and
diplomacy fail to end the crisis soon, a ground war would be the
only way to guarantee the return of most of the refugees before
winter sets in, they say.
</P>
<P>
   But Germany, among other allies, vowed to block a land campaign,
calling it ``unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   The administration has been wary of suggestions involving ground
troops in a combat role, and American officials have tried to avoid
public discussion of the sensitive subject.
</P>
<P>
   Some allied officials have seized on reports of Yugoslav army
deserters and new signs of Yugoslavia's willingness to cut a peace
deal as indications that the air war is finally having an impact on
Milosevic. But many seasoned diplomats here concede that this may
be the wishful thinking of an alliance fighting its first war, and
learning on a steep curve at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a half-war, fought for half a result, and that's where
we're heading,'' said one senior NATO diplomat. ``Milosevic is
still sitting there.''
</P>
<P>
   The calendar isn't the only pressure on NATO diplomats and
generals. Deadly mistakes like the bombings of a hospital, a prison
and the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade are chipping away at public
support for the war in many countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be great care taken to avoid tragic errors that
would increase the sense of uneasiness and impossibility to
understand among our public opinion,'' Prime Minister Massimo
D'Alema of Italy said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of returning refugees to their homes are also
daunting. ``The longer the refugees are gone from their homes, and
the more they're spread out, the harder it will be to get them back
in,'' said one senior NATO diplomat. ``In the long run, Milosevic
may win.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Several diplomatic initiatives that could defuse the crisis are
lagging. President Clinton and NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana
expressed pessimism last week about a swift agreement on a U.N.
Security Council resolution that encompasses the allies' demands to
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of work has to be done both militarily and politically
in order to have that possibility of a debate,'' Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   But negotiators from the so-called G-8 countries met in Bonn,
Germany, last week in an effort to write a draft resolution that
would win the support of China and Russia, both of which hold
Security Council vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   The parties are still far apart on key issues like whether all
Yugoslav military and security forces would withdraw from Kosovo,
and the composition of an international peacekeeping force that
would escort the refugees home.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, talks between a Russian envoy, Viktor Chernomyrdin,
and Milosevic have yielded few concrete results, largely because
NATO has so far been unwilling to compromise on what amount to
terms of unconditional surrender.
</P>
<P>
   ``The weakness of all this is that Milosevic sits there with the
key to a diplomatic solution,'' said one senior NATO diplomat.
``And he has shown an unexpected capacity to absorb our attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   A special group of military analysts in Clark's headquarters and
in Washington are poring over reconnaissance photos and
handicapping the strength of the Yugoslav forces in Kosovo down to
individual battalions.
</P>
<P>
   This analysis, called battle damage assessment, is an art, not a
science. The intelligence experts must also incorporate Yugoslav
forces' skill at camouflaging their weaponry, dispersing into small
groups that are harder to identify, and, according to Western
accounts, using refugees as human shields.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement last week by Maj. Gen. Walter Jertz, a NATO
military spokesman, that allied bombing had destroyed 31 percent of
Yugoslavia's tanks, artillery and other heavy weaponry in Kosovo,
served two purposes.
</P>
<P>
   It sought to support NATO's claim that the air campaign is
having success against Milosevic's heavy forces in Kosovo. It also
set a benchmark to follow as the debate over ground forces
intensifies. Military theory holds that combat units lose their
ability to fight after suffering losses of 50 percent or more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, if you lose a third of your capability,
how effective are you?'' said one senior NATO official. ``From a
military perspective, as you watch the cumulative damage to their
forces, they obviously have to be losing effectiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   At what point that level is low enough for NATO forces to enter
Kosovo is a question diplomats and commanders here will likely
struggle with over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats say NATO commanders could declare Kosovo a
``permissive environment,'' in military terms, if the allied
bombing pounded Yugoslav forces to the point where they threatened
only scattered resistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sensitive issue,'' a senior diplomat said. ``But we
can't be here come winter. We don't want that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7265 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-NUKE-2TAKES-NYT     05-22 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-NUKE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEHIND THE SECRET INQUIRY INTO CHINA'S ESPIONAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JEFF GERTH and TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Inside Room H407, a tightly guarded chamber of the
Capitol, Rep. Christopher Cox, a R-Calif., listened last October as
Donald Rumsfeld, a former secretary of defense, talked about
China's missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Cox asked a crucial question: How had the Chinese managed to
modernize their nuclear weapons program? The special House
committee he led was investigating China's access to American
technology. It needed an answer.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was a secret, replied Rumsfeld, author of a highly
classified report on missile threats commissioned by Congress. The
committee could not be told. But Cox would not be denied. He went
to the CIA, asking for inside information on China's espionage. And
he got it.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, his committee will report that China has
systematically stolen design information on U.S. nuclear warheads
and missiles from the nation's weapons laboratories since the
1970s, said officials familiar with its conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was what Chris Cox stumbled onto as he started peeling
the onion layers back,'' said William Schneider Jr., a Rumsfeld
commission member, who witnessed the meeting in H407. ``The
chairman had his eyes opened.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., a Cox committee member, said the secret
files ``opened not only Chris' eyes, but all our eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Cox committee found over the next few months was that
relentless espionage, assiduous research and open exchanges with
American scientists had saved China incalculable time and money in
its drive to build a modern nuclear arsenal, said officials who
have been told the contents of the committee's report.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also learned of thefts of nuclear weapons
information in the mid-1990s _ yet another espionage case still
under investigation, whose details the report cannot publicly
disclose. The committee believes that Chinese spying continues at
the nation's weapons laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   And it concluded that China will field a new generation of
nuclear weapons in coming years, based at least in part on stolen
information, that could alter the balance of power in Asia,
especially regarding Taiwan, which China views as a breakaway
province.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee's members do not necessarily believe that the
United States is directly threatened by China's nuclear advances.
The U.S. nuclear arsenal overwhelmingly outmatches China's. And
while its espionage may have propelled a great leap toward modern
nuclear forces, China has not yet deployed a weapon based on the
stolen data.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it make them less dangerous? More dangerous? I don't
know,'' said Rep. Porter Goss, R-Fla., chairman of the House
Intelligence Committee and Cox committee member.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said the report ``ought not to chill relations'' between
Beijing and Washington, ``for the simple reason that the underlying
facts were known to both governments beforehand.'' But he said ``it
should provide the basis for a reassessment of U.S. policy'' toward
China.
</P>
<P>
   The report will give the nation the deepest look ever into a
realm of cloaks and daggers that lives on long after the Cold War.
It already has ignited a debate on the balance between science and
security at the national laboratories, not to mention spawning 10
more congressional investigations.
</P>
<P>
   Its publication, after a five-month struggle over its
declassification, will cap an unusual effort to pierce the shield
of secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox committee was created in late May 1998 by Newt Gingrich,
then the speaker of the House, who saw it as a political tool to
attack Clinton's commercial diplomacy with China, which he called
``a threat to the survival of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Given those beginnings, ``Democrats were suspicious because the
Republicans had made it clear there were going to be impeachable
offenses here,'' said Rep. Norm Dicks of Washington, the
committee's ranking Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee held together. It stayed away from explosive
but unproven charges that Chinese military and intelligence
officials tried to sway the 1996 elections for the Democrats by
buying access to politicians.
</P>
<P>
   While Congress fought furiously over impeachment, the four
Republicans and four Democrats under Cox achieved quiet consensus
and delivered a unanimous report.
</P>
<P>
   The committee began work in July with a seemingly narrow focus:
how American commercial satellite technology leaked to China under
export licenses approved by President Clinton and President Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider, a State Department official in the Reagan
administration, said: ``Cox was seen by the Democrats as a fair guy
who was undertaking a narrow investigation into satellite launches.
The committee had a fixed life of six months, and Congress would be
out of session over much of that time, so they would not be around
to do the heavy lifting of reading documents.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee's staff included some who had served on the
Rumsfeld commission, which had uncovered at least one crucial file
pointing to Chinese nuclear espionage. They went to work in a
windowless bunker with 36 cubicles, ``burn bags'' for classified
litter and alarm systems to ward off visitors.
</P>
<P>
   The heavy lifting began in October, after Cox gained access to
the secret intelligence files. Goss, chairman of the House
Intelligence Committee, said he told the CIA, where he once worked,
that ``Cox was an honorable man.'' He helped win the necessary
security clearances for the committee and its chairman.
</P>
<P>
   The access transformed the committee's investigation. From
security problems involving commercial satellites, the committee
was soon examining far more disturbing breaches involving nuclear
weapons designs stolen from government laboratories. ``The
committee started out going through a door, and we came into a
room, and there was more in that room than we thought there would
be,'' Goss said. ``We could have gone on for another six months.''
</P>
<P>
   The director of Central Intelligence, George J. Tenet, ``was
willing to give us access and to open the doors of the CIA,'' said
Weldon. ``That was a sea change, when George offered that
openness.''
</P>
<P>
   The committee was less successful on another front. Cox
repeatedly asked the Justice Department for information from
federal grand jury investigations of American companies' exports of
satellites, computers and machine tools to China. He was rebuffed.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But in late October, days before the 1998 elections, the
committee made its most important discovery.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1995, scientists at the Los Alamos nuclear laboratory
told Notra Trulock, then intelligence director at the Energy
Department, which oversees the national labs, of their fears that
China had achieved a remarkable breakthrough in its nuclear tests.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time that those fears were raised, the
intelligence files showed, a Chinese agent had handed over a secret
document to American officials. The document contained evidence
that China had stolen design data on American nuclear warheads and
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the CIA decided that the agent had been planted by the
Chinese intelligence service, to send a message whose meaning is
debated to this day. But the agency determined that the document he
had delivered contained at least a measure of truth _ that American
secrets had been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   This should have set off alarm bells at the national weapons
laboratories. But the alarms were broken, said Trulock, who became
the Cox committee's star witness in the fall of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   He secretly testified that he had tried to raise warnings about
espionage at the labs, but had been thwarted by his superiors at
the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   In late October, at a White House meeting, Bill Richardson, the
new energy secretary, pulled aside Sandy Berger, the national
security adviser, said a senior administration official. Richardson
said, in so many words: We're starting to get requests for
information from the Cox committee, and this China stuff is a
problem, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   The White House knew what the committee wanted to know. Clinton
had been told about the problems at the weapons laboratories, but
no earlier than July 1997 and possibly as late as February 1998,
according to the varied recollections of Berger.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats said they feared the information about the Chinese
espionage would leak and damage them politically on the eve of the
November 1998 elections.
</P>
<P>
   It did not. ``We had a sworn pact among the nine of us that we
would not divulge information, and for the first time in my career
in Congress, that worked,'' Weldon said.
</P>
<P>
   After the elections, as the storm of impeachment hearings
gathered over the Capitol, the committee's deadline loomed. The
committee would cease to exist when the newly elected Congress
convened in January. It wanted to complete its research by Dec. 1
and finish its report by Dec. 31.
</P>
<P>
   It considered subpoenaing Richardson and the Energy Department
for crucial documents, including some that sat on Richardson's desk
for a week before he read them, a senior administration official
said. Dicks prodded Richardson to produce the information. He
finally did, briefing the committee on Dec. 7.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 12 days, the nine members of the committee tried to
finish their report, which was approaching the length of a Russian
novel, while weighing the impeachment of the president. On the
16th, they took their last testimony from Trulock, a self-described
whistle-blower who, more than anyone, saw the security breaches at
the weapons laboratories as the gravest of threats. On the 19th,
the House impeached the president.
</P>
<P>
   The Cox committee report was completed on Dec. 30, after less
than six months of intense work. It would take nearly five months
more to declassify it.
</P>
<P>
   Without consulting the committee, the White House summarily
declassified the panel's 32 recommendations, including tightening
security at the labs, toughening export controls and sharing
intelligence information between government agencies. The White
House released the Cox recommendations, along with its own
responses, to selected reporters on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were hoping to spin the report,'' Weldon said.
</P>
<P>
   A few days later Cox and Dicks asked to meet with Clinton to
discuss their findings. The White House did not respond for weeks.
For more than a month, Clinton did not have much to say in public
about the report's findings; some had already appeared in The New
York Times, The Wall Street Journal and other publications.
</P>
<P>
   On March 19, at a press conference, Clinton assured the public
that ``there has been no espionage at the labs since I have been
president'' and ``no one has reported to me that they suspect such
a thing has occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout March and April, the White House and the committee
fought over how to declassify the report. Nearly a third of its
findings will remain secret at the behest of American intelligence
and law-enforcement agencies, Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   As the fight dragged on, the CIA, at the committee's
recommendation, pulled together an analysis of the impact of the
spying, reflecting the consensus of American intelligence
officials.
</P>
<P>
   On April 21, the CIA published its findings. It did not
highlight espionage as a critical element of China's effort to
improve its nuclear capabilities. It could not determine the
relative importance of espionage, openly available information and
home-grown Chinese know-how.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line,'' said a senior intelligence official, ``is
we don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did they know ``whether any weapon design documentation
or blueprints were stolen.'' The Cox committee said China may have
obtained such documents, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the CIA report agreed with the Cox committee's
central conclusion: Stolen American nuclear secrets had accelerated
the Chinese drive toward a modern arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   On April 22, the day after the CIA report was published, Cox and
Dicks got their meeting with the president and discussed the
findings of their report.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since, Clinton has not repeated his earlier statements that
he was unaware of suspicions of Chinese espionage on his watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
