<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-KLA _ KOSARE, Kosovo _ The hard-faced soldiers lining the
perimeter of this guerrilla army base stood at the ready, fingers
on the triggers of their AK-47 assault rifles, prepared to mow down
an attacking Serb force. But the immediate purpose of the Kovoso
Liberation Army troops was to serve as targets for us, a dozen
visiting foreign correspondents and cameramen, the first group of
its kind escorted by the KLA from Albania into the southern
highlands of Kosovo. The KLA wanted us to see their base at Kosare,
and talk to their soldiers, to demonstrate their existence in the
face of claims from Belgrade that the armed resistance movement has
been eliminated, along with the 800,000 refugees who have fled
Kosovo.The evidence was plain to see: The rebels exist.They also
bleed. The sudden artillery duel with Serb forces that left three
KLA soldiers seriously wounded wasn't necessarily what the KLA
wanted us to see. But it was all too genuine. The KLA has
discovered, as has NATO, that conquering Serb forces is not an easy
task. (Holmes, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   With information for locator map.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moved Thurs., May 20.
</P>
<P>
   SAELECTION _ South Africa, which many people predicted could
plunge into war before apartheid would end, has experienced a
degree of reconciliation that many people consider a miracle. But
as South Africans prepare to elect a new president to succeed
Nelson Mandela, they know that _ with unemployment and crime sky
high, the economy stagnant and education in desperate straits _
this country that is basking in the glow of one miracle is now
badly in need of a second. An overview of where the country stands
five years after the end of apartheid and a few weeks before its
second all-race elections. (Melvin, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   ROCKDALE-SCHOOL _ CONYERS, Ga. _ Heritage High School reopens
Saturday morning so kids can retrieve their stuff from their
lockers. Counselors on hand. Also, one of the victim is released
rom the hospital. We have her account of what happened and an
interview with her mom. (Scott/Stanford, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTO: Yes
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ROCKDALE-LEGAL _ CONYERS, Ga. _ Lawyer calls him ``really
charming young man . . . I am clueless why he did it. There's no
anger.'' Lawyer waives Monday hearing, will try to keep case in
juvenile but realizes the odds are heavily against him. Says
parents never gave the kid a gun, etc.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TEENS-BREAKINGUP _ Jay Bakker was enjoying a dinner this week at
an Atlanta restaurant when his beeper went off. The caller was a
teen upset about breaking up with her boyfriend. Bakker, a youth
minister, said he was thrilled he could help her talk through her
pain - which many adults may underestimate. The demise of a love
affair is particularly hard on teenagers, whose raging hormones can
make a breakup a prescription for depression or destruction. Such a
loss seems to have played a role in several recent school
shootings, including Heritage High. In fact, federal teen violence
stats say such rampages are preceded by a breakup more than 50
percent of the time. We talk to specialists and teens about the
intensity of such relationships and how to help kids cope. (Lore,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30-3.
</P>
<P>
   COLA-WAR _ MIAMI _ Coca-Cola may be America's most popular soft
drink, yet Orlando housewife America Vaughan(CQ both) is eager to
point out how her new soda, Havana Cola, is different. It has a
citric taste, she says, with the distinctive touch of Key lime. And
although Havana Cola's can is red _ like Coca-Cola's _ its shade is
a candy-apple one. ``It has a different taste, and I think a better
one,'' boasts Vaughan, a 48-year-old mother of four. ``I believe
once people try it they'll pull a switcheroo.'' If sheer exuberance
were an asset, Vaughan _ who's never run a business before _ would
already be a millionaire. But exuberance alone may not be enough.
(Emling, Cox News Service)
</P>
