<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: WHAT MAKES THE POLS RUN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By BOB HERBERT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the Rolling Stones famously warbled, you can't
always get what you want. So New York's top politicians are doing
the next best thing _ scrambling to take what they can get.
</P>
<P>
   Start with Rudolph Giuliani, the mayor with the totalitarian
inclinations. He'd like to be president but that's not happening.
His next choice probably would be governor but fellow Republican
George Pataki holds a lease on that office through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's third choice might be to stay on as mayor (he likes
to run things and torment people) but mischief-makers imposed term
limits a few years ago. So he's apparently piecing together a
campaign for a seat in the U.S. Senate, a job for which he is
wildly unsuited and which he is almost guaranteed to hate.
</P>
<P>
   (Imagine Rudolph Giuliani, just one of 100 senators, listening
to the likes of Phil Gramm or John D. Rockefeller IV, both with
greater seniority, droning on about agricultural production or some
problem related to the inland waterways. You could start a
countdown to the meltdown.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Pataki is pretty restless himself. He, too, would
like to be president but that's not happening. As he traveled the
country _ Illinois, Missouri, New Hampshire _ trying to gauge his
chances of capturing the Republican nomination, the question most
people asked was, ``Who's that?''
</P>
<P>
   He'd settle, of course, for the second spot on a national ticket
but that's looking unlikely as well. What to do? The governor plans
a big announcement Monday. The word is that he is going to endorse
George W. Bush, which is pretty anticlimactic given the big,
mysterious buildup orchestrated by the governor's office last week.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever happens, a safe bet is that Pataki and his good
buddy, former Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, will do all in their
considerable power to keep Giuliani from going to the Senate. When
Pataki, a D'Amato protege, first ran for governor, Giuliani was not
satisfied to simply endorse his Democratic opponent, Mario Cuomo.
The mayor went on to rub salt in the wound he inflicted on Pataki
by publicly declaring that ``if the D'Amato-Pataki crew ever get
control, ethics will be trashed.''
</P>
<P>
   Politicians know better than anyone that revenge is a dish best
served cold. D'Amato wept when he lost his seat in the Senate,
which he loved. Watching Giuliani set up shop on the Senate floor
won't make him feel any better. The D'Amato-Pataki crew is now,
five years later, doing its best to trash any advance by the
ambitious mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The man who wanted to go to the Senate as much as anyone was
Mark Green, now the city's public advocate. Green is
temperamentally well suited to be a senator and would give almost
anything for a crack at the seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick
Moynihan. But that's not happening. Green has fully absorbed the
lesson of the Rolling Stones, having already run twice for the
Senate and lost. So he plans to run for mayor in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The political scene in New York is starting to resemble a dinner
party at which the place cards have been shuffled and some
invitations withdrawn. The weirdest situation involves Rep. Nita
Lowey, a Westchester County Democrat who really, really wants to
run for Moynihan's seat. She's all set. Ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a small problem called Hillary Rodham Clinton. Mrs.
Clinton, whose last known addresses were in Illinois, Arkansas and
Washington, is thinking about running for the Senate from New York.
As a potential candidate, she is a tsunami to Nita Lowey's ripple.
Therefore, if Mrs. Clinton were to run, and it looks more and more
as if that will happen, Ms. Lowey would surrender her Senate
fantasies and run for another term in the House.
</P>
<P>
   The really weird part? Mrs. Clinton will be the big draw at a
gala fund-raiser for Ms. Lowey at the Grand Hyatt Hotel in
Manhattan on Monday night. Awards will be handed out for the most
convincing smiles.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Mrs. Clinton knows something. By all accounts she hadn't
taken a Senate run seriously until a few months ago. The whole
thing started as a lark, wishful thinking on the part of a few New
York Democrats. Maybe that's the key to coming out on top. Not
wanting it too badly.
</P>
</TEXT>
