<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: BILE IN BLOOM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For many years, the favorite rite of spring in
Washington was awaiting the mating of the pandas at the National
Zoo.
</P>
<P>
   The late Henry Mitchell of The Washington Post put it best:
</P>
<P>
   ``Spring is here. The sap is ris.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder how the pandas is?''
</P>
<P>
   There is only one panda left, so this spring the capital is
fascinated with the conjugal arrangements of a higher order.
</P>
<P>
   The town is abuzz with rumors that Elizabeth, who admitted that
her husband was in ``the family woodshed,'' locked Bob out of their
apartment after he gave The New York Times an interview belittling
her presidential chances.
</P>
<P>
   The town is febrile with speculation about whether Hillary, who
never lets her husband out of the woodshed, might drag Bill on
holiday to the Adirondacks _ to help her Senate chances, but also
to aggravate his allergy to trees.
</P>
<P>
   The sap is ris and so is tempers. Suddenly, everyone is mad at
everyone else. You really need a diagram, with arrows pointing, to
keep track of all the spats and snits.
</P>
<P>
   The Doles, who have spent decades promoting themselves as close
partners, are, for the moment, beyond the inspiration of Viagra.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar Lips is mad at Bob for his loose lips. As Dick Armey puts
it, ``He is going to be singing `Strangers in the Night' for a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Liddy's strategists are mad at Bob for knocking the campaign off
track just as it was getting on track and launching a big
fund-raising drive.
</P>
<P>
   Bob is mad at Liddy for being the center of attention. (Now
Liddy, who hates to be called Liddy, will be mad at me.)
</P>
<P>
   Bob's campaign aides from his '96 presidential run are mad that
people didn't realize sooner how hard they had it with Grumpy.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain is mad because now Bob will have to stop supporting
him and start supporting his own wife.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons and Gores, whose '92 campaign was like a yuppie
double date on a cross-country bus, are not so cozy now. That New
Age communitarian spirit has been replaced with old-fashioned
crankiness.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary is mad at Bill. Duh.
</P>
<P>
   Al is mad at Hillary and Bill. Al is ticked that Hillary is
steaming toward the Senate race. Not only would her star turn
overshadow his plodding quest for the White House, diverting
attention and donations. It also would inevitably dredge up those
Clinton skeletons. Al must have gotten even madder at word last
week from Hillary pals that the Senate run is merely a prelude to a
White House run in 2004 _ a feminist dream predicated on the
assumption that Al won't make it.
</P>
<P>
   Al is mad at Bill for not warning him before he called The
Times' Richard Berke to chew over Al's limitations.
</P>
<P>
   Bill is mad at Al back, because he feels Vice President Lame-o
should be grateful that he also told The Times so many nice things
that it was practically a paid ad. Bill feels he should be able to
speak his mind sometimes without filters.
</P>
<P>
   Bill is also mad at Al because there is one word Al never utters
on the campaign trail: Bill.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill is not mad at himself, of course. He never is.)
</P>
<P>
   Top Gore strategists are mad at Bill and at each other. Tony
Coelho, the new campaign chairman, is mad at Ron Klain, Gore's
chief of staff, for going along with Bill's call. Ron is mad at
Tony for publicly blaming him for going along with the call. Craig
Smith, the unwitting campaign manager, is mad at both those guys.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper is mad at Bill for continuing to make messes just as Al
is trying to shake off Bill's dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary is mad at Tipper for abruptly distancing herself, saying
she'd be a very different kind of first lady.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are mad at Trent for bungling the Senate guns fight
and letting Al become the hero of gun control with a tie-breaking
vote just hours after another school shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Bill is mad at Hillary and Al for being able to run in 2000, as
he contemplates his phantom legacy and the dread thought that he'd
have to give the Oval Office over to George Bush after getting it
from George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bill is mad at Hillary for planning a future in which she is the
center of attention.
</P>
<P>
   Bill is mad at Tony and Gerhard is mad at Tony _ oh, let's not
get into global bickering or we'll never get out of here. (BOX)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
