<HEADER>
A7276 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-BUSH-AGENDA-ART     05-22 0640
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-BUSH-AGENDA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH LEGACY RIDES ON TAX CUT AND SCHOOL FUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When he gave his opening address to the 76th session
of the Texas Legislature in January, Gov. George W. Bush, widely
touted as the Republican front-runner for president in 2000, told
the legislators that as a result, like it or not, the eyes of the
nation were on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can either view it as a distraction or seize it as an
opportunity to show the world what limited and constructive
government looks like,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, four months later, the legislative session is entering its
final full week with some of Bush's initiatives _ a crackdown on
social promotions in elementary schools, mandated parental
notification for almost all abortions by teen-agers _ not finalized
but expected to pass. At least one, a pilot program for school
vouchers, is apparently dead for this session.
</P>
<P>
   The two centerpieces of his legislative agenda, a major tax cut
and additional spending on education, are only now moving to the
center of the debate after a last-minute infusion of cash from
higher-than-expected state budget surplus estimates seems to have
brought both goals within reach.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how much will go to tax cuts and how much to education
will be hammered out in the session's final days, as will all the
ancillary issues still hanging in the wind. On the strength of that
result will ride the legacy that Bush carries into next year's
presidential race, as well as the clearest indication that voters
nationwide may have of his policy priorities and his vision of
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax cut is the centerpiece, the most important thing to
his presidential race,'' said Bruce Buchanan, a government
professor at the University of Texas who is an authority on
presidential politics. ``And it looks like he'll get it.''
</P>
<P>
   What is less clear is whether Bush's bipartisan image or his
stature as a leader will have been enhanced by an agenda that
opponents call timid and by a session that was, in the words of
Richard Murray, a government professor at the University of
Houston, ``one of the very boring sessions in modern Texas
history.''
</P>
<P>
   In Murray's view, the governor ``avoided major damage, but did
not enhance his image as a leader that has a sense of where he
wants to take the state or the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan attributed this in part to a lack of boldness in the
agenda put forward by Bush, who preferred to go for a small number
of achievable goals rather than risking political capital on
grander gambles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is not one to take impassioned stands on controversial
issues,'' Buchanan said. ``And he's very sensitive to the situation
that he's in, as the front-runner, so he's playing defense a little
more. He sets things up in such a way that he can't fail, pushing
for items for which a sizable constituency already exists.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's staff members shrug off criticism and insist that
when the final gavel falls on May 31, the session will be seen as a
success for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``Outside of, perhaps, a pilot program for school vouchers, the
governor looks like he is going to achieve just about everything he
wanted this session,'' said Karen Hughes, Bush's communications
director.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan maintained that if anything could be gleaned about
governor Bush's theory of government by studying this session, it
is that ``he has an almost Whiggish attitude regarding the
Legislature, by which I mean that he puts his ideas forward and
then lets the Legislature hash them out, almost a policy of
legislative deference.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In his state-of-the-state address in January, Bush told the
legislators how he wanted to divide up the state's budget surplus,
then estimated to be $5.6 billion. Some $2 billion of it, he said,
should go for property tax relief, with $600 million split among
small-business tax cuts, incentives for research and development
and targeted sales tax relief.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two weeks ago, there was doubt about whether the
governor would get his tax-cutting wishes. Fighting over how much
of the surplus to spend on education and how much to spend on tax
relief failed to produce a bill in either the Republican-controlled
Senate or the Democratic-controlled House that came close to the $2
billion in property tax cuts that Bush had outlined in January.
</P>
<P>
   But then, about a week ago, the state comptroller, Carole Keeton
Rylander, said that price increases in oil and gas, as well as
other factors, had flushed out $800 million more in surplus money _
enough to provide the tax relief that Bush wants and the
across-the-board teachers raises that the Democrats want. All over
Austin, champagne was put on ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the governor will get fairly close to what he asked
for,'' said Rep. Paul Sadler, a Democrat who shepherded the House
education bill, which called for a $3,000 pay increase for the
state's public school teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the $2 billion property tax cut that Bush seeks,
Sadler said: ``There's not anything magic about the number `2.'
Even if he comes out with $1.5 billion in cuts, he'll still be able
to say it's the biggest tax cut in Texas history.''
</P>
<P>
   After the comptroller had made public the new surplus estimate,
even the governor said it opened the way to ``meaningful tax
cuts,'' and did not mention the $2 billion figure.
</P>
<P>
   The state's teachers are happy that the comptroller's new budget
estimate appears to make possible the across-the-board raise rather
than one that was proposed in the state Senate, which would have
guaranteed $4,000 raises only to those teachers who earn the
minimum salary and left any other pay increases largely to the
discretion of school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would agree that it looks promising, but we are still very
vigilant,'' said Jay Levin, director of government relations for
the Texas State Teachers Association. ``We won't know until a few
minutes before the final gavel goes down as the legislators make up
their mind how they are going to distribute that money, whether
it's going to be into education or tax cuts or a combination of
both.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor had said when announcing the formation of his
presidential exploratory committee in February that he would do no
campaigning or traveling until the legislative session ended.
Democratic officials said that regardless, he was noticeably more
distant this session than in past ones.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Ms. Hughes, the Bush communications director, at
least where it counts. The governor may not have had as many
late-night meetings with legislators as he had in his previous two
sessions, she said, but he was available when needed.
</P>
<P>
   At least a couple of Democratic legislators agreed with her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not once failed to be there when I needed him,'' Sadler
said. ``He has either gotten right on the phone or responded within
a number of minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Sen. Rodney Ellis, the Houston Democrat whose hate-crimes
bill became the focus of partisan bickering and who accused
Republicans of killing it so that Bush would not be forced to take
a public position on it, said the governor had been more than
accessible during the session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always got a meeting or a call back from him, every time,''
Ellis said. ``Look, I'm as proud of a Republican governor from this
state being a national figure as I was when Democratic governors
became national figures in the past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1439EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
