<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0112 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7278 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-WELFARE-ART-1     05-22 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-WELFARE-ART-1070(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAIR'S COUNTERCULTURAL PLAN FOR WELFARE IN BRITAIN: GET WORK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ There were dozens of job opportunities listed at the
shiny new Palmers Green job center in the far north of the city,
but they were not of immediate concern to James Baxter, who has
been unemployed for several months and gets about 50 pounds a week,
or $80, in dole money.
</P>
<P>
   What was he doing there, then? ``I'm waiting to go see that
lady, sign a piece of paper and disappear,'' explained Baxter, 23.
``The primary reason I'm here is because they pay out benefits.
That's the main reason anyone comes to a job center.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but it is an attitude that Prime Minister Tony Blair
says he is determined to change. Through a two-pronged program that
aims both to put the unemployed back to work and to rein in the
country's $158.9 billion dollar-a-year welfare bill, Blair has
pledged nothing less than an end to what he calls the
``something-for-nothing welfare state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of an automatic right to benefit will go,'' Blair
said in February. ``If you can work, you should work.''
</P>
<P>
   It sounds reasonable, but it is a tall order. Aspects of the
welfare reform program have infuriated legislators on Labor's left
wing and interest groups representing the sick and disabled, who
say that some of the proposed cuts will take benefits away from
some of the neediest people.
</P>
<P>
   The welfare culture is so entrenched in Britain that some 30
million of its 59 million residents currently receive some kind of
state assistance, in the form of pensions, housing benefits,
disability benefits, unemployment benefits, child benefits and the
like. And to most people, such support is seen as a right, not a
privilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always been quite a profound difference in philosophy
between here and America when it comes to welfare,'' said Maeve
Sherlock, director of the National Council of One-Parent Families,
an interest group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here, if my husband walked out and I lost my job,'' she added,
``I wouldn't for one minute feel guilty about claiming benefits.
The danger of Tony Blair's rhetoric is that he seems to be saying
there is something intrinsically wrong with your going out and
getting your benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, many critics of the government's program argue
that it reflects what they say is Blair's Achilles' Heel: the
desire to be all things to all people, to appeal to the
conservative-leaning middle class that helped propel him into
office in 1997 while not abandoning the poor and working classes,
Labor's traditional base. The tough talk, they say, is one thing;
the reality may fall short of the promise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tony Blair is like someone who has inherited a bar from an
elderly widow who's spent nothing on it for years, and he's trying
to tell his mum that everything's going to be the same _ nothing's
going to change _ and at the same time he's trying to tell his
friends that everything's going to change,'' said Martin Evans, a
research fellow at the Center for Analysis of Public Exclusion at
the London School of Economics.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as the director of one poverty interest group put it, ``The
rhetoric is much worse than the action.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair's program, which freely borrows much of its stern
philosophical message from the United States, is re-examining many
segments of the welfare state. Conceived during the second World
War by economist William Beveridge as a way to provide Britons with
social security ``from the cradle to the grave,'' the system has
grown wildly, now representing about a third of the government's
total annual spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was designed to pay out stopgap insurance between periods
of unemployment,'' Alistair Darling, the British Social Security
secretary, said in a recent interview. ``It was designed to be
progressive, as a force for good and achievement. The reason we
have to reform the system is because it is no longer in tune with
modern needs and modern times.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the government has begun a program in which people
ages 18 to 24 who have been unemployed for at least six months face
losing their dole money unless they get a job or enter a training
program, although the jobless rate among the group is 13.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   It has also proposed legislation under which recipients of most
state benefits, including single mothers, the long-term unemployed
and the disabled, would be required to attend regular interviews
with job counselors or risk losing the payments.
</P>
<P>
   Blair has pledged to cut $1.6 billion a year from the nation's
welfare bill by eradicating waste and fraud, and to cut $1.2
billion a year from the disability benefits programs by tightening
up eligibility requirements and cutting benefits to higher-income
recipients. And he has made it clear that the old system, under
which people could sometimes receive benefits without even having
to provide proof of identification, is no longer acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was amazed to find that many people receive benefits for
years at a time without anyone returning to see if they are still
entitled to them,'' Blair said in February.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most notorious programs in the system, at least from
the government's point of view, is the incapacity, or disability,
benefits program, which pays up to $106.80 a week to people who,
through illness or accident, are physically unable to work.
</P>
<P>
   During the Thatcher years, when whole industries collapsed, many
people who lost their jobs found that their doctors were willing to
declare them incapable of working. This enabled them to sign up for
incapacity benefits _ which pay more than unemployment benefits _
and allowed the government to claim that fewer people were actually
unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Darling said, a quarter of men over the age of 60
are claiming the incapacity benefit. ``There was an acceptance that
people would write themselves off, or be written off,'' he said.
The general unemployment rate _ 6.2 percent _ remains artificially
low because of the strict definition of unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   But even as it cracks down on some benefits programs, the
government has poured money into others by, for instance,
increasing child benefits by nearly $4.80, to $23 a week for the
eldest child (subsequent children generate $15.35 a week). It has
also increased the state pension to $106.80 a week for single
people, and $170.70 for couples, and vowed to increase the amount
it spends on disabled and incapacitated people by $1.6 billion in
the next several years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Still, Labor's program has drawn fire from both the right and
the left.
</P>
<P>
   The most stringent cuts have outraged Labor politicians on the
party's left wing, as well as interest groups representing the poor
and disabled. Frank Field, who resigned as the government's
minister for Welfare Reform over policy and personality
disagreements last summer, has repeatedly accused Labor of backing
down on its promises and of abandoning the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I had hoped was that the government had moved away from
this kind of blanket, machine-gun attack, thinking that savings can
be made by firing at all claimants in the hope of catching some of
those who should not be claiming,'' Field said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a spokesman for the Tory Party said: ``It's
all talk and no action. In very broad terms, the government came
into office saying that they would cut welfare bills. But the bills
have gone up.''
</P>
<P>
   It is far too soon, of course, to assess the full impact of the
government's program, particularly because its centerpiece, the
Welfare Reform and Pensions Bill, has yet to be enacted by
Parliament. The bill passed the House of Commons by a vote of
360-142 this week, after a raucous debate in which 67 Labor members
defied Blair by voting against the amendment to cut the incapacity
benefits program. It now goes to the House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
   The program the government points to as being the most
successful is its $4.16 billion scheme to get young people back to
work. Under the program, Labor says, 61,380 young people have found
jobs lasting longer than six months, and 58,000 others have
received training and work experience. About 515,000 youths remain
without jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It is just this program that Baxter, who has been happily
picking up his dole checks for several months, will be forced to
enter if he does not find work soon. The $80 he collects each week
is about average here. Hoping to increase the incentive to work,
this year the government enacted a minimum wage for people 18 and
over _ $4.80 an hour for 18- to 20-year-olds, and $5.75 for people
21 and over.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, however, Baxter's prospects are better than most:
He is a recent college graduate who sees his unemployment benefit
as a stopgap measure between jobs, not a long-term way of life.
</P>
<P>
   But even he wonders how useful the New Deal program will be.
``It's supposed to be a shock, so it gets you hunting for a job,''
he said. ``But we have such an entrenched benefit culture here.
People don't want to be seen loafing around and not doing work. But
it's so easy to get benefits. And people expect that those who need
help will get it from the government.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
