<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, May 23, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A small, but intense disturbance will migrate into southern New
England on Sunday causing showers and thunderstorms from eastern
New York to southern Maine. The most concentrated area of showers
will be near New York City, where over an inch of rain may fall. A
weak cold front extending south from low pressure in the Poconos
will trigger a few thunderstorms Sunday afternoon near the Atlantic
Seaboard as far south as Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Very cool air will arrive in the northern Plains as a strong
jet-stream disturbance induces low pressure in Wisconsin.
Thunderstorms will develop in the upper Great Lakes and some may
contain damaging winds and hail. The leading edge of cooler, drier
air will push southeastward. More thunderstorms will erupt over
Missouri, Arkansas and the lower Ohio Valley. A few of these storms
may spawn tornadoes.
</P>
<P>
   Partly sunny skies and seasonably warm weather are likely in the
wedge between the New England and Midwest disturbances. A large
area of high pressure will stretch from the plains of southern
Canada to near Vancouver. A clockwise air flow will direct dry and
rather hot air into the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   A large but weak disturbance over the Southwest will keep a deep
layer of marine air in place over southern California. Ribbons of
moist air circulating around low pressure will promote a few
afternoon thundershowers in the southern Sierra. Winds ascending
the southern Rockies will produce clouds and thunderstorms.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Warm First Third
</P>
<P>
   Despite regular surges of very cool air into the Pacific states
this spring, the first third of 1999 still ranks in seventh place
as the warmest since records began in 1895. In fact, during the
first 120 days of this year, no part of the nation averaged well
below normal readings, while nearly 40 percent of the country did
average much above seasonal readings. There have been two centers
of warmth, the upper plains and the Southeast. Recently the mild
weather in the upper plains has been tempered by record rainfall
and its attendant cloud cover. The Southeast stays generally warm
and quite dry.
</P>
</TEXT>
