<SLUG> BC-JORDAN-ABDULLAH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN'S KING MAKES MOST OF HIS VISIT TO THE STATES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Call him the unorthodox royal.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after he ascended the throne, 37-year-old King
Abdullah of Jordan came to Washington for serious work and a bit of
fun.
</P>
<P>
   On the weighty side, he paid the kinds of visits expected of a
head of state: to the White House and Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   On the business side, he did something unusual for a king. He
was guest of honor at a lunch at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce and
asked chief executives to please invest in his needy country.
</P>
<P>
   On the fun side, Abdullah, a bearded ``Star Trek'' buff, went to
the movies. He chose ``The Matrix,'' a cyber-age action film.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to the movie was not so amusing, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pretty shocked,'' the king said, describing his regal
transition in a talk with scholars, diplomats and journalists at
the Center for Strategic and International Studies. ``I was so used
to just jump in a taxi and go to a movie theater. I had to go in a
six-car motorcade with sirens blaring. When I got out I felt like
putting a jacket over my head, I was so embarrassed.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdullah became king in February after the death of his father,
Hussein, one of the best-known foreign visitors to a succession of
American presidents.
</P>
<P>
   The new king came to introduce himself, to stress what he called
the ``continuity'' of his father's foreign policy and to emphasize
Jordan's need for economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats and Middle East experts here greeted him with
particular interest, not only out of respect for his father but
also because he represents the first in what is likely to be a new
guard of Arab leadership.
</P>
<P>
   In coming years, the aging leaders of Syria, Morocco and the
Palestinians will pass on, leaving Abdullah in the next decade or
so as probably the most experienced of a new generation of Arab
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever he spoke during his weeklong stay, Abdullah stressed
that for Jordan to play a role as mediator in the Middle East and
be a confident friend to Israel as well as Arab countries, its
stagnant economy had to improve.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, he is asking Western governments _ chiefly Japan,
France and Germany _ to forgive $3.5 billion of Jordan's
obligations, half the country's crushing debt burden. The United
States forgave $700 million in Jordanian debt last year.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the king said, Jordan is reforming its largely
state-run economy. ``We're streamlining the government, privatizing
the economy,'' he told the executives at the Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   As evidence of his intentions in pushing economic reform, he
pointed to his new prime minister, Abdel Rauf Rawabdeh, whom he
introduced to the business people by his nickname, ``the
Bulldozer.''
</P>
<P>
   He promised potential investors that if they came to Jordan they
would find a reduced bureaucracy and almost instant connections.
``We're doing the best we can so that anyone coming to Jordan meets
the right people right away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the third day of the king's visit, Ehud Barak was elected
prime minister of Israel, a victory that Abdullah made no secret of
welcoming. His father made peace with Israel in 1994, but the
decision remains deeply unpopular among Jordanians. The new king
has vowed to remain ``absolutely committed'' to the peace made by
his father.
</P>
<P>
   Trained at Sandhurst, the British military academy, Abdullah
commanded Jordan's special forces until his elevation to the
throne. He said he got along well with Barak, Israel's most
decorated general.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good working relationship with this government,'' he
said at the Strategic Studies forum. ``They are a government of
soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   But he warned that Palestinians may be unrealistic to hope for
better ties with Israel now that Benjamin Netanyahu is no longer
prime minister. ``The fear is obviously with such a high comes high
expectations,'' he said. ``If you have an increase in aspirations
and nothing happens in four to five months down the line, there
could be a worse backlash.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1455EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 14:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7283 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNINSURED-NYT &LR;      05-22 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNINSURED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURERS ASK GOVERNMENT TO EXTEND HEALTH PLANS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT PEAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Health insurance companies are proposing new
federal programs and tax breaks to subsidize insurance for millions
of people without coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry, which helped kill President Clinton's
plan to guarantee coverage for all Americans in 1994, said it had
become alarmed at the growing number of uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every American ought to be concerned that more than 43 million
people lack health insurance,'' said Leonard D. Schaeffer, chairman
of the Health Insurance Association of America, which mocked the
president's plan with its ``Harry and Louise'' commercials five
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton plan would have tightly regulated the operations,
and squeezed the profits, of health insurance companies. The
association's proposals, announced on Friday and intended to cover
up to 28 million of the uninsured, would amount to a huge new
federal subsidy to the industry. But Schaeffer said most of the
money would be passed on to doctors, hospitals and others who
provide health care.
</P>
<P>
   The insurers proposed expansion of the new Children's Health
Insurance Program to cover uninsured people of all ages under the
official poverty level (an annual income of $13,880 for a family of
three). States would have a large role in arranging this coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance companies also proposed a new government subsidy,
in the form of vouchers, for uninsured people between 100 percent
and 200 percent of the poverty level. The vouchers, about $2,000 a
year for each person, could be used to buy private health insurance
of the type sold by members of the association.
</P>
<P>
   The industry also said the federal government should subsidize
existing state insurance pools, for people in poor health who
cannot get insurance in the private market.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the insurers asked Congress to create new tax
deductions and tax credits to help small employers, self-employed
people and uninsured individuals buy coverage. Congress is
considering such tax breaks.
</P>
<P>
   The association said these initiatives, taken together, could
cost as much as $60 billion a year. But, it added, Congress could
start with parts of the plan costing much less.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Feder, a health policy expert who worked in the Clinton
administration from 1993 to 1995 and is now dean of policy studies
at Georgetown University, said: ``I commend the insurance industry
for supporting the expansion of public health insurance programs
for low-income people. At present, there's no medical safety net
for millions of childless adults with low incomes. But it makes me
nervous to depend on an undependable private insurance market for
people above the poverty level.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Congress and Clinton have focused on ways to
assist people who already have health insurance, by defining the
rights of patients in health maintenance organizations and by
expanding Medicare to cover prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles N. Kahn III, president of the Health Insurance
Association of America, said it was more urgent to provide at least
basic coverage to people who did not have it.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress uses some of the federal budget surplus for health
care, Kahn said, it should ``spend the surplus first on basic
health coverage for all Americans before it's spent on prescription
drugs for seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to dismiss the association's proposals as
self-interested. But the proposals reflect the anxiety of many
business, labor and consumer groups over the erosion of health
insurance coverage in the United States. The erosion is remarkable
because it coincides with an economic boom in which the
unemployment rate is at the lowest level in 29 years.
</P>
<P>
   Health insurance executives say they fear that if the erosion of
private insurance coverage continues, people will demand new
government programs to guarantee health benefits. Such programs
could marginalize private insurance companies or force them to
operate like a heavily regulated public utility.
</P>
<P>
   Kahn said he saw no inconsistency between the industry's
positions in 1993-94 and in 1999. Back then, he said, the
association supported Clinton's goal of universal health insurance
coverage and even the means to that end favored by the president, a
mandate for all employers to subsidize coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our problem with Clinton care was the overall superstructure,
the bureaucratic and regulatory apparatus, not universal coverage
or the employer mandate,'' Kahn said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
