<HEADER>
A7287 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-NOTES-NYT &LR;      05-22 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL NOTES: FLORIDA SENATE RACE; HAYDEN ON KOSOVO; THIRD-PARTY
MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Calif., N.H.)   (bl)  
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florida Democrats Feeling a Thorn  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Sen. Connie Mack of Florida announced that he would
not seek re-election this fall, the political scene in the Sunshine
State has resembled a free-for-all. No fewer than 12 people have
expressed interest in replacing Mack, a two-term Republican,
proving yet again that an open seat in politics is like honey to
the bee.
</P>
<P>
   For a brief moment last week it seemed the situation might be
clearing up a bit on the Democratic side, when Rep. Robert Wexler
withdrew as a possible contender. Coming on the heels of an earlier
pullout by Rep. Peter Deutsch, Wexler's withdrawal pretty well
guaranteed that state Insurance Commissioner Bill Nelson would
become the Democratic nominee, given the weakness of the rest of
the party's hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden narrowing of the Democratic field greatly relieved
party leaders. They had been concerned that a crowded, divisive
Democratic primary might leave the eventual winner too broke and
beaten up to take on the winner of the Republican primary, expected
to be either state Education Commissioner Tom Gallagher or Rep.
Bill McCollum.
</P>
<P>
   But with Nelson seemingly assured a peaceful nomination, the
Democratic leaders figured to slow the Republican juggernaut that
has been rolling through Florida for the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Enter state Rep. Willie Logan of Opa-Locka. Again.
</P>
<P>
   Logan is a Democrat by registration. But in practice he is a
political free agent, going back to that time almost two years ago
when white legislators connived to keep him from becoming the first
black speaker of the Florida House.
</P>
<P>
   Logan got his revenge in the 1998 gubernatorial race, siding
with Republican candidate Jeb Bush and helping him win by urging
black voters, a significant part of the Democratic base, to either
vote Republican or stay home.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Logan had an announcement. He said he was
exploring the possibility of jumping in.
</P>
<P>
   As a Democrat, Republican or independent?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Democrat, but more importantly, I'm a Floridian,'' Logan
replied enigmatically.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, his chances of winning would be slim to nil. In
fact, running as a Democrat or a Republican, he probably would not
even get past the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Should he run as an independent, he would face no primary, yet
would still have almost no chance of winning. But in losing he
likely would siphon off a big chunk of the state's black vote, a
vote that any victorious Florida Democrat needs _ and a vote that
Logan boldly pilfered once before with notable success.
</P>
<P>
   For Tom Hayden, Almost Old Times  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He's back!
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hayden, one of the leaders of the anti-war movement in the
Vietnam era _ he organized some of the most disruptive
demonstrations and made a pilgrimage to Hanoi _ has begun writing
and speaking out against U.S. involvement in the war in the
Balkans. The way he sees it, another Vietnam quagmire is in the
making, and President Clinton and the nation are once again mired
``knee-deep in the Big Muddy.''
</P>
<P>
   But this time around, Hayden is not out in the streets,
bellowing distrust of the Establishment. Today he is part of the
Establishment, a 59-year-old graying California state senator from
the very wealthy west side of Los Angeles. His worries now are
mostly about things like schools and roads and whether he can
capture a seat in the state Assembly next year when the state's
term-limits law forces him out of the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there smolders in him some of the old liberal,
Democratic, anti-war fervor. And so the other day when he could
stand no longer to watch the wrenching television images coming at
him from the Balkans, he fired off an ``open letter'' to the White
House that had some of that old fervor, telling the president:
</P>
<P>
   ``When I watch the bombs over Serbia, I smell the stench of
hypocrisy. Why the Kosovars and not the Mayans or Rwandans? It can
only be a geopolitical abstraction like restoring U.S. dominance of
a new NATO. As you recall from Vietnam, Americans deeply resent
credibility gaps and official lies. Don't allow the Balkans to
become a Vietnam.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days later, he told Los Angeles Times political columnist
George Skelton: ``I feel from my past that if we don't stop this
now, it's going to take us over.''
</P>
<P>
   Most recently in The Nation magazine, he wrote that the damage
caused by the bombing in the Balkans threatened to become
``collateral damage'' for the Democratic Party's hopes in Election
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Does he plan to take to the streets again?
</P>
<P>
   No, he says. But he acknowledges keeping in touch by computer
and telephone with some fellow agitators from the old anti-war
days.
</P>
<P>
   Is Someone Calling for a Third Party?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Of all the candidates, announced and unannounced, in next year's
presidential race, the most improbable is probably Sen. Robert
Smith, a granite-hard Republican conservative from New Hampshire.
He has little money, little organization and almost no standing in
the polls, even in his home state, which, of course, holds the
first primary.
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent poll of Republicans in Iowa, which holds the
first caucuses, he did not register at all. Zero. Zip. Zilch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Smith plods on toward Election 2000, holding high the
banner of hard-right conservatism _ no surrender on keeping gun
rights, banning abortion, legalizing school prayer, strengthening
national defense and cutting taxes. Somebody has to do it, he says,
because other Republicans are caving in all around.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he began warning last week, if party leaders do not
stiffen and stop the backsliding, there is a danger that hard-core
conservatives would rebel and form a third party.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more people talking about it than you think,''
Smith told The Washington Times on Monday. ``I'm worried for the
sake of my party. If you take the pro-life, pro-gun and Christian
conservative people out of the Republican Party, well, you don't
have a Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, campaigning in New Hampshire, he told reporters he
was not advocating formation of a third party. But he refused to
rule out joining one should it be formed, nor would he rule out
leading it if chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't a third party formed by breakaway Republicans assure
election of another Democratic president?
</P>
<P>
   A third party led by the right candidate, he replied, would be a
formidable competitor in its own right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1501EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
