<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIVETTI-NYT &LR;      05-22 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVETTI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVETTI TAKES GAMBLE IN SEIZING TELECOM ITALIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany, Italy)  (mk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ In seizing control of stumbling Telecom Italia, Olivetti,
the former typewriter manufacturer that has become a powerful
European phone company, has embarked on a risky business gamble
that will reshuffle the European phone landscape.
</P>
<P>
   The deal attempts to restore direction and purpose to Telecom
Italia, Europe's fourth-largest phone company, which has gone
through three management shifts in the last two years, and now
faces a fourth. Olivetti, for its part, emerged only three years
ago from a major management reshuffling and redesigning of its
businesses, shedding interests in computers and office machinery in
favor of more profitable phone services.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Olivetti's management appears well aware that its
victory raises as many fresh challenges as it has resolved. Last
week, investors tendered Olivetti 51.02 percent of Telecom Italia
shares in the bid, which expired Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now comes the good part,'' Olivetti's chief executive, Roberto
Colaninno, the architect of the takeover, told associates.
</P>
<P>
   The 51 percent result, which will cost Olivetti almost $33
billion, will be financed in part by issuing bonds worth $7.9
billion, meaning that the debt burden ultimately falling on Telecom
Italia will be lighter than if Olivetti had won a higher stake. Yet
at the same time, the slim result means uncertain control. That
could become even more fragile if, as Olivetti plans, it dilutes
its share further by proceeding with a merger of Telecom Italia and
Tecnost, the Olivetti unit that is the financial vehicle for the
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Telecom Italia has had little luck in breaking
out of international isolation. Efforts to forge alliances with
Britain's Cable &AMP; Wireless and with AT&AMP;T in the United States
failed.
</P>
<P>
   Franco Bernabe, Telecom Italia's present chief executive, had
sought to deflect the Olivetti bid by arranging a merger with the
German phone giant, Deutsche Telekom, but an adviser to Colaninno
said Saturday that it was ``pretty unlikely'' that deal would now
proceed.
</P>
<P>
   The most far-reaching consequence of Olivetti's win may be the
agreement by Olivetti to cede its present telephone activities to
Mannesmann AG of Germany, its present phone partner, after the
Telecom Italia takeover becomes effective. Mannesmann, once best
known for steel pipes and heavy machinery, will pay $8 billion for
Olivetti's Italian phone businesses, thereby pushing forward its
strategy across Europe of lining up with the challengers to the old
national phone companies rather than with the less nimble former
national monopolies themselves. On Saturday, Mannesmann said it
will offer an option to Bell Atlantic, another partner, to acquire
an additional 2 percent of the Italian operation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1504EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7291 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POSTAL-RATES-NYT &LR;      05-22 0182
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POSTAL-RATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL RATES FOR PARCEL POST RISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The U.S. Postal Service is raising rates for international
parcel post and for letters and cards to Canada and Mexico,
effective May 30.
</P>
<P>
   The sharpest rises come for parcel post, with the rate for a
two-pound surface parcel to Canada, for example, up 68 percent, to
$11.33. For a 2-pound surface parcel going outside North America,
the increase is 74 percent, to $15.70. But the increases are much
less for larger packages, and for Canada the surface rates for
parcels over 9 pounds actually decline.
</P>
<P>
   Air mail parcel post rates are also rising, with a 2-pound
package to Western Europe now costing $13.71, up 39 percent. Here
too, the increases are less for larger parcels.
</P>
<P>
   The basic rate for a half-ounce letter to Canada rises to 48
cents, from 46 cents, and a 1-ounce letter rises to 55 cents, from
52 cents.
</P>
<P>
   All international postcard rates rise 5 cents. The new rate to
Canada is 45 cents, to Mexico 40 cents and to all other countries
55 cents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
