<HEADER>
A7292 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-COLUMBINE-GRADUA     05-22 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-COLUMBINE-GRADUATION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SADNESS AND TRIUMPH UNDERLIE COLUMBINE'S POMP AND CIRCUMSTANCE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ As Columbine High School seniors and their
relatives gathered in an open-air amphitheater for graduation
exercises Saturday morning, four seniors were missing from the 440
faces that appeared smiling only days ago in the pages of the new
class yearbook.
</P>
<P>
   Lauren Townsend, a straight-A student and captain of the girls'
varsity volleyball team, was to have been a valedictorian Saturday,
standing before her classmates spread over the green lawn of
Fiddler's Green Amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   But Miss Townsend, who wanted to be a wildlife biologist, was
one of two seniors killed in the shooting that left 15 people dead
and 23 wounded at the school on April 20. Sunday, her older sister
and two older brothers, all Columbine graduates, went to the
ceremony to receive her diploma.
</P>
<P>
   Isaiah Shoels, who impatiently charted the dwindling days to
graduation by crossing dates off a calendar, also was killed. His
parents, who have already received his diploma, said they could not
bear to attend Saturday's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Graduation day ``is going to be a very bad and sad day for me
and my family,'' Michael Shoels, Isaiah's father, said in an
interview Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The other two missing faces from the senior class Saturday were
Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold, who committed suicide in the
school's library after carrying out the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Their faces smile from the pages of the yearbook, which went to
press two months before the shooting. But Harris and Klebold were
left out of two memorial supplements, one for the yearbook and one
for the year-end issue of the school newspaper, The Courier. Their
names were not to be read at Saturday's ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Another missing face was that of William David Sanders, a
business teacher and coach, who was shot after directing dozens of
students to safety. A familiar presence at Columbine graduations,
Sanders joined the staff 25 years ago, a year after the school
opened.
</P>
<P>
   Three seniors who were injured in the shooting were to receive
their diplomas. Jeanna Park, Lisa Kreutz and Valeen Schnurr were
shot as they huddled under a table in the school library.
</P>
<P>
   The theme of Saturday's ceremony was triumph over adversity. On
a day devoted to students, Frank DeAngelis was one of two adults
scheduled to speak.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, at a memorial ceremony attended by President
Clinton that took on the air of a pep rally, DeAngelis, the
principal, said to the cheers of students: ``I look forward to the
day when we once again walk down the halls of Columbine High
School, holding our heads high. We want our school back.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton offered words of encouragement to the students, who for
the last three weeks have attended classes at Chatfield High
School, their longtime rival in athletics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two days from now you are going to have your commencement,''
the president said. ``It will be bittersweet. It will certainly be
different for those of you who are graduating than you thought it
was going to be when you were freshmen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But, as I understand it, there will be some compensations,''
he continued. ``Even your archrivals at Chatfield will be cheering
you on. When you hear those people cheer for you, I want you to
hear the voice of America, because America will be cheering on.''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton joined her husband on Thursday in
congratulating the graduates and the entire student body.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened here at Columbine a month ago has had an impact
unlike any that I have ever seen or felt, _ it has pierced the
heart of America,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``But I hope you know that
the way you've conducted yourselves, and your story, and the
stories of those killed and injured have been an inspiration and a
motivation for many people whom you'll never meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're inspired by the strength of the students and the
teachers, by your determination to return to school to finish out
your year with your friends and your classmates,'' she added.
``We're inspired by your refusal to let violence and hatred win.''
</P>
<P>
   Heather Dinkel, the Columbine student body president, sounded
the same theme in a letter published Friday in USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we take those last steps of high school across the stage,
we will not be alone,'' Miss Dinkel, a senior, wrote. ``Everyone
who has sent us a letter or card, left flowers or wept by
themselves for the loss of precious lives, will be with us.''
</P>
<P>
   At other graduation ceremonies across the greater Denver area
Saturday, seniors pinned to their clothes or to their black gowns
ribbons of blue and silver, the colors of Columbine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
