<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-ASSES     05-22 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: MEXICAN PARTY FLIRTS WITH DEMOCRATIC WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Long before governing party politicians were
finished casting ballots last week on how to change the way their
presidential nominee is chosen, party leaders were busy handing out
advance copies of a speech thanking them for selecting the method
preferred by President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians were selecting among four new ways of choosing
the nominee, including Zedillo's proposal to use a primary
election, which the party calls ``direct consultation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentlemen, thank you very much for your vote in
favor of direct consultation,'' the speech began. ``This is the
option that will democratize the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that is indeed the case, however, has fast become a
national riddle, and Mexicans are obsessed with it.
</P>
<P>
   The politicians gathered at the conference of the governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI, voted as
Zedillo wanted. And the incident was one of several last week that
left Mexicans uncertain whether the party was truly embracing
democracy or simply freshening up democratic appearances, which
have been crucial throughout its 70-year domination of Mexican
politics.
</P>
<P>
   In a long, unbroken tradition, Mexican presidents from the
governing party have chosen their own successors, and the party has
never lost a presidential vote.
</P>
<P>
   A new book, ``The Inheritance,'' which describes in play-by-play
detail how the last five Mexican presidents named their successors,
is a huge best seller; it has sold 115,000 copies in the month
since its publication. In it, its author, political scientist Jorge
Castaneda, offers numerous examples of how democratic appearances
have masked authoritarian traditions within the party.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, for example, President Gustavo Diaz Ordaz had decided
to name Interior Minister Luis Echeverria Alvarez as the candidate,
Castaneda says. But then in a meeting with nine top party leaders,
the president attributed the decision to labor union chiefs,
peasant leaders and the party rank-and-file.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a distinguished member of our party, I've been commissioned
to tell you,'' Diaz said, according to Castaneda. ``I understand
that all of you have arrived at the same conclusion. I congratulate
you on your decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The new rules that the party adopted last week abolished this
tradition, known as the ``dedazo,'' literally the tapping of the
candidate. Instead, the party voted Monday to schedule a nationwide
primary for Nov. 7 to elect its presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a revolution in the PRI's rules,'' said Luis Rubio, a
political analyst with a Mexico City research institute. ``The
president just can't decide who the candidate will be anymore.
That's an enormous change.''
</P>
<P>
   Other recent electoral reforms have allowed opposition parties
to win control of Mexico's congress and a third of the
governorships, and have given them a credible chance at winning the
presidency next year; the governing party candidate can no longer
count on coasting to victory in the general elections.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo referred to this rising opposition challenge when he
first outlined his plan for a primary election to party leaders in
March, arguing that heightened democracy within the party would
foster the unity that has become crucial to its continued electoral
success. Yet in the days after the party adopted his proposals
Monday, traditions associated with the dedazo re-emerged, raising
questions about just how much the party is actually changing.
</P>
<P>
   Since February, analysts have been saying that Zedillo's
preferred choice was Interior Minister Francisco Labastida Ochoa.
And one day after the party changed its rules, Labastida announced
his presidential candidacy. Hundreds of government officials,
leaders of party-affiliated labor and peasant organizations and at
least one mariachi band packed into a convention center, whooping
in delirium as Labastida made his announcement.
</P>
<P>
   One party labor leader shrieked with joy into television cameras
broadcasting the spectacle live, nationwide: ``We have a candidate!
We have a candidate!''
</P>
<P>
   Several prominent millionaires and a string of governing party
governors spoke out to glorify Labastida as a brilliant leader, and
two party politicians who had been seen as potential rivals to
Labastida quickly bowed out of the race, one of them praising
Labastida as he did so.
</P>
<P>
   After their withdrawals, Labastida's only remaining rivals for
the party nomination were Roberto Madrazo Pintado, the governor of
Tabasco, Manuel Bartlett Diaz, the former governor of Puebla, and
Humberto Roque Villanueva, a former congressman. And there were
doubts about how seriously they could compete with Labastida.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the opposition parties lampooned the week's theatrics
as a traditional governing party ritual, known as the ``la
cargada,'' the charge, or ``la bufalada,'' the buffalo stampede, in
which party leaders rush to proclaim publicly their loyalty to the
official candidate once the President has made his choice known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not even their grandmother believes it when they say this is
the end of the dedazo,'' said Vicente Fox Quezada, the likely
presidential candidate of the pro-business National Action Party.
</P>
<P>
   Porfirio Munoz Ledo, who is seeking the presidential nomination
from the leftist Party of the Democratic Revolution, called the
outpouring of praise for Labastida ``the consecration of the
president's candidate in the oldest style of Mexican
authoritarianism.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous newspaper columnists and political cartoonists agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's clear is that Labastida is now alone as the President's
candidate,'' the newspaper Reforma said in its main editorial
column on Thursday. ``The PRI still doesn't understand the word
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sergio Sarmiento, a prominent columnist, wrote Labastida ``is
now seen as the beneficiary of a new type of presidential dedazo.''
</P>
<P>
   John Bailey, a Mexico specialist at Georgetown University, said
Zedillo wants to reduce his own influence in selecting the
candidate and give the party a larger role, but that 70 years of
party traditions will die hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``A vote will be taking place, that's new,'' Bailey said. ``But
there's a culture within the PRI in which everybody waits around
trying to figure out the party line, so they can position
themselves around it. There's an almost military discipline to obey
the president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1512EDT &QL; 
