<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7294 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-NYT &LR;      05-22 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TROOPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DECISION ON TROOPS IS CONSISTENT WITH SOME EXPERT VIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NEIL MacFARQUHAR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's decision to press for quick
deployment of 50,000 NATO troops on Kosovo's border is in tune with
the views of military and Balkans experts who in recent weeks have
said that ground troops are essential to resolving the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The troops will be needed even in the case of a negotiated
settlement, they said, and the faster they get to the region, the
faster such a resolution may emerge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation right now in Kosovo calls for ground troops,''
said Gen. John Galvin, who retired as head of NATO forces in Europe
in 1992, and is now dean of the Fletcher School of Law and
Diplomacy at Tufts University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you have to be a military person to see that you
need military forces on the ground there to reestablish security
and stability, so people can get back to living their lives,'' he
said. ``Hopefully it can be done through a peacetime environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, after eight weeks of aerial bombing, they still see few
signals that President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia is disposed
to accept NATO's demand for an international force entering Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Balkans experts point out that the early deployment of
NATO forces in the region, whether or not the troops eventually
enter Kosovo, could help shape a settlement in NATO's favor. But
they caution that troops should not be deployed unless political
leaders are prepared to use them if a settlement does not
materialize or if one collapses.
</P>
<P>
   At best, if Milosevic yields to a negotiated compromise, ground
troops will deploy in Kosovo to keep the peace. At worst, if no
settlement emerges, these experts say, ground troops may have to
fight their way into the southern Serbian province in an attempt to
stave off an embarrassing defeat.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, troops are crucial, especially if NATO is to
insure the return of the hundreds of thousands of Albanians who
have been forced out of Kosovo by Serb forces, a goal that many
experts say they fear NATO has lost sight of.
</P>
<P>
   The air campaign, they say, has done little toward attaining
that end so far. The experts are divided, however, on how far the
alliance should go in using ground troops to get the refugees home,
and they are somewhat reluctant to second-guess military commanders
on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bombing has not been sufficient to cause a genuine change
in the Serbian position, so we should not move into the negotiating
phase until there is clear evidence that the bombing has taken its
toll on Milosevic,'' said Warren Zimmerman, the last U.S.
ambassador to Yugoslavia, who served from 1989 to 1992 and is
currently a professor at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The further we go in destroying the Serbs' military power,''
he said, ``the more chance that Milosevic will not last in
office.''
</P>
<P>
   If a negotiated settlement falls short of NATO's goal, Zimmerman
believes that the Serbian leadership could still threaten Kosovo's
Albanian population. Such an end would let stand the injustice of
``ethnic cleansing,'' he said, would destabilize the surrounding
states and ``would continue in power the most repressive
dictatorship in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Western powers were similarly divided about using military power
to force an end to the three-year war in Bosnia that started in
1992. Eventually air power, combined with local Croatian and
Bosnian Muslim ground troops, pushed the Serbs to settle _ after
some 250,000 people had been killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``One should have learned from Bosnia that delaying means
accepting many more casualties in advance,'' said Hans van den
Broek, the Dutch foreign minister from 1982 to 1993 and now the
European commissioner responsible for East European affairs.
</P>
<P>
   More than 850,000 Albanian refugees from Kosovo have flooded
into Macedonia, Albania and Montenegro, the other republic inside
Yugoslavia, and threaten to overwhelm those areas by altering their
own fragile ethnic mixes and taxing their limited resources.
</P>
<P>
   The key question in any settlement, said Barnett Rubin, a Kosovo
specialist at the New York-based Council on Foreign Relations, is
whether enough Serbian forces will withdraw from Kosovo to convince
the refugees that it is safe to go home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't reverse the deaths or the rapes,'' Rubin said, ``but
we can reverse the ethnic cleansing.'' Otherwise, he added, ``It
will be a Palestinian problem in Europe _ a permanent refugee
underclass in Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has been criticized repeatedly since the
bombing started for precluding the use of ground forces,
advertising to the Serbs in advance that the campaign would be
limited.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were Milosevic, I would be more encouraged than I was at
the beginning,'' said retired Gen. Brent Scowcroft, who was
President George Bush's national security adviser during the
Persian Gulf war. ``Milosevic thinks he doesn't have to worry about
anything further. All the signals we're sending to him are the
wrong signals, other than saying we are going to go on bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   In the event of a land war, the most frequently repeated
estimate is that 100,000 NATO troops would be needed to push about
40,000 Serbian soldiers and military police out of Kosovo, an area
about half the size of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But experts disagree on what such a force's mandate might be.
Some say it might include a far wider war with an invasion of
Serbia beyond Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has two forces _ the Allied Command Europe Mobile Force and
the Rapid Reaction Corps _ both of which were assembled after the
Cold War to make NATO troops more flexible in a crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Both are drawn from the armies of at least 10 members, the first
consisting of about 7,000 advance troops and the second made up of
a full division of about 15,000 troops from each country. Both
consistently train together. Military experts said the forces would
not be troubled by the mountainous terrain that runs along Kosovo's
borders with Albania and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Milosevic still has the initiative and until we get
the initiative away from him he will dictate the pace of
settlement,'' said Gen. George Joulwan, who preceded Gen. Wesley
Clark as supreme allied commander in Europe, serving from 1993 to
1997. ``Bombing alone won't take the initiative away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
