<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 15:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7295 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-STRIKEZONE-COX     05-22 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-STRIKEZONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Strike zone adjustment goes slowly
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a tirade better directed at his own stratospheric ERA than at
the men in blue, the Chicago White Sox's Jaime Navarro finally had
had enough last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The umpires are supposed to be working on a new strike zone,''
Navarro said after Cleveland mauled him for nine runs, ``and they
aren't working on anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Navarro spoke, if somewhat loudly, for nearly everyone in the
majors. The predicament is wonderfully baseball, a game where the
foul poles are fair. The new, improved strike zone, which has been
used as a scapegoat for virtually every woe, including Greg
Maddux's mysterious vulnerability, hasn't really expanded at all.
Umpires were instructed to tighten the strike zone on the corners
and increase the height of the zone, creating the high strike
possibility for pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   But it's become a matter of interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the exception of a couple guys, there's not much
difference,'' said Atlanta shortstop Walt Weiss, a connoisseur of
the strike zone. ``I thought there was in spring training, maybe
the first week or two. But I think, gradually, it's gotten back to
what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball, which touched the match to the issue on
Feb. 19 with the infamous ``high strike'' directive to its umpires,
naturally thinks otherwise. With a fourth of the season gone, clubs
are hitting .272, a six-point increase from a year ago, and bases
on balls have increased nearly one-half walk per nine innings. Only
two clubs entered the weekend with ERAs under 4.00, as opposed to
eight in 1993, all of which suggests that pitchers have been forced
to work the true outside corner and are paying the price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on our observational and empirical data, the strike zone
is being called in and out more consistently on the plate,'' said
Sandy Alderson, baseball's vice president for operations and the
author of the ``high strike'' document. ``In the lower end of the
strike zone, the pitch at the knee is also being called more
consistently right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's the upper end of the strike zone, the high strike,
that is still causing some trouble for some umpires,'' Alderson
said, ``and we thought going in that would be the hardest pitch for
some umpires to adjust to.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet other evidence suggests that little has changed. The average
major-league at-bat, according to STATS Inc., is right at 3.72
pitches, consistent with the rest of the decade. Hitters were
striking out just as frequently on the older strike zone three
years ago, 6.5 per nine innings.
</P>
<P>
   And if baseball's hope was to give pitchers a new area to
exploit with the high strike, it has not happened. Only a handful
of hard throwers, including Randy Johnson and Curt Schilling, can
get away with the overpowering high fastball at the navel, and like
the umpires, they aren't comfortable throwing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't do me good,'' Philadelphia's Schilling said. ``I
don't want to throw pitches up for strikes, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   All that has really changed is the interpretation of the new
strike zone, not the zone itself, a troubling state for those who
make their living around its edges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It fluctuates. I thought it was pretty consistent before,''
Atlanta pitching coach Leo Mazzone said. ``I knew what the strike
zone was last year, and then I saw it change. As far as calling the
high strike, you can forget about that. So if you don't call the
high strike and you narrow the corners, it's smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   That result hardly was the original intent. Bud Selig made
umpiring one of his first issues after becoming full-time
commissioner last year. Baseball was mortified by umpire Eric
Gregg's coast-to-coast strike zone in Livan Hernandez's
15-strikeout performance in Game 5 of the 1997 NLCS against the
Braves. Further concern followed from the twin first-inning
ejections of Cleveland's Doc Gooden and Mike Hargrove in Game 2 of
last year's American League Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   Conforming the strike zone to the written rule _ ``midpoint
between the top of the shoulders and the top of the uniform pants''
to ``the hollow beneath the kneecap'' _ was made clear in
Alderson's Feb. 19 memo. The Umpires Association called the
initiative ``deplorable.'' The Players Association, in a rare move,
lauded baseball's move. The players remained privately suspicious.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weren't they supposed to start calling the high strike eight
years ago?'' asked Atlanta's Maddux, who has been unwilling to
blame his implausible 5.02 ERA on the strike zone. ``I just think
it's tough to change. You've been calling balls and strikes for 15
years, and then they ask you to change the way you see a strike. I
think that's asking a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw in spring training there was a conscious effort being
made,'' Braves second baseman Bret Boone said. ``I don't think
there is now. I think the whole thing is being blown a little bit
out of proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't tell that to Tom Glavine, who concedes that his early
problems this season were caused by trying to break his change-up
closer to the outside corner. That effort caused mechanical
problems with his delivery that only now, after three victories in
four decisions, seem corrected.
</P>
<P>
   And if Maddux, whose 88 hits are the most allowed in the majors,
won't blame the strike zone, others will for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he wants to say that's his biggest problem right
now,'' catcher Eddie Perez said. ``But I think it is. Maybe he
won't agree with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the majors, managers have worked to reduce the anxiety of
their clubs, who perceive a new strike zone as making an already
difficult game unfair. Navarro's tirade this week verbalized much
of the early off-the-record clubhouse sentiment. After the Phillies
beat Cincinnati 1-0 in extra innings earlier this year while
Schilling struck out nine, Reds manager Jack McKeon sent this
message to his players griping about the strike zone: ``My father
always told me it is better to be thought a fool than to open your
mouth and remove all doubt. Some of our players need to hear
that.''
</P>
<P>
   None of it has been easy on umpires. To make the corners easier
to monitor, some umpires dictate strict observance of the catcher's
box. With catchers unable to move more than a few inches outside to
frame the plate, the hope was that the umpires would get an
unobstructed view of the two inches on either side of the
17-inch-wide plate.
</P>
<P>
   But the obscure rule has not been enforced consistently. For
example, Bruce Froemming, the NL's senior ump, repeatedly allowed
Javy Lopez to set up Wednesday with a foot outside the box.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the umpires really need to do is stay behind the middle
of the plate, instead of chasing the catchers,'' said Astros
manager Larry Dierker, who pitched 14 big-league seasons. ``If they
stay in the middle and call the corners, I think both the hitters
and the pitchers will be satisfied with the results.''
</P>
<P>
   As the zone reconformed slowly to its old dimensions, many in
the game _ and most of the umpires _ view the issue as having less
to do with ball and strikes and more to do with umpire control.
Selig has made it clear he intends to take charge of the current
system, with the eventual goal of eliminating exclusivity between
leagues in favor of one umpire pool.
</P>
<P>
   As the umpire's union has gained strength since two work
stoppages last decade, baseball has become frustrated in monitoring
ump performance and almost powerless in disciplining umpires or
removing inept ones. The umpires' current work agreement expires
after this season, and umpires see Selig's intentions as a clear
threat to their power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The commissioner has made it clear that starting next season,
he intends for the umpires to fall under the authority of the
commissioner's office,'' Alderson said. ``He just felt the strike
zone was something that couldn't wait until next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, some umpires have viewed that with more draconian intent
than the facts support,'' he said. ``But the fact remains, the
commissioner will take over supervision of the umpires next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: The 1999 interpretation of the strike zone will be
nothing compared with 2000's labor interpretation. Until then, the
game only seeks order at the plate. And slowly, it is emerging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think when this all blows over,'' Boone said, ``it will all
go back to where it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
