<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INSIDE PRO FOOTBALL NOTEBOOK
 &HT;    Bucs tailor offense to Dilfer
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has become chic to blame quarterback Trent Dilfer for the
failures of the Tampa Bay Buccaneers' offense, and general manager
Rich McKay and coach Tony Dungy unwittingly added to the pressure
in the past month by trading for Eric Zeier and using a
second-round pick on prospect Shaun King of Tulane.
</P>
<P>
   Dilfer's shaky play aside, there's still a lot of culpability to
go around in an ill-designed attack that rated 27th in passing in
1998 and 22nd overall. Dungy steadfastly defended coordinator Mike
Shula, youngest son of Hall of Fame coach Don Shula, a year ago but
has decided he might need some assistance. So Dungy reassigned
tight ends coach Clyde Christensen to coach the quarterbacks. Early
results have been promising.
</P>
<P>
   At the behest of Dilfer, a five-year veteran who has slimmed to
232 pounds, Christensen and Shula quietly are revamping the Tampa
Bay passing game. Stealing a page from Dan Reeves' design, they
will add more seven-step drops that will permit Dilfer to throw the
deep ball off play-action, a strength he shares with Atlanta's
Chris Chandler.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches cleared up the misconception that Dilfer didn't like the
offensive plan, which featured running backs Mike Alstott and
Warrick Dunn, and that he preferred to throw the ball more than the
26.8 times per game he averaged in 1998. And in taking Darnell
McDonald of Kansas State in the seventh round, the Bucs not only
got one of the best bargains in the draft, but added a bigger wide
receiver to a group of small players _ Reidel Anthony, Bert Emanuel
and Jacquez Green.
</P>
<P>
   If the offseason moves succeed, Tampa Bay, a disappointing 8-8
last year, could be one of the top bounce-back teams of 1999. If
they fail, Dilfer could be bounced, period.
</P>
<P>
   Tip sheet
</P>
<P>
   Brett Favre credits the fact that he will turn 30 in four months
for his new sobriety and more family-oriented lifestyle. Green Bay
insiders, however, credit his wife, Deanna, who is pregnant and due
to deliver the couple's second daughter on Aug. 17. ... John Elway,
who will meet in coming days with Eli Broad, one of the men
attempting to bring an expansion franchise to Los Angeles, has
decided he probably won't attempt a TV career in 1999. Elway would
prefer to work in a front office with the kind of
general-manager-in-training role Dwight Clark once had with the
49ers. ... For the second time in six months, local agent Hadley
Engelhard is forced to negotiate an injury settlement for a client
whose NFL career was cut short by back problems. The Carolina
Panthers used a third-round pick in '98 on Penn defensive lineman
Mitch Marrow, who sat out his entire rookie season. Now Marrow has
been advised to retire because of a back injury similar to the one
that forced another Engelhard client, former Georgia Tech center
Michael Cheever, out of the game.... Add wide receiver Johnnie
Morton to a lengthening list of Detroit Lions veterans growing
weary of coach Bobby Ross. ... Florida State wide receiver Peter
Warrick continues to insist he will not leave the Seminoles and
petition the league for a special supplemental draft this summer.
One receiver who is making some noise about a supplemental draft,
however, is R. Jay Soward of USC. ... With youngsters Shaun
Williams and Percy Ellworth pushing for playing time, the New York
Giants will consider releasing troubled free safety Tito Wooten
after June 1. ... In what might be the latest indication that Gene
Williams isn't part of the team's plans for '99, the Falcons
recently moved second-year guard Bob Hallen from the left side to
the right side. ... New England is seeking a veteran tailback, but
don't believe the rumors that the Patriots will take a chance on
Lawrence Phillips, who is leading the NFL Europe League in rushing.
Myra Kraft, the wife of owner Bob Kraft, forced the release of
defensive tackle Christian Peter two summers ago when the scope of
his violence against women became public. Bobby GrierPete
