<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-WILLIAMS-CONTRACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Contract consensus: Saints rooked Williams
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heisman running back Ricky Williams signed a deal with the New
Orleans Saints that requires him to reach extraordinary performance
levels or settle for the NFL equivalent of chump change. By doing
so, Williams could further polarize league owners and player agents
and significantly slow the pace of first-round agreements.
</P>
<P>
   In signing the seven-year contract, Williams became a hero to
owners and a bona fide member of the proletariat. And he and
representative Leland Hardy became easy targets for agents
accustomed to negotiating contracts based more on potential than
production.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Brown, owner of the Cincinnati Bengals, views the Williams
deal as a landmark case, a play-for-pay agreement that forces a
prospect to fulfill his potential. But agents have vowed that the
contract will not start a trend.
</P>
<P>
   Agents insist that paying players according to their draft
status will remain the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans think it's great, I'm sure, because it's all based on
incentives,'' Atlanta area agent Hadley Engelhard said. ``The truth
is, it's a terrible deal. As the fifth player taken in the draft,
(Williams) is entitled to the fifth-best contract. For him to
collect all this money he's talked about, though, is unrealistic.
The odds are stacked against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Even league salary-cap experts concede that the Saints snookered
Hardy.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a contract that gives Williams, who played at the
University of Texas, the maximum signing bonus under the league's
rookie salary pool, $8.84 million. But $5 million will be deferred
until next year. Williams will receive the minimum salaries of
$175,000, $250,000 and $325,000 for his first three seasons. But
unless he averages 1,600 yards during his first four NFL seasons, a
feat accomplished by only Terrell Davis and Eric Dickerson, he will
continue to earn minimum base salaries throughout his career.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing that triggers higher salaries during the second
half of Williams' deal is the 1,600-yard average, a number probably
unattainable if he is injured. In four college seasons, Williams
averaged 1,570 yards per year.
</P>
<P>
   Hardy, an honors graduate of the renowned Wharton School of
Business at the University of Pennsylvania, is an inexperienced
player agent who had never done an NFL deal. He declined counsel
from the NFL Players Association while working the contract, and he
often was distracted by telephone calls from tennis star Venus
Williams, who was in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Now Brown must hammer out a contract with quarterback Akili
Smith, the Bengals' first-round pick, and for the fifth time in 12
years he will face off against agent Leigh Steinberg in
negotiations. Steinberg created the concepts of ``voidable years''
and ``buybacks,'' two formulas most used to circumvent salary-cap
restraints for rookies. The thrifty Brown, who can't even get
Steinberg to return calls, likes the Williams deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of concept we have in mind,'' Brown said. ``If
Akili plays well and we win, he'll be paid well. If not ...''
</P>
<P>
   Other owners have thought about using the concept but say they
have little shot of gaining concessions from players and agents.
Several said that Hardy set the bar too high for his client and
erred in not including ``rollovers'' _ incentives that would become
base salary in subsequent seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams contract includes 26 benchmarks that could earn
annual incentives of $50,000 each. But the contract shows that
those bonuses can't exceed $500,000 in a given year and that some
of them _ such as getting 12 touchdown catches in a season _ are
unrealistic. In addition, Williams faces four weigh-ins annually
and must repay the Saints $25,000 anytime he weighs more than 240
pounds. Staying svelte might be difficult for a player who ate 11
doughnuts after his April 6 workout for NFL scouts, then had four
desserts at an April 7 dinner with New Orleans club executives.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clear from what I've seen that the contract is a
gamble,'' agent Kenny Zuckerman said. ``It's well below the market
value. If he explodes in the first couple years, he will be
dramatically underpaid.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
