<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEATBELT-CRACKDOWN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAT-BELT CAMPAIGN SET FOR HOLIDAY WEEKEND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Calif., Kan., N.H., Ore., Pa., S.D., Wis., Wyo.)  (rk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Police agencies are planning another highly
publicized enforcement blitz to encourage people to wear seat belts
during the Memorial Day weekend, as safety experts have concluded
that the twice-yearly crackdowns are causing lasting increases in
the numbers of people who buckle up.
</P>
<P>
   With the support of 42 governors, more than 5,000 police
agencies will join the effort, according to the Air Bag and Seat
Belt Safety Campaign, an advertising and advocacy program whose
sponsors include government agencies, insurance companies, auto
companies and auto parts suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years they sponsored similar events around
Thanksgiving and Memorial Day, two of the busiest driving holidays
of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The governors signed a statement calling for ``highly visible
enforcement and the adoption of a policy of zero tolerance for
unbuckled kids.'' By emphasizing protection of children, the
crackdown seeks to avoid a backlash from adult drivers who feel the
police should not interfere with their own seat-belt decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drivers who allow children to ride unrestrained should be
stopped and enforcement action taken,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   All 50 states have laws allowing police officers to stop cars
and ticket drivers if children are not in a child seat or in a belt
appropriate for their size. Only 19 states have a similar law for
adults; most states allow the police to write tickets for not
wearing a belt only if the car was pulled over for some other
reason. The one holdout, New Hampshire, does not require belt use
by adults.
</P>
<P>
   At the National Safety Council, a nonprofit organization
supported by the insurance industry that is helping organize the
blitz, Chuck Hurley, a spokesman, said, ``Nobody in this country
has a right to put a child at risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Hurley and others credit previous coordinated enforcement
campaigns with increasing belt use. The rate of seat-belt
compliance for all people in vehicles, as measured by observers
standing by the roadside, improved after the first blitz, during
Thanksgiving 1997, and jumped to 70 percent from 62 percent after
the enforcement blitz over Memorial Day weekend in 1998, according
to Department of Transportation statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Experts believe it rose again after last Thanksgiving. The
Transportation Department said in February that the increase in
belt use in 1998, if it is permanent, would cut the number of
deaths by 1,500 annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suppose you were running a medical trial with a vaccine, and
you saved 1,500 lives; would you do it again?'' Hurley asked.
</P>
<P>
   Experts would like to raise the U.S. average in seat-belt use to
levels already achieved in California and Canada, both over 90
percent. The Department of Transportation last year estimated that
raising the level to 90 percent from 68 percent would save 5,500
lives a year, and cut the number of serious injuries by 133,000.
</P>
<P>
   States will conduct their efforts in different ways. Many will
set up roadblocks and checkpoints. That is uncommon in New York
City, but the police will set up such a checkpoint on Thursday, in
front of the Javits Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   The governors who had not signed on, as of Friday, were those of
Wisconsin, South Dakota, Alabama, Wyoming, Texas, Pennsylvania,
Oregon and Kansas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
