<SLUG> BC-GUNS-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW REPUBLICANS MISSED THE MARK ON GUN CONTROL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Idaho, R.I., Va.)  (lb) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Across the chaotic Senate struggle over gun
control, Sen. Larry Craig of Idaho, a champion of gun rights,
played scrambling quarterback for his fellow Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, a board member of the National Rifle Association, turned
his hideaway Capitol office into a place for huddles with the
group's lobbyists. Yet no matter how they tried to turn back the
Democrats on gun control, they failed.
</P>
<P>
   As disgruntled Republicans tried this weekend to sort out how
they had allowed the Democrats to gain control of the Senate's
agenda, they pointed to miscalculations by Sen. Trent Lott, their
majority leader, and by Craig and other Republican leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans say the party was drawn into a fight before it was
ready, hastily put together flawed answers to Democratic proposals
and had little sense of where its caucus actually stood.
</P>
<P>
   They failed to recognize the image that would be created by
allowing Craig to act as their most visible figure, some
Republicans said.
</P>
<P>
   And most startling of all, they created for Vice President Al
Gore a heady turn in the spotlight on Thursday as he cast a rare
tie-breaking vote to pass a Democratic measure to require
background checks at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all hurrying,'' Craig said. ``I like time to shape an
issue, to know where my membership is, so that I have no surprises.
We were simply not afforded that luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican, who did not want to be named, said, ``They
were not clearly thinking through where the Republicans were going
to be, post-Littleton, that we need to adapt to the world of today,
not the world of five years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   By not making that readjustment, the Republicans allowed Senate
passage of the first significant gun-control legislation in five
years and gave momentum to the Democrats. President Clinton on
Saturday challenged the House to vote on gun control before the
school year ends in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``No parent should have to fear sending a child to school,''
Clinton said in his weekly radio address.
</P>
<P>
   From the first, Republicans tried to cast gun violence in
schools as primarily a cultural issue. ``When we stopped having
prayer in schools, things started to going to pot,'' Lott said
recently.
</P>
<P>
   But Senate Republicans were drawn into the gun debate
prematurely by their effort to stop Democratic attempts to stall a
bill protecting computer companies from lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   So when Democrats tried to graft gun control onto the computer
bill, Lott dusted off a juvenile-crime bill and presented it as a
vehicle for firearms restrictions instead.
</P>
<P>
   The leading role in countering the Democrats went to Craig. He
is chairman of the Senate Republican Policy Committee, which makes
him third in the Senate leadership, often playing point man.
</P>
<P>
   But symbolism is important _ particularly with the Democrats
casting the NRA as a villain. Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., who is
aligned with the Democrats on this issue, said, ``I don't think it
was the best PR to have someone on the board of the NRA seen to be
leading the charge.''
</P>
<P>
   Of his consultations with the NRA, Craig said, ``This is not
something unique. Lobbyists are all over the Hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with his expertise, Craig was caught off guard by the
Democrats. He said he was unaware, until days beforehand, that the
first measure Democrats would introduce was an amendment to mandate
checks on all buyers at gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said he had little time to formulate his alternative,
which created incentives _ but not requirements _ for voluntary
background checks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not much time to clarify and shape an issue and really
feel out your colleagues,'' Craig said. It would have helped, he
said, to have had ``another week of time to shape the issues and do
some effective polling of my own Senate membership.''
</P>
<P>
   As it was, the Democrats' initial requirement for background
checks was defeated, and Craig's initial amendment passed. But six
Republicans voted with the Democrats. And the next morning, after
Democrats pointedly noted that Craig's amendment also relaxed some
current gun laws and as headlines blared that Republicans had
defeated gun control, at least four Republican moderates panicked
over their vote with Craig.
</P>
<P>
   Craig was forced to introduce a new, stricter gun-show proposal,
and that retreat gave Democrats a potent oratorical wedge that
ultimately led, one week later on Thursday, to the passage of the
Democratic gun-show amendment, which had previously been defeated.
</P>
<P>
   James Jay Baker, the chief lobbyist for the rifle association,
said the Democratic proposal might not have succeeded if
Republicans had introduced Craig's second measure first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly had to regroup,'' Baker said. ``The benefit of
hindsight is 20-20.''
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, the day before a second vote on the Democratic
gun-show amendment, Republicans knew the tally was close.
</P>
<P>
   Of the six Republicans who had voted a week earlier for the
first Democratic amendment, which failed narrowly, Sen. John Warner
of Virginia was thought to be the most likely Republican to be
brought back into the fold.
</P>
<P>
   Both Craig and Lott talked with Warner on Wednesday evening.
Late Thursday morning, before the vote, Warner alone among the six
renegade Republicans was corralled again on the Senate floor by
Lott.
</P>
<P>
   But Warner again sided with Democrats. Several Republicans said
that was because Warner was still nursing a grudge against the
rifle association, which backed a Republican primary opponent
against him in his last Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Warner, however, said he was moved by his conscience and his
constituents. ``Women, primarily, are tugging at my sleeve in a
courteous way and saying, `Senator, I'm so worried about this,
isn't there something we can do?''' Warner said. ``And these are
not people who ordinarily tug at my sleeve.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior Republican aide said that Republicans realized, hours
before the vote on Thursday on the resurrected Democratic gun-show
proposal, that it could end in a tie, handing Gore his moment. And
Republicans discussed throwing an extra vote to the Democrats, to
deny Gore that opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   But, the aide said, they felt the maneuver would be transparent
and would come back to haunt them.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the vote, Lott tried to act unconcerned. ``So on
that issue I would call on the Democrats _ you've had your fun and
you've made your points,'' he said. ``We've made our points with
regard to violence in school. Now it's time to move on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1536EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
