<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 15:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7308 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-JACKSON-NY     05-22 1464
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-JACKSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KNICKS AND PHIL JACKSON HELD A SECRET MEETING NEARLY A MONTH
AGO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill.)   By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nearly a month ago, with the Knicks in disarray and
in danger of missing the playoffs for the first time in 12 years,
Dave Checketts, the president of Madison Square Garden, sensed
disastrous regression for the franchise. In secret, he met with
Phil Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts and Jackson convened at an undisclosed location in the
New York metropolitan area and informally discussed team personnel
and the future of the Knicks, according to an official with a
National Basketball Association team and a second person with
knowledge of the meeting. Checketts made no offer to Jackson, but
the meeting represented the first inquiry into whether the coach of
the six-time champion Chicago Bulls would be interested in taking
over the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the informal get-together, Checketts dismissed Ernie
Grunfeld as team president and general manager, took over the
operation of the team and announced that Coach Jeff Van Gundy's
status would be reviewed at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   However, the unexpected resurgence of the team _ making the
playoffs, defeating the reviled Miami Heat and Pat Riley in the
first round and winning the first two games of its Eastern
Conference semifinal series against Atlanta _ has put Checketts in
a perplexing situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks will seek their third straight victory against the
Hawks today at Madison Square Garden. A victory would catapult them
to a 3-0 lead in the four-of-seven-game series and put New York on
the verge of its first appearance in the Eastern Conference finals
since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Only a week ago, Van Gundy was in danger of losing his job;
seven days later there is speculation that he will end up with a
contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts denied through a Knicks spokesman that he has had
discussions with Jackson or any of his representatives. Jackson
could not be reached. His agent, Todd Musburger, also denied that a
discussion with Checketts had taken place, and refused to discuss
any and all teams that might be interested in Jackson, citing
strict confidentiality agreements between the respective parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are actively involved in sifting through some very
interesting situations,'' said Musburger. ``Phil has yet to make a
definite decision. But the process is moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, 53, who was part of two Knicks championship teams in
the 1970s and has recently had a home built in Woodstock, N.Y., has
kept a low profile while on sabbatical this season and has not said
for sure that he will return to coaching next season. According to
the NBA team official, Jackson has narrowed his consideration to
six teams. The two most serious contenders are the Los Angeles
Lakers and the Knicks, but no decision is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Other possibilities include the Nets. They, according to an
Eastern Conference team official who spoke on condition of
anonymity, met with Jackson on a flight in the past week. Though
Nets players have endorsed hiring Don Casey, who served as the
interim coach after John Calipari was fired on March 15, the owner
Lewis Katz is said to be interested in Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   According to the NBA team official, the meeting between
Checketts and Jackson lasted approximately 90 minutes and was also
attended by Musburger.
</P>
<P>
   One of the subjects that Jackson and Checketts discussed was
Patrick Ewing, the 14-year cornerstone of the franchise who is a
Van Gundy loyalist and has stated that he will not play for
Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shocks me,'' Ewing said last week after being asked what he
thought of the meeting between the two parties. ``I've said it, I'm
not playing for Phil Jackson. There's no way. They can trade me if
they get Phil.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts and Jackson did not discuss the possibility of trading
Ewing if Jackson became the Knicks coach. He is owed $30 million
over the next two seasons and the possibility of acquiring a
marquee player in exchange for the 36-year-old, injury-plagued
center is slim; Checketts has said that he wants Ewing to finish
his career in New York, but he has also said that no player is
untradeable.
</P>
<P>
   The team official familiar with Jackson's meeting with Checketts
said Jackson emerged from it with the perception that the Knicks'
style of play would gradually shift its focus away from Ewing in
what many believe will be his final two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   That information would address Jackson's worst fears about
taking over the Knicks: that the team would continue to be
hamstrung by a predictable halfcourt offense with Ewing as its
focal point. Jackson favors the motion-oriented triangle offense he
employed in Chicago, where Michael Jordan, Scottie Pippen and
another player were used interchangeably to create mismatches and
scoring opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has one more year guaranteed on a three-year, $6
million contract. However, the contract gives the Knicks the option
of renewing Van Gundy for a fourth season at more than $3 million.
The contract also includes an incentive clause guaranteeing that
Van Gundy will be paid for a fourth season if the Knicks reach the
NBA finals either this season or next.
</P>
<P>
   Given the recent history of Garden management paying off former
coaches and overpaying less-than-star players, the money owed to
Van Gundy would not be an impediment to dismissing him. Now,
though, the team's postseason success may not only have saved Van
Gundy's job, it has also raised the possibility that the Knicks
could reward him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think, with the way they're going now, they would tear
up the old deal and give him a guaranteed two-year extension with a
third-year option with undisclosed terms,'' said an NBA agent who
requested anonymity. ``That way, all the speculation goes away and
everybody is happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy would not discuss his contract situation nor the
meeting between Jackson and Checketts and how that would affect his
future.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's agent, Rob Ades, said: ``I don't believe that the
Knicks would be interviewing another coach in light of the
performance of the team over the last several weeks. I just do not
believe they would do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ades added, ``Here is a guy who was in his office every single
day during the lockout, preparing for the season. He's loyal,
committed and he's done a great job for them. If he keeps it up,
you got the next Red Holzman.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy was in charge of a maddeningly inconsistent team that
had a 21-21 record with eight games left in the regular season. At
the same time he was trying to guide his team into the playoffs, he
was engaged in a bitter power struggle with Grunfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld wanted Marcus Camby, for whom he had traded Charles
Oakley to Toronto and signed to a nearly $50 million contract, to
see more playing time and not languish on the bench. Van Gundy
opposed the unpopular trade, and was determined to make Camby _ who
had earned a reputation as a soft, unfocused player _ earn his
minutes in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Twice during the regular season, after blowout losses to Chicago
on March 12 and Charlotte on April 7, Grunfeld was apparently on
the verge of dismissing Van Gundy. Adding to their split, Van Gundy
began politicking as if he were a Garden executive instead of a
coaching lifer, intent on preserving his reputation instead of
merely coaching his team.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, Checketts determined that the off-the-court
distraction was detrimental to the team's fortunes. He decided to
make a bold move, firing Grunfeld and assuming the team president
role for the first time in five years _ traveling with the team on
the road and being involved in its day-to-day operations.
</P>
<P>
   On April 26, Checketts watched the lightning rod for the Knicks'
resurrection _ an implausible second-half comeback from a 20-point
deficit against Miami. In the same arena three weeks later,
Checketts watched an even more improbable Knick victory.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston's running jump shot in the lane bounced off the
front of the rim, off the backboard and through the net with 0.8
seconds remaining to win a decisive Game 5 inside a stunned and
subdued Miami Arena _ the third job-saving victory in three months.
</P>
<P>
   In that game, Ewing _ playing on a throbbing Achilles' tendon,
two sore knees and a strained rib cage suffered in the third
quarter _ silenced his critics by playing one of the his most
courageous games. Scoring 22 points and hauling down 11 rebounds,
he outplayed Alonzo Mourning, who is a candidate for the league's
most valuable player award.
</P>
<P>
   If Van Gundy and Ewing were going out, they would go out
together.
</P>
<P>
   Since their meeting, Checketts has never got back to Jackson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
