<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7321 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     05-22 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: YOGI JOINS FAMOUS FOES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE FALLS, N.J. _ Up on the screen in grainy black-and-white
film, the New York Yankees were playing the Brooklyn Dodgers in
their six World Series from 1947 to 1956 and every so often Yogi
Berra would appear, swinging a bat or in his catcher's mask. And
now, in the Yogi Berra Museum's theater, Lawrence Peter Berra
himself stood up Friday for his induction into, of all things, the
Brooklyn Dodger Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``They weren't easy,'' he was saying, alluding to those Dodger
teams. ``They were a real good ball club.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind him, Joe Pignatano, a former Mets coach and once a Dodger
catcher, interrupted, saying with a smile, ``You still know how to
lie.'' Yogi never blinked.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a real good ball club,'' Yogi said firmly. ``We just
beat 'em, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   Beat 'em in five of those six World Series, and more often than
not, Yogi Berra was in the middle of what was going on. He caught
Don Larsen's perfect game in 1956 and over those six Series, he hit
eight homers and knocked in 21 runs with a .298 average, including
three homers and 10 runs batted in in 1956, the last series in
Ebbets Field.
</P>
<P>
   Along with dozens of familiar Brooklyn Dodgers, this Yankee folk
hero is now in perhaps the only pantheon to also honor famous foes.
Bobby Thomson is in it. So is Stan Musial, Ralph Kiner, Johnny
Vander Meer, Warren Spahn, Johnny Sain, Robin Roberts, Curt Simmons
and two other Yankees _ Tommy Henrich and Johnny Kucks.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody remembers Johnny Kucks, but anybody who was in
Brooklyn in 1956 remembers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seventh game, we didn't know who was going to pitch,''
Berra said. ``Kucks didn't know. I didn't know. But Frank Crossetti
put a ball on the chair at his locker in Ebbets Field. That's how
how Casey Stengel told a pitcher he was pitching. He had his third
base coach put a ball on his chair.''
</P>
<P>
   Kucks, a sinkerball right-hander with an 18-9 record who had
worked twice in relief in that Series, pitched a 9-0 six-hitter
supported by Berra's pair of two-run homers off Don Newcombe, the
Dodger ace with a 27-7 record that season. Berra also hit a grand
slam off Newcombe in the second game of that series.
</P>
<P>
   ``On those two homers in the seventh game, Newk threw two good
pitches _ one away, one in,'' Berra recalled. ``I just saw the ball
good. Before one of 'em, Roy Campanella didn't hold a foul tip that
would have been a third strike.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, when the Dodgers won their only World Series
representing Brooklyn, Jackie Robinson stole home in the opener at
Yankee Stadium with Whitey Ford pitching and Frank Kellert at bat.
When American League umpire Bill Summers ruled Robinson safe, Berra
hopped around in protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was out,'' Berra was saying now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out by how much?'' a listener asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was out,'' Berra repeated. ``Out.''
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning of that Series' seventh game, with the
Dodgers leading, 2-0, Billy Martin on second and Gil McDougald on
first, left-hander Johnny Podres threw a high outside pitch. Berra
swung and lifted a short fly ball down the left-field line. ``If
Amoros wasn't there, it's a hit'' Berra said. ``Amoros was fast. He
ran a long ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Amoros was also left-handed. He stuck out his glove,
caught the ball on the run, then threw to shortstop Pee Wee Reese,
who threw to first baseman Gil Hodges to double up McDougald.``Pee
Wee had looked back,'' Podres said, ``and knew where everybody
was.''
</P>
<P>
   Podres was there Friday along with fellow Hall of Fame members
Ralph Branca, Clem Labine, Roger Craig and Pignatano, as well as
this year's other inductees _ right-hander Jim Hughes, outfielders
Don Thompson and Don Demeter and bat boy Angelo Ambrosio. Of that
group the noisiest applause from about 200 spectators was for
Podres, whose eight-hit shutout in 1955 set off a celebration in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We let 'em win that year,'' Berra said with a smile. This was
baseball's version of the Mountain coming to Mohammed. For the
occasion, the Brooklyn Dodger Hall of Fame, housed in the Brooklyn
Historical Society building in Brooklyn Heights, came to Yogi's
museum here on the Montclair State College campus not far from his
Montclair home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people don't know,'' Yogi said, ``that the Dodgers wanted
to sign me.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in St. Louis as an outfielder and third baseman,
Berra was scouted by the Cardinals, but their general manager,
Branch Rickey, downplayed Berra's potential. ``Rickey told me I'd
never be a big league ballplayer,'' Berra recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Rickey, however, was about to desert the Cardinals to become the
Brooklyn Dodgers president. He was hoping to sign Berra as a Dodger
farmhand. But in 1943 the Yankees signed Berra.
</P>
<P>
   ``After I signed with the Yankees,'' Berra said, ``I got a
telegram from Rickey to join the Dodgers in spring training.'' By
the 1947 Series, Berra was the Yankees rookie catcher as
right-hander Floyd ``Bill'' Bevens, leading 2-1, went into the
ninth inning of the fourth game with a no-hitter. With two out, Al
Gionfriddo, running or Carl Furillo, tried to steal second.
</P>
<P>
   ``I threw high,'' Berra remembered. ``With a good throw, maybe
Bevens gets his no-hitter, but I was a terrible catcher then.''
</P>
<P>
   Gionfriddo was safe. Pete Reiser walked; Eddie Miksis ran for
him. Harry ``Cookie'' Lavagetto broke up the no-hitter with a
double off the right-field wall as Gionfriddo and Miksis scored.
The Dodgers won, 3-2, but the Yankees won that Series in seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   But what if the Dodgers had signed Lawrence Peter Berra?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Dodgers instead of the Yankees would have won five of
those six World Series from 1947 to 1956. And When Roy Campanella
arrived in 1948 as the Dodgers catcher, who would have been moved
to another position, probably left field?
</P>
<P>
   ``Me,'' Yogi Berra said. ``I was a terrible catcher then.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
