<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7326 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-SELES-NYT &LR;      05-22 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-SELES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SELES TRIES TO RECAPTURE MAGIC AT FRENCH OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ A survivalist in sneakers, Monica Seles has come full
circle after five years lost to calamities beyond her control. She
has arrived at the French Open, which she monopolized from 1990 to
1992 and where she improbably resurfaced as last year's runner-up
three weeks after her father's death.
</P>
<P>
   She is determined to use the next few years to retool herself
and her game _ before the game, with its streamlined teen-age
contingent, passes her by.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to have five years where no outside things come in
and take over, and where I can see my full potential,'' Seles said
recently, undeterred that her training for the French, which begins
Monday, was interrupted by bronchitis. After all, her 1998
preparation was nonexistent, and look what transpired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that I want to win at any cost, and I don't want that
kind of people around me,'' said Seles, coachless since dismissing
Gavin Hopper last November. ``But there are a few more things I
want to achieve before I'm done, and one of them is going back to
playing the fearless tennis I used to play.''
</P>
<P>
   In a fearful world, one where she has had her confidence eroded
by every reality check from an on-court stabbing to the loss of her
father, to the current NATO bombings of Novi Sad, Yugoslavia, her
Balkan birthplace, Seles has decided to overcome instead of buckle
under. When she was the fiercest and youngest No. 1 to raise a
racquet, Seles wore rarefied success like a coat-of-arms.
</P>
<P>
   Now her daily demons include melancholy and binge-eating and a
homesickness all the more acute because it hurts to go home. But
she means to conquer them before they spoil what's left of her
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are major issues I've been dealing with for the past
five years; we're not talking about crying over lost luggage at the
airport,'' Seles, 25, said. ``They're not my fault, and I'm not
causing them, but they're hard to get over. I'd have to be a robot
to lose someone as key as my dad and go on like nothing has
happened. I really miss his advice. On the road, I feel pretty
alone without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And now there's this thing in Yugoslavia,'' she said. ``I see
images from my childhood, bridges where I used to run as a kid
being blown up. You're hoping that it isn't your generation that
starts World War III. You're hoping somebody learns from what's
gone wrong in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles has.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, when she took a miserable bow to Arantxa Sanchez
Vicario in the final at Roland Garros, Seles couldn't help
believing she was destined to be a perennial victim of
circumstance, of adversity that started with the stab in the back
that cost her the top ranking in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was the first time she was forced to look outside
her life, which was kind of storybook, and notice that there was a
whole other world out there and some of it was bad,'' said Betsy
Nagelsen, a former player who, with her husband, Mark McCormack,
founder of the International Management Group, is a Seles mentor.
``Then just when she was getting back on track, she lost her dad. I
don't think she felt she could go on with her tennis when she
wasn't sure who or what she was playing for.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles was summoned home from the 1998 Italian Open when Karolj
Seles lapsed into what turned out to be a final coma. After his
death, she retreated to her bedroom and refused to venture out
until her mother, Ester, hoping tennis would be a tonic, persuaded
her to return to Europe and play the 1998 French Open as Seles and
her father planned.
</P>
<P>
   Seles' sentimental odyssey lasted all the way to the final, but
instead of looking back on her run as a sort of miracle, she
berates herself for taking an unprofessional attitude into the
match. Had she won it, she would have earned her 10th Grand Slam
title.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it didn't matter to me whether I won or lost, and you
can't not care in a Grand Slam final,'' she said. ``I was just
playing to play. I wasn't ready to fight. That chapter is closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles played through the rest of 1998 but didn't like what she
saw when she looked in the mirror at the start of 1999. ``In the
top 50 on the women's tour, you don't see anybody else in the shape
I'm in,'' she said. ``I'm not embarrassed to admit that.''
Especially not now that she has decided to shed the weight that has
crept onto her 5-foot-10-inch frame since 1993, when she quit
tennis for 27 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call it emotional eating,'' she said of her tendency to
nibble the nearest edible in stressful moments. ``Some people
drink, some smoke, some take pills, and I eat; it calms me down.
For the past seven years, you could tell by my weight how I was
doing emotionally.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides providing a glimpse of her disheveled emotional state,
the extra pounds acted like unwanted ballast on the tennis court.
``Back when I was No. 1 I was moving so quick, getting to every
ball,'' she said. ``And catching the ball early is really the basis
of my game. If you hit me 30 balls, I'd hit you 31. But lately I'd
be out there thinking, `I've got to finish this point in three
balls or I'm gonna be dead.'''
</P>
<P>
   It was fearful tennis, and she was tired of playing that way.
</P>
<P>
   This spring Seles hired Markus Kittler, a trainer and bodyguard,
to whittle her into shape with a steady diet of weight-training,
cardiovascular work, mealtime moderation and hectic sessions on the
Stairmaster.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Seles captured her first title in seven months, and
her first on clay since the 1992 French Open, at the Bausch and
Lomb Championships, and a week later she improved her Fed Cup
singles record to 10-0 while helping the United States sweep
Croatia. Her progress, and new platform on fitness, were not lost
on Billie Jean King, the Fed Cup captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's still got what she always had, her trademark, being
great off both wings with incredible accuracy, but if she will just
get in the best shape of her life physically, I think she can win
anything this year,'' King predicted. ``She can be No. 1 in the
world again whenever she wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Iva Majoli, the 1997 French Open champion, counts Seles as a
favorite in 1999. ``Actually, I thought last year Monica was going
to win it for sure,'' Majoli said. ``She can still hurt everybody
when she's playing good, and she's still at the top of the women's
game.''
</P>
<P>
   After watching Lindsay Davenport make a fitness commitment that
paid off last year in a U.S. Open title and the top ranking, Seles
is intrigued by the possibility she can do it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for her right now, getting back to her best tennis is
a case of `I've got to lose 30 pounds and hit a thousand balls,'''
Nagelsen said. ``She's not interested in listening to a sports
psychologist, not interested in trying to replace her father. But
here she is, No. 3 in the world and not even close to peaking:
that's the most incredible part.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
