<HEADER>
A7329 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUTDOORS-STRIPED-BASS     05-22 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-STRIPED-BASS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: STRIPED BASS RETURN OFF MANHATTAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By JOHN WALDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Bounding down Upper New York Bay under a soft May sun
on Friday, New York Harbor alive with pleasure boats, ferries and
tankers, it seemed a far better day for sightseeing than
competitively chasing stripers. But at 3 p.m., Manhattan's first
major striped bass fishing tournament had officially begun with a
horn blast at Chelsea Piers. The first annual Manhattan Cup, a
two-day event designed to focus attention on the wealth of stripers
that exists today in the Hudson River and New York Harbor, was
under way.
</P>
<P>
   At that moment, 22 boats, mostly run by charter captains,
dispersed all over New York Harbor to play their hunches as to
where they might find stripers under classic wrong conditions: It
was too pleasant for a fish notorious for cooperating best when the
weather is worst.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan Cup, a fund-raiser, was sponsored by the city's
chapter of the Coastal Conservation Association, a national
environmental group dedicated to preserving marine resources. By
7:30 p.m. Saturday, prizes were awarded for the largest striped
bass taken by fly fishing, lure fishing and bait fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The first Manhattan Cup didn't have the trappings of
commercialism associated with the freshwater black bass tournament
circuit, with its decal-laden, jumpsuited pros and large cash
prizes. This event was sweeter _ more a collection of city types
smitten by striper fishing.
</P>
<P>
   I was on board with an old friend, Captain Joe Shastay, and his
anglers, three stock traders: Brad Berk, Mike Cannizaro and Joe
Seminara. More than a decade ago, Captain Joe, as he is often
called, sensed the unrealized potential of guided sport fishing in
New York Harbor for stripers, bluefish and weakfish.
</P>
<P>
   Now in his ninth professional year, Shastay has seen bluefish
catches in the harbor go down, as they have along the rest of the
coast, but increased numbers of striped bass and weakfish have more
than compensated.
</P>
<P>
   Shastay stopped the boat near Bay Ridge in Brooklyn and anchored
over a small ledge. Brad and Mike wanted to compete in the
fly-fishing category, but fishing a wispy bundle of hair and
feathers is not easily done in a deep and murky harbor. Shastay has
developed an unnamed fly meant to resemble a diamond jig, perhaps
the premier deep-water lure. Ten inches long, sparkly, and with
large lead eyes, it is impossible to cast, but twitched deep in a
current, it is a fine, if not a definition-broadening solution to
harbor fly fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Although a nearby troller landed a husky striper, we went
fishless there and so Shastay headed up the East River. The first
stop was against the sea wall along the FDR Drive, where he
instructed the group to cast under a moored barge where ``last year
one of my fly fishermen hooked a striper so large it emptied his
reel.'' The fish ignored us here, too, but not the passersby _ it
was entertaining to watch the pedestrians and rollerbladers do
double takes when they looked down and saw us. A small gallery
formed. One woman with a baby stroller couldn't believe we were
simply fishing and asked if we were scientists searching for life
in the East River.
</P>
<P>
   Next, we tried an attractively fishy-looking field of rotting
pilings on the Brooklyn side of the river. Shastay relayed precise
instructions based on his years of experience: ``Cast five feet to
the left of the two shortest timbers and let the lure sink for 17
to 20 seconds.'' But no fish struck in the still sunny shallows.
</P>
<P>
   With time getting short before the first day's 7:30 p.m. finish,
we motored to some deep reefs in the East River near the Water Club
at 30th Street.
</P>
<P>
   We cruised around trying to located stripers with the electronic
fish finder while watching seaplanes take off and land around us,
busy on this Friday evening taking passengers to vacation homes
along far more pristine shores. Shastay marked a few fish on his
machine and our hopes were raised.
</P>
<P>
   Brad and Mike continued to ``fly fish,'' but Joe Seminara, the
realist of our group, put on a live eel. Quickly, he hooked a large
fish, but it soon came off. The tooth marks on the eel bait
indicated bluefish. This happened several more times _ a hard hit _
a 10- or 20-second fight before the blue sensed something was not
right _ and then he would reel up a wounded eel.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, though, Seminara had a strike and the fish stayed on.
Obviously large, it waged a strong battle complicated by an urban
touch, a plastic bag that became entangled in the line. Eventually
the bag fell off, the fish came to starboard, and Shastay leaned
over the gunwale, net in hand. After much splashing and grunting,
he hoisted a 17-pound blue _ admired, photographed and released to
fight again. Not a striper, and so, not a legitimate cup entry, but
a fine example of the riches of a healthy harbor and in keeping
with the spirit of the first Manhattan Cup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
