<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIRING WANNSTEDT LIFTS JOHNSON'S SPIRITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the tumult of January, when Jimmy Johnson's mother died and
he quit as head coach of the Miami Dolphins and then, in a flash,
returned, Johnson called a friend: Dave Wannstedt.
</P>
<P>
   Wannstedt was there to listen to Johnson the way Johnson had
been there to listen to Wannstedt during his six years of angst as
the Chicago Bears' head coach. The two have been doing this for the
last 23 years, since they met as assistant coaches at the
University of Pittsburgh. It was two years together there, four at
Oklahoma State, three at the University of Miami and then four more
with the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Johnson felt frazzled and disillusioned and
ready to leave behind an unfinished work in Miami. But then the two
friends brainstormed and stroked each other, and in a blink,
Wannstedt, dismissed in Chicago, was on his way to Miami as the
Dolphins' assistant head coach. Johnson and Wannstedt, reunited one
more time.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was asked at the National Football League's annual
meeting recently about his relationship with Wannstedt and what his
addition meant to Johnson and to the Dolphins. Speaking softly and
emotionally, he talked about friendship and comfort levels and how
he had his ``guy'' back. He said Wannstedt would tell him when he
was wrong more readily than his other coaches would. He had back
his jogging partner, and someone to whom, on occasion, he could
comfortably entrust the entire Dolphins organization.
</P>
<P>
   This is Johnson's fourth season in Miami, and this one is
different. Wannstedt is there. And Johnson believes this is his
most talented team in Miami, one ready to make a serious Super Bowl
run. Miami, which finished 10-6 last season and reached the second
round of the playoffs, did not lose any prime free agents during
the off season. It gained a few sparkling ones in defensive end
Rich Owens, tackle Kevin Gogan, wide receiver Tony Martin and
running back Tyrone Wheatley, and drafted impact players including
running backs J.J. Johnson, Cecil Collins and Rob Konrad. A defense
that allowed the fewest points in the league last year (265) still
has as its complement Dan Marino, a quarterback yearning to win at
least one Super Bowl late in his career.
</P>
<P>
   And no NFL team has a coaching setup quite like Miami's with
Wannstedt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit in on free-agency meetings, salary cap meetings, in
discussions with agents with Jimmy, on draft decisions, on
offensive meetings, defensive meetings, special teams _ I try to
cover all bases and walk in and not assume anything, offer a fresh
perspective and help to create a sense of urgency,'' Wannstedt
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy is head coach and general manager and everything that
goes on here goes across his desk. This is a team like some of the
others Jimmy has had, with youth and speed. It's going to be a
team, if it stays healthy, that can beat anybody. Sure, there is
Super Bowl talk. Every team believes it has that chance or it has
no chance. There is some reason here, though, to believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   There was not, however, in Chicago, where Wannstedt's record was
41-57, including 4-12 the last two seasons. Poor free-agent
acquisitions, poor free-agent retention and poor drafts _ in all of
which Wannstedt was involved _ helped doom him. .
</P>
<P>
   In Miami's voluntary practices this month, Wannsetdt has seen
good players. He will see more in Miami's minicamp beginning June
1. The Dolphins are especially strong on the defensive line, where
the starters Tim Bowens, Daryl Gardener, Jason Taylor and Kenny
Mixon are good. Wannstedt's specialty is defense. Maybe he can help
them become great linemen. Dominant ones.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to win the American Conference East, where the Jets,
Buffalo and New England reside, strong teams all. Wannstedt will
most likely work from the press box during games with both
offensive coordinator Kippy Brown and defensive coordinator George
Hill, piping information to Johnson on the sideline. He will be the
ears and eyes for Johnson while creating new opportunities for
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to try and help these young players mature into
dominant players and help this good team become a dominant team,''
Wannstedt said. ``I'm going to coach 'em and work 'em along with
the entire staff here and see if we can reach that next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's plenty of time for Jimmy and me to talk now. We jog
every day and some of our best work and ideas come then. How far do
we run? Depends on how many Heinekens and nachos went down from the
night before. I've been involved in four championship teams with
Jimmy, two at the University of Miami and two in Dallas. We
click.''
</P>
<P>
   Might the Dolphins now, too? &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
