<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTEBOOK: FAST STARTS FOR TWO ROOKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the draft picks already wooing their teammates and coaches
are Antoine Winfield at Buffalo and Daunte Culpepper at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Winfield, a cornerback, has impressed the Bills with his tough
style and big plays. At Ohio State, Winfield, who is 5 feet 9
inches, was known for playing in a fashion bigger than his size
indicated. But Buffalo has found that his quickness and speed are
even better than perceived. There is every indication, already,
that he will be a Bills starter.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper is soaring with the Vikings, where for now he is an
understudy to the starter, Randall Cunningham, and Cunningham's
backup, Jeff George.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had him rated as the highest player in the draft,'' said
Dennis Green, the Vikings head coach. ``Anytime you take a
first-year quarterback and put him in the sophisticated offense
we've had in place for eight years, you expect a rookie to look out
of place. But this looks second-nature to him. He's got it all _
size, speed, competitiveness and character, and he's making the
plays.''
</P>
<P>
   When Minnesota drafted Culpepper, there was instant murmuring of
``Culpepper to Moss.'' The quarterback to the rookie receiver from
a year ago, Randy Moss, could become an NFL staple of the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy is a guy who splashed on the scene a year ago and is
barely 22 years old,'' Green said. ``Daunte and him have a chance
to do some great things for a while. Both of them have amazing
stories. They make you open-minded. They take you outside of the
box.''
</P>
<P>
   A Steward for Stewart
</P>
<P>
   It got ugly for Steelers quarterback Kordell Stewart last year:
five consecutive losses to end the season, a 7-9 record, only 11
passing touchdowns (10 fewer than the year before) and a sulky,
somber presence.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh head coach Bill Cowher did something about it. First,
he told Stewart and the world that this was still the Pittsburgh
quarterback. And then Cowher hired Kevin Gilbride, one of the most
organized, productive and efficient offensive minds in football.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year Kordell fell on his face and we all did,'' Cowher
said. ``It wasn't easy. But especially for Kordell, it was
humbling. I think he might have needed that. Now he knows how hard
it is to win and keep winning and stay there as a quarterback and
he appreciates the good times because of that down time. I have
every faith in him and that the new coaching from Kevin Gilbride
will make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Steelers made a tangible show of their faith, signing
Stewart to a three-year contract extension that means he will earn
$27 million over the next five years, including an $8.1 million
signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe in Kordell,'' Cowher said. ``You watch, this
year is going to be something, because Kordell is going to come
back awfully strong. I really believe it. I'm counting on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
