<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7336 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-PHILLIES-SCHILLIN     05-22 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PHILLIES-SCHILLING-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CURT SCHILLING'S APPROACH: COMPLETE AND CANDID 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether he is fairly paid or underpaid, Curt Schilling earns his
money. No, he more than earns it. He works overtime, both on days
when he is supposed to work and on days when he is supposed to be
off. In an era of pitch counts and pitcher pampering, Schilling is
the square peg in the round hole. He just doesn't fit.
</P>
<P>
   The dean of the Philadelphia Phillies' attractive young team,
Schilling is the reincarnation of Robin Roberts, the team's Hall of
Fame pitching star of the first half of the 1950s, a player who
more often than not completed what he started.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Schilling led the major leagues in pitchers'
blue-collar statistics, working 268 2/3 innings and throwing 4,213
pitches, according to Stats Inc. Half of that work was the result
of a major league-leading 15 complete games, which matched the most
anyone has achieved since Roger Clemens completed 18 starts in
1987.
</P>
<P>
   Earning about one-third of Kevin Brown's average salary of $15
million, Schilling again leads in complete games with four, double
anyone else's total, and is near the top in innings pitched and
pitches thrown.
</P>
<P>
   He also apparently leads the league in outspokenness, which
resulted, he told some Mets players, in screaming matches with
Phillies managing partner David Montgomery and general manager Ed
Wade last Thursday. The confrontations stemmed from his comments in
interviews that ownership wasn't committed to winning.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies' officials took exception to his stinging remarks,
but they have never had a problem with his work ethic, which sets
Schilling apart from most starting pitchers working today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I approach the game as mine,'' Schilling said. ``With pitch
counts and all the junk that comes with being a young pitcher in
the '90s, it's not something a lot of teams are interested in
pushing their kids to do. They don't care to have them learn what
it's like to get a guy out for a fourth time without your good
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The questionable lesson, he said, is not lost on pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've run into a lot more guys who get pulled out after six
with a lead and have a smile on their face than guys who are angry
being pulled after six,'' Schilling said.
</P>
<P>
   This 32-year-old right-hander becomes angry with anyone who is
responsible for his premature departure, especially himself. He
puts in too much effort, he feels, not to be in a game in the ninth
inning. He is scheduled to start against the New York Mets at Shea
Stadium on Sunday, and he has been preparing for this start since
his last one on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm putting my Mets game plan together now,'' Schilling said
last week. ``I envision a way to get a hitter out, and there will
be variables to that. I'll get so and so out this way; he's the
kind of hitter who won't adjust, so I'll keep pitching him that way
unless he adjusts. This guy I have to change. The first at-bat,
I'll do this, the next time this. These are things I write down in
my notes and have on the bench with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``My whole mind-set in devising my game plan is to get ready to
get each hitter out three or four times a night. So I prepare to be
the guy getting hitters out in the ninth inning in their fourth
at-bat. I don't know any other way to get ready to pitch other than
going nine. I've never approached it any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   The tools of Schilling's preparation are as important to his
success as his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have notes on hitters, notes on umpires; everything I need
to be ready to pitch on the day I pitch,'' he said. ``I've been
keeping notes since 1992. I have every at-bat on my laptop. There's
no reason why I shouldn't be able to go out and win if I throw
strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   When Schilling had been in the major leagues for only a week, in
September 1989, after being called up by Baltimore, the Orioles
were playing in Texas, and he and his fellow rookie Ben McDonald
mustered the nerve to talk to Nolan Ryan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said there are things I can and can't do on days I pitch,''
Schilling related, recalling the conversation vividly. ``He said I
can't control the weather, the umpires or the emotional state of
the other team. But I can control one thing. I can be better
prepared than the hitters I face that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If preparation was that important to him, everybody else
should be playing catch up. It took me a while to figure out how to
do that. I've done it. I believe I'm better prepared than any
hitter I face.''
</P>
<P>
   But even the best laid plans go awry once in a while, no?
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to prepare so thoroughly that there's never a situation
that arises in a game that surprises me,'' Schilling said. ``I
might be not sure of myself because I have more than one idea, but
I'm never surprised because surprise is not a good thing. I've made
200 starts and never been shocked on the mound by something.''
</P>
<P>
   Schilling, who has never won more than 17 games in a season, is
off to his best start, with a 7-1 record, since the Phillies'
pennant-winning season of 1993. With Randy Johnson in the National
League, Schilling is unlikely to lead the league in strikeouts for
the third successive season, but he could still join Ryan as the
only pitchers in history to strike out 300 or more batters in three
successive seasons. He has 58 strikeouts and a 2.58 earned run
average.
</P>
<P>
   The garrulous Schilling did not reach this juncture as an
overnight sensation. He was traded three times in less than four
years before he established himself as a major league starter.
</P>
<P>
   Boston traded him and Brady Anderson to the Orioles in 1988 for
Mike Boddicker. The Orioles sent him to Houston with Pete Harnisch
and Steve Finley in a 1991 trade for Glenn Davis. And then the
Astros traded him to the Phillies in 1992 for Jason Grimsley, who
seven seasons later has revived his pitching career with the New
York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Now Schilling is the most sought-after pitcher in the majors.
Just about every contending team that does not have a platoon of
good starters is eager to acquire him by the July 31 nonwaiver
trading deadline, if not before. The hitch is that the Phillies do
not have to trade him; they have Schilling under contract through
the 2001 season.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Phillies could add to their nucleus of good young
players by trading Schilling, who has a no-trade provision, meaning
he has to approve the team he would be traded to.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first choice is where I'm at,'' the pitcher said. ``I want
to be here if something positive is going to happen with this club.
That's really up to the ownership of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing the Phillies' low, $30 million payroll, Schilling said he
has seen no signs in the last couple of years that the owners are
serious about contending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ownership has to step up and help, come the trading deadline,
and make a financial commitment to this team,'' he said. ``If they
don't want to do that, I don't want to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Schilling doesn't like what he sees in the surprising
Phillies, who are 21-19 after Friday night's 7-5 loss to the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a different environment to pitch in from what I've
been accustomed to here the last four, five years,'' he said. ``It
changes your mentality as a pitcher. Going through what we've gone
through, with nobody to blame but ourselves, for the last five
years, it's nice to see a big league club take the field every day
and not a patchwork collection of guys. We have an incredibly
talented nucleus of young players.''
</P>
<P>
   As complimentary as Schilling was about the team, he incurred
the wrath of Phillies owners and executives when he repeated his
comments about lack of commitment on Major League Baseball's weekly
national telephone conference call last Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Ed Wade, whom Schilling praised in the interview
for doing the best he could under the economic circumstances
imposed upon him, criticized his star pitcher for being anything
but positive about the Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Schilling's charge that the team hadn't tried to
upgrade its pitching staff with an established starter, Wade said
in a statement, ``There is not a club in baseball that has been
more active than the Phillies in its pursuit of starting
pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Schilling passed up the chance to play out his contract
and leave the Phillies as a free agent. He opted to stay, signing a
contract that will pay him an average of not quite $5.5 million a
year for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I chose to stay with the team that was loyal to me for two
years when I was hurt,'' Schilling said. ``Would I like to be
making twice as much as I am? Sure, who wouldn't? But I'm being
paid an obscene amount of money, even though it's half of what the
market value says I'm worth. I'm still making more money than 99.9
percent of the people walking the earth. And I get it for doing
something I've been doing since I was 4 years old.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1629EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
