<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     05-22 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: KNICKS DOMINATE THEIR FOES, AND OUR MINDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   All hands on deck. All shore leaves canceled. Nobody is going
anywhere while the Knicks are on a rampage.
</P>
<P>
   There are all kinds of sports going on this spring. College
lacrosse at Hofstra on Saturday. The Indy 500 next weekend. But I
know, I know, everybody wants to talk about the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   The basketball playoffs are like the old Sergeant Pepper movie,
with the Knicks flitting through the East, turning people into
stone in their wake. Tim Hardaway, as inert as an Easter Island
statue. Pat Riley, his features as frozen as a Mayan sculpture.
Steve Smith, the balls of his feet stuck to the floor like those of
a Degas dancer.
</P>
<P>
   My theory about the playoffs is that the Heat and the Hawks have
hit the wall, right on schedule, 50-plus games into the season.
That usually happens in February, with guys plodding through weeks
at a time and nobody noticing or caring. But in this season,
shortened by the lockout, the wall has arrived at the start of the
playoffs. Since the Knicks frittered away part of the season tuning
out Van Gundy and each other, they have energy to burn.
</P>
<P>
   Could be the Knicks will never reach the wall. It's quite likely
that the Indiana Pacers will devour the Knicks in the next round.
Jalen Rose will be to the Knicks what Latrell Sprewell is to the
Hawks. Mark Jackson will post up the Knicks' point guards, just as
a way of saying hi to his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball is not the only winter sport lingering into spring.
The Stanley Cup playoffs have an intriguing pairing between Buffalo
and Toronto, those two neighbors linked by Queen Elizabeth Way, the
highway where Americans try to puzzle out how many liters fill a
gas tank.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't it be nice to be near Lake Ontario in late May? Aw, but
you want to talk about the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   People want to talk about Marcus Camby, he of the tomahawk dunk
right over that international benefactor, Dikembe Mutombo.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago Camby was Exhibit A for the young and the clueless,
out of shape, out of synch, the kind of wastrel who could get a
general manager fired in an organization looking for a scapegoat.
</P>
<P>
   Now Camby is fresh and rested, sullen but somewhat short of
mutinous. The playoffs are all about matchups, and Atlanta has
nobody who can match his leaps. Camby is Jeff Van Gundy's secret
weapon. Say, do you think the sly coach kept him in wraps all
season just for this element of surprise?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there are so many other issues to discuss. Gen. Barry
McCaffrey, the White House director of national drug control
policy, still wants to investigate the impact of androstenedione,
the legal body-building supplement used last year by Mark McGwire
when he hit 70 homers. Most sports authorities have banned it as a
dangerous steroid, but baseball is banking on our soppy instant
nostalgia for that wonderful year of 1998, and we'll forget about
andro.
</P>
<P>
   Andro. Andro. Andro. Right, but you want to talk about the
Knicks. You want to talk about Chris Dudley, the hulk from Yale,
who sat for two straight games against Miami and did not let the
layoff ruin his attitude, and bellied up to Mutombo two games in a
row in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Subs are important. Back when the Knicks were really the Knicks,
people used to spend hours discussing the fine points of subs like
Nate Bowman, Iron Mike Riordan, Dave the Rave Stallworth and Phil
Jackson. What ever became of Phil Jackson?
</P>
<P>
   What with the Knicks and all, have you noticed that racing has
another chance for its first Triple Crown winner since 1978?
Charismatic has dashed through the Kentucky Derby and the
Preakness, en route to the Belmont, 13 days from today. Will it be
the cavern of the Garden in early June, or the fragrant barns of
Belmont? Maybe Rik Smits will get us outdoors in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   We really shouldn't be talking basketball. The weather's too
nice. Time to get out to the ball park and boo the third-base coach
for not flipping the ball into the stands. It seems that baseball _
this sounds like lawyer stuff to me _ is afraid of lawsuits
resulting from brawny louts (undoubtedly on andro) stomping
children in their zeal for balls tossed into the stands. The
post-strike goodwill era is over.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball had its own labor troubles. We all vowed we would not
recognize basketball this season, but here we are, talking about
the Spurs, talking about Iverson, talking about the Blazers,
talking about Bird's coaching, talking about Spree.
</P>
<P>
   I could tell you all about the FA Cup final Saturday, Manchester
United against Newcastle United, at Wembley. What's that? You want
to talk about the Knicks? The game is listed for 3 p.m. in New York
today, followed by Sprewell a few minutes later. Catch the sour
look on his face when Van Gundy calls his name. We are into the
subtleties of facial expressions. It's all about the Knicks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
