<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE TAMING OF THE SHREWD IVERSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ When we made a run, they were chillin','' said
Tyrone Hill, assessing the damage after his Philadelphia 76ers got
whipped again by Indiana, 97-86, Friday night here in First Union
Center. ``They're a veteran team. We're a young team. But we're
learning.''
</P>
<P>
   They'd better cram quick, call in a battalion of hoop tutors,
have their noses in their playbooks till game time, because they
play again this afternoon at home and face being swept in this
second-round playoff series.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tribute, however, to the team, and particularly the
coach, the peregrination expert Larry Brown _ this is the sixth
team he has coached in the National Basketball Association, and the
sixth different team he has taken to the playoffs _ that they are
here at all. Few expected a virtually new dramatis personae to
perform at this level, making the playoffs and then knocking off
the favored Orlando Magic in the first round. And as late as eight
weeks ago, it seemed highly unlikely, at best.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers had played the Cavaliers and Philadelphia's youthful,
exciting, gifted, high-scoring, resplendently coifed second-year
guard, Allen Iverson, had, as Brown recalls, ``run his mouth'' when
Brown had removed him from the game _ after 12 minutes and an
0-for-7 shooting night _ and sulked at the end of the bench.
</P>
<P>
   When Brown called to return him to action, Iverson repeated his
profane lecture to the coach. Brown stopped Iverson in his tracks
and sat him for the rest of the game, which the 76ers lost. Brown
told the news media afterward that Iverson did not play again
because he was ``hurt.'' The implication was not necessarily to the
ego.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the Sixers, who had added by trade, draft and
acquisition such significant new players this season as Matt
Geiger, Theo Ratliff, Eric Snow, Aaron McKie, Larry Hughes, George
Lynch and Hill, were contending to make the playoffs for the first
time since 1991. At practice the next day, Iverson showed up late.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't let this continue,'' Brown said. ``He's a young kid
and this is what young kids do. And maybe he was embarrassed by my
taking him out of the game, and it had become a public issue. But
still, I was going to confront Allen. I had to.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when Aaron McKie, a fifth-year veteran, stepped in.
``Coach,'' he told Brown, ``let us handle it.'' Meaning, the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But by me not doing anything, I don't want you guys to lose
respect for me,'' Brown replied. ``And I know Allen growing up had
it hard.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hold it, Coach,'' interrupted McKie. ``Everyone in that locker
room has had it hard. Allen's important to us. We've got a good
shot at the playoffs. We don't want to blow it now. Let us talk to
him.''
</P>
<P>
   And they did. They told the 23-year-old Iverson that it's ``a
mental thing'' for everybody to follow rules, to get the maximum
effort by being on time, practicing hard _ something he hasn't
always done _ and listening to the coach who all, including the
sometimes recalcitrant Iverson, seem to esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're competitive,'' McKie said to Iverson, ``the coach is
competitive. But you don't need to go overboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson listened. ``I gotta stop messin' up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the next game, when Iverson was given a rest, he came off the
floor and sat down next to Brown, to discuss strategy, of all
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allen,'' Brown said with a straight face, ``you're ruining my
image. Maybe you should get back to where you normally sit.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson laughed. And every time he comes out of a game now, he
sits beside the coach, including Friday night, when assistant
coaches and players all moved down a seat to give Iverson room
beside Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Allen knows when he's done wrong,'' Brown said. ``Some kids,
you can't reason with. Allen, you can. And I know where his heart
is. I know he's a good kid. And he's maturing.''
</P>
<P>
   On the court, Iverson often appears an unfettered athletic
genius, swift as an arrow, daring as a trapeze artist,
unpredictable as a kaleidoscope. But he does not always look as if
he is familiar with the depth and the nuances of the game of
basketball. He shot 13-for-33 Friday night, and seemed unable to
pace himself after having scored 20 points in the first half. True,
he understood that his team was involved in a critical game and he
must do all he can as soon as he can _ but still, the game is four
quarters long. And it appears he is reluctant to pass the ball
unless he is flying through the air and unable to get off a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows that a great player helps make his teammates
better,'' Brown said. ``And he is making progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Not enough for Julius Erving, however. It was Erving, the former
Sixers great, who said there are ``a hundred guys playing street
ball who can play like Iverson.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he took offense at the remark. ``Julius is one of the
classiest guys in the world,'' Brown said, ``and he is idolized in
this town. But for him to say that about Allen was terrible. Allen
and this team are underdogs. And he's a young kid trying to do the
right things. And he's doing exactly what the coach has told him to
do _ well, not a hundred percent, but he's getting there.''
</P>
<P>
   He's not there yet, and it seems unlikely that he will be there
this afternoon. But it's not impossible. There is, after all, no
accounting for genius.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1635EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0159 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7345 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-LEAFS-DRYDEN-2TAK     05-22 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LEAFS-DRYDEN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRYDEN'S DRIVE FOR SUCCESS IN TORONTO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Ken Dryden is a tall man accustomed to high
achievement. After entering the hockey Hall of Fame as a goalie,
earning a law degree and prospering as an author and television
documentarian, Dryden became president and general manager of the
Toronto Maple Leafs, who are to hockey in English-speaking Canada
what Notre Dame is to college football in the United States, only
more so.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of his second season as a novice executive, Dryden's
rebuilt team has soared from playoff absenteeism to the final four
of the Stanley Cup playoffs. The Maple Leafs will open the Eastern
Conference finals Sunday afternoon in Air Canada Center against the
Buffalo Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Friday represented a new height, even for Dryden, now 51,
slightly gray at the temples, hair a little thin on top. On the
Peace Bridge, well above the Niagara River, which separates Buffalo
and New York and the United States from Fort Erie and Ontario and
Canada, Dryden and John Rigas, the owner of the Buffalo Sabres,
climbed into the bucket of a cherry picker on a crane that lifted
them even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Outlined against a blue, May, transborder sky, they pulled ropes
to hoist the flags of their two teams. The banners temporarily
replaced those of the states and provinces and will remain there
until either the Maple Leafs or the Sabres win the right to face
either Dallas or Colorado in the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Dryden's brief speech, at the base of the flag poles, was more
down to earth. In discussing hockey, which he calls Canada's
national theater, Dryden often alludes to other sports or to
literature and film, and this was no exception. This series between
neighboring cities, he said, would produce scenes like one in the
basketball film ``Hoosiers,'' which showed the headlights of cars
filled with fans traveling between Indiana towns to watch ``their
team on the road'' in high school competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there will be a lot of that, going in both directions,''
Dryden said. ``So, let's let the games begin.''
</P>
<P>
   During the ceremony, as motorists lined up for customs and
immigration inspection, they honked their horns, called out to
Dryden and waved. A man from Welland, Ontario, who said he had
worked all night in an auto plant and had not yet been to bed,
approached Dryden in the midday sun and handed him a hand-lettered
sweatshirt that proclaimed Dryden ``Most Valuable President.''
After meeting Dryden, the man stood to the side with his wife,
hugging and kissing her, with tears in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   As Dryden walked to his car after the ceremony, a woman in an
official uniform, who had escorted him to the podium before the
ceremony, stood watching Dryden, her eyes wide, her gaze rapt.
Against the border guard's chest, protected by her crossed arms,
was the folded fabric of the American flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, nice to meet you,'' Dryden said to her, extending
his hand to shake hers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said, smiling and nodding in a way that bordered on
a bow.
</P>
<P>
   Back in his black Saab, Dryden steered toward Toronto, which is
about a two-hour drive from Buffalo on a road called Queen
Elizabeth Way. Next was a board meeting at Air Canada Center, the
Leafs' new arena. Like many athletes and former athletes, Dryden
drove faster than most motorists, shifting lanes and accelerating
with calculated confidence. As he drove, he talked, some of his
answers lasting 10 kilometers, which is 6.2 miles by American
measure. He spoke of his job, his sport, his life and how sport is
life and life is sport and work is sometimes fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Toronto Maple Leafs already were special,'' he said.
``What they needed to become is a successful team. They are an
important team, by definition, by being in Toronto, by the history
they bring to the game and to the league. But what the Toronto
Maple Leafs had not been, for a long time, in any consistent way,
was a successful team. And that was wrong. There wasn't a good
reason why they couldn't be. And the league was weaker for it and
hockey in this country was weaker for it and the fans were unhappy
for it and that's too bad. What you first need to do is sort of
break the back of 30 years of disappointment, resentment,
frustration, bitterness.''
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Leafs have done this, becoming not only winners
but also entertaining and high-scoring. In a decade of mechanical
defensive systems and dwindling scores, the Leafs blew like a
crisp, cool breeze out of Canada, a brisk wind of change. In the
councils of hockey bosses, Dryden's voice was heard and heeded. It
probably did not hurt that he attended Cornell, the same school as
Commissioner Gary Bettman, although Dryden graduated before Bettman
arrived. Dryden got the league to move the Leafs from the Western
Conference back to the East. Although he was a great goalie, Dryden
argued against large goalie equipment and the unfair advantages it
gave netminders and helped write new rules to restrict it. And he
argued forcefully against the hooking, holding and interference
that negates skilled players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge is for offense to overcome defense,'' Dryden
said, saying the balance had become ``out of whack.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``We're doing somewhat better that way but we need to
still do better.''
</P>
<P>
   His car sped along, around big trucks, slowing down as it went
past a police car, then gradually picking up the pace. Dryden
laughed as he spotted a sign above the one welcoming drivers to
Stoney Creek, Ontario. The sign said, ``Go, Sabres, Go,'' and
Dryden said, ``I wonder how long that sign will last.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In response to questions, he changed topics as smoothly as he
changed lanes. He talked of how he micromanaged much of the decor
of the new arena, insisting that photographs that hung in the
corridors of old Maple Leaf Gardens be enlarged and placed in the
halls of the new building. That, he said, is the way to make a new
arena feel like home. Some scenes from ancient games can be viewed
from the sidewalks outside the new building, even when it is dark
and locked.
</P>
<P>
   And he insisted that black-and-white photographs of fans from
the 1940s and 1950s be displayed around the rim of the seating
areas, between the high and low bowls, so that modern fans would
have a connection with the past. High above them, on big, blue
banners that hang from the rafters, Dryden designed and displayed
photographs of past Leaf greats, some of them deceased, their
motionless eyes gazing down over current players and fans.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on the bigger picture of sport and life, Dryden said,
``In the last generation, sports has become mainstream in terms of
life,'' no longer just ``this separate, idealized world.'' He seems
to see himself as a producer, director and guardian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure there are many experiences through which people
learn more than they do through sport, and watching that drama
night after night, year after year, on the television screens and
through the newspaper,'' Dryden said. ``Kids are learning lessons,
parents are learning lessons. That's what you are picking up: `Be
like so-and-do. Don't be like somebody else.' In what other area
are more people experiencing the same things as vividly? It's
there, uncontrollable, right there in front of you. For good and
bad, sport has immense influence.''
</P>
<P>
   He paused, perhaps aware that his voice had become louder, with
emotion, his hands briefly leaving the steering wheel as he
gestured. Dryden remains in touch with his childhood self as a
sports fan. He talked of how his father took him on a tour of major
league baseball parks one summer and of how he did the same thing a
few years ago with his son, now in college. He still has, Dryden
said, a letter from Elston Howard, the late Yankee catcher, which
Howard wrote to him in the 1950s, when Dryden was a boy and Howard
was a young prospect playing for a minor league team then called
the Toronto Maple Leafs. Dryden recalled getting Frank Mahovlich's
autograph four times as a schoolboy when the Big M was a Leafs
hockey star.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's supposed to stand for a moment of connection,'' he said
of autographs. ``Don't you remember when you were a kid and you
asked for autographs? Have you forgotten? For a moment, I felt like
I was in the same world as Frank.''
</P>
<P>
   He said a child's relationship with an athlete, even if they
never meet, is an early chapter in a book of that child's life
story.
</P>
<P>
   So many subjects, so little time. The car purred through
Hamilton and Burlington and Oakville and Mississauga. By now, the
city skyline loomed, the soaring CN Tower, the retractable white
roof of the Skydome, the steel and glass skyscrapers among the
low-rise piles of Victorian bricks that make Toronto seem to some
like the emerald city of Oz. When the conversation veered somehow
into mountain climbing, Dryden told of meeting a man who climbed a
peak called K2 in the Himalayas and how, on the way down, the man's
companion slipped and fell and died. When he was 20, Dryden said,
he might have tried something like that. But in his middle age, he
said, such things aren't worth the risk. His climbs and journeys
now are more metaphorical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come some distance,'' he said of his team's progress.
``It's a fragile distance. And it can be reversed. The distance
from the bottom to the top is just not as far as you think it is or
as far as it used to be. The bad news is the reverse is also true.
It doesn't take much to fall very far, very fast.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1640EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7350 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-22 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SOCCER MOMS WHO PLAY ARE AN EXAMPLE FOR CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest sports trophy in my house does not belong to me or
either of my young sons. My wife carried it home several weeks ago
after her soccer team won its league's inaugural championship. The
boys were more startled by the size of the trophythan the fact that
their mother had won it, or that she even plays a game that most
suburban children believe to be their precious and exclusive
domain.
</P>
<P>
   And this, I believe, has not only been a triumph for her but for
them.
</P>
<P>
   At 40, my wife, Beth Albert, took up soccer this year, and her
team immediately claimed its place in the boys' coterie of teams to
root for. For children 9 and 5, granted, there is a capricious
nature to these things, but last week, given a choice between the
Knicks' playoff game on television and the Bluestone Belles against
the Pokemoms over at our town's indoor soccer facility, they left
their father home alone on the couch with his clicker and the
chips.
</P>
<P>
   I couldn't help smiling as they trudged out the door, promising
to behave. I recalled the questions raised by my colleague Robert
Lipsyte about a runaway jock culture that continues to produce
raging specimens who can't distinguish between an opponent standing
in their way and a woman getting on their nerves. On the subject of
the potential remedies, Lipsyte requested of readers, if we may
assume society isn't about to wake up one morning in a less
fanatical sports mood, it is logical to hope that more of the same
for women and girls is one path toward heightened mutual respect,
if not a solution unto itself.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Junior may not be as likely to bask in his
athletic and physical superiority if he is told enough times that
he can't have the field this afternoon, because his sister's
playing at 2, and then, if he's really lucky, his mother's on at 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Treat your daughters as you would your sons, and be conscious
of the fact that you may not be,'' writes the soccer coach and
trainer Ashley Hammond in a new book, ``Goal! The Ultimate Guide
for Soccer Moms and Dads'' (Rodale Press), co-authored with the
writer Gloria Averbuch.
</P>
<P>
   More than two-and-one-half decades after Title IX, this may
sound like obvious advice but the truth is that it may not feel
entirely legitimate in a sports universe so conditioned to ascribe
greater significance to what boys and men produce on the field. As
a father who has been involved in sports his entire life and has
even coached his beginner kids in an unfamiliar game, I'll be
honest: it feels very strange to have been so abruptly displaced as
the hip sports parent, the one who leads by example and whose
tactical advice has greater weight. Strange, but equally thrilling
to know that my sons now recognize their soccer mom as someone who
packs serious clout, along with game-day snacks.
</P>
<P>
   Opportunity doesn't necessarily beget equality. It wasn't until
last year that Hammond, who came to the Essex County area of New
Jersey area about a decade ago from England, decided to
``experiment,'' to train an under-8 girls' team as seriously as he
trained the boys. That meant more practices, harder practices, in
bad weather. Many parents were skeptical, and even Hammond had
preconceived notions, but his conclusion after one season of
perfect attendance and convincing achievement was this: ``Don't set
limits. If you treat them as soccer players, they will go out and
work as hard, if not harder, than any of the boys' teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Averbuch, the mother of two soccer-playing daughters, has stood
on the sideline this year and watched her 12-year-old, Yael,
compete on an elite boys' 13-and-under team. For a mother, the
athletic achievement in itself has been inspirational but nothing
compared to the moment when an opposing coach could be overheard
lecturing his players: ``I don't want to hear one remark. I've seen
her play and if you underestimate her, she'll leave you flat on
your behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Many advanced young girls compete with boys but the overwhelming
majority are separated before they can read. Then their games are
often treated as lesser events, friendly mornings outside, gender
equity exercise. Turn on the sports talk radio shows and there are
nothing but snickers if a caller dares broach the subject of
women's basketball or the coming Women's World Cup. Getting the
chance to play sports is one thing. Getting men to recognize that a
women's game is just as meaningful is another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that 42 percent of the kids playing soccer nationally
are girls is an extraordinary statistic,'' Averbuch said. Her point
was that this grass-roots game, probably more than others, presents
an important opportunity for parents to help re-pattern the way
boys view girls and, by extension, the way boys view boys.
</P>
<P>
   In the endgame, a more important trophy is the son who grows up
not thinking he's the sun and that women are in orbit around him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1647EDT &QL; 
