<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7365 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEENS-BREAKINGUP-COX     05-22 1571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEENS-BREAKINGUP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Teen breakups can be a prescription for depression and
destruction
 &HT;    EDs: For use with follow-ups on school shooting stories
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jay Bakker, a youth minister, was enjoying a midnight dinner
last week at an Atlanta restaurant when his beeper went off. It was
a teen upset about breaking up with her boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Through her tears, she apologized for intruding so late. But
Bakker, director of Revolution - a ministry for adolescents - was
thrilled he could be there for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm only 23, so I'm not so far away from the pain these kids
feel,'' said Bakker, whose youth group is run out of Mt. Paran
SafeHouse Ministries of Atlanta. ``I remember what it was like. I
remember the stress and the agony. And I remember what it's like
not to have anyone to talk to.''
</P>
<P>
   The demise of a love affair is tough on anyone, but it can be
particularly hard on teenagers, who don't have the coping skills,
social network or the ability to control their emotions that most
adults do, child psychologists say. That volatile adolescent mix
can make a breakup a prescription for depression and destruction.
</P>
<P>
   Failed romances are believed to have played contributing roles
in several recent school shootings, including Thursday's rampage at
Heritage High School in Rockdale County in suburban Atlanta. As
investigators seek motives, it's not uncommon to find that romantic
breakups preceded these frightening blowups. For instance: _ A
Fayetteville, Tenn., honor student opened fire on his classmates
last May, killing a student who was dating his ex-girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two Jonesboro, Ark., boys, ages 11 and 13, killed four girls
and a teacher in March 1998 after they pulled a fire alarm and shot
people as they fled the building. One of the boys said he was angry
in part because he had been dumped by his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Pearl, Miss., 16-year-old killed his mother and then shot
nine students at his high school in 1997. Two died, including his
ex-girlfriend _ who apparently was a primary target of the shooter.
</P>
<P>
   The pattern was repeated again this past week in suburban
Atlanta, where a disgruntled 15-year-old opened fire into a crowd
of students at Heritage High. Friends of the sophomore, a former
Boy Scout, said he had broken up with his girlfriend of two years
just two days before the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, these sorts of things happen when you have someone
who doesn't have a very strong sense of self,'' said Dr. Ken
Fleishman, a psychiatrist and medical director of Laurel Heights
Hospital, an Atlanta mental-health facility for children. ``The
person gets a lot of self esteem from the relationship. But when it
breaks up, they experience a complete loss _ not only do they lose
the relationship, but their own self-worth. And in some cases, this
causes them to get very angry and strike out.''
</P>
<P>
   But break-ups are never the sole reason for violence in the
classroom, experts say: A tapestry of factors are involved. But the
loss could either mark a teen's final severing of ties with loved
ones or be the killing blow to a child's fragile ego. More than
half of teen suicides, for example, are preceded by a troubled or
broken relationship, psychologists say. Almost 2,000 teens
committed suicide in 1996, according to the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some people, break-ups make them feel all alone and
unloved,'' said Dr. Nadine Kaslow, chief psychologist at Atlanta's
Grady Health System and an Emory University professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But adults know that won't always be the case, they have
enough experience to know they can survive this. Teens, on the
other hand, sometimes don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Teenage love affairs are nothing new, but experts say today's
lifestyles have intensified what already were a strong brew of
emotions in young people.
</P>
<P>
   A key difference: Families are more fractured than in past
generations, with some teen couples depending more on each other
than on their parents, who may be separated, divorced or simply too
busy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a big void nowadays in some family situations, '' said
Steve Richardson, a language arts teacher and basketball coach at
Parkview High School in Lilburn, noting that he knows nothing about
the Rockdale suspect's family. ``Kids are just human beings, they
want to be loved, they want to be cared for, and if they don't get
that at home, they put all their emotional eggs in one basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when it fails, it's a lot harder on them.''
</P>
<P>
   David Issa, a junior at Dunwoody High School, said some
teenagers start to depend on each other too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes a sickness,'' Issa said. ``They start isolating
themselves and only want to be with each other. And finally, they
end up warping what was a healthy relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   And teenagers are more sexually active today, which means they
may be getting in too deep too fast. There's a higher probability
that things will go awry for any number of reasons, including
unplanned pregnancy, sexually transmitted disease or simply because
one partner is less committed than the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen situations where the girl might feel obligated to
have sex, and eventually she does,'' said Tani Gaan, a senior at
McIntosh High School in Peachtree City. ``But then things break up,
and they're angry and hurt. They'll say, `Here, I gave all this up,
and now it's just over.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gaan said some teen couples magnify the problem because they
drop their friends in order to spend all their time together. ``In
those cases, they look around and find they're lost'' after a
breakup, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half of high school students have had sex, according to
studies by the CDC. And that figure has risen steadily for two
decades to a record 54 percent in 1991 _ although it dropped to 48
percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sexual activity at such a young age has been detrimental for
teens,'' said Lisa Terry, a Roswell counselor. ``Oftentimes, they
don't know what they're doing; they don't have the life skills to
manage it. Simply put, they're playing with toys they shouldn't be
playing with.''
</P>
<P>
   If teens are having sex, they run the risk of not only having to
deal with emotional rejection, but sexual rejection too _ and being
embarrassed about the whole thing. Unlike adults, who may keep
details of their personal lives limited to a handful of family and
friends, teens must face the scrutiny of high school, which means a
jury of hundreds. And those who fail to pass muster must find their
way at a time when they are most concerned about their image.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one, whether they're a teen or an adult, likes being made
the fool,'' said Dr. Lyndon Waugh, an Atlanta child psychiatrist
and author of ``Tired of Yelling: Teaching Our Children to Resolve
Conflict'' ($22.95, Longstreet).
</P>
<P>
   Children, meanwhile, are bombarded with images of violence _ and
not only in the media. Many learn the lessons of violence in their
own homes. In 1997, close to 1,000 women were killed by their
husbands or boyfriends, according to the Federal Bureau of
Investigation. And the FBI reports that a man beats a woman every
12 seconds in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an increasing awareness that (violence) is an action
you could potentially do,'' Waugh said. ``It's not abstract
anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   What's needed, experts say, is for more adults to pay attention
to teens with broken hearts, and to respond to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teen romances really do feel like real love to the kids,''
Waugh said. ``But teens feel the adult world at times discounts the
relationships and the very real nature of their pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Too often, Bakker said, a teen's deep sadness goes undetected or
is written off as a harmless mood swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teens may not want to talk to their parents; after all, this
is a time they're hesitant to talk to them about anything,'' said
Dr. Tom Cummins, a pediatric psychiatrist at Emory University
School of Medicine. ``But a parent (needs to) say, `Hey are you
okay? I know you just broke up and that's got to be tough.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Parents also should point out that a shattered relationship is a
normal experience, without belittling it, experts say. And parents
can offer to let their children talk to someone else _ a counselor,
minister or family member who might give them a broader perspective
on love.
</P>
<P>
   ``You think it's the end of the world, no matter what anyone
tells you,'' Kaslow said.
</P>
<P>
   If they see certain warning signs, however, adults need to take
action beyond words. If a child's grades drop, his eating or
sleeping patterns change, and he's no longer taking calls or
hanging out with his friends, it's a warning flag. And if a teen is
talking about killing himself or others, or shows a newfound
interest in weapons, it's time for friends and family to step in
and get help.
</P>
<P>
   The Heritage High sophomore, for example, talked about killing
himself and bringing a gun to school almost a week before he shot
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a good side to all of this,'' Kaslow said of the
recent incidents, ``it's that this has been a wake-up call to many
parents.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry agrees. In her practice of two psychiatrists and three
counselors, ``things have never been busier.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that parents are far more attuned now,'' she said.
``They're finally paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
