<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7367 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LOUIMA-WITNESSES-2     05-22 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LOUIMA-WITNESSES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO ONE CRIES `RAT' AS OFFICERS TAKE STAND IN LOUIMA TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KEVIN FLYNN and KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Listen hard for the slurs like ``rat'' or ``cheese
eater.'' Listen again for the hissing anger that New York City
police officers often show toward colleagues who tell on their
brethren.
</P>
<P>
   It is curiously missing from the case of Abner Louima, a trial
in which four officers have come forward to testify against Officer
Justin Volpe, who is charged with torturing Louima in a Brooklyn
station house.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some muttering, for sure, about the officers who
took the stand. Detective Eric Turetzky even got a few disturbing
phone calls at night with no one on the other end. But there has
been no great chorus of disapproval directed at them, just as there
has been no great demonstration of support by fellow officers for
Officer Volpe or the four other officers indicted in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody has a problem with them testifying,''
said a detective from Manhattan with 14 years on the job. ``In a
situation like this, these guys coming forward and stating what
they saw, and being honest, can only help the department.''
</P>
<P>
   To some, such statements suggest that the unwritten rule of
reticence so ingrained in police culture, the so-called blue wall
of silence, is beginning to fade, just as the Mafia oath of
silence, omerta, dissolved as informer after informer came forward
to break the bond.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews in four boroughs with two dozen officers of
different ranks, many said the Louima case was so aberrant that
they did not believe the muted response to these station house
witnesses reflected any historic shift in police attitudes toward
officers who break the code of silence.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they said the alleged assault, in which Louima says he
was sodomized with a stick, was so savage that it was difficult for
most officers to identify with those who were indicted or to summon
outrage against those who have helped prosecute them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never inform about anything petty,'' said a patrolman
in his 40s, who has spent two decades on the force and now works in
a plainclothes detail in the Bronx. ``Most cops would turn their
back on it because they don't think cops get a fair break and they
believe cops get punished more than they should. But this is such a
reprehensible, sadistic thing. This is not about protecting another
cop.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, veteran officers say they sense a change in officers'
attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it different than it was 20 years ago?'' said Lt. Anthony
Garvey, president of the Lieutenants Benevolent Association. ``It
is. There seems to be more of a willingness to testify.''
</P>
<P>
   A homicide and narcotics detective, with more than 20 years on
the force, agreed as he sat on a stool inside O'Hanlon's Bar on
East 14th Street. ``Twenty years ago, maybe some of these cops
would have just walked away. But 20 years ago, this might not have
happened. Another cop would have stopped them. Somebody would have
said, `What are you, out of your mind?'''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the officers interviewed, most of whom refused to speak
without a promise of anonymity, said they were still withholding
judgment on whether the attack in the bathroom of the 70th Precinct
station house had actually happened as Louima described. ``They're
being tried in the media, and it isn't fair,'' said Officer Jesus
Aponte, outside the 76th Precinct station house in the Carroll
Gardens section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But as the layers of testimony from fellow officers built upon
one another over the last two weeks, several said they were
beginning to believe that a crime had occurred.
</P>
<P>
   None of those interviewed expressed hostility toward the
officers who had testified, although few were inclined to call them
heroes. Several questioned whether the officers had come forward
because they feared that to do otherwise would have hurt their
careers or led them to be accused of withholding evidence.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than a week after Louima was hospitalized in August
1997 before some of the officers came forward under pressure from
investigators to tell what they knew. One of them, Mark Schofield,
has admitted holding back for eight days because he was too scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fear motivated their testimony more than honesty or some
higher calling,'' said a captain assigned to an investigative job
in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   A 43-year-old lieutenant from the Bronx said: ``I don't know if
they are modern-day Frank Serpicos. They might be just guys with
promotions hanging over their heads.'' Serpico was an officer who
exposed police corruption in the late 1960s and early '70s, at the
expense of his police career.
</P>
<P>
   Turetzky, a patrolman at the time the attack is alleged to have
occurred, was transferred to the Internal Affairs Bureau after the
incident and later promoted to detective. The Police Department has
disputed any suggestion that his promotion was related to his
testimony. A third officer to testify, Kenneth Wernick, was
promoted to sergeant, based on his score on a civil service exam,
sometime after he came forward to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be very careful before we attach hero status to
them,'' said Lt. Eric Adams, co-founder of 100 Blacks in Law
Enforcement Who Care. ``For the first time in history we saw an
aggressive, strong-arm police investigation where they compelled
officers to come forward. These officers did not come forward out
of the goodness of their heart.''
</P>
<P>
   The commander of a precinct in Manhattan said he was,
nonetheless, impressed with the courage they demonstrated. ``I
don't know if it is something I could do or something that guys
with my time on the job could do,'' he said. ``You are taking a
chance of being ostracized for the rest of your career.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department insists that retaliation has decreased
significantly since the days when whistle-blowers lost friends,
received dead rats in the mail and suffered mysterious acts of
vandalism. ``This is so beyond belief that I don't perceive there
should be hard feelings against these guys,'' said a supervisor for
a squad in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   If that sentiment proves true, then the department has come a
long way in the three years since Officer Daisy Boria took the
stand and contradicted the account of her partner, Francis Livoti,
who was ultimately convicted of federal civil rights violations in
the choke-hold death of Anthony Baez in the Bronx. Officer Boria
was shunned immediately, and concerns for her well-being grew so
great, she said, that her superior officer in the 46th Precinct
checked her locker hourly for tampering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Daisy was completely ostracized,'' said Susan Karten, a lawyer
for the Baez family. ``She had to wear a bulletproof vest to come
to court. She was a completely demoralized women then and she still
is now.''
</P>
<P>
   Officer Boria's brother, Jeffrey Ramirez, said: ``Whenever you
are going against so many of your colleagues and tell the truth,
that's how it is, a lot of looking over your back and a lot of
threats. But I am very proud of her, and I think she is very proud
of these four cops who are now following in her footsteps in the
Louima case.''
</P>
<P>
   Officer Boria, a 17-year veteran of the force, is in the process
of leaving the department, according to one of her lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Baez case was a patrol incident, the type in
which officers often find a way to extend the benefit of the doubt
to their peers because they identify so closely with the pressures
of working the streets, criminal justice experts said. For similar
reasons, officers have stood squarely behind the four Bronx
officers charged in the killing of an unarmed man, Amadou Diallo.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of officers have attended rallies organized by the
Patrolmen's Benevolent Association for the officers accused in that
case. No rallies have been held for the officers accused in the
Louima case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cops want to believe that their fellow cops could not be
capable of doing such a horrible thing,'' said Lt. Donald Jirak,
president of the Gay Officers Action League. ``But with the Diallo
case, the reaction was different. Everyone was, ``Oh, that could
have been me.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
