<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7369 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-NY     05-22 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SCHOOL-VOUCHERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL VOUCHER FOES UNITE IN NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Wis.)   (bl)  
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A broad-based group of religious, civic and political
leaders has organized to fight Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's push for
publicly financed school vouchers in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The group, called the Emergency Campaign Against Vouchers,
attracted about 200 people to a conference at New York University
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Noreen Connell, an organizer of the group and executive director
of the Educational Priorities Panel, a nonprofit organization that
monitors school spending, said the campaign was trying to provide a
counterweight to the well-organized foundations supporting
vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, she said, the group hardly compares in clout and
financial resources to the forces supporting vouchers. She said the
campaign's operating money has come from small contributions,
ranging from $50 from the United Parents Association, an
organization of parents with children in public schools, to $300
from the Citizens' Committee for Children, an advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   The city teachers' union, the United Federation of Teachers, has
provided copying services and materials while spending tens of
thousands of dollars on newspaper advertising in the campaign's
name, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad how well coordinated, how well monied, the other
side is,'' Ms. Connell said. ``On our side, there's no
coordination. Foundations are not forthcoming, and they're not
providing money or really attempting to prevent this sort of
right-wing assault on the schools.'' The group hopes to mobilize
public opinion against vouchers through rallies and teach-ins.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of vouchers include the Bradley Foundation in
Milwaukee and the Institute for Justice in Washington, which
mounted a legal defense for Milwaukee's voucher program in state
courts.
</P>
<P>
   Several speakers at the conference contended that Giuliani had
misrepresented Milwaukee's voucher program, which he has held up as
a model for New York. The Mayor contends that Milwaukee's program
provides low-income students with an escape from failing urban
public schools without compromising the constitutionally mandated
separation of church and state or hurting the students left behind.
</P>
<P>
   One speaker, Elliot Mincberg, legal director of People for the
American Way, a Washington-based group that opposes vouchers, said
60 percent of the 6,000 students in the Milwaukee program this year
were not even from the public schools, but had gone to private
schools last year.
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, the program has drained nearly $25 million in
state aid from Milwaukee's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``The overall view is that the program has, number one, hurt the
public schools, and number two, has not provided meaningful choice
for the poorest of public school students,'' Mincberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Coles, a senior adviser to Giuliani, questioned
Mincberg's analysis of the Milwaukee program, and emphasized that
under Giuliani's proposal, vouchers would be available to children
in public schools only and would go to the poorest 15 percent or 20
percent. Asked if the program would be made available to
prekindergarten pupils, who have not yet enrolled in either public
or private school, he said the grades to be included would have to
be negotiated with the City Council. But the goal, he said, was to
serve only public school students.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Fruchter, of the Institute for Education and Social
Policy at NYU, warned that the only effective way of stopping the
voucher movement was to improve the public schools. He noted that
the greatest support for vouchers had come from the parents of
inner-city schoolchildren attending failing public schools,
particularly black and Hispanic families. Support for vouchers
tends to diminish, according to polls, among suburban residents and
people with higher incomes who have access to better schools.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's proposal has drawn stiff opposition from Schools
Chancellor Rudy Crew, who has threatened to resign if it is
approved by the Board of Education. In his latest version, Giuliani
proposes to administer the program through City Hall, though it
remains unclear whether it would be financed by deducting the cost
of the vouchers from the public school budget or through a separate
revenue stream. To be enacted, the program requires City Council
approval.
</P>
<P>
   At the NYU event, state Assemblyman Steven Sanders, D-Manhattan,
and Arthur Eisenberg, legal director of the New York Civil
Liberties Union, said state law prohibits city government from
making substantial decisions about the use of state education money
without the participation of the Board of Education. They also said
vouchers violate an amendment to the State Constitution that
prohibits direct or indirect public financing of schools controlled
by any religious denomination.
</P>
<P>
   Coles said the Wisconsin courts had found that vouchers could be
used for religious schools as long as parents _ not government _
chose where to use them.
</P>
</TEXT>
