<SLUG> BC-ARIZ-HEALTH-REAL-845&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: FITNESS CENTERS FOR PATIENTS AND PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By VERNE G. KOPYTOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KINGMAN, Ariz. _ In an effort to make money and encourage people
to live healthier lives, the Kingman Regional Medical Center _ the
only hospital in this dusty desert town 180 miles northwest of
Phoenix _ opened a fitness center in February that follows a model
already established in hundreds of other communities in recent
years. It serves the dues-paying public as well as patients who
require physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the air smells of health,'' said Linda VanKirk, a
schoolteacher, who was sitting on a rowing machine in the Del E.
Webb Wellness and Rehabilitation Center, trying to catch her breath
after a workout.
</P>
<P>
   While the hospital's fitness club offers activities found in
traditional gyms, like weight lifting, there are some differences.
The clientele is, on average, older and has less athletic
experience; patients work out with therapists alongside healthy
members of the public and there are support groups for arthritics,
diabetics and alcoholics.
</P>
<P>
   Executives at the Kingman Regional Medical Center first
considered opening a so-called wellness center in 1995. At first,
they only wanted to build a cardiac rehabilitation unit. In the
end, however, they expanded the size of their plans many times
over.
</P>
<P>
   One of the reasons was to provide more physical therapy
equipment than was otherwise possible. Allowing the public to use
that equipment would allow the hospital to maximize its return.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor was to try to offset the low rate of
reimbursement from Medicare. It was also thought that making people
healthier would reduce the 124-bed hospital's high occupancy rate
so that seriously ill patients would be sure to have a bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of becoming defensive and building more beds, we took
the offensive and said, `Why don't we make the people healthier so
they don't need help?''' said Carla Malvick, the hospital's
spokeswoman. ``We want to target the 45-year-old who is in danger
of a heart attack so they don't come in the hospital with chest
pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Hospital executives hired a consulting company that advised them
about the complexities of opening a fitness center. Construction
proceeded after a survey showed that there was a large enough
client base to make the project successful.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the gym cost $3.5 million, of which $1 million came
from the Del E. Webb Foundation, a charitable organization that
finances health-care projects. The 35,000-square-foot facility was
built on land that the hospital already owned.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from exercise machines, the fitness center features an
indoor pool, a therapeutic pool, two racquetball courts, an indoor
basketball court, a walking track, an aerobics room, locker rooms,
steam rooms, Jacuzzi, conference room and library. The interior is
spacious and painted in the colors of a Southwest sunset.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its nonprofit mission, the gym offers reduced
membership rates for low-income people. It also plans to open the
facility to some charitable organizations free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the fitness center, which charges $41 in monthly dues
and a $100 initiation fee (including blood test, physical and
exercise prescription) for a single adult, has nearly 1,300
members. A few dozen physical therapy patients use the gym each
day.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, hospital-owned fitness centers appear to be a growing
phenomenon, with their numbers increasing from 150 in 1991 to
nearly 600 today, according to the Medical Fitness Association, the
industry's trade group.
</P>
<P>
   As is the case with Kingman, most wellness centers are situated
on the campus of their parent hospital and are built specifically
to be gyms. Some hospitals share the same building with their
wellness center.
</P>
<P>
   Robin Schuette, executive director of the Medical Fitness
Association, said that hospital-owned gyms are generally found in
small towns and suburbs, possibly because of the lower cost of real
estate than in major cities. Most are built by local hospitals or
small hospital chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the hospitals that are more attuned to the needs of
the community,'' Ms. Schuette said. ``They probably don't have the
bureaucratic layers of larger hospitals, which are more concerned
with things like acquiring physician groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Though there are companies that can be hired to manage fitness
centers, most hospitals choose to do the job on their own. If a gym
is managed properly, a hospital can expect a 15 percent to 20
percent annual return on its investment, Ms. Schuette said.
</P>
<P>
   The physical therapy performed in hospital-owned fitness centers
gives the facilities a natural base from which to draw members.
Many physical therapy patients sign up as gym members after their
rehabilitation is over.
</P>
<P>
   Among them are people recovering from heart attacks, injuries
from work and arthritis. Some of the patients in Kingman, typically
elderly people who are going to a fitness center for the first time
in their lives, said they would probably not continue to exercise
if they had to switch gyms after their therapy ended.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These patients do not appear to mind being rehabilitated with
the help of a therapist alongside regular gym members. Marilyn
Stoneberger, a sheriff's dispatcher who was getting therapy for an
injured shoulder from heavy lifting at work, said that the mix of
healthy exercisers and patients like herself ``seems to chime in
together.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It kind of gives you a little inspiration when you look at
some of these girls exercising,'' she said after working out her
arm and getting a massage from one of the therapists.
</P>
<P>
   If Kingman's wellness center is any indication, such facilities
are well received by their members. But traditional gym owners
criticize the nearly 80 percent of the wellness centers that do not
pay taxes because of their nonprofit status.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Dehaybib, who owns the Kingman Fitness and Racquet Club
in this town of 16,000, complained that such exemptions were
unfair. He said that because of its tax advantage, Kingman's
wellness center can charge lower fees than otherwise possible and
provide more services.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the upper hand,'' Dehaybib said. ``I'm struggling to
keep my nose above water. In November and July we have to come up
with big bucks to pay taxes while they don't. I can't compete
against that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Ablondi, assistant director of government relations for the
International Health, Racquet and Sportsclub Association, which
represents for-profit health clubs, is trying to level the playing
field by encouraging legislators to change laws concerning
nonprofit organizations. He said that the Wisconsin Legislature,
for example, passed a bill in 1998 that obligated nonprofit
wellness centers to pay property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have rehab programs, then those types of revenues can
be tax-exempt,'' Ablondi said. ``Where the issues gets a little
heated is when they begin aggressively marketing to the healthy
part of the community. We encourage them to do that, but they
should pay taxes. That goes beyond their mission of helping the
sick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
