<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-OUTLOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU'RE TALKING SWEEP, THE KNICKS AREN'T LISTENING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Chris Childs stormed out of the New York Knicks'
practice facility at SUNY-Purchase on Friday, flying past reporters
as if they were the Atlanta Hawks in transition defense. Asked to
give enlightenment on the Knicks' playoff performance, and perhaps
speak a word or two about the probability of advancing to the
Eastern Conference finals, the second-unit point guard kept quiet
and kept walking.
</P>
<P>
   You would have thought his Knicks were the ones trailing, two
games to none, in their conference semifinal series with the Hawks.
Had Childs been reminded that these are actually good times for the
Knicks, he might have put his hands over his ears and sped along
even faster.
</P>
<P>
   Heading into Sunday's Game 3 at Madison Square Garden, Childs
and his teammates are trying to forget about the 2-0 lead that
leaves them only two straight games worth of ball movement away
from an impressive sweep of Atlanta. The Knicks want the mind-set
of a desperate team fighting for a final playoff spot, of one
striving for redemption from a tumultuous regular season. After
all, that is the kind of thinking that has led to their vast
improvement and put them on a collision course with the Indiana
Pacers in what teases to be a suspenseful conference championship
series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't think about the fact that we're up, 2-0,'' said
Knicks starting forward Kurt Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be up two-zip,'' said Knicks assistant coach Don
Chaney. ``It puts an unbelievable amount of pressure on Atlanta.
But I don't even want to think sweep right now.''
</P>
<P>
   While fans and analysts are preparing for yet another momentous
matchup between the Knicks and the Pacers, who hold a 3-0 lead in
their semifinal series with the Philadelphia 76ers, the Knicks are
studying their history and hoping not to repeat it. Just moments
after the Knicks all but buried the Hawks by winning their second
game in Atlanta, Coach Jeff Van Gundy brought up the 1993 playoffs,
when the Knicks won the first two games over the Chicago Bulls only
to lose the next four.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the infamous series with Miami two years ago,
when the Knicks wasted a 3-1 lead and fell in seven games to the
Heat. But those were special circumstances. Patrick Ewing's career
nemesis, Michael Jordan, was playing for Chicago when the Bulls
aborted the Knicks' seemingly certain trip to the NBA finals. And
against Miami, Ewing, Allan Houston, Larry Johnson, John Starks and
Charlie Ward were suspended for one or both of the final two games
for their part in the Game 5 brouhaha between Ward and Miami's P.J.
Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more appropriate admonitions would be the 1994 series
with Chicago and Indiana, when the Knicks grabbed 2-0 leads over
both clubs before staggering to victory in seven games. And the
Bulls were without Jordan at the time. That was the last time the
Knicks advanced past the second round of the playoffs, something
they seem to be on the verge of doing for only the third time this
decade. But they don't want to hear that.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't feel too confident right now,'' Houston said. ``You
still have to take it one game at a time.''
</P>
<P>
   While the caution is appreciated, Atlanta does not appear
capable of endangering the Knicks in this series. The Hawks' status
as one of the best road teams in the league was clouded by their
two convincing first-round losses in Detroit. Moreover, the Knicks
played poorly in dispatching of Hawks by 77-70 in Game 2. It is as
true as it is discouraging that the Knicks are inconsistent, apt to
be brilliant one night and inept the next. But if their irritating
pattern continues, they will play well Sunday. In Game 2, the
Knicks' starters brought little, shooting 32 percent from the floor
and being outrebounded by 46-24. Houston, who blitzed the Hawks for
34 points in Game 1, scored only 2 points. And Ewing, clearly
slowed by his aching left Achilles' in Game 2, should be stronger
Sunday after getting two days of rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we didn't play the way we really wanted to play but we
have confidence,'' said Thomas, who managed only 1 point and 3
rebounds in Game 2. ``We're coming home and we want to have a good
outcome back in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, owners of the second-best home record in the Eastern
Conference, have a 32-13 record in playoff games at Madison Square
Garden in the 1990's.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to take care of business and win your home games, in
which case we would sweep,'' center Chris Dudley said. ``But you
have to be real careful and not have a letdown.''
</P>
<P>
   REBOUNDS
</P>
<P>
   If LATRELL SPREWELL and MARCUS CAMBY, the stars of the Knicks'
Game 2 victory, are feeling a sense of vindication for their
post-season play, they are keeping it to themselves. Sprewell, who
has scored 62 points in the two victories over Atlanta, was said to
be able to put up such numbers only on a losing team. ``I don't
really care what people say,'' Sprewell said. ``I'm just playing my
game.''
</P>
<P>
   While it is now doubtful that anyone would trade CHARLES
OAKLEY's rugged hustle for Camby's high-flying athleticism, the
young forward was castigated earlier in the season for not being
Oakley. ``Some people are going to rip me no matter what, so it
really doesn't matter,'' Camby said. ``I just go out there and try
to be myself.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
