<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL NOTEBOOK: THE TRAVAILS OF PENNY HARDAWAY; OAKLEY LOOKS
AHEAD; EVALUATING GRUNFELD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Anfernee Hardaway decided he was being disrespected by the
Orlando Magic again last week, treated badly by a franchise that
has merely acquiesced to his every demand since 1995. The fussy
Hardaway, grumpy and fed up, said he would exercise an option in
his contract to move to another team in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Penny. It was not enough that he engineered the firing of
the former coach Brian Hill in 1997, and that he did not have the
conviction to admit it afterward. Or that he felt so disconnected
from the current Magic coach, Chuck Daly, this past season that he
needed assurances from Daly that he was still a special player.
</P>
<P>
   You could look at this development as the final blow to the
Magic, an organization unable to capture its form from the NBA
finals four years ago. But that may be shortsighted, given that
Orlando has stocked its cupboard with capable young players and
appears to be on the verge of getting better.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, Hardaway's declaration may just be the latest example of
pro basketball's losing another bright, young star to petulance. He
is in a sense the first casualty of the post-Michael Jordan era, a
player with all the tools and talent to carry the torch, but unable
to do so because of his insecurities.
</P>
<P>
   If the star point guard's stance is another power play to make
Daly step down and force the Magic to give him what he wants, you
only hope management lets him go this time. Since his defining
moment in Game 7 of the 1995 Eastern Conference finals _ the day
Hardaway and Shaquille O'Neal stood atop the basketball world after
knocking off the Indiana Pacers _ he has led the Magic to a 3-14
record in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Included in that mark is a first-round loss in four games to
Philadelphia this month, a series dominated by a more resilient and
talented point guard, Allen Iverson.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando should have seen this coming. It's not the first time
that Hardaway has wanted out or shown that he does not particularly
care for his teammates. This is the former franchise player who
rehabilitated an injury specifically to play in the All-Star Game
last season at Madison Square Garden, then deserted the Magic for
the rest of the season and flew to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond firing Hill, the Magic has made numerous concessions to
keep Hardaway happy.
</P>
<P>
   One day last season, the former Magic reserve Derek Harper got
into a profane, trash-talking duel with Hardaway after dominating
him on the floor during and after practice. Hardaway became so
enraged and upset that he told a Magic public-relations employee to
go to his office for statistics showing how Hardaway had outscored
and outplayed Harper when the latter was with the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway later complained to management that players were
guarding him too tightly in practice. Harper was summoned by
general manager John Gabriel and was chastised for being too hard
on Hardaway. Take it easy on Penny, he's fragile, Harper was
essentially told.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Hill last season compared living up to Michael Jordan's
legacy with living up to Muhammad Ali's legacy. He called it ``The
Larry Holmes Syndrome.'' Hill drew parallels between himself,
O'Neal and Hardaway and the former heavyweight boxing champion who
just happened to succeed the Greatest.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all suffer from it,'' Hill said. ``We can't be Mike, so
many of us will never be appreciated for the players we were _ just
as people never truly appreciated Larry Holmes for his dominance.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardaway never had to be the next Jordan. He could have merely
been an all-star who eventually matured into a great player. With
each new petty grievance he airs, he gives new meaning to Little
Penny, his diminutive alter-ego on TV commercials. Little Penny, it
appears, has a long way to go before he grows up.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley Mulls His Future
</P>
<P>
   Charles Oakley is not saying whether he will re-sign with the
Toronto Raptors, but the chances are beginning to look slim. With
Gary Payton's agent imploring the Seattle SuperSonics to acquire
Oakley and Bill Walton singing his praises on NBC, suitors are
already lining up for him.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, 34, was offered a $12 million, three-year deal by the
Raptors earlier this season, but he considered the opening bid
insulting enough to make it public.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for Oakley is, Toronto can pay him more to play
power forward than any other team.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is, the clubs with enough salary cap room to pay
him handsomely include the Los Angeles Clippers and the Chicago
Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles may really surprise people where he ends up because of
having different priorities in his life and career,'' Billy
Diamond, Oakley's business manager, said. ``He's financially
secure. He doesn't need to make money. People tell me, `You mean,
he would turn down $8 million from Toronto to get a ring?' Look,
money plays a small factor in Charles' decision-making.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many veterans, Oakley will probably not sign with another
team until late this summer. Though teams can begin negotiating
with free agents on July 1, contracts cannot be signed until after
Aug. 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants to explore situations, find out who's drafted, who's
coaching and what free agents they're going to sign before
committing,'' Diamond said. ``Charles wants to be a part of a good
situation. He's not ruling out Toronto, but he is keeping his
options open.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottom Line on Grunfeld
</P>
<P>
   The temptation is to paint Ernie Grunfeld as a martyr, a deposed
general manager who was wronged after putting together the key
components of a Knick team headed full-steam toward the Eastern
Conference finals for the first time in five years.
</P>
<P>
   Relieved of his duties as team president with eight games left
in the regular season, Grunfeld is watching his vision of an
open-court, uptempo team come to life in the playoffs. His recent
acquisitions _ Latrell Sprewell and Marcus Camby _ are sparkling
against Atlanta, and his roster additions from three years ago _
Allan Houston, Larry Johnson and Chris Childs _ all played huge
roles in knocking off the Miami Heat in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld should be accorded approval for assembling the parts of
a team that finally rejuvenated itself, even though the Knicks may
not advance to the NBA finals this season, their stated goal.
</P>
<P>
   But to canonize his efforts now would be to overlook his obvious
shortcomings _ and to dismiss the actual reason Dave Checketts, the
Madison Square Garden president and a longtime friend of
Grunfeld's, made the decision to replace him last month.
</P>
<P>
   By failing to upgrade the point-guard position and weakening the
team at power forward in the off-season, Grunfeld set the team up
for imminent destruction against physical and poised Indiana in the
next round.
</P>
<P>
   And, other than a congenial ``How's everything?'' Grunfeld had
no relationship to speak of with many of the players. That made it
impossible for him to recognize and remedy the controversies that
gradually engulfed the team this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people criticize what I did, but I did what was in
the best interests of the organization,'' Grunfeld said last week.
``I still feel very good about it. And now it's starting to come
around. And people are starting to see why I made the decisions I
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Relieving Grunfeld of his duties may have been premature. But
whether the move was made during the season or afterward, he was
not going to make another key personnel move, however necessary,
for the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   That fact had little do with how he evaluated talent and
everything to do with his inability to comprehend his own
shortcomings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
