<SLUG> BC-NY-TAX-TUSSLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC COUNCIL SAYS IT MUST CURB TAX CUT PLANS DUE TO END OF COMMUTER
LEVY 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ City Council leaders announced Saturday that the
state Legislature's repeal of the commuter tax had forced them to
abandon proposals for at least $443 million in tax cuts for city
residents, including $173 million worth of cuts proposed by Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders said they had withdrawn plans to reduce the
commercial rent tax and several other business taxes, as well as
proposals to cut taxes paid by first-time home buyers. They also
said the Council had rejected Giuliani's proposals to eliminate the
sales tax on books, construction materials and clothing that costs
more than $110, which would have saved taxpayers about $113 million
a year.
</P>
<P>
   Council Speaker Peter Vallone said he and Giuliani had no choice
but to sharply curtail their tax cut plans, because the commuter
tax repeal would cost the city $360 million in revenue next year
and $400 million in 2001. The speaker and the mayor are negotiating
a budget agreement, and say they hope to adopt a plan by early
June.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had worked for close to six months on coming together on a
tax reduction package which would spur the economy,'' Vallone said
Saturday in a news conference at City Hall, where Council members
met to discuss the impact of the commuter tax repeal on Giuliani's
$35.3 billion spending plan. ``Now we have to, in 15 days, figure
out how to readjust the entire budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Vallone and Giuliani said that despite the repeal, they
still hoped to eliminate the sales tax on clothing that costs less
than $110 and to provide a tax credit worth $48 million for the
working poor. Other tax cut proposals that are still under
consideration include a property tax reduction for owners of
condominiums and co-ops, worth $166 million, and a tax credit for
families who pay for child care, worth $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   While the mayor and the Council usually negotiate a budget
agreement together, the Council has the power to adopt a budget
without the mayor's consent. But Joseph Lhota, the deputy mayor for
operations, indicated Saturday that the Giuliani administration
would probably not fight the Council's plan to abandon nearly half
of Giuliani's $405 million tax cut package.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their proposals are not inconsistent with what we are
discussing during our negotiations,'' Lhota said. ``We believe that
we will have a successful conclusion to our budget discussions and
move forward with adopting a budget in June.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Vallone also said Saturday that they hoped to restore
the $165 million in cuts in city programs and services that
Giuliani had proposed. But they said such restorations would be
more difficult than usual because of the unexpected loss of the
commuter tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Vallone said that with a record $2.1 billion
city surplus, he and the mayor would almost certainly not resort to
layoffs or further cuts in programs and services this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's highly unlikely that we are going to do anything that is
going to inflict unnecessary damage on the people of New York
City,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
