<HEADLINE>
N.Y. COLUMN: CITY'S ARTISTS ARE ITS PRIDE, AND A PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEEKSKILL, N.Y. _ This old river city made a pretty good living
in the last century as a factory and shipping town, but by the
start of this decade the factories and the ships were long gone,
and all that remained was a dying downtown and a declining
population.
</P>
<P>
   Then somebody had an idea: artists!
</P>
<P>
   Artists are a kind of pilot fish for gentrification, the City
Council reasoned. They like cheap lodging, they aren't fussy about
their surroundings, and yet they attract flocks of big spenders. No
pushy billionaire ever bothered the fishermen and potato farmers of
the East End of Long Island until artists started moving there at
the turn of the century. Soho did not even have a name, let alone
languid connoisseurs in expensive black clothes, until artists
discovered its industrial lofts.
</P>
<P>
   But artists also bring their prickly politics, as Peekskill's
City Council has learned in the 10 years of success in luring
dozens of painters and sculptors to the city's specially zoned Arts
District.
</P>
<P>
   It was a group of artists who tried last fall to change the name
of North Division Street to Paul Robeson Street, to honor the
singer whose concerts 50 years ago in nearby Cortlandt were
famously disrupted by racist rioters. Artists, too, are at the core
of a group that has protested loudly at recent Council meetings to
keep the city from installing police surveillance cameras at
downtown intersections. The city says there has been drug dealing
there, but Georgia Svolos, a sculptor who moved here from
Manhattan's Lower East Side five years ago, says she smells racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town council wants to gentrify Peekskill, and they want to
do it by pandering to the fears of the white people they are trying
to attract,'' said Ms. Svolos, who is white and a grandmother.
``They feel that fear of violence, a k a fear of blacks, is keeping
people away, so they want to put cameras on Main Street to make the
blacks make themselves invisible.''
</P>
<P>
   Peekskill Mayor Frances Gibbs said the anticamera insurgents are
a minority, and if she has any regrets about inviting them to
Peekskill, she isn't saying.
</P>
<P>
   Peekskill has about 60 artists at work now _ there will be an
``open studios'' day for visitors on Saturday _ and its reviving
downtown is ``like a cross between Mayberry and the Bronx,'' as
Lynne Nayman, a real estate agent, puts it. But unlike the Bronx,
Peekskill has not elected a Democratic mayor or Council member
since before a young Republican comer named George Pataki became
mayor in 1981, and this may have widened the gap between city
officials and protesters, who use ``Republican'' as a
self-explanatory slur.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Svolos was recently arrested, with Valerie Courreges, a
multimedia artist, and Nick Mottern, a carpenter and member of a
vegetarian restaurant collective, for violating the city's new
rules on addressing the council. A ``Cookies for Court Costs'' bake
sale last weekend raised $148.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Courreges, who came from Brooklyn, sees Peekskill's plan for
public cameras in the light of 19th-century prison design and
20th-century deconstructionist philosophy. ``Foucault wrote about
how architecture and design are made to surveil and control
people,'' she said. ``To me, the cameras are the technological
equivalent of Jeremy Bentham's panopticon _ it is like bringing the
prisons to the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Svolos said her group had collected 150 signatures opposing
the cameras, but on the streets there was considerable support for
them. ``I've seen things get worse since I got here,'' said Anthony
Soto, who works for the Veterans Administration and moved to
Peekskill from Manhattan's 110th Street and Lexington Avenue two
years ago. ``I think the cameras are a good idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Mucci, who recently opened Vintage Hudson Realty at Main
and North Division Streets, where one camera would go, is also in
favor. ``We're working very hard to create a historic district and
to promote business, and to attract people we need to get some of
those people off the streets,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters do not represent all of the arts community, said
Larry D'Amico, a painter. ``There are plenty of artists who are
opposed to the cameras,'' he said, ``but they are also opposed to
the tactics of this radical clique.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
