u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-LEGIS-ELECTION-NYT     05-22 0958
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGIS-ELECTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP GOES ALL OUT IN SPECIAL RACE FOR KEY STATE SENATE SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Gov. George Pataki has never publicly supported a
mandate that insurers cover infertility treatments, and his aides
say they do not even know his position on the idea. But several
Orthodox Jewish leaders in Rockland County say the governor spoke
favorably about it when he met privately with them to seek their
backing for the Republican in Tuesday's special election for the
state Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought it up and said he would be supportive of it,'' said
Rabbi Moshe David Tendler, who heads the Community Synagogue in
Monsey, the largest Orthodox congregation in the county. ``It's a
real issue in our community, because children are so important.
Having 10 children does not raise an eyebrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the governor could not confirm that he had endorsed the
mandate, which is contained in several bills before the
Legislature, but such a declaration would be notable, particularly
because Senate Republican Majority Leader Joseph Bruno has
expressed serious reservations about mandating coverage for costly
treatments like in vitro fertilization.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting between the governor and Orthodox Jewish leaders
last Sunday exemplified how, factions in the 38th state Senate
District say, powerful Republicans have romanced, cajoled, tempted
and even threatened them to win support for their candidate, Thomas
Morahan over Democrat Kenneth Zebrowski. As Bruno, said recently,
``We're pulling out all the stops.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual for the parties to go all out in a race in a
swing district, particularly since the Republican edge in the
Senate is less than overwhelming at 35 to 25. Bruno and Morahan
have been blunt about their main pitch to voters: that as the
majority party in the Senate, they can deliver more pork-barrel
spending to the district, which encompasses all of Rockland and
part of Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Senate has approved a school transportation bill
that would channel about $4 million to the East Ramapo schools, a
measure cited by Bruno as an example of the Republicans' ability to
provide for the district.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats and others say the brand of hardball being played
in this race is tougher than usual. Leaders of labor unions in
particular, all of them speaking on condition of anonymity, charge
that prominent Republicans _ especially Bruno, his colleagues and
his aides _ have implied or made outright threats that if the
unions endorse or work for Zebrowski, the bills they want to see
passed in Albany will die.
</P>
<P>
   Bruno declined to be interviewed about such claims. A spokesman
for the Senate Republicans, John McArdle, said: ``That is total
nonsense being pitched by Democrats. It sounds like the Democrats
already conceding defeat. No one is making any threats.''
</P>
<P>
   Unions are among the biggest lobbying groups and campaign
contributors in the state. They frequently seek bills for things
like increased pensions and union wage requirements on certain
projects.
</P>
<P>
   Several building trades unions have been lobbying the Pataki
administration, so far without success, to require that union labor
be used on projects at Stewart Airport in Newburgh.
</P>
<P>
   A leader of one union said: ``What we're being told is, `You
support Zebrowski, and the lines of communication will be cut, to
the Senate, to the governor's office.'''
</P>
<P>
   An official of another union said that people close to Bruno and
Pataki ``let us know that backing Zebrowski, we weren't likely to
see our bills get through.'' A union lobbyist said such threats are
not even necessary. ``It's understood, you want help that might be
a heavy lift, you don't work against them.''
</P>
<P>
   Laborers' Union Local 754 endorsed Zebrowski, but the statewide
union remained neutral and made a contribution to Morahan. The
union has been seeking to close loopholes in state laws requiring
that prevailing union wages be paid on state projects.
</P>
<P>
   The Civil Service Employees Association local representing
Rockland County employees endorsed Zebrowski. But then the union's
Region 3 council, representing 55 locals in the Hudson Valley,
voted to rescind that endorsement and back Morahan. The statewide
union, now in talks with the Pataki administration on a new
contract, supported that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Harnett, a lobbyist in Albany for the Laborers' Union,
and Carmine DiBattista, Region 3 president of the CSEA, insisted
that Republicans did not apply any pressure to reverse those
endorsements, but other union officials dispute that account.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate seat was left vacant by Joseph Holland, a Republican
who earlier this year became Rockland County's social services
commissioner. Each side says it will spend at least $400,000, a
high figure for a legislative contest, though the race began in
earnest just four weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent full campaign finance statements filed with the
state Board of Elections show that Morahan's campaign had collected
$39,000 as of May 10. Of that, $30,000 came from the Senate
Republican Campaign Committee, which also spent $94,000 on his
campaign indirectly. The Republican State Committee spent $50,000
on the race, records show. Supplementary filings show that the
Senate Republican Campaign Committee raised almost $100,000 on May
18 and May 20, much of which, officials said, would go to Morahan's
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Zebrowski's filings show he had raised just $39,000 by May 10.
The Senate Democratic Campaign Committee reported spending $94,000
on his behalf, but did not report any significant fund-raising in
the last week. The Democratic State Committee reported no spending
on the race.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
