<SLUG> BC-SOC-BRAZIL-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL'S FEMALE SOCCER PLAYERS GAIN RESPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Luis Miguel Estevao had what seemed an
impossible mission. Even in Brazil, where soccer is a secular
religion, women who wanted to play were often met with closed minds
instead of open arms.
</P>
<P>
   It was Estevao's job to build the Brazilian women into a power
rivaling the Brazilian men, who have won four world championships.
He might as well have been asked to open a ski resort in Alabama.
At the first Women's World Cup in 1991, Brazil was a distant ninth
to the Americans. Brazil did not field a real team, Estevao said,
``just a bunch of people who got together with no preparation.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Estevao gathered the top women's club teams and
organized a national championship of Brazil in the southern city of
Arceburgo. One of the local priests, Estevao said, went on strike,
closed his church and said he would not say Mass as long as the
women's tournament was in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that soccer was a men's sport and that if women
played, they were trying to be like men,'' recalled Estevao, the
general manager of the women's national team.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly, though, the cultural barriers began to splinter. When
Brazil was host to Argentina for the 1995 South American
championships, Estevao said, 80,000 fans attended the match. A year
later, Brazil finished fourth at the 1996 Summer Olympics. In 1997,
it defeated the United States for the first time. Nothing brings
legitimacy quicker than success.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Women's World Cup does not begin until June 19, but the
Brazilians have already arrived to play a series of preparatory
matches that began Saturday night against the Americans at the
Citrus Bowl. The Brazilian women now have the corporate backing of
Nike and Coca-Cola, the support of the top men's club teams and
salaries that can reach $6,000 to $8,000 a month for the top
players.
</P>
<P>
   The stated goal for Brazil is not to win the 16-team World Cup,
but rather to reach the quarterfinals, guaranteeing a spot in the
2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia. But the players and the
coaches want much more. Brazilian soccer comes with expectations
the way shirts come with collars.
</P>
<P>
   Told that the Americans are concerned about the Brazilians, whom
they could meet July 4 in the semifinals at Stanford Stadium, the
star forward Katia said: ``In the past, the U.S. would step on the
field and they knew they would beat us. We respect them, but now
they have to respect us as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Katia, 22, was a South American hurdling champion when officials
approached her before the 1995 Women's World Cup and asked her to
play soccer full time. She declined until the Brazilian soccer
federation offered to match her track and field earnings. In the
past three seasons, the tall, lean striker has scored 132 goals for
Sao Paulo in the Brazilian league.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Brazil's top forwards, Roseli, will miss the World
Cup with a knee injury. Also missing from the roster is Michael
Jackson, nicknamed after the pop star. ``She didn't really look
like Michael Jackson,'' joked Julie Foudy, the American co-captain,
who has played against her, ``but she did wear one glove.''
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian women play soccer the way the men do, to a samba
beat, possessing the ball as if it is tethered to their feet. Only
200,000 girls and women officially play soccer in Brazil, compared
with 7.5 million registered female players in the United States.
But Brazilian officials are so committed to developing the women's
game that 50 scouts now comb the favelas, or slums, of Rio and Sao
Paulo, looking for the top female players, according to Tony
DiCicco, coach of the American team.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other countries, they are saying: `Soccer is our national
sport. Why are we so far behind? Why are the Americans as good as
they are? We need to change that. We need to put more resources
into it,''' DiCicco said. ``A perfect example is Brazil. Brazil
doesn't want to be second in soccer to anyone, in any gender, any
age.''
</P>
<P>
   There are soccer schools for girls now in Brazil, soccer
officials said. The girls attend classes in the morning and play
soccer in the afternoon. Several players on the national team said
they had grown up playing in the streets with their brothers and
that the prejudices against women seemed to fade for good after
Brazil's strong showing in the 1996 Summer Olympics. When they
appear in public, people recognize them and stop them for
autographs, just as they stop the men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the Olympics, women's soccer is like any other sport,''
Pretinha, a forward, said. ``It's not like it used to be. I never
have any problems. People are always respectful.''
</P>
<P>
   To a point. It is said that everyone in Brazil is a coach. And
while soccer is the favorite sport, the second-favorite sport is
criticizing soccer. Wilson Oliveira Rica, the good-humored women's
coach, knows it is only a matter of time before, in the eyes of
Brazilian fans, he will be able to do nothing right, only wrong. It
is the inevitable price of progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a lot of expectation and criticism,'' he said
with a smile. ``That is part of soccer.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
