<SLUG> BC-BOATING-TRANSATLANTIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WAITING, TO TAME THE NORTH ATLANTIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Teams on race boats with a craving for adventure are
tied up at yacht harbors around New York, all eager for a chance at
toppling the trans-Atlantic speed record. Each covets a brisk
breeze, a windy low-pressure system that will carry its sailboat
into a record-breaking passage across a notoriously tricky North
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   At Liberty Landing, a marina in Jersey City, N.J., the 60-foot
trimaran Foncia Immobilier, has waited for a favorable weather
window for two weeks. At North Cove Yacht Harbor in Lower
Manhattan, the 92-foot monohull, Stealth, has been in and out of
the basin since April 12 on its watch. And within the next month,
Explorer, the 86-foot catamaran that in 1993 sailed around the
world in a record 79 days, is expected to tie up for the Atlantic
wait at Chelsea Piers in Manhattan. Giovanni Soldini, however, the
recent victor in the Around Alone, has decided to forgo his record
attempt this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's historically what put sailboat racing on the map,'' said
Cam Lewis, a 42-year-old ocean racer from Lincolnville, Maine,
referring to the trans-Atlantic voyage. ``Giant sailboats with some
of the wealthiest people in America set the whole thing up when
they tried to beat each other across the Atlantic in their yachts.
The trip from New York to England is the classic speed distance
record. In everybody's heart, it is the Holy Grail of long-distance
passages.''
</P>
<P>
   The players, of course, have changed over the years. No longer
do grand prix races such as the America's Cup require that
participants sail their race boats trans-Atlantic to reach the
event, as they did in the late 19th century. Now corporate
sponsorship is involved, and so too is a fascination for
long-distance racing by French sailors.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis was the only American in a French crew aboard Explorer
when it set its global record six years ago. Bruno Peyron of
France, its skipper then and now, has made sailboat records his
life's pursuit. Two years ago, the Peyron team set a five-day
trans-Pacific record. And last August, he and his crew set a 14-day
pace from Yokohama, Japan, to San Francisco, a 4,500-mile trip.
</P>
<P>
   But still eluding Peyron is the six-day trans-Atlantic multihull
passage set in 1990 by Serge Madec, another Frenchman, aboard his
75-foot catamaran, Jet Services V. The time is faster by three days
than the current monohull record of nine days set by Mari-Chah III
last October.
</P>
<P>
   As sailboat records go, Jet Services' pace has been uncommonly
enduring. But it would seem that Peyron could easily beat it since
his yacht Explorer is the old Jet Services. Modified by Peyron for
his 1993 circumnavigation, the catamaran is 11 feet longer than it
was in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Peyron, however, is about to face a formidable rival for the
Atlantic title in Steve Fossett, a securities executive from
Chicago. Fossett, whose effort to set a round-the-world passage in
a balloon was ended on March 19 when a Swiss team completed the
trip first, has increasingly focused on sailing among his other
record pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   Fossett's boat, which he has named Play Station, is a 105-foot
catamaran, which established a 24-hour record for sailboats with a
580-nautical-mile day in March off the coast of New Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last week in Newport, R.I., Fossett said he also
has his eyes on the trans-Atlantic record. A recent fire on board,
however, which started in the catamaran's battery bank, has delayed
the Play Station project by three or four months. A 26-foot section
of the boat's starboard hull was ruined.
</P>
<P>
   Fossett plans to ship the repaired multihull to the United
States from New Zealand in September for a trans-Atlantic record
attempt out of New York this fall. ``Each sailing record is an
adventure,'' Fossett said, ``an attempt to do it faster than
anybody before. But Jet Services has a very good record. That is
part of its appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   MAKING WAVES
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 sailors from 16 colleges and universities are
expected to compete for 10 days beginning Wednesday in the 1999
U.S. Collegiate Sailing Championships.
</P>
<P>
   The event, based at Eckerd College in St. Petersburg, Fla.,
includes a coed racing championship, a women's event and a national
team event. Ranked first as of May 2 was St. Mary's College in
Maryland; second, Tufts University; and third, Old Dominion
University.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
