<SLUG> BC-NY-OFFICE-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: LONGTIME LANDLORD PONDERS BECOMING A DEVELOPER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As the subsidiary of an institution that is 302 years
old, Trinity Real Estate tends to take the long view of things. For
the last decade and a half it has been transforming most of the 5.5
million square feet of industrial buildings it acquired _
unwillingly _ during the 1930s into office space.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is about to take the next step: development. Executives
of the unit of the Parish of Trinity Church have selected four
properties that can be demolished or totally remodeled into 2
million square feet of new offices.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone is getting carried away. These projects are not
likely to be built on speculation. Tenants, in most cases, will
have to sign leases for a substantial share of each building before
a spade goes into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not risk takers,'' said Joseph Palombi, executive vice
president of real estate for Trinity Church. ``The only way we are
going ahead with these projects is if we have tenants for 60
percent or more of the space.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he said, the time is ripe for development by a
company that owns its building sites, does not need zoning changes
and is in an area that has proved attractive to the computer- and
Internet-related companies that have been multiplying in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   Handling architects' renderings of new buildings is an unusual
sensation for managers of a portfolio of former lofts and factories
clustered near the Holland Tunnel that until the early 1990s mostly
housed printing companies. The buildings are a lingering legacy of
a gift of 215 acres of land by England's Queen Anne in 1705 that is
now generally thought of as the west side of lower Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the royally deeded land was sold or given away over the
intervening centuries to found churches, hospitals and an
educational institution now known as Columbia University. As New
York industrialized in the early part of the 1900s, the church
allowed developers to build sturdy factory buildings, most of them
occupied by printing companies eager to be close to their
financial-industry clients on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity retained ownership of the land and simply collected the
ground rent until the Depression of the 1930s. The collapse of the
economy left tenants unable to make mortgage and tax payments and
the church was forced to take title to the properties to avoid
losing them to lenders or the city. The debt it assumed was not
retired until the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1980s, Trinity's real estate managers decided they
did not want to be in a printing business that was clearly in
long-term decline with the advent of electronic communications.
They began remodeling the industrial buildings to attract office
tenants, particularly the new-media and other computer-related
companies that were springing up in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Companies like these were not interested in the supposed
prestige and high cost of midtown Manhattan. They installed
open-space layouts and strung the multitude of wires needed for
connections in overhead racks and got to work.
</P>
<P>
   That conversion process is still under way.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity is renovating a triangular, 1.1-million-square-foot
building bounded by Canal, Varick and Watts streets for office use
by enlarging the lobby, replacing elevators, bringing in additional
electrical power and telecommunications and installing new windows
to shut out the din of traffic at the Holland Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Once known as 75 Varick St., the building has been renamed 1
Hudson Square as part of an effort to put a brand name on the
Trinity portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed development projects include one large building
that would occupy the entire block bounded by Hudson, Varick,
Spring and Vandam streets and three more modest undertakings.
</P>
<P>
   Palombi said the low vacancy rates and the dearth of new
construction in the city has convinced Trinity's leaders that there
will be tenants eager to occupy brand-new space. And because the
church owns the land, it can charge lower rents than are possible
in situations where a third-party landowner is part of the
equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figure that we have a $15 to $20 a square foot advantage
over comparable space in midtown,'' he said, referring to projected
annual rents. ``That adds up to a big number over a period of
years.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that a 1.2-million-square-foot building could be erected
on the site, which is currently occupied with smaller,
Trinity-owned structures, without the need for a change in zoning.
Because the building, to be designated 4 Hudson Square, would cost
from $260 million to $300 million to build, the church will not
proceed without a lease, and possibly financial participation, from
a tenant whose solid credit will enable economical borrowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fantasy is that a company like AT&AMP;T or IBM will take the
entire building,'' said Stephen Heyman, the director of commercial
leasing for Trinity.
</P>
<P>
   Palombi said that while Trinity will be the owner of the
building, the church will hire a developer to supervise the
detailed planning and construction.
</P>
<P>
   One of the buildings on the site, 304 Hudson St., which is 85
percent occupied, largely by information-technology tenants, may be
incorporated in the larger structure, but smaller buildings facing
Varick Street are likely to be demolished, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If a suitable tenant can be found soon, the building could be
ready for occupancy by early 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining 800,000 square feet of potential development is
divided among three projects. One is at 330 Hudson _ to be
designated 6 Hudson Square _ which occupies the western half of the
block bounded by Hudson, Varick, Vandam and Charlton streets. The
building is occupied by a document-storage company, but Trinity
officials said there is an opportunity to terminate the lease in
about a year.
</P>
<P>
   The plan here would be to strip the building down to its steel
frame, use an alley in back to install a modern core and add four
floors to the top, expanding it to 425,000 square feet. Once again,
Trinity officials say they can make the alterations within existing
zoning, a situation that is called ``as of right'' in the industry.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   u fxxnt06 nt22 nt26 nt11 nt33 &QL; 
ufxx &QL; 
 &UR; BC-NY-OFFICE-REAL-2NDTAKE-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; NEW YORK: the industry. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because no foundation work will be involved, Trinity officials
say they will be able to deliver what will amount to a new building
quicker and cheaper, possibly by the end of 2002. ``We may do this
one without a tenant,'' said Palombi, who noted that the building
would offer new space at a rental rate in the mid-30s per square
foot annually compared with $45 a square foot and above for older
space in midtown.
</P>
<P>
   A small parking lot and garage to the east of the building at
345 Hudson St., now known as 555 Greenwich St., would be replaced
with a slender building that has been designated 7 Hudson Square.
The building could rise as much as 15 stories with 220,000 square
feet of space. The building is being designed so that its floors
match up with the Trinity-owned 345 Hudson, so that tenants in the
Hudson Street building could expand via connections with the new
structure.
</P>
<P>
   An unused automobile service station adjacent to a Trinity
property at 100 Ave. of the Americas would be converted into a
six-story office building with 23,000 square feet of office space
that could be connected to the larger structure.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the new building, Trinity officials said there is
an opportunity to add 50,000 square feet of penthouse space to the
building at 350 Hudson St.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity officials say the benefits of the new buildings will be
greater than the rents they can collect on the added space. New
Class A buildings, they say, will enhance the entire portfolio by
enhancing the image of the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our interest in developing these buildings goes beyond any
individual project,'' Heyman said. ``These developments will raise
the value of the other space in the area.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the area began its transformation from light
manufacturing to office when the Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi advertising
agency moved into a new building at 375 Hudson St. in the
mid-1980s. Although Trinity does not own the building, which was
built by Tishman Speyer Properties, the company that controls
Rockefeller Center, the church benefits from more than the changed
image the building brought to the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We,'' Palombi said, ``own the land.''
</P>
</TEXT>
