<HEADLINE>
IN HARTFORD, A NEW BATTLEGROUND FOR ABORTION DEBATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ For most of the decade, supporters of abortion
rights at the Connecticut Capitol wanted little more than to bask
in the state's reputation for friendliness toward their agenda.
They had insurance _ in 1990, the Legislature had enacted the
provisions of Roe vs. Wade into state law, in case the Supreme
Court ever reversed that decision _ and a vote on any other
abortion measure was seen by women's groups as asking for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   So for the last nine years, as political careers elsewhere were
staked on such fights as whether parents should consent to a
teen-ager's planned abortion or merely be notified about it,
legislative leaders in Hartford did not even permit a debate on an
abortion bill.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years however, both sides had come up with
something they dearly wanted. Women's groups began pushing what
they called ``the pill bill,'' which would require health insurers
to pay for prescription birth control. And anti-abortion groups
were seeking, state by state, to outlaw the late-term procedure
they call partial-birth abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion opponents promised that any time the pill bill came up,
they would try to add a partial-birth amendment, effectively
sabotaging the contraceptive measure. This was just the sort of
fight women's groups wanted to avoid, since they believed it could
usher in other anti-abortion inroads, like restrictions for minors,
or rights for fetuses in criminal cases.
</P>
<P>
   But a new speaker of the House, Moira Lyons, D-Stamford, took
office in January, and she brokered a deal that may seem obvious
but was the product of more than a year of shuttle negotiations
between the abortion camps. She gave each side a clean shot _ a
separate vote and debate on its bill, with no amendments allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side was confident about the outcome. Democrats control
both chambers of the state Legislature, but, flouting the platforms
of their national parties, a big bloc of Democrats opposes abortion
and quite a few Republicans favor abortion rights. Lobbying groups
for both sides engineered a flood of calls and faxes to
legislators. The Connecticut Catholic Conference even included
legislators' phone numbers in alerts to parishes.
</P>
<P>
   When the votes were over last week, abortion opponents, who had
finally got their chance, were further behind than ever.
</P>
<P>
   The pill bill sailed through both the House and Senate, and the
late-term abortion measure was overwhelmingly defeated by both
chambers. Reflecting the issue's complex calculus, Speaker Lyons,
who refuses to classify herself as ``pro-choice'' or ``pro-life,''
voted for the contraceptive measure but also for the late-term
abortion ban.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John Rowland, a moderate Republican who once opposed
abortion but now seems comfortable with his stance in favor of
abortion rights, has said he will sign the contraceptive measure,
which has passed several other legislatures but is in effect only
in Maryland. The Connecticut measure includes a ``conscience
clause'' that exempts church-affiliated employers, like Catholic
hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators in Hartford said the debates were the most memorable
in years. Many legislators conspicuously sorted papers or stared at
their laptop computers while abortion opponents in the House read
gruesome descriptions of the late-term procedure, which doctors
call ``intact dilation and extraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Adela Eads, R-Kent, argued that abortion was a private
matter. ``This is the end of the 1990s _ get with it,'' said Sen.
Eads, 79, who is the minority leader. Noting that women feel birth,
she said, ``What do you fellas feel? It's just another mouth to
feed.''
</P>
<P>
   Several leading legislators argued that the late-term procedure
defeats _ 86-57 in the House, and 26-10 in the Senate _ were
decisive enough that abortion questions are unlikely to be taken up
again for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would have to be a demonstration that you would not be
wasting the chamber's time,'' said Rep. Claudia ``Dolly'' Powers, a
Republican from Greenwich who helped engineer the victory for
women's groups.
</P>
<P>
   Judith Blei, the lobbyist for the Connecticut chapters of
Planned Parenthood and the National Abortion Rights Action League,
is not so sure. ``Defeat will mean the opposition will work hard to
organize,'' she said. She seems to be on to something.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, abortion opponents gathered in Baltic, 50 miles
southeast of the Capitol, and, surrounded by booths featuring
colorful plastic fetuses at various stages of development, promised
to keep fighting, even as they anticipated defeat. ``We're not just
going to say, `Gosh darn!' and go home,'' said Lynne Poulos, the
treasurer of the Connecticut Christian Coalition. ``It's tough in
icy, cold Connecticut. But we know the Bible, so we know how it
comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   And Connecticut Right to Life president William C. O'Brien said
the defeats have a strategic byproduct: a clear voting record for
use in future campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
