<SLUG> BC-EDIT-IRAN-MIDEAST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: IRAN'S DIPLOMATIC INITIATIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, May 23:
</P>
<P>
   Iranian President Mohammad Khatami's trip to three Arab
countries last week was a revealing effort to ease Tehran's
isolation from most of its Mideast neighbors. Khatami's tour got
off to a disturbing start in Syria, the one major Arab country with
which Tehran has maintained close relations since Iran's 1979
revolution. Among other things, Syria allows Iran to arm and train
anti-Israeli Hezbollah guerrillas in Lebanon. Regrettably, Khatami
met in Damascus not only with Hezbollah's leadership, but also with
representatives of radical Palestinian groups that reject the peace
agreements between Israel and the mainstream Palestinian leadership
under Yasser Arafat. Iran's position is that it would accept any
peace treaty with Israel agreed to by Arafat _ or by Syrian
President Hafez Assad.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant destination was Saudi Arabia, where Khatami
spent four days. He was the first Iranian president since 1979 to
visit this important Persian Gulf neighbor. Iran and Saudi Arabia
have clashed repeatedly over Tehran's support for Shiite
revolutionaries and the management of Iranian pilgrimages to Mecca.
Iran has also denounced Saudi military ties with the United States.
But last week, the stress was on common interests, including
cooperation to raise low oil prices. Khatami avoided criticism of
Riyadh's relations with Washington. The final stop was Qatar, which
has warm relations with the United States and moderate positions on
Israel but has still managed to remain friendly with Iran.
</P>
<P>
   If Khatami can keep his clerical foes in check, cut Tehran's
remaining ties with terrorism and halt Iranian nuclear weapons
development, normal relations with America will also be possible. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1751EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
