</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME RUN BARRAGE CONTRIBUTES TO THE RISE IN SCORING 
THEORIES FOR THE HOMER SURGE 
DIAMONDBACKS RETURN INVESTMENT 
TATIS CREDITS HIS COACH
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before last season, no one had ever hit 70 home runs in a
season, but before this season no one had ever hit two grand slams
in the same inning and no one had hit a grand slam in each game of
a doubleheader. It's offensive mayhem, Part II.
</P>
<P>
   ``You check the scoreboard during games and see all these
lopsided games,'' Mike Hargrove, the Cleveland Indians' manager,
said. ``I haven't looked at any cumulative numbers, but it
certainly seems to me that there are a lot more runs being
scored.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove's hunch is correct. Teams are scoring runs this season
at a rate nearly 8 percent ahead of last year at the equivalent
time; they are hitting home runs at a clip 15 percent above last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the team he watches every day has produced a major
share of the increase. Not only do the Indians have a controversial
nickname, but they also have a mightily offensive group of guys.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove's hackers have scored two runs a game more than they
did last year, and they have hit nearly 50 percent more home runs.
They are also at the forefront of a general increase in
double-digit scoring and grand slam slugging.
</P>
<P>
   Last year at this time hitters had crushed 38 pitches for grand
slams; this year they have socked 46. Last year Sandy Alomar Jr.
hit the lone grand slam to this point for the Indians. His brother,
Roberto, hit the team's first this season, and David Justice, Manny
Ramirez and Richie Sexson added three in a five-game span last
week.
</P>
<P>
   But the four most notable grand slam feats this season belong to
Fernando Tatis of St. Louis, Robin Ventura of the Mets, Nomar
Garciaparra of Boston and Ken Griffey Jr. of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   In any other season, the pair of grand slams that Griffey hit in
successive games on consecutive days and the pair that Garciaparra
hit in one game would have grabbed all of the attention.
</P>
<P>
   But on April 23, Tatis became the first player to hit two grand
slams in one inning, and last Thursday Ventura, who in 1995 slugged
two grand slams in consecutive innings, became the first to hit one
in each game of a doubleheader.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's explosive production powered the Mets to double
figures in each game, giving them five such games compared with two
at this time last year. They are one of the teams responsible for
an increase in double-digit scoring this season. The American
League is up slightly to 65 double-figure scores from 63, and the
National League is up to 57 from 47.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Diamondbacks have made the most eye-opening advance,
scoring 10 runs or more eight times this season compared with one
in a similar period last year. The Indians have raised their
double-digit output, to 10 games from 6.
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate double-digit game was played last Wednesday in
Denver, where Cincinnati outslugged Colorado, 24-12. The score
prompted Jack McKeon, the Reds' manager, to remark about Jim
Leyland, the Rockies' manager, ``He ought to go across town and get
a kicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Hammonds epitomized the bizarre nature of the game. He
entered with a .132 batting average (5 for 38) and no home runs,
then became the fifth player this year to hit three home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of the pitchers had any zip,'' McKeon said. ``Whether it
was the air, the atmosphere or what, I don't know. It was like
watching batting practice, the way balls were flying out of there
and going against the walls, going 30, 40 feet farther than they
normally do. I just threw that game out the window and said forget
it; you probably won't see another one too quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   But less than two weeks earlier, the Indians scored 18 runs in
their final three turns at bat and beat Tampa Bay, 20-11. The way
runs are cascading across the plate more such games will follow.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
