<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7394 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2NDTAKE-     05-22 1099
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: will follow.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Theories for the Homer Surge
</P>
<P>
   As in every other year when runs and home runs have increased,
the question is asked. Why?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a year and a half beyond expansion, and the pitching
right now is absolutely horrible,'' Don Baylor, the Atlanta hitting
coach, said.
</P>
<P>
   Jack McKeon goes for the ball theory. ``The ball is livelier;
it's smaller,'' the Cincinnati manager said. ``Everybody denies it,
but I don't think all of a sudden the guys have become this
strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Curt Schilling offered yet a third reason: the umpires and the
new strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've stopped calling the pitch off plate,'' the
Philadelphia pitcher said, ``but to make sure they're not accused
of it, they've stopped calling corners. You have to throw the ball
not over the plate but over the white middle of the plate more than
I've ever had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Umpires, Schilling added, have also stopped calling low strikes
because they are calling high strikes. ``The strike zone is
incredibly different this year,'' he said. ``It's smaller; it's
different. It's drastically different.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the strike zone has been altered this season by fiat of
the commissioner's office, it presents the most intriguing
possibility. Sandy Alderson, the man in the commissioner's office
who is most directly involved in strike zone developments, didn't
reject the possibility of a link between umpires' ball-strike calls
and run production.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strike zone may have something to do with it,'' said
Alderson, the executive vice president for baseball operations.
``That hasn't been mentioned to me directly, but we're monitoring
both the strike zone and the run production. It is conceivable the
zone has gotten smaller. What we're seeing through the charting
we're doing is the pitch off the plate is no longer being called a
strike, but there is some inconsistency at the top end of the
strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Umpires were told before the season to stop calling strikes on
pitches off the corners of the plate. In recent years, the strike
zone had spread horizontally. At the same time, umpires were told
to call strikes on pitches two inches above the belt. For years,
pitches above the waist had been called balls.
</P>
<P>
   With clubs instructed to chart pitches of each game, officials
are following the degree to which umpires have adhered to the
instructions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Umpires almost uniformly are correct on those in and out
pitches,'' Alderson said. ``Very few pitches are being `missed' in
and out. And down by the way. There has been a little inconsistency
at the top of the strike zone based on what we're seeing.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson said he had not studied the run production, but he
figured to be unhappy with what he sees when he looks at the
numbers. Through Friday, 6,318 runs had been scored in 609 games
compared with 5,871 runs scored in the first 612 games last season.
Home runs were up, 1,413 to 1,225.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only speaking for myself in this instance, I am not happy with
the amount of run production that exists in the game right now,''
Alderson said. ``We're threatening to see a real imbalance.''
</P>
<P>
   Alderson said he believed the growing imbalance had more to do
with the strength of hitters and thinness of pitching than the
strike zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep our eye on the proper balance between pitching
and hitting,'' he said. ``We have to be constantly vigilant of the
balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Because home runs stand out in any scrutiny of the mushrooming
offense, Alderson said, ``In our long-term approach and vision for
the game, we have to think in terms of how important we want the
home run to become.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not say what steps might be taken if it is determined
that pitchers are taking too much of a beating, but one option
would be further adjustment to the strike zone. The zone might be
smaller horizontally, or east-west, but it could grow vertically,
north-south, with a return to the rule-book definition of the upper
limit.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the midpoint between the top of the uniform pants
and the top of the shoulders. That strike hasn't been seen during
the careers of the players in the major leagues today.
</P>
<P>
   A larger strike zone certainly would reduce the number of walks,
meaning fewer runners on base for the big run producers to drive
in. Like runs and home runs, walks are up this season, nearly 5
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks Return Investment
</P>
<P>
   When the two-year-old Arizona Diamondbacks took over first place
in the N.L. West last week _ for a day, it turned out _ Jerry
Colangelo did not rush to the telephone to ask his fellow owners
what they thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not polling to see what anyone's opinion is,'' said
Colangelo, the managing partner, whose off-season expenditures on
free agents were criticized by other owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still maintain we all need to do what we feel is appropriate
and what is in the best interests of our franchise. I stand by our
investments in players to protect the investment we have.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said the owners have more than $350 million invested
in the team, adding, ``When you have that kind of an investment, my
attitude was we need to win and be competitive in order to make
sure we maintain a great deal of interest.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he added: ``There are some teams with substantially higher
payrolls that aren't doing nearly as well. I would be very
concerned if we were near the bottom with our payroll.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks spent most of their money to improve their
starting pitching, but they didn't ignore their offense and it has
been more impressive than the pitching. Arizona leads the league in
runs, home runs, total bases and slugging percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Tatis Credits His Coach
</P>
<P>
   When Mo Vaughn heard that Mike Easler, the St. Louis Cardinals'
new hitting coach, was being credited for the improvement in
Fernando Tatis' hitting, he was not surprised. Vaughn has long
credited Easler for making him the hitter he is today.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to believe in yourself and he makes you believe you
can be successful,'' Anaheim's Vaughn said. ``The best thing about
a hitting instructor is that he can get you to transfer what you
practice in the batting cage to the field. Mike is good at doing
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said that when he encountered Easler in Boston in 1993:
``I was a natural hitter, but I didn't know how to get the best out
of my ability. He gave me a good solid base that I could always
refer back to as a hitter. Fernando Tatis will always remember Mike
Easler from here on out in his career, the same as I always
will.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1753EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-NY-MINIMARATHON-N     05-22 0498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-NY-MINIMARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING DOWNHILL, LOROUPE OUTDISTANCES FIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With about two miles remaining in Saturday's Avon
Mini Marathon in Central Park, Tegla Loroupe, the world-class
Kenyan distance runner, peeked over her shoulder for the first
time. She saw pain on the faces behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing weakness, Loroupe did what all champions do; she pushed
the pace. Down a steep hill, around a tight bend, Loroupe's lead
grew quickly. Five seconds, and then 10 seconds, until she was
alone, headed for the finish line near Tavern on the Green, where
she won the 10-kilometer race for the fourth time in 31 minutes 48
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so happy to win this race again,'' said Loroupe, who
collected $15,000 for her victory. The $50,000 purse was a record
amount for a women's 6.2-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   Gete Wami of Ethiopia finished second in 32:00 and Lidia Simon
of Romania was third in 32:01. Wami, 24, won the 8-kilometer race
at this year's world cross-country championships and was running
her first road race in the United States on Saturday. Simon, 25, is
especially noted for her sixth-place finish in the marathon at the
1996 Olympic Games in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Loroupe's only challenger in the final mile Saturday was a
stubborn in-line skater who did not clear a path for her. ``I
almost collided with him,'' she said. ``I was scared because that
guy was huge and I'm small. I was lucky not to hit him.''
</P>
<P>
   Loroupe, 26, won here in 1993, 1996 and 1997, and is a two-time
winner of the New York City Marathon (1994 and 1995). She set the
marathon world record of 2:20:47 in Rotterdam in 1998. Known for
her endurance, Loroupe on Saturday proved once again that she has
speed, too. She ran the fifth mile in a blistering 4:47, a pace
that proved too much for the other lead-pack runners.
</P>
<P>
   About Loroupe's decisive downhill surge, Wami said: ``I'm not so
good going downhill. When Tegla made the move, she was too fast for
me. My legs could not keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's times were disappointing, because the race featured
dozens of the world's best female runners. In fact, the field was
considered the most talented in the race's 28-year history. But the
quality of runners could not overcome a conservative start and
draining heat and humidity. So the race record of 31:00, set by the
nine-time New York City Marathon winner Grete Waitz in 1980, will
remain the standard for at least one more year.
</P>
<P>
   The first Americans to cross the finish line Saturday were
Libbie Hickman, 34, of Fort Collins, Colo. (10th, 32:39), and Anne
Marie Lauck of Hampton, N.J. (12th, 33:12). Hickman was named
distance runner of the year by USA Track and Field in each of the
least two years. Lauck, 30, won the Mini Marathon in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the dozens of elite athletes in the field, more
than 6,000 recreational runners competed Saturday. The race was
founded in 1972 to promote women's fitness. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
