<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKDALE-MAIN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School shooting suspect ``charming young man,'' lawyer says
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ The attorney for the Rockdale County, Ga., boy
accused in the shootings at Heritage High School about 25 miles
east of dwontown Atlanta described him Saturday as ``a really
charming young man'' who, contrary to what acquaintances have said,
did not own a gun or have easy access to his stepfather's gun
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't seem to have an evil bone in his body and I am just
clueless as to why he did it; there's no anger,'' Atlanta attorney
Don Samuel said Saturday. The lawyer visited the boy at a youth
detention center in Lawrenceville Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel declined to relate anything the boy said during Friday's
visit, leaving unanswered the biggest question: Why?
</P>
<P>
   Samuel said he waived a detention hearing that had been
scheduled for Monday in Rockdale County Juvenile Court. He said he
expects Rockdale District Attorney Richard Read to file a motion
early next week to have the suspect tried as an adult. A judge's
decision on that could be weeks away.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel said the suspect's stepfather and mother are struggling
to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are just absolute shocked, just horrified, just thankful
that the kids are all right,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The parents deny students' accounts that they gave their son a
handgun as a gift, Samuel said. Acquaintances in Rockdale and in
Kernersville, N.C., where the suspect's family lived for three
years until moving to Georgia in 1997, have recalled how the boy
liked to show off a handgun. The boy's parents told Samuel that the
revolver used Thursday belonged to the stepfather and that the boy
never touched it before Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rifle used in the Heritage shootings, Samuel said the
boy and his stepfather were avid deer hunters, and that the boy was
licensed and trained to use such a weapon.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, students returned to Heritage to reclaim the
bags and books they left behind when the shooting started. Some
just came to see the aftermath of the attack, which left six
students wounded.
</P>
<P>
   As the last students trickled into Heritage just before noon,
doctors discharged 15-year-old Cania Cullins from Rockdale
Hospital, where surgeons removed a bullet from her knee. She and
her mother, Felicia Cullins, went home ``to take a nap,'' Mrs.
Cullins said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie Laster, also 15, was the only shooting victim left
hospitalized Saturday. A spokeswoman for Hughes Spalding Medical
Center said Laster was listed in good condition. She still has a
bullet lodged in her abdomen, but doctors plan to release her early
next week.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Barnhardt, 16, and Jason Cheek, 17, were released from
Rockdale Hospital on Friday. Drake Hoy and Ryan Rosa, both 18, were
released from the hospital hours after they were wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel said he will contest Read's expected attempt to move the
case to an adult court, but added, ``It seems most juvenile court
judges in these kinds of cases are going to acquiesce to the D.A.'s
demand.''
</P>
<P>
   Before a decision, Samuel said, both sides will hire
psychatrists to evaluate the suspect. Read, who has said he expects
to seek to have the suspect tied as an adult, could not be reached
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
