<P>
   UNEXPLORED _ MIAMI _ The explorers battled fat leeches and
cliffsides so steep and slippery, one false step could mean a
plunge of thousands of feet. They navigated a raging, treacherous
river. They even heard rumors of the Dugmas, a cult of females who
attack outsiders with snake venom concealed beneath their
fingernails. It sounds like an Indiana Jones-style adventure, but
it was real. The expedition, sponsored by the National Geographic
Society last November, took four Americans into the inner gorge of
the Tsangpo River, the world's deepest canyon, in a remote part of
Tibet. The 17-day undertaking was a lesson in endurance, but the
reward was extraordinary: the sight of a thundering, 100-foot-high
cascade, dubbed ``Hidden Falls.'' But what's equally extraordinary
is that a giant waterfall on a major river had yet to be recorded.
Indeed, on the eve of the 21st century, there are lots of
unexplored spots on the planet _ even in North America. (Emling,
Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   UNEXPLORED-CENTURY _ Great discoveries of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTOS.
