<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRROGERS-COMMENCEMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MR. ROGERS, MARIST GRADS JOIN IN SONG 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   POUGHKEEPSIE, N.Y. _ Fred Rogers, the creator and star of
``Mister Rogers' Neighborhood'' on public television, addressed
1,050 graduates and received an honorary degree at Marist College's
53rd commencement Saturday. Also receiving honorary degrees were
the director of the Peace Corps, Mark Gearan, and Dr. Anne Dyson, a
children's advocate.
</P>
<P>
   Though Rogers, 71, had carefully composed a 15-minute speech,
the sight of an electronic piano on stage inspired a quick change.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a little piano over here,'' he said to the
graduates, who were already clapping with enthusiasm. ``Do you want
to sing?''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers smiled and began: ``It's a beautiful day in the
neighborhood. A beautiful day for a neighbor. Would you be mine?
Could you be mine?''
</P>
<P>
   As more students joined in, Rogers shouted, ``Good! Good for
you!''
</P>
<P>
   There were quiet moments, too. The soft-spoken educator, an
ordained Presbyterian minister, spoke of ethnic cleaning in Kosovo,
the high school massacre in Littleton, Colo., and environmental
destruction as he counseled graduates to make their choices
carefully. And just as he says each day on television, Rogers
assured the graduates that they were special, just by being
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a good feeling to know you're alive,'' he finished,
to applause that went on and on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7406 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEOGAME-TOURNAMENT-     05-22 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEOGAME-TOURNAMENT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO GAME TOURNAMENT DRAWS TOP `QUAKE II,' `STARCRAFT' PLAYERS  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ga., Ill.)  (rk) 
 By STEPHEN C. MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The tournament had all the trappings of a big league
sporting event: large cash prizes, pre- and post-game interviews
and a broadcast team perched above the action, providing
play-by-play and color commentary.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not sport, at least not in the traditional sense; it
was a championship video game tournament held Friday and Saturday
at an arcade in Times Square called XS New York.
</P>
<P>
   And the broadcast was not on network television, but on the
Internet, with sound bites that had their own distinctive tone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a really tough competitor,'' one player told an
interviewer. ``I thought that I had him after that last spawn, but
he made excellent use of the railgun to frag me a couple of times
before I could get back to my game.''
</P>
<P>
   The tournament, run by the AMD Professional Gamers League,
featured two games, ``Quake II'' and ``Starcraft,'' and the top
prizes included $10,000 in cash. The players, most of them in high
school or college, were between the ages of 16 and 24.
</P>
<P>
   The referees, all about the same age as the competitors, were in
another part of the building, following each game and player with a
bank of computers with sophisticated software monitoring every
aspect of the game. At one point, in a ``Quake II'' Deathmatch, one
player's computer froze. The referees were able to reset both games
to the exact point at which the lockup occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Manfredi, a market researcher from a suburb of Chicago,
cheered like any Little League dad as his 16-year-old son, Eric
``SaboTaj'' Manfredi, played what most considered the best ``Quake
II'' Deathmatch of the tournament. With his son down by one point
and less than a minute to go in the match, Manfredi, who was
upstairs watching on a giant television screen, kept whispering,
``Come on Eric, you can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   With less than 10 seconds left, Eric Manfredi tied the score and
forced the match into overtime. His father yelled, applauded and
grinned from ear to ear. Even though Eric lost in overtime, his
father still seemed proud. One of the other spectators shook his
hand and said, ``What a great game.''
</P>
<P>
   Manfredi was upstairs in the equivalent of a skybox, where VIP's
got to sit down and watch the matches on monitors. Most of the
spectators had to stand in front of the stage downstairs with a
limited view of the players, since the contestants were partially
hidden by a computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   It was the second tournament for Kurt Shimada, a 15-year-old
honor student from Pleasanton, Calif. ``This competition is really
cool,'' he said. ``It's great to meet some of the players that I
have been playing online all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though there was running commentary on each match, it was
hard to hear because of the explosions, gunfire and squealing tires
of all the arcade's regular games _ ``House of the Dead,'' ``Time
Crisis II,'' ``Battle Tank'' and ``Sega Rally.'' Despite the
tournament, the arcade was still open for business and there were
just as many people engrossed in their own digitally enhanced
escape into shooting bad guys or driving fast cars to pay much
attention.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament began the day after a 15-year-old in Conyers,
Ga., opened fire in his high school, injuring six students, and
most of the contestants were uncomfortable when reporters asked
about the relationship between violent video games and real-life
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Sebastian ``Sybek'' Lenart, 20, a ``Quake II'' finalist from
Ontario, said the games weren't about violence but about
competition. ``You don't think about killing your opponent, but how
to outsmart him. It's a game of skill and intelligence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy Chapelsky whose 17-year-old son, Patrick, is known as Kain
the Feared, said that keeping the lines of communication open was
the key to helping children understand the difference between
fantasy and reality. She said the games were beneficial to players.
``It can be a way of getting out frustrations,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
