<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAGOP-CONVENTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Republicans rail against gun control
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Alan Judd and Kathey Pruitt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ From Republican presidential candidates to a
leading official of the National Rifle Association, speakers at the
Georgia Republican Party's annual convention in Augusta Friday and
Saturday argued that societal change and enforcement of existing
gun laws would be the most effective ways to prevent shootings like
the ones that injured six people Thursday at Heritage High School
in the Atlanta suburb of Rockdale County and left 15 dead last
month in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two horrible kids'' who went on a rampage in Colorado
broke 20 federal and state gun laws, said Wayne LaPierre, the NRA's
executive vice president, whose appearance Saturday after the
Georgia school shootings had caused an internal party dispute.
``You could have put another 50 laws on the books and they would
have broken those, too. ... How about blaming the people who pull
the trigger, set off the bombs and do the killing?''
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre's views seemed prevalent among the 2,000 Georgia GOP
activists who attended the convention. The only speaker expected to
differ _ Republican presidential candidate Elizabeth Dole _
canceled her appearance because she was suffering from laryngitis.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers who rejected calls for more gun control were warmly
welcomed by the delegates, and LaPierre received a partial standing
ovation after his 15-minute speech. Ron Jackson, a candidate for
state party chairman, drew prolonged cheers when he declared to the
delegates, ``I am a 30-year member of the National Rifle
Association and damn proud of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue of guns and violence in public schools dominated the
two-day convention, which was supposed to serve as a showcase for
Republican presidential contenders and to select a new state
chairman to lead the party after its 1998 defeats.
</P>
<P>
   None of the gun control supporters who had been expected
actually showed up to demonstrate outside the Augusta Civic Center.
But inside, all but a few speakers addressed the gun issue. Most
contended that President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore had
exploited recent school shootings to win support for more gun
restrictions. They also blamed the violence on a permissive society
that has no moral compass.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I was a kid, if somebody came to school with a shaved
head, wearing a trench coat and celebrating Hitler's birthday, the
headmaster would have had him against the wall or sent him home,
and the ACLU wouldn't have been a factor in the equation,'' said
one presidential candidate, magazine publisher Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Another contender, anti-abortion activist Alan Keyes, told the
delegates: ''We don't need more gun control. We need more control
over the judges that are taking God's name out of our schools and
prayer out of our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other candidates _ former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander and
conversative activist Gary Bauer _ expressed similar sentiments
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But it was LaPierre, and his repeated attacks on what he called
''made-for-TV lawmaking,'' that drew some of the loudest support
from convention delegates.
</P>
<P>
   He never mentioned the Conyers, Ga., shooting, instead confining
himself to a general assault against the Clinton administration for
refusing to enforce existing federal gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   While thousands of convicted felons have attempted to buy guns
or have used them in crimes, he said, officals under Clinton have
refused to prosecute those crimes. That, he said, proves a gun bill
that cleared the Senate on Thursday with the support of the
administration is ''phony.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody knows what the real agenda was in pushing that gun
legislation, and it sure wasn't about keeping children safe,''
LaPierre said. ''These are people ... who are brick by brick trying
to take the Second Amendment apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Although LaPierre's brief appearance _ the result of a 4-month
old invitation by party leaders _ had caused some division in the
GOP ranks, the only fallout was that the highly publicized speech
eclipsed the late afternoon balloting for state party chairman.
Delegates selected Chuck Clay of Marietta as their leader for the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It might come across as a little insensitive,'' said Bob Lane,
a convention delegate from Conyers who had initially questioned
LaPierre's role on the agenda. ''But it was concidence that it
happened at this time. I'm willing to listen to his side.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
