<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCKDALE-KIDS-COX     05-22 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKDALE-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wounded teen forgives school shooter
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Duane D. Stanford and Peter Scott
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. _ On her way out of Rockdale Hospital Saturday,
Cania Cullins said she is no longer angry with the Heritage High
School shooter who put a .22-caliber slug in her knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just learn to forgive people regardless, and just go on with
my life,'' the 15-year-old said before exchanging a wheelchair for
crutches and climbing into a Ford van for the ride home.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Cania will be riding in a limousine to be sent by Pastor
Jim Earl Swilley of Church In The Now, where Cania has worshipped
for more than two years. Cania and hundreds of fellow church
members will gather there to pray and celebrate life three days
after she and five others were wounded by a fellow student.
</P>
<P>
   As Cania recounted the shooting to local and national reporters
in the hospital on the north side of Conyers, students visited the
high school south of Conyers to collect their belongings now that
authorities have finished gathering evidence. The building was
opened for four hours Saturday morning and then closed again.
</P>
<P>
   As students filed in, a half-dozen maintenance workers pruned
the campus landscaping. Inmates from the Rockdale County jail
picked up trash on the grounds. Across the street from the school,
media camped out next to a handmade sign on a stake at the entrance
to the Heritage Heights subdivision that read, ``Good Luck
Seniors''
</P>
<P>
   Fawne Derosia, 17, was one of the first students to enter the
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frightening being in there knowing what happened,'' she
said after a gaggle of reporters stopped her on her way out of the
school's parking lot, which was restricted to students.
</P>
<P>
   Students said the area of the shooting had been cleared. Many of
the book bags that were scattered Thursday had been collected and
put in the teacher's lounge for students to pick up. Others
remained in the classrooms where they had been dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Freshman Allan Duncan came to the school briefly to retrieve
some notebooks from his locker that he needed for science and
English classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very chaotic Thursday and when I walked in there today
it brought back lots of bad memories,'' he said, recalling that he
had seen fellow student Jason Cheek get shot.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Alexis Diamond said she felt an ``eeriness'' when she
entered the building to look for her black jacket. She plans to
come to school Monday, but does not plan to stay for the remainder
of the school term. Students have been given the option of skipping
final exams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took our security away,'' Alexis said of the 15-year-old
shooter.
</P>
<P>
   Another sophomore, Susan Dunn, found her bookbag open, which is
not the way she remembers leaving it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt very empty,'' she said of being in the school.
</P>
<P>
   Cania said she isn't ready to return to school. Her experience
is still too fresh in her mind, and she wants more time to recover
from Friday's surgery to remove a bullet from her knee.
</P>
<P>
   Cania was with her friend Shaquita Usher, 16, in the school
cafeteria when she heard what she called a ``loud pop'' that she
thought was a fire cracker or balloon popping. After hearing the
sounds again, Cania and Usher hit the floor and began to crawl to
the back of the lunchroom. That's when she felt something sting her
leg.
</P>
<P>
   Pushed by panicking classmates, Cania crawled under a table,
crying. She told her friend she was shot, although the wound didn't
seem to hurt. Cheek, who had been shot twice in the attack, tried
to help, Cania said. After the shooting stopped. Cania said she
remained under the table for what seemed like three to five
minutes. Cafeteria workers brought her ice and cold rags to put on
her wound until paramedics arrived.
</P>
<P>
   Cania's mother, Felecia, was on Ga. 400 on the way back from
work at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel in Buckhead when she heard news of
the shooting on the radio. She pulled off at a Firestone tire
store, where she found a television on which to watch news
coverage. Seeing no evidence of her daughter, she called work to
see if authorities had tried to contact her. Co-workers said they
had, and that Cania had been shot.
</P>
<P>
   Cania's mother sped through DeKalb right past a motorcycle cop.
Figuring she had better explain, she waved the officer over and
pulled to the side of the road. The officer told her he understood
none of the injuries were life threatening. She then went to
Rockdale Hospital, where she found her daughter shaken, but alive.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
