<HEADER>
A7419 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-GENDER-KAN &LR;      05-22 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-GENDER-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS SEE A CHANCE TO CLOSE THE GENDER GAP IN 2000  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For Democrats, women have been like money in the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   They helped put Bill Clinton in the White House twice. They
stood by him in the scandal over his relationship with a White
House intern.
</P>
<P>
   They also helped the party pick up four Senate seats last year
when political tradition and forecasts predicted defeats.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, when they stay home, as they did in the 1994
congressional elections, Democrats lose _ badly.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans see an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of Texas Gov. George W. Bush as a presidential
contender and the candidacy of Elizabeth Dole offer signs that this
Democratic lifeline could fray in the 2000 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   According to several surveys, both Bush and Dole beat Vice
President Al Gore in early presidential match-ups. And it's women
who give them the edge. In a Gallup Poll, Dole was ahead by 14
percentage points among women, Bush by 12.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists caution that Bush and Dole are not well-known beyond
their famous names and that the public's mood will shift many times
before November 2000. Several, however, worry about a weakness in a
core Democratic constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Democrats need as many women as possible, because they
have been losing men,'' said Harriett Woods, former president of
the bipartisan National Women's Political Caucus and a former
Democratic lieutenant governor of Missouri. ``The Republicans don't
need all the women, they just need enough women to supplement.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, two events this spring could significantly affect the 2000
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One is if first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton decides to run for
the Senate in New York. If she does, Gore _ assuming he defeats
Democrat Bill Bradley for the nomination _ could get a bounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem we have in my business is apathy,'' said
Ellen Malcolm, president of Emily's List, a network of women who
donate money to Democrats. ``Hillary Clinton is going to blow
apathy apart in that race.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The second event is the gun-control debate. Women favor more gun
control, and they trust Democrats more than Republicans to do
something about it _ just as they do on improving education and
health care, two other chief concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Their faith was rewarded last week.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the deaths of 14 high school students and a
teacher in Colorado, and on the very day that a student wounded six
classmates in Georgia, Democrats won a big victory in the Senate by
passing the first strict gun-control measure in five years.
</P>
<P>
   And Gore basked in the glow of what could become a crucial
campaign moment. As president of the Senate, he cast the vote that
broke a 50-50 tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guns, equal pay, the environment _ when people focus and
realize the vice president is on the good side of those issues,''
said Chris Lehane, Gore's press secretary, ``he's going to fare
extremely well.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Laszlo, a Democratic consultant, said Gore's problems
with women echoed his standing with all voters _ it's hard to
articulate his vision without seeming to disagree with the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   The gun-control bill could start turning Gore's fortunes around
with women. Republican opposition allowed the Democrats to paint
them as political captives of the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Flemming, a survey director of the Pew Research Center for
the People and the Press, said Democrats could benefit if the issue
stayed hot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would certainly sustain the gender gap, if not increase
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gender gap'' describes differences in attitudes on issues and
voting choices between women and men. In numbers, it reflects the
proportion of women's vote and men's vote captured by a winning
candidate. In 1996, Bill Clinton's 11-point gender gap was the
largest ever recorded in a presidential contest.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republican leaders recognize that winning the White House
and holding their slim majority in Congress could depend on how
much they narrow that gap.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jennifer Dunn, a Republican from Washington and a Bush ally
in the House, said women represent 53 percent of the electorate,
yet the typical Republican enters a race already 17 points down in
the number of women supporters compared with the number of men.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's huge,'' she said. But the wound has been
self-inflicted, she said. The party's message when it took over
Congress in 1994 was too harsh, particularly toward the concerns of
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just don't say you want to cut out the Department of
Education and leave it that,'' Dunn said. ``People assume you don't
care about education.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican women, she said, are looking for ``an upbeat,
optimistic candidate'' such as Dole, or Bush, in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Linda DiVall, Dole's pollster, referred to Bush and Dole as
``nonthreatening Republicans'' who lower the rhetoric. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dole has spoken out about guns. She distanced herself early from
the rest of her party by backing child-safety locks and an assault
weapons ban and by opposing the right to carry concealed weapons.
Bush has supported some gun restrictions but has not been nearly as
vocal on the issue. He also signed a bill to allow the carrying of
concealed weapons in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Dole are also against abortion, but both have said the
party should concentrate on more-achievable goals such as banning
late-term abortions. They have been called ``compassionate
conservatives,'' a new term that embraces some conservative and
some centrist viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, most Americans know little about them beyond the
fact that Bush's father and namesake was president and that Dole's
husband, former Sen. Bob Dole, ran for the White House in 1996.
Voters can give them whatever viewpoints they hope to see
expressed, which may account for their high poll numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats take comfort in the fact that the political dynamic
will change once Bush begins to campaign next month and he and Dole
have to take more specific stands on ``women's issues.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just fine, DiVall said. Both candidates can handle it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is having a difficult time stepping outside from the
shadows of the vice presidency and the larger magnetic charms of
Bill Clinton,'' she said. ``Women in particular find the Dole
candidacy a very intriguing historic opportunity, and swing voters
who might have been with Gore in the past are shopping around and
looking at Bush and Dole.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
