<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEGREE-DISABILITY-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MISSOURI WOMAN OVERCOMES PHYSICAL DISABILITIES TO EARN PH.D. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TRISHA L. HOWARD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lawrence, Kan. _ Denise Lance almost didn't make it to her
graduation day.
</P>
<P>
   She was born with her umbilical cord wrapped around her neck,
depriving her of oxygen in the first few minutes of her life.
</P>
<P>
   The result: severe cerebral palsy.
</P>
<P>
   She learned to walk with the help of braces. When her elementary
school asked that she not use crutches, because other students
might trip over them, she walked on her knees. Now she doesn't need
crutches at all.
</P>
<P>
   She used to type her assignments by holding a stick in each hand
and pecking out the letters on her typewriter. Computer programs
that could translate the spoken word into the written would not
work for Lance, because her speech is unintelligible at times.
Then, her parents bought her a regular computer, and she discovered
that she could type faster with her toes.
</P>
<P>
   Lance, 30, has never been one to focus on what she cannot do.
She would rather share what she has done.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday she celebrated her biggest achievement yet when she
walked across the stage at the University of Kansas' Lied Center to
receive her doctorate in special education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time somebody talked to me about it, I thought they
were kidding,'' said Lance, who lives north of Independence, Mo.
``I didn't know if I could get a B.A., let alone a Ph.D.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lance wants to share with special-education teachers her
knowledge about disabilities and assistive technology.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough teachers know about the new resources available, said
Lance, who has talked about and demonstrated her toe-typing skills
at conferences.
</P>
<P>
   Special software allows her to type in abbreviations, which are
then translated into words. Her keyboard is mounted to a footrest.
</P>
<P>
   Lance taught herself how to design Web pages and launched her
own site about assistive technology. On her ``to-do'' list is a
book that offers suggestions for adapting computers to special
needs for less than $100.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot that teachers don't know about technology, so
kids aren't getting what they need,'' Lance said. ``Schools just
have to provide enough so kids can pass from grade to grade, but it
might not be enough for them to live up to their potential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the sad part...that people have low
expectations for children with disabilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance and her parents, Dorothy and Calvin Lance, know firsthand
about low expectations.
</P>
<P>
   When Lance was 4, doctors advised her parents that test results
showed her to be mentally impaired. Two years later, Lance's
first-grade teacher told Dorothy that her daughter was too smart to
stay in special- education classes.
</P>
<P>
   Another teacher kept Lance from participating in student
council, even after her classmates elected her to serve, her mother
said. When Dorothy Lance confronted the teacher, the teacher asked:
``Well, what can she do?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the worst year of my life,'' Denise Lance said.
</P>
<P>
   For every doubter, Lance also had fans. Heidi Wiggins grew up
next door to Lance in Buckner, and the two became fast friends. If
people stared when the two girls went shopping, Wiggins would stare
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was really brave to go to public school,'' Wiggins said.
``People didn't understand what was wrong with her, that she was
not mentally handicapped, just physically.''
</P>
<P>
   What Lance couldn't do on her own, her mother helped her do.
Dorothy drove Lance to her classes at William Jewell College in
Liberty, Mo., and at KU, making the 75-minute trip to Lawrence up
to four times a week. Dorothy also feeds, bathes and dresses her
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were things that I couldn't do for myself,'' Lance said,
``so I learned to let people help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Even as a kid, Lance didn't let the physical limitations slow
her down. When the other children in her neighborhood got bicycles,
she begged her parents for one. Her father, a retired machinist,
equipped Lance's bike with braces _ a sturdier version of training
wheels _ to keep it from tipping over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I couldn't do something,'' Lance said. ``Even
when other people said I couldn't, I didn't believe them.''
</P>
<P>
   She graduated from Fort Osage High School in 1987 and that fall
started classes at Jewell. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Aides took notes for Lance in class. Even so, she spent 12 hours
a day, seven days a week, doing her schoolwork. She still used her
typewriter and hand-held sticks to complete her assignments _ at a
pace of eight words a minute. The physical strain was crushing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to keep up,'' she said. ``That was the first time
I really felt handicapped.''
Lance dropped out after a semester, hoping that physical and speech
therapy would improve her abilities. It didn't. She went back to
college anyway.
</P>
<P>
   She started toe-typing in her junior year. Four years after her
return, she graduated with a double major in English and psychology
_ and a 3.86 grade point average. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ann Marie Shannon, a retired professor of English, remembers
when Lance enrolled in an upper-level Shakespeare course in her
third semester at William Jewell. Shannon worried that the course
was too difficult for any underclassman, but by the end of the
semester, she was convinced that Lance was no typical student. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some students who have a particular confidence, and
the drive it takes to study for several years,'' Shannon said.
``Denise enjoyed literature so much _ and she was so astute _ that
she could have gotten a Ph.D. in English.''
</P>
<P>
   Lance had a similar effect on Steve Colson, an assistant
professor in KU's special-education department and one of her
doctoral advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Lance's extraordinary characteristic is that she doesn't seem
very extraordinary at all, Colson said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Colson grew accustomed to the sight of Lance tapping out notes
with her toes. She met deadlines, never asked for special treatment
and did not complain, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I soon became aware that I was just seeing her as another
student, not as a student who has a disability,'' Colson said.
</P>
<P>
   Lance wants to teach in a university classroom, preferably close
to home. She did her student teaching online but prefers human
interaction. A voice synthesizer turns her written words into
lectures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not much stands between Lance and her dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a difference between being handicapped and being
disabled,'' Lance said. ``I will always have a disability, but I
don't have to be handicapped by it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
