<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOSPITALS-Y2K-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEALTH-CARE INDUSTRY FIGHTS YEAR 2000 BUG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FINN BULLERS and JULIUS A. KARASH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, MO. _ Some industries have already declared
victory, but hospitals, doctors and health insurers still are
straining to battle the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
   That is one reason health care, which relies on computer
technology for everything from bypass surgery to billing, has come
under harsh criticism for its slowness to address year 2000
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the health-care industry deals with matters of life
and limb, you would think it would be the best prepared,'' said Don
Meyer, a spokesman for the U.S. Senate Specia Committee on the
Year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The medical industry acknowledges that it may go down to the
wire for Y2K fixes _ Blue Cross and Blue Shield of Kansas City, in
fact, has 100 people working full time to implement a new computer
system this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Y2K repairs have been going on for years, and they will be
done in time, spokesmen say.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public can be confident that virtually every hospital and
a very large percentage of physician offices will continue to
operate normally,'' said Richard Corlin of the American Medical
Association. ``What we are likely to see are a series of annoyances
rather than a series of catastrophes.''
</P>
<P>
   Work is being done in two main areas: medical equipment, much of
which relies on embedded computer chips; and billing, which runs on
computer networks. The American Hospital Association says the
industry will spend $8.2 billion to exterminate the computer bug.
</P>
<P>
   While the industry says the job will be done, critics are far
less optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released a month ago, the President's Council on
Year 2000 Conversion said the health-care sector had ``not made
adequate progress in addressing the Year 2000 problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Bennett, a Utah Republican who leads the Senate's
year 2000 Committee, said the industry's ``current readiness levels
are amongst the lowest of any industry in the nation.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, Bennett's committee heard one of the most ominous
predictions from the Rx2000 Solutions Institute, a Y2K
medical-industry watchdog group in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are convinced the American health-care community is in
deeply serious trouble due to anticipated problems of the year 2000
changeover,'' said Joel Ackerman, Rx2000 director. ``Rx2000
believes that patient care, and indeed patient lives, are at
stake.''
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials bristle when they hear that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public does not have to be panicked into thinking that
physicians or hospitals are ignoring the situation,'' Corlin said.
``We're paying a great deal of attention to (Y2K), and most
facilities will work just fine.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In April the hospital association reported that 13 percent of
the hospitals surveyed were Y2K compliant and that 81 percent were
``moving toward Y2K compliance without major difficulty.''
</P>
<P>
   And on May 12 the American Medical Group Association released a
study showing that 11 percent of the 45,000 physicians it
represents in 40 states said their practices were Y2K ready,
although only half the members responded by the deadline. Of those,
96 percent said they would be ready by Dec. 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0204 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7422 &Cx1f; kan-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FISHER-BOOK-KAN &LR;      05-22 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-BOOK-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH ROOTS IN THE CEMENT INDUSTRY, SURVIVES IN A BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; txr:ILASCO, Mo. _ The world knows where Ilasco is.
</P>
<P>
   Not by name, although it's on the official state highway map.
Not by size, because only a dozen people live here.
</P>
<P>
   Yet anyone who reads knows Ilasco's location.
</P>
<P>
   Ilasco, you see, abuts the malevolent cave in The Adventures of
Tom Sawyer by Mark Twain _ the claustrophobic, dripping cave, with
Becky and Tom lost in the blackness with only their flickering
candles, and somewhere in that darkness the menacing Injun Joe.
</P>
<P>
   Ilasco is just south of Hannibal, Mo., and hard by the bluffs
that cloak, among others, the Mark Twain cave, now a relentlessly
promoted tourist attraction.
</P>
<P>
   What's left of this once booming town is a smattering of houses
on the east side of Missouri 79, structures that are dwarfed by the
bustling Continental Cement Co. plant across the road, with the
second-longest cement kiln in the world.
</P>
<P>
   So the ``where'' of Ilasco is familiar. But its ``who, what,
when and how'' had largely been forgotten until three years ago
when, curiously enough, another book appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of another tale by Twain, it was scholarly in approach,
encyclopedic in breadth, and a revelation of time and place. City
of Dust, A Cement Company Town in the Land of Tom Sawyer, by Gregg
Andrews, has become a linchpin of sorts for a metamorphic revival
of Ilasco.
</P>
<P>
   The book, residents say straightaway, assures Ilasco will be
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, City of Dust has around here become known simply as
``the book.'' Ask a question, the book appears and pages turn.
</P>
<P>
   When did the Atlas Portland Cement Co., the first of several
owners of the facility that employs 225 workers, first buy land
here? In 1901. When did production start? In 1903. And who named
Ilasco? It was L.P. Sprout, an Atlas chemist, who coined the
acronym for some of the ingredients used to make cement _ iron,
lime, aluminum, silica, calcium and oxygen _ Ilasco.
</P>
<P>
   There was more. There once were 3,000 people, speaking a babel
of languages, who lived and loved here while cement was shipped to
the Panama Canal, the Mississippi's locks and dams, an infinite
number of roads and bridges, the Empire State Building, even St.
Louis' Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Who recollected Ilasco's labor union militancy and the state
militia arriving in 1910; the churches, schools, taverns, gardens,
and even a communal pasture for family cows; or that into 1950s
Ilasco still more resembled a hodgepodge eastern European
settlement than any grid-constructed Missouri town?
</P>
<P>
   Who remembered the specifics of questionable land deals and
murders, the chemistry of cement and the machinations of
turn-of-the century capitalists, European immigration patterns
between 1900 and 1930, and that Jim Burge's right arm, irreparably
mangled in a rock mill accident in 1906, was worth exactly $70?
</P>
<P>
   And who recalled that 30-odd years ago the town was literally
flattened almost overnight to expand the cement plant, create a
highway, and rid the area south of Hannibal of what some termed an
eyesore?
</P>
<P>
   Except for old-time Ilasco residents, not many.
</P>
<P>
   That's changing, said David Polc, who grew up here. A group of
old-time residents have become zealots in seeing that Ilasco's tale
be told, not just in Andrews' book, but also be put out in the open
where anybody can see it.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with what happened here from 1901 to 1970, said Polc,
the escapades of Tom Sawyer and Huckleberry Finn look pretty spare.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, about 500 people filled Hannibal's Knights
of Columbus hall to celebrate Ilasco's heritage; visit; dance;
listen to old tunes; eat Hungarian, German, Italian, Slovakian,
Romanian, Ukrainian, Polish and American food; and, above all,
raise money for a historical monument on Missouri 79, across from
the still-standing Holy Cross Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   As markers go, the one planned will be sizable. Tentatively
budgeted at $9,000, the stone will tell Ilasco's story on one side
and have the names of donors carved on the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We raised a bunch of money,'' said Sally Polc, David's wife.
``People want that memorial. They want some recognition for what
happened here all those years ago. Tom Sawyer and Huck Finn are
fine. But Ilasco was the America most people who came to this
country as immigrants knew.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Northcutt, whose kin worked at the cement plant and
remembers that Ilasco was always referred to as ``the village,''
never ``the town,'' said:
</P>
<P>
   ``We're the children of the last people who lived in Ilasco. We
have to do this. We have to tell our story for others to see. If we
don't, it'll be gone forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews, an Ilasco native and an associate professor of history
at Southwest Texas University in San Marcos, said that when he was
a boy Ilasco's history amounted to little more than stories and
anecdotes told over dinner or out on the front porch.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got into my research, it was like a novel,'' Andrews
said. ``There was everything. You couldn't make this stuff up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Gregg mentions it in his book, but the one thing I think back
about is the dust,'' said David Polc. ``It was so thick that you
could walk right into somebody. You wouldn't see them coming. The
wind would change and your mother would holler and you'd head for
the clothesline to get the laundry off.''
</P>
<P>
   Northcutt, in turn, remembered silicosis, the filling and
hardening of the lower lung sacs caused by years of breathing the
dust. Northcutt made the noise of heavy wheezing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still hear that sound,'' he said. ``Young men who were
old men because their lungs were full of cement. It's a sound you
can't forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew said that without the help of Ilasco's residents, he
never could have finished his book.
</P>
<P>
   Yet his educated background and the book's numerous footnotes
and scholastic origins worried Andrews a couple of years ago when
he came to Big River Discount Books in Hannibal for a signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to expect,'' Andrews said. ``Here I was, a
local kid who'd become a college professor. What would the people
of Ilasco think? I hadn't pulled any punches.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews needn't have worried. Extending out the door of the
bookstore and down Broadway was a seemingly endless line of people
with roots in Ilasco _ some from as far away as Michigan, Ohio and
Texas. Most had surnames that strangers would stumble over trying
to pronounce. They were waiting to buy one of the thickest, most
expensive ($37) and most scholarly books of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``That line of people said to me that they knew an unbelievable
story had happened in their town,'' Andrews said. ``And somebody
was validating what they'd been through by telling it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
