<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREEK-BISHOP-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New Greek bishop enthroned in Atlanta
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Surrounded by mosaic apostles and saints and with
Jesus looking down from a dome overhead, Atlanta's new Greek
Orthodox bishop took his throne Saturday at the Cathedral of the
Annunciation in suburban Atlanta's DeKalb County.
</P>
<P>
   ``My beloved fellow bishop, you are entrusted with the very
authority that the Lord Jesus Christ entrusted to his apostles,''
said Archbishop Spyridon, head of the Greek Orthodox Archdiocese of
America, who presided over the installation.
</P>
<P>
   The hundreds of Greek Orthodox Christians who watched the
enthronement cheered their new bishop by shouting, ``Axios, Axios,
Axios,'' which means ``worthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Episcopal Bishop Frank K. Allan and the Rev. Leland
Collins, the United Methodist clergyman who heads the Georgia
Christian Council, participated in the service along with about 65
Orthodox priests and monks and several Orthodox bishops.
</P>
<P>
   Allan praised the ``collegiality'' and ``dialogue'' between
Anglicans and Orthodox Christians. ``I wanted to be here to support
the new bishop,'' he said after the service. ``We need all the
support we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this is a great day for Georgia as well as a great
day for the Greek diocese,'' Collins said. ``We've been waiting
sometimes patiently, sometimes impatiently, for this day for two
years. Bishop Alexios, in the time he has been here, has show a
great ecumenical spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   The enthronement ceremony began with a long procession of a mass
choir leading blue and gold-garbed altar boys, who were in turn
followed by rows of priests, monks, bishops and lay leaders of the
diocese. Archbishop Spyridon and Bishop Alexios brought up the
rear.
</P>
<P>
   The procession moved through dozens of children, many in Greek
costume, waving gladioli. When Bishop Alexios reached the steps of
the Cathedral, the children surrounded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're proud of him,'' said Nicole Paxton, 14, a student at
Brookwood High School in Gwinnett County.
</P>
<P>
   ``He works a lot with the youth,'' said her friend Mary
Katherine Patronis, a 16-year-old student at Pace Academy. ``He's a
wonderful people person. He's going to do great things for our
diocese.''
</P>
<P>
   Cathedral President George Vasilos compared Saturday's service
to a marriage ceremony. ``It's a wedding between the bishop and the
church,'' he said. ``This isn't like a corporation where you'll
serve for a few years and get transferred. Once you're made bishop,
this is your home.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexios, who was born on Christmas Day 1943 in Patras, Greece,
has served as temporary head of the Diocese of Atlanta since Jan.
1, 1997. The diocese had been vacant since the death of Bishop
Philip of Atlanta on Dec. 28, 1995.
</P>
<P>
   About 20,000 Greek Orthodox Christians are registered in the 65
parishes, four missions and four monasteries of the seven
Southeastern states in the Diocese of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech responding to his enthronment, Bishop Alexios said
his commitment to youth and promised to lead the church to help
them cope with problems from guns to drugs to interfaith marriages.
He also vowed to support the clergy of the diocese and to
evangelize on behalf of the church.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to the congregation, he said, ``All I ask of each one of
you is to give me_and through me to the diocese and through the
diocese to our Lord Jesus Christ_your time, talent and treasure.``
</P>
<P>
   He was not asking for money, he explained, but for love. ``I
pledge to you,''he said, ``that my love is unconditional.``
</P>
<P>
   Like a wedding followed by a reception, the solemn service was
followed by a festive banquet at a downtown hotel. There the new
bishop was saluted with the American and Greek national anthems and
an orchestral version of ``Georgia On My Mind.``
</P>
<P>
   Both Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell and DeKalb County CEO Liane
Levetan claimed him as their own, and both declared Saturday a day
in his honor in their respective jurisdictions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
