<SLUG> BC-NATO-BOMBING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO BOMBS KOSOVO REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH AND KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO acknowledged Saturday the mistaken bombing of
a well-known Kosovar rebel stronghold inside Yugoslavia, an attack
that killed and injured forces fighting the Yugoslav Army. It was
the latest in a near-daily string of fatal errors that have plagued
the NATO air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A report by an international monitor said that one Kosovo
Liberation Army rebel was killed and 15 were wounded on the hilltop
post in Kosare. The KLA said seven of its guerrilla soldiers were
killed.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie P. Shea said that military planners thought
the barracks 37 miles west of the Kosovo capital of Pristina,
seized by the guerrillas weeks earlier, still were occupied by
Yugoslav Army forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did strike that border command post,'' Shea told reporters
in Brussels. ``It was until very recently in the hands of the
Yugoslav Army, but it appears that it was then subsequently taken
over by the KLA.''
</P>
<P>
   The bombing was especially surprising because Western
journalists have been visiting the camp for the last two weeks, and
it has been shown on television regularly as an example of the
rebel army seizing back land formerly occupied by Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   KLA leader Hashim Thaci called the bombing a ``technical
mistake'' and said that despite the error, ``the NATO airstrikes
must continue, even more intensified.''
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, US officials sought to clarify why President
Clinton has asked NATO allies to mass 50,000 troops on the Kosovo
border. Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said that the troops
are not for an invasion, but are for a peacekeeping force that the
United States hopes eventually will be allowed into Kosovo. But US
officials clearly hoped that reports about the massing of troops on
the border would send a message to Belgrade that NATO is serious
about its demand and may be preparing for a ground war if
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   NATO members will meet next weekend in Brussels to work out the
details of the force. While some NATO countries, such as Britain,
have urged preparation for a ground war, other nations have urged a
temporary halt in the bombing to prod peace negotiations. In one
sign of NATO plans to boost the pressure on Belgrade, 18 F-18
fighters arrived Saturday at a base in the southern Hungarian town
of Taszar, and six more aircraft were expected there Sunday. The
bombing of the barracks overshadowed what NATO said was its busiest
night over Serbia, with 684 sorties, and its most devastating
attack yet on the Serbian electric power system. By early Saturday
afternoon, air raid sirens were sounding in Belgrade, and NATO jets
could be seen and heard overheard, suggesting another heavy 24-hour
period of bombing in the offing.
</P>
<P>
   At least 16 cities and towns across Serbia, including the
Yugoslav capital Belgrade, lost power when graphite bombs
short-circuited electrical transformers, the fourth-time NATO has
used so-called soft bombs to cut power.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time, NATO also used conventional bombs to
destroy transformers at the Kolubara power plant south of Belgrade,
suggesting an escalation in NATO's plans to make conditions harder
on civilians and increase pressure on the government of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic to give in to NATO's demands.
</P>
<P>
   By midafternoon, technicians had repaired enough of the
equipment at Kolubara to restore power to about 20 percent of the
capital, but brownouts were common and the government-owned
electricity board accused NATO of trying to create a humanitarian
disaster by cutting power nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   The Beta news agency reported that NATO's bombing had caused
complete blackouts in some major towns, including Cacak, Kraljevo,
Leskovac and Nis. Bombs also struck a residence of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO said it has hit hundreds of targets successfully, the
mistakes have attracted attention because they have sometimes
resulted in the deaths of the very people that the military
alliance is trying to help. NATO, for example, has acknowledged
striking refugee convoys and a hospital outside Belgrade. After
NATO bombs hit the Chinese Embassy on May 6, officials in Beijing
expressed outrage, temporarily deterring peace negotiations and
giving Milosevic a public relations bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   Among other developments Saturday:
</P>
<P>
   -- Finnish President Martti Ahtisaari briefed UN Secretary
General Kofi Annan on his talks with Russian Balkans envoy Viktor
S. Chernomyrdin and US Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott,
saying that ``we all see eye to eye'' on key issues. The talks
centered on a proposal for an international peacekeeping force, but
questions remains about NATO's demand that it take the lead role in
such an operation.
</P>
<P>
   -- Yugoslav forces freed an estimated 2,000 ethnic Albanians
from prison, where they had been held since trying to flee Kosovo.
``When the Serbs grabbed me, they said I was a terrorist,'' said
Sulejman Pec, 24. ``Sunday when they released me, they said, `You
are looking for NATO, so go find them.' ''
</P>
<P>
   -- After a lull, refugees once again began crossing the border
from Kosovo, with 3,700 moving to Albania on Friday and 5,000
expected in Macedonia on Saturday. A large group of refugees came
from Suva Reka, a town northeast of Prizren that formerly had
18,000 residents. Refugees from the town were ``driven from their
homes at gunpoint with half an hour to pack, gathered in the city
center and loaded onto buses,'' Shea said. The refugees were
transported to another town and then walked across the border.
</P>
<P>
   -- Another 2,740 refugees were flown out of Macedonia to various
countries for temporary resettlement. The Macedonian government,
meanwhile, was considering the contruction of two new refugees
camps.
</P>
<P>
   -- Serbian officials denied that its soldiers are deserting,
rebutting US suggestions that morale is low and that forces are in
disarray. The Serbs said that some forces are returning home as
scheduled, not deserting.
</P>
<P>
   -- The KLA's Thaqi, who spent the last two months inside Kosovo,
visited a refugee camp in Albania and was given a hero's welcome by
crowds of displaced residents. ``We are not alone. Albania is
supporting us, the world is supporting us,'' the 29-year-old rebel
leader told the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Another Kosovo leader, Rexhep Qosja, also appeared at the camps.
Qosja, 62, who heads the United Democratic Movement, urged an end
to the rift between the KLA and another Kosovo leader, Ibrahim
Rugova, whom the KLA considers a pacifist.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO countries, countries that have such different political
attitudes as Greece and Turkey, are agreeing,'' Qosja said. ``It
does not make sense if Albanians do not agree with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Kranish reported from Washington and Cullen from Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
