<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL ANIMOSITY AMONG OWNERS BREWING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Forbes magazine reported in the May 31 issue that
the Los Angeles Dodgers lost $11.5 million last season. What does
that mean to you?
</P>
<P>
   Will ticket prices rise again? Probably. Will the club attempt
to seek public assistance to help build lucrative luxury boxes so
they can afford another Kevin Brown?
</P>
<P>
   While those would be unpopular moves, how about another work
stoppage in two years when baseball's collective bargaining
agreement is set to expire?
</P>
<P>
   The animosity between management and players isn't an issue,
yet. But owners, whose unity always is a problem in these matters,
already are crumbling. In the last agreement, forged after the 1994
World Series was canceled, wealthy owners were required to pay a
percentage of their revenue to the smaller clubs to promote
competition.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees paid $13 million in revenue sharing. The
lowly Montreal Expos received $13 million. The Reds, Pirates and
A's received more than $6 million and actually turned a profit last
year as a result. The Dodgers paid almost that much and dumped the
salaries of pitchers Dave Mlicki and Mel Rojas to cut payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Don't cry for them. They are not about to throw Eric Young into
the street. The new owners at Fox lost $10 million televising the
World Series and didn't flinch. The O'Malleys lost $35 million over
the previous three years and did not cancel one cocktail party.
Corporations with many entities like Fox can shift around profits
and losses. And besides, business losses can be written off for the
first five years after a company is purchased.
</P>
<P>
   But wealthy clubs are angry because the money they've shelled
out has not been used to bridge the competitive imbalance. Instead
of going after free agents, smaller market club actually have
reduced payroll. They have taken the money to stay afloat, not to
bid for Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the wealthy owners felt strong-armed by the small-market
clubs during the last negotiations. It was one man, one vote _ not
three votes for George Steinbrenner because he has the best cable
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Bud Selig, now full-time commissioner after several years in an
interim role, pleaded that his Milwaukee Brewers could not survive
without assistance. Even with a new ballpark ready to open next
year, there is little chance the Brewers can make up ground.
</P>
<P>
   As always, the credibility of the owners' financial records will
come into question. Forbes put the number of clubs losing money at
14. Selig says it could be as high as 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in each one of our meetings since December 1997 and
there have been significant losses,'' Philadelphia GM Ed Wade said.
``Unless the whole thing is a charade _ and they would do that for
my benefit _ there are a lot of teams in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet every winter, free-agent money continues to pour. Not only
did the Dodgers give Brown $105 million last winter, the St. Louis
Cardinals gave Scott Radinsky $5 million for two years and the New
York Mets gave Dennis Cook $6 million for three. Both are
left-handed setup men, not even closers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that was the biggest statement for the health of the
game,'' agent Scott Boras said. ``The stars are going to get their
money, but when teams recognize and compensate the valuable but
lesser-known players like that, the game is in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   The players are watching from a distance, some closer than
others. If revenue sharing is not expanded as Selig wants, it's
unlikely any of the smaller clubs will be competitive and free
agents will have fewer options.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Phillies, playing in a top-five market, are
complaining. They have attempted fiscal restraint and balk at
Forbes' claim they made $4.5 million last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat in the room in 1994 during the lockout and listened to
the rhetoric,'' Phillies ace Curt Schilling said. ``I have a couple
businesses ... and I do know there are ways to manipulate the
numbers to make them say whatever you'd like. If they want to quell
the problem, open your books.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
