</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES BEAT WHITE SOX, 10-2  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Roger Clemens had waited 25 agonizing days for this
day to arrive. While Clemens was on the disabled list, George
Steinbrenner ignored Don Zimmer, Zimmer made incorrect predictions
about Joe Torre's return as manager, Torre surprised everyone when
he rejoined the team last Tuesday and the Red Sox leapt over the
Yankees into first place. Through it all, Clemens was merely
another spectator.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed dramatically Saturday as Clemens returned and
helped the Yankees subdue the White Sox, 10-2, at Comiskey Park in
Game 1 of a doubleheader. The Yankees almost forgot how he looked
in his uniform, but Clemens reminded them and everyone else why he
is so valuable and why he should be able to give this plodding team
a boost.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens recorded his 18th straight winning decision, setting an
American League record, but it was somewhat anticlimactic because
he has had 10 no-decisions during the streak. The Yankees helped
preserve Clemens' streak by rallying after he had been bruised
twice in his first five starts for them. But that was unnecessary
Saturday because the five-time Cy Young award winner allowed one
earned run and six hits over six innings. Andy Pettitte started
against Mike Sirotka in the second game as the Yankees searched for
their third straight victory after enduring a stretch in which they
lost 7 of 8.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by Jorge Posada's two-run homer and five runs batted in
and two-run home runs by Tino Martinez and Bernie Williams, Clemens
(3-0) will now pursue the major league record of 24 straight
victories by Carl Hubbell of the New York Giants (1936-37). As
excited as Torre was to see the Yankees hit three homers in a game
for the first time since May 4 and see an offense that had mustered
14 runs in the last 8 games erupt, the most important development
was Clemens' 89-pitch effort. Four days after the Yankees got their
manager back, they got their ace back, and his winning streak
continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a Hall of Fame-caliber guy,'' Torre said.
``The whole thing about pitching is anyone can light it up for one
or two starts. To do it over the course of a year, you have to be a
superstar.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens performed like a superstar when Frank Thomas batted with
runners on first and second in the fifth. The Yankees were ahead,
6-2, but Thomas had three homers in 43 at-bats off Clemens so it
was a tense moment. When Thomas hit a grounder to third base,
Clemens began skipping off the mound. He stared as the play
unraveled and pumped his fist when the Yankees turned two to end
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen years and two days after Clemens won his first major
league game, he won his 236th to tie the Hall of Famer Whitey Ford,
perhaps the best pitcher in Yankees history, for 49th place on the
career list. Clemens last lost on May 29, 1998, to Cleveland, while
he was with Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was late in finishing his warm-ups. He trotted across
the outfield grass with the Yankees' pitching coach, Mel
Stottlemyre, as Derek Jeter was about to bat in the first inning.
The bizarre scene, coupled with the sparse crowd for the opening
game, gave the sunny afternoon a casual feel. That changed in the
bottom of the first.
</P>
<P>
   When Clemens ambled to the mound for the first time in three and
a half weeks, he was typically fierce. He struck out Chris
Singleton with a 1-2 split-finger fastball and got Mike Caruso to
tap out to third base. But Ray Durham laced a single to right,
Thomas had an infield single when Jeter did not charge a roller to
shortstop, and both advanced on a wild pitch. Clemens figured he
was out of the inning when Magglio Ordonez hit a chopper to third,
but Scott Brosius bounced a throw to first and the White Sox were
ahead, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees countered in the second when Posada lined a fastball
off John Snyder over the center-field fence for a two-run homer. It
was Posada's first homer since May 8 and it gave Clemens a 2-1
edge. Posada also slapped a three-run double in the eighth, missing
a grand slam by five feet when the ball caromed off the left-field
fence. The five runs batted in gave Posada half as many r.b.i.
Saturday as the 10 he had managed in his first 88 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox tied it, 2-2, in the third, and the Yankees again
retaliated with power. After Williams walked to open the fourth,
Martinez belted a fastball that sneaked over the right-field fence
for another two-run homer and a 4-2 lead. It was Martinez's first
homer in 17 games. Would it be enough for Clemens to succeed and
remain unbeaten? It definitely was.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
