<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOTTERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS TO HAVE FIRST CHOICE IN MIXED BAG  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SECAUCUS, N.J. _ If winning six National Basketball Association
championships did not prove that Jerry Krause was good, he found
out Saturday that he could be lucky too, earning the No. 1 overall
pick in the coming draft for his Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls had the third-worst record in the NBA this season at
13-37 and therefore the third-most chances in the draft lottery,
after the Vancouver Grizzlies and Los Angeles Clippers. But after
winning the right to select first, Krause, the Bulls' general
manager, will not find a Michael Jordan in the draft. He may not
find a guaranteed impact player at all.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest winners Saturday were the Charlotte Hornets,
who had the fewest chances in the lottery (0.7 percent) but won the
third pick in the draft June 30 in Washington. The Grizzlies drew
the No. 2 pick, and the Clippers fell to the fourth spot.
</P>
<P>
   There is no clear-cut No. 1 pick and maybe not even a tier of
players that general managers and scouts can agree on as the class
of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a peculiar draft,'' said Marty Blake, the NBA scouting
director. ``There are going to be a lot of guys taken from about 15
to 40 that are going to turn out to be pretty good. This draft has
unusual depth. I'm not saying that they are great, but it's unusual
depth.''
</P>
<P>
   The players expected to go at the top of the draft are mostly
from the crop of underclassmen, including Lamar Odom of Rhode
Island, Corey Maggette and Elton Brand of Duke, Baron Davis of UCLA
and Steve Francis of Maryland. But no one seems sure which of those
players can emerge as an impact player.
</P>
<P>
   Maggette has drawn the most attention for his athletic
abilities, even more so than Brand, the college player of the year.
Maggette has been compared to Jordan, but he played just one year
at Duke and did not even start, which had coaches and family urging
him to return to school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Certainly Corey Maggette could be one of the top prospects
even though he didn't start for his college team,'' said Stu
Jackson, Vancouver's general manager. ``Most people feel that way
simply because he's got size for his position, 6 foot 6 at the
shooting guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a player whom teams had seen little of early, Michael
Olowokandi, emerged as the first pick. Still, with Maggette not
having an opportunity to show his wares on an extended basis, teams
may turn to one of the other underclassmen.
</P>
<P>
   Experience may not count for much, with the top seniors _ Wally
Szczerbiak of Miami of Ohio, Andre Miller of Utah, Jason Terry of
Arizona and Kenny Thomas of New Mexico _ projected below the top
three spots, lumped in with the likes of Ron Artest of St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   Among the underclassmen, Francis has been compared to Allen
Iverson of the Philadelphia 76ers, while some compare Odom to Magic
Johnson or Scottie Pippen with his size and skills.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing that most scouts and general managers agree on is
that the draft is unusually deep at the point guard position.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could have five point guards in the lottery this year and
five more that could be very good,'' Blake said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 2014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
