A7439 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN     05-22 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE'S OFF, PIAZZA PERFORMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ For those of you wishing Mike Piazza was still a
Los Angeles Dodger, the next few months could be painful.
</P>
<P>
   In the first game of Thursday's doubleheader between the New
York Mets and Milwaukee Brewers, Piazza finally had the kind of
night that made him the most feared catcher in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Although Robin Ventura!off hit grand slams in both games of the
Mets' sweep, Piazza's 3-for-5 with three runs and a two-run homer
set the tone.
</P>
<P>
   Until that point, Piazza, who spent two weeks on the disabled
list with a sprained knee, was having a below-average season for
him, and merely average for the rest of the league.
</P>
<P>
   The average among National League catchers was .273 with four
homers and 18 RBI. Before the streak and entering that game, Piazza
was at .273 with four homers and 19 RBI. With his home run Friday,
Piazza had homered in four straight games.
</P>
<P>
   One year after he was traded by the Dodgers to the Marlins and
onto the Mets in a seven-day span, Piazza feels it has all worked
out for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I have a big job, but I don't feel this team lives and
dies with me the way it was in Los Angeles,'' he said. ``I have a
responsibility, but I don't feel like it is `if I hit we win and if
I don't we lose.'''
</P>
<P>
   Stung in Arizona: The Arizona Diamondbacks spent a day in first
place this past week and outfielder Luis Gonzalez had a 30-game
hitting streak. But not all the news was good.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Stottlemyre will miss 4-6 weeks, possibly the season, after
two MRIs Wednesday disclosed a partially torn right rotator cuff
and a slight tear of the right labrum. He was 4-1, 3.49 in nine
starts after signing a four-year, $32 million free-agent contract
in the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre will try to rehab the injuries without surgery, but
if that does not take, he will face season-ending arthroscopic
surgery. While with the Mets, teammate Armando Reynoso underwent
surgery for similar shoulder injuries on Aug. 18, 1997. He made his
next major-league start on July 24, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a reason: Rod Beck had elbow surgery Saturday to remove
bone chips. Beck, who saved 51 games last year, says his elbow has
bothered him for a few years. He calls the surgery ``a 500-inning
tuneup.''
</P>
<P>
   With Beck absent, the Cubs didn't waste much time in filling the
closer's role. The team traded two minor-leaguers to Minnesota for
Rick Aguilera.
</P>
<P>
   Aguilera, who is earning $3.25 million in the last year of his
contract, is believed to be interested in a contract extension (one
or two years at $3 million a year). Beck is making $5.5 million
this year and will earn $3.5 next year. The Cubs have an option for
2001 at $4.5 with a $500,000 buyout.
</P>
<P>
   Wake-up call: Cincinnati's Jeff Hammonds hit three home runs in
Tuesday's 24-12 victory over the Colorado Rockies at Coors Field.
Entering the game, Hammonds was batting .132 with no homers and
three RBI...
</P>
<P>
   After hitting .273 with 44 doubles, 13 home runs and 73 RBI as a
rookie, Expos first baseman and Montclair Prep grad Brad Fullmer
now finds himself back at Triple-A Ottawa. Fullmer, who was hitting
.209 with 10 RBI in 29 games, had also hit just .197 last
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a team where a lot of guys are in the development
stage and there has to be something wrong when you have a worse
year than you had last year,'' manager Felipe Alou said. ``There
are some guys here who would be better off in the minors.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
