<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE AGENT INVESTIGATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was launching a wad of paper at my official Michael Jordan
wastebasket when she strolled into the office.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, she was hotter than Jeff Van Gundy's forehead
when the Knicks trail at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're scoring, the wad of paper fell harmlessly on the
indoor-outdoor carpet. I had been fouled, roughed up, worked over,
given the business.
</P>
<P>
   Glancing at the official Dick Bavetta 24-second clock on the
wall, I knew my best shot had to be forced.
</P>
<P>
   I took it. ``What's a woman like you doin' in a column like
this?''
</P>
<P>
   She smiled and reached into her purse.
</P>
<P>
   I reached for my super-soaker water pistol.
</P>
<P>
   She held up a piece of paper and said this: ``Do you validate
parking?''
</P>
<P>
   I let her have it with the super-soaker, then made the universal
sign of the technical foul. ``Hit the bricks,'' I said, pausing to
point the way with an unlit Red Auerbach cigar.
</P>
<P>
   As she was going out, a poorly dressed man was coming in.
</P>
<P>
   He nodded, then said what he had to say. ``I need free agents.
And don't even bother with Karl Malone and John Stockton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why, because there's no way they won't be back with Utah?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said, ``because they're dirtier than a truck stop
toilet.''
</P>
<P>
   Had me there. I changed the subject. ``You have cap room?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have cap room.''
</P>
<P>
   That meant he worked for the Clippers, Bulls or Raptors. But
rather than press him for more info, the 911, the scoop, I just
laughed. ``Do you know the free-agent market is as sparse as a
Thanksgiving turkey carcass after a victory lap by Milwaukee Bucks
coach George Karl?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Just do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's in it for me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clippers tickets.''
</P>
<P>
   I did it anyway. Thanks to the restrictive nature of the new
collective bargaining deal, most of these suspects will stay put.
Here's the best of what's left:
</P>
<P>
   POWER FORWARD
</P>
<P>
   1. Vin Baker (Seattle): Even though he had, for him, a
remarkably rotten season, he should be able to use his opt-out
clause to make the Sonics bleed.
</P>
<P>
   2. Gary Trent (Dallas): He represents the best move Don Nelson's
made since Nellie quit wearing sneakers with suits. The Mavs will
cough up big scoots to keep Trent.
</P>
<P>
   3. Charles Oakley (Toronto): Will make the Raptors pay dearly or
sign with a contender for much less.
</P>
<P>
   POWERLESS (SMALL) FORWARD
</P>
<P>
   1. Cliff Robinson (Phoenix): A 6-foot-11 ``three'' man who can
run, shoot and defend. Pay up, Suns.
</P>
<P>
   2. Corliss Williamson (Sacramento): Signed for only half a mil
so Kings could bring in Vlade Divac. Too bad he played like he was
paid.
</P>
<P>
   3. Detlef Schrempf (Seattle): His status may be affected by that
of volatile teammate Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER
</P>
<P>
   1. Erick Dampier (Golden State): A good shot blocker who truly
would be valuable if he could figure out how to block his own
shots.
</P>
<P>
   2. Olden Polynice (Seattle): Should be known as Lden, because he
has no O.
</P>
<P>
   3. Wilt Chamberlain (Motel 6): It was him or Will Perdue.
</P>
<P>
   SHOOTING GUARD
</P>
<P>
   1. Mitch Richmond (Washington): Sign-and-trade bait. Still would
look great in a Kings uniform.
</P>
<P>
   2. Penny Hardaway (Orlando): Too immature to ride the grown-up
rides at Disney World. Has inspired descendents of Abe Lincoln to
have Abe's mug removed from the one-cent piece.
</P>
<P>
   3. J.R. Rider (Portland): The good news ... hiring a babysitter
does not count against the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   POINT GUARD
</P>
<P>
   1. Terrell Brandon (Minnesota): Even though his agent and
T'wolves personnel boss Kevin McHale were college roomies, Brandon
could move.
</P>
<P>
   2. Nick Van Exel (Denver): Nuggets think the good outweighs the
bad.
</P>
<P>
   3. Eric Snow (Philadelphia): Shame, shame on his agent if this
guy signs with another team.
</P>
<P>
   I submitted my list to the poorly dressed man, then asked him to
reveal the name of his employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell ya,'' he said, ``but then I'd have to make ya
watch the 1999 Chicago Bulls highlight tape.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 30 seconds I just couldn't spare.
</P>
<P>
   WEAKLY DRAFT UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   The list of early entry draft candidates released this week did
not include the name Yao Ming. Ming is the 18-year-old from China,
who checks in at somewhere between 7-3 and 7-5, depending on the
quality of his sweat socks.
</P>
<P>
   The kid reportedly had signed with a Cleveland-based agent who
planned to make Ming available for the '99 draft. But the NBA
invalidated the agreement, so Ming is expected to be represented by
Bill Duffy (he is the agent for Brandon and Michael Olowokandi,
among others) when the draft rolls around next year.
</P>
<P>
   According to rumor, Chinese officials had hoped Ming would play
in L.A., then changed their minds upon realizing the L.A. in
question was not Los Alamos.
</P>
<P>
   The early entry list did include junior college hotshots
DeeAndre Hulett and Alexsandar Radojevic.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-7 Hulett (College of the Sequoias) is an athletic small
forward with shooting range and enough early hype to interest teams
selecting at the end of round 1 or the top of round 2.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-3 Radojevic (Barton County, Kan.) had signed to play at
Ohio State, but the NCAA put the kibosh on that move after finding
out this poor man's Zydrunas Ilgauskas had been paid to play in
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the list includes high schoolers Jonathan Bender
(Picayune, Miss.) and Leon Smith (Chicago). Bender, high-lottery
material, is a 6-11 forward who could be described as an unplugged
version of Kevin Garnett.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, second-round material, is a 6-9 center who played at
Martin Luther King High, and could be described as an unplugged
version of Elmore Smith.
</P>
<P>
   SHOT-CLOCK VIOLATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Rashard Griffith, the ex-Wisconsin bruiser who also played at
Chicago MLK, may return from an extended stay in Europe. The Bucks
still own the rights to the 6-10 Griffith, and just happen to have
an inside game that's weaker than frat-house beer. ... Thanks to
the Stephon Marbury trade, the Timberwolves have New Jersey's high
lottery pick, but prefer trading it for a player who shaves. ...
Shaquille O'Neal's destruction of an Alamodome TV proves he still
can't handle the screen. ... Hey, Dennis Rodman! You know it's time
to chill when you've been served with more suits than you've worn.
... Pacers center Rik Smits is evidence that socks education is not
being taught in Indiana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
