<HEADER>
A7447 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SHAS-BOS &LR;      05-22 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SHAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGIOUS SHAS PARTY: ONE OF ISRAELI ELECTION'S BIG WINNERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Down the streets of the insular world of Israel's
ultra-Orthodox Jewish neighborhoods, men in traditional black coats
and wide-brimmed hats glare with suspicion at outsiders. Young boys
and girls stare blankly before their mothers herd them inside their
homes, away from the strangers.
</P>
<P>
   They are known as the ``haredim,'' or ``God fearing.''
</P>
<P>
   But after capturing many more seats in parliament in Monday's
general election, the haredim are the ones instilling fear in many
Israelis. Especially the majority who want Israel to be first and
foremost a secular democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak, who was handed a landslide
victory, begins to form his government &UR;  &LR; Sunday. And Barak may
consider inviting the ultra-Orthodox party Shas, or perhaps one of
the other religious parties, into his Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts say that if Barak invites the
ultra-Orthodox in, he runs the risk of alienating the secular left
wing that worked hard to get him elected. Other observers say the
power of the ultra-Orthodox, and particularly Shas, has become so
overwhelming it can't be ignored if Barak wants to effectively
govern.
</P>
<P>
   Shas, a ``haredi'' movement that represents mostly first- and
second-generation immigrants from North Africa and the greater
Middle East, captured 17 seats in Israel's 120-member parliament.
By picking up seven seats, Shas, a Hebrew acronym for Sephardic
Guardians of the Torah, consolidated its place as the third-largest
party in Israel and reached a political parity with the
conservative Likud Party, which plunged to only 19 seats from the
32 it had before the elections.
</P>
<P>
   The secular left parties also scored big victories and many
secular voters, even those from the political right, said they
voted for Barak's left-of-center One Israel list because they
thought it would contain ultra-Orthodox influence in politics. So
the results of the election revealed a deepening of the
religious-secular divide.
</P>
<P>
   Religious law
</P>
<P>
   The political haredim are Jewish fundamentalists who
overwhelmingly support the implementation of ``halacha,'' or Jewish
religious law.
</P>
<P>
   The growing power of the haredim has also made many American
Jews, whether secular, Conservative, or Reform, uneasy about the
direction they think the haredim are trying to take a nation to
which they have strong ties.
</P>
<P>
   Since Zionism began a century ago, the underlying question has
been whether a Jewish state would define itself as a democracy or a
theocracy. The rise of the haredim has given the question new
urgency.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Rosenblum, 43, a Yale Law School graduate who grew up
in a traditional Jewish home in suburban Chicago, is a member of
the haredim and writes a column for the Jerusalem Post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shas is a reflection of traditional Jews returning to a more
intense religious experience,'' he said. ``There is a fear among
seculars, a terror of the haredim that vastly exaggerates our
political influence. It is a form of bigotry, plain and simple.''
</P>
<P>
   High birthrate
</P>
<P>
   The fear is brought on by a sense that Israel, especially
Jerusalem, has become overrun by the ultra-Orthodox. The haredim
have an average of seven children per family. More than 50 percent
of children in Jerusalem, and about 25 percent across Israel,
attend haredi schools.
</P>
<P>
   The community is a significant drain on the Israeli economy. The
unemployment rate among Haredi men is an estimated 60 percent
because so many are enrolled in yeshivas, or religious seminaries.
The number of yeshiva students has surged from 35,000 in 1990 to
almost 80,000 Sunday, and the black-clad ultra-Orthodox young men
leafing through Talmudic texts and praying in a rhythmic
back-and-forth movement seem ubiquitous in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The army of yeshiva students has given Israel a higher rate of
nonparticipation in the adult male workforce than any other country
in the developed world, according to one study. They receive
welfare, tax exemptions, national insurance, and stipends for books
and are given a blanket draft deferment while they study. This has
caused seething resentment in a nation where the economy is
faltering and where a selfless devotion to mandatory military
service is a point of pride. One of Barak's most resonant campaign
themes was to put an end to the blanket deferments and force the
students to carry out some form of national service.
</P>
<P>
   Political power
</P>
<P>
   The Jerusalem neighborhood of Har Nof is a manifestation of the
religious zeal, the factionalism, the mysticism, and the raw
political power of the ultra-Orthodox community. A swath of modern
symmetrical apartment buildings built of white stone, the community
overlooks the sprawling, ancient Jewish cemeteries on the Mount of
Olives outside the Old City.
</P>
<P>
   Here lives the spiritual leader of Shas, Rabbi Ovadia Yosef, as
does Aryeh Deri, who stepped down as the group's political leader
after the election. Deri can be compared to America's populist,
immigrant political bosses _ playing off ethnic resentment,
religious affiliation, and the suffering of the underclass, in this
case to gain influence for the Jewish migrants from North Africa
and the Arab world known as the Sephardim.
</P>
<P>
   In Benjamin Netanyahu's outgoing governing coalition, Deri was
particularly skillfull at channeling funding to Sephardic housing,
to educational institutions and health care clinics in
disenfranchised Sephardic neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   And like many old school political bosses, Deri has run into
trouble with the law. Deri was convicted of corruption, bribery,
and fraud and sentenced last month to four years in prison. He is
awaiting appeal, but has lashed out at Israel's judicial system,
saying it is controlled by the secular, Ashkenazi elite of European
Jews, who want to keep him from empowering the Sephardim.
</P>
<P>
   On land issues, the ultra-Orthodox, especially Shas, are more
pliable than the ultranationalists, who are also religious. But the
ultra-Orthodox are just as rigid on social issues.
</P>
<P>
   Arazi Cohen, 39, of Moroccan ancestry, a Yeshiva student, was
carrying thick, leather-bound volumes of Talmudic interpretations
under his arm, excited about the success of Shas in the recent
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of this nation wants Judaism, more Jewish life.
This country should be established with religious laws,'' said
Cohen, reflecting the messianic fervor among the ultra-Orthodox who
believe Israel is destined to become a theocratic state.
</P>
<P>
   Culture war
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the religious-secular divide in Israel is a
culture war between Jerusalem, where the haredi are thriving, and
Tel Aviv, the heart of Israel's secular culture.
</P>
<P>
   Haredim are casually referred to by secular Israelis as ``the
blacks,'' a comment on the color of the men's clothing, but many
religious people believe it is said with derision and an underlying
bigotry.
</P>
<P>
   But the haredim, too, have a lexicon of hatred, referring to the
nonreligious as ``the Messiah's donkeys.''
</P>
<P>
   Sefi Rachlevski, author of a nonfiction book titled ``Messiah's
Donkey,'' said, ``More and more secular Israelis feel they are
losing the identity of Israel. They feel they have become donkeys
for a dream of the messianic ultra-Orthodox, and for the settler
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In this election,'' Rachlevski said, ``the donkeys said,
`Enough is enough.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 2057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7448 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELGRADE-SCENE-BOS &LR;      05-22 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELGRADE-SCENE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFIANCE GIVES WAY TO GRIM RESIGNATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE _ A few days ago, the outdoor cafes in the Skadarlija
section of the Yugoslav capital were teeming with patrons, as
Belgrade residents sipped beer and soaked up the late afternoon
sun.
</P>
<P>
   Without warning, there was a huge explosion nearby, a thud that
jerked conversation to a sudden halt. But only briefly. People
paused for a few seconds, looked at each other, then turned back to
their conversations. In the beer garden of the BiP brewery, none of
the two dozen patrons got up to leave.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO's air campaign enters its third month, the constant
bombardment of this capital has left its 2 million residents more
than war-weary. They are literally weary. Sleep deprivation is one
of the biggest byproducts of the bombing of Belgrade. Virtually
everyone complains of not having slept soundly since the bombing
began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The exuberant defiance shown in outdoor rallies in the early
days of the bombing has been replaced by something more like groggy
resignation that the war, and the widespread inconvenience and
occasional violent death that goes along with it, will continue
indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   There is a certain routine and normality to the days, while
nights are almost always accompanied by wailing air raid sirens,
the hum of NATO warplanes overhead, and the booms of missiles,
striking in and around the city.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from some isolated staples, such as sugar and cooking oil,
there are no obvious food shortages. Buses and trolleys run, and
they are always full, though more than half of the population is
out of work. People wait in line for hours to buy cigarettes, while
impatient or desperate smokers pay double or triple prices on the
black market. Gas is being rationed, but plenty is available on the
black market for those willing to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the people of Sarajevo, who lost their electricity and
water for years, people in Belgrade so far have not had to put up
with the sort of maddening inconvenience that others in the Balkans
have had to endure for parts of the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   There is an unsettling unpredictability about the war. After
nearly two weeks of relative calm that followed NATO's mistaken
bombing of the Chinese Embassy, nightly bombing resumed last
Tuesday, and some of the heaviest bombing of the last two months
occurred Wednesday night into Thursday morning. Saturday, NATO said
it had flown the most sorties in any 24-hour period, and vowed to
increase them.
</P>
<P>
   Few people here now believe it's going to get better before it
gets worse. There were widespread blackouts Saturday. The
inconvenience factor may be about to be racheted up considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Residents say the bomb shelters are less crowded these days than
when the bombing first began _ not because there is any less
bombing, but because more people have decided to take their chances
in the comfort of their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   Vera Balabanic does a mean impression of a cruise missile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weeeee-oooooooo, boom!'' says the 73-year-old woman. She says
her nerves are shot, that she fears that the missiles that struck
the police building just a block from her home will one day come
through her wall. That isn't enough to get her to leave her
9th-floor apartment for the bomb shelter in her basement. After a
few sleepless nights in the basement, she swore off shelters.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Veljko, also 73, agrees, saying he would rather die
in his bed than endure the claustrophobic cacophony of the shelter.
For him, suffering is relative. As a 17-year-old partisan, he was
captured and held in a concentration camp for nearly two years by
the Nazis' Croatian collaborators.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the fear is bigger than the rational thinking, then you go
to the bomb shelter,'' he explains, sitting in his living room,
strains of Marvin Gaye's ``What's Going On'' coming from the
stereo. ``Right now, rationally, I don't want to go to the bomb
shelter.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Balabanics, like tens of thousands of Belgrade residents,
take the odds that their homes won't be hit by stray NATO missiles.
The strategy is not without risk. Every one here mentions a
3-year-old girl killed in one of the early raids. On Thursday, a
missile fell 500 yards short of its target, a military complex,
flattening a hospital neurological unit and killing at least four
people.
</P>
<P>
   But if staying in one's apartment is better than trying to get a
night's sleep in a bomb shelter, it is only marginally better.
Sladana Topalovic, a dentist, said she has never felt more tired in
her life. She said that when she gets up in the morning she feels
as if she has closed her eyes but not slept.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody feels like this, it's not just me,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   If Belgrade residents think they have it bad, there are some who
believe they don't have it bad enough. Some NATO commanders want to
cut off electricity and water, in hopes of stirring resistance to
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Still, few people here expect a public uprising, or for
Milosevic to sacrifice himself for a settlement. As NATO turns the
screws, ordinary people voice anger at NATO, not Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   But judging dissent here is difficult. Police, many of them in
plainclothes, are everywhere. After opposition party leaders
suggested Milosevic cut a deal with NATO, their offices were
vandalized by mobs as police looked on.
</P>
<P>
   Like many who have relatives in the countryside, Joca Dokoc sent
his wife and 7-year-old son to a rural area last month. Without
telling him in advance, they returned on Wednesday, just in time
for the heaviest bombing, including the first bombs that fell in
their neighborhood, aimed at nearby fuel tanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son is very frightened,'' says Dokoc. ``He said, `Can I
sleep in your bed?' I said, `OK for tonight. Tomorrow, you go back
to the country.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
