 COLUMN-TEX 
MODEL CITIZEN OR NOT, SPREWELL IS A PLAYER (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like it or not, Latrell Sprewell is back.
</P>
<P>
   As an impact player. As a model citizen. As the American dream?
</P>
<P>
   ``People say I'm what's wrong with sports today,'' Sprewell says
in his new TV ad for And-1 shoes while Jimi Hendrix' Woodstock
rendition of the national anthem plays. ``I say I'm the American
dream.''
</P>
<P>
   While the NBA league office and Warriors coach P.J. Carlesimo
cringe, Sprewell has single-handedly grabbed the Hawks by the
throat with a combined 62 points in the first two games. Still
coming off the bench, Sprewell is dominating Atlanta with his
full-court athleticism and an aggressive offensive attitude lacking
in New York this decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just finds ways to score,'' teammate Chris Childs said. ``I
don't know if there's a better improviser in the league. He can
finish in transition, and when things break down for us, he can
always create a good look for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   While critics complain about a postseason littered with
predictable low-post offenses and double-down defenses, Sprewell
should be a breath of fresh air. Unlike the regular season, he has
stopped laughing on the bus after losses, stopped suing the NBA for
his one-year suspension and even put on hold an appeal of a $25,000
fine from the Knicks for his agent's criticism of him not starting
in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to play basketball and nothing else,'' Sprewell
said. ``I'm having fun.''
</P>
<P>
   So are the Knicks, 4-1 on the road in the playoffs after going
8-17 during the season. So are the fans, evidenced by No. 1 Knick
fan Spike Lee showing up wearing Sprewell's No. 8 jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Just leaves you wondering, given Sprewell's physical gifts, if
he wouldn't have made a difference in all those New York losses to
Jordan and the Bulls? PACERS-SIXERS
</P>
<P>
   Allen Iverson has taken 83 shots to score his 86 points in the
first three games. ``As good as Allen is, I don't think you can
compare him to Michael Jordan,'' Pacers coach Larry Bird said.
``When Michael scored 30 or 40 on you you'd usually get beat.'' ...
As it has been all season Indiana's bench has been the difference,
outscoring the 76ers by an average of 24-9. LAKERS-SPURS
</P>
<P>
   Call it on-the-job-training: Lakers coach Kurt Rambis thought he
made it clear that he wanted a double-team on Tim Duncan and that
his team had a foul to give. He thought that until he watched
Duncan make a game-winning 8-foot jump hook over J.R. Reid's single
coverage. ... After his dismal Game 1 performance, Shaquille O'Neal
punched a VCR/TV set in the Alamodome locker room costing around
$500. ... Will Perdue could go scoreless and be San Antonio's MVP
of the series for his banging of O'Neal. ``I just try to make his
3-foot hook a 4-foot hook,'' Perdue said. ``With him, it makes a
difference.'' JAZZ-BLAZERS
</P>
<P>
   Hard to imagine a team playing better defense than Portland
during Saturday's 19-0 run in which the Blazers held the Jazz and
its pet pick-and-roll without a basket for more than 10 minutes.
... NBA's most underrated player: Blazers power forward Brian
Grant. Most overrated: Damon Stoudamire, who isn't even the best
point guard on his team (Greg Anthony). ... Jazz coach Jerry Sloan
hates to double-team, but he paid Grant the ultimate compliment by
having John Stockton double him any time Grant dribbled in Game 3.
NUMBERS GAME
</P>
<P>
   6-0: The Pacers' record in the playoffs. The past four teams to
start 6-0 won the title. BAD LOOKS
</P>
<P>
   Worst look: Just when you thought nothing could be worse than
Rik Smits' shaved head last season, he breaks out ridiculous
knee-high black socks.
</P>
<P>
   Worst hair: Portland's Brian Grant has too much, and his coach,
Mike Dunleavy, has too little. 24 SECONDS
</P>
<P>
   One term rarely heard during the exciting, if not artistic
playoffs: lockout. ... Ugliest sight of the postseason: Bloated
Bulls general manager Jerry Krause gloating over winning Saturday's
lottery. ... Don't bet on Charles Barkley retiring, though money
won't be his motivation to return. ``I got $30 million in the
bank,'' Barkley said. ``If I spend all that, I deserve to be broke.
I'd just be leaving more to my freeloading relatives to fight over
when I die.'' ... Also don't be shocked if Penny Hardaway isn't
back in Orlando next season. ``I think he's sending some pretty
strong signals that he'd like to be somewhere else. If that's the
case, we'll help him do that,'' Magic owner Rich DeVos said. ``I
don't think he performed at the level he wanted to be at, and it
was frustrating for him. But it just seems like we can't please
him.'' ... One last wager: The Heat will stay intact despite its
second consecutive upset loss to New York. ``One bounce of the
ball, with eight-tenths of a second left in the game, is not going
to deter me from staying with these guys,'' Miami coach Pat Riley
said. ``Heads are not rolling, unless it's mine.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
