<HEADLINE>
WHILE PLAYOFFS RAGE, IDLE TEAMS PLAYING GAMES OF THEIR OWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We're down to the Elite Eight, NBA style, which
means two things.
</P>
<P>
   You can no longer avoid play-by-play from Bob Costas, who at
least has been deprived this season of moaning his trademark
``Michael!'' in sycophantic tribute to Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   It also means 21 other teams no longer have anything to do.
Well, that isn't completely true. The good organizations are
eagerly awaiting the draft, free agency and trading periods.
</P>
<P>
   So let's take a scan around the league to see what the have-nots
are thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Boston: Rick Pitino wants to gut the roster, which is good,
because the Celtic players have had it with the Slick Rick routine,
especially former Kentucky stars Antoine Walker and Ron Mercer.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte: Looking to dump troublemaker Anthony Mason before he
gets Elden Campbell back to his sulking self. On the other hand,
desperate to re-sign Eddie Jones, a free agent in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago: Tim Floyd was a miracle-worker this season, so that may
be why the Bulls are prepared to make an offer to everybody's least
favorite player, Orlando's Penny Hardaway.
</P>
<P>
   Clippers: There is lots of buzz that they are keenly interested
in trading their draft pick. They always get plenty of offers.
They'll take one if owner Donald T. Sterling and VP's Andy Roeser
and Elgin Baylor agree on something. Oh, Chris Ford's opinion
counts too.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland: Here's the Cavs' offseason wish list: 1.Obtain Wally
Szczerbiak. 2. Keep Mike Fratello. 3.Extend contracts of Brevin
Knight and Derek Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas: Mavs fans are bracing themselves for Don Nelson's next
disastrous move. They have offered Robert Pack to Charlotte for
Anthony Mason. Hmmm, not so disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   Denver: Nick Van Exel will be brought back, but the Nuggets'
prized possession this offseason is Phil Jackson. Good luck, guys.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit: Team already has given ultimatum to Bison Dele.
Management is in a quandary over how to secure talent to keep Grant
Hill from bolting when his contract is up.
</P>
<P>
   Golden State: Say adios to Tony Delk, Duane Ferrell, Muggsy
Bogues, Felton Spencer and possibly Erick Dampier as the Warriors
try to remold their bench.
</P>
<P>
   Houston: No cap room because of bloated payroll, and trades are
unlikely. Rudy T.'s challenge is to introduce offense to Scottie
Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   Miami: As usual, Pat Riley has lots of ideas on how Heat got
knocked off (none involving himself). So that means some roster
purging, starting with Dan Majerle and P.J. Brown, and a longshot
stab at Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee: George Karl wants a big man and wants to make a run
at Lorenzen Wright and Vin Baker. He also wants to trade Chris
Gatling and Ervin Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota: How to sign Joe Smith? He's this year's Gugliotta for
the T'Wolves. Terrell Brandon wants to play elsewhere, but has
graciously agreed to a sign-and-trade deal.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey: They want to bring back Don Casey _ unless Phil
Jackson is dumb enough to take the job. Then they need to figure
out how to get Jayson Williams' broken leg to heal in time for next
season.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando: Remember when they were worried Hardaway might not be
back? Today, Chuck Daly's practically buying him a one-way ticket
out of Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix: The Suns are trying to re-sign Cliff Robinson but the
hot news is that Tom Gugliotta might be sent off. How 'bout to the
Lakers for Glen Rice?
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento: The Kings will be happy to make some minor
adjustments and let Rick Adelman have a full training camp. By
then, he might not be drawing heat for keeping Jason Williams on
the bench in the fourth quarter of Game 5 against Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle: Local institution Detlef Schrempf wants out and Hersey
Hawkins is on the block. Don't expect Don MacLean back either. The
problem is what to do about Payton, with rumors flying that Miami
wants to make a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto: The Raptors want to re-sign Charles Oakley but are
sending out feelers to anyone who wants Doug Christie. They are
also looking to deal one of their lottery picks.
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver: As of today, the Grizzlies are torn between trading
their pick or drafting Lamar Odom. The dilemma is they need
experience to blend with youngsters Mike Bibby, Shareef-Abdur Rahim
and Big Country Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   Washington: Hey, hiring a coach would be nice. Darrell Walker
and John Lucas are the latest candidates. Then they need to figure
out how to keep Mitch Richmond, who wants to leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
