<SLUG> BC-BBN-LIEBERTHAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERTHAL IS A CATCHER ON THE RISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hanging out by the pool did not sound like a fun
offseason for Mike Lieberthal.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies starting catcher missed the final 2{ months of the
season with a stress fracture to his pelvis, suffered during an
early June collision with Toronto's Carlos Delgado at home plate.
He couldn't squat, couldn't run. All he could do was swim.
</P>
<P>
   Before he could resume his career as one of the National
League's most promising catchers, Lieberthal, 27, spent the winter
at his home in Thousand Oaks, swimming and running in neck-deep
water, drills designed to build strength in the pelvic area without
applying much weight.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors said the injury would take six months to heal.
Eleven months later, he is on a tear, batting .351, including eight
homers and 20 RBI in his past 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, he hit two homers, including a grand slam, and
drove in six runs against the Montreal Expos. In Saturday's 9-3
victory over the Mets, Lieberthal hit a three-run home run and
finished with four RBI. He is batting .361 with runners in scoring
position and has just one error in 38 games behind the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to take patience,'' he said, ``and so far
the patience has paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   Diligence might be a better word, a word Phillies manager Terry
Francona uses to describe Lieberthal's approach throughout his
professional career.
</P>
<P>
   _Although he was just 150 pounds as a senior at Westlake High,
Lieberthal was selected third overall in the 1990 draft. He was a
controversial pick, taken ahead of future big-league stars Alex
Fernandez and Mike Mussina by the pitching-starved Phillies.
</P>
<P>
   _Lieberthal also was groomed to replace popular and gritty
Darren Daulton on a team that began to stumble badly after reaching
the World Series in 1993. He was chastised by the Phillies pitching
staff, especially ace Curt Schilling, for his work behind the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   _And after reaching career highs with 20 homers and 77 RBI in
his first full season (1997) Lieberthal was grounded by the injury
to his pelvis.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has had a lot to work through, but I think his success is
testimony to the kind of person he is,'' Francona said. ``Guys here
say he is a laid-back California kid and he is. But he burns to
succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his gaudy statistics, Lieberthal's greatest contribution
to the Phillies' strong start is his improved relationship with the
pitchers. After four years, his signal calling is now deeply
respected.
</P>
<P>
   So much so that when Schilling struck out 319 batters in 1997,
he gave Lieberthal a Rolex watch ``for making it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As well as Mike hits and throws, the success of this team
depends on how he develops the pitching staff,'' Francona said.
``If we are to move forward we need that relationship to be strong.
You can't have a veteran catcher he has been around awhile. And he
was replacing Daulton. But look at the way he handles them now. I
think that is why we have gotten off to a better start.''
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies are 22-19, just one game behind the second-place
Mets in the National League East. Lieberthal is cautious about his
early numbers and tapered his enthusiasm about last Wednesday's
home-run binge. He has never hit above .256 in the big leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost the game so it was not as much fun as it could have
been,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberthal knows he won't receive much All-Star ballot support.
He has outplayed Mike Piazza during the first seven weeks of the
season, but Piazza had homered in four consecutive games entering
Saturday's game.
</P>
<P>
   After going 3 for 4 with two home runs and six RBI on Wednesday
night in Montreal, Lieberthal was hitting .352 with eight homers
and a team-high 27 RBI after 39 games. He also is far superior to
Piazza defensively, and has six more RBI than the Mets catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so early,'' Lieberthal said when asked about All-Star
consideration. ``I really don't think about it, because I feel like
Piazza and (Jason) Kendall are going to be the two catchers who
make it. But if they want to carry a third catcher and I still have
these stats halfway through, it's something I've always wanted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 2149EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
