<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOTTERY-CLIPPERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS DRAW NO. 4 IN DRAFT LOTTERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Chris Ford, whose team (finally) had put him in a
swell position to win, had a front-row seat when Saturday's NBA
Draft lottery loss applied the frosting to his first Los Angeles
Clippers season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we would have liked to have done a little better,'' Ford
said after his Clippers, whose 9-41 record gave this franchise the
second-best chance to nab the first pick, were ping-ponged into the
fourth spot for this year's first round. Among the 13 lottery
teams, the Clipper's two-spot tumble was the furthest.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Bulls, who earned the third-best chance by putting
the ``nasty'' in dynasty, rallied to finish first. The Charlotte
Hornets, who arrived with the slimmest chance at victory, left with
the third pick.
</P>
<P>
   However, identifying the true winners and losers is impure
speculation; this season's projected Rookie of the Year, Vince
Carter of the Toronto Raptors, was the fifth player drafted last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a definitive No.1 pick,'' Ford said on a
conference call after representing the Clippers for the benefit of
NBC cameras. ``The most important thing is to see these guys up
close.''
</P>
<P>
   The potential lottery list that includes 6-foot-9 Rhode Island
swingman Lamar Odom, Maryland combo guard Steve Francis, UCLA point
guard Baron Davis, Connecticut shooting guard Richard Hamilton and
young Corey Maggette, a gymnast disguised as a forward during his
one season at Duke.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers plan to haul several players into L.A. for private
auditions, although their fall to fourth may cross them off the
travel itinerary written by agents of the hottest prospects.
</P>
<P>
   ``At four, some players won't even come work out for you,'' Ford
said.
</P>
<P>
   Further complicating his predicament is the franchise's evolving
battle plan for the eight free agents who wore the Clippers colors
in 1999. The personnel needs of any team can be twisted with one
swipe of a pen. But, as dictated by the NBA, free agents can't be
signed until Aug. 1. The draft will be held June 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to look at each and every position,'' Ford said of the
draft candidates. ``We have to make sure we cover our bases. When
you have eight free agents, anything can happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the draft is the first priority. We have to be happy with
who we select.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers, who picked first after achieving the league's
third-worst record last season, remain pleased with center Michael
Olowokandi, the player selected with the top choice in '98. And
they are thrilled with the progress of power forward Maurice
Taylor, their first-round pick (14th overall) in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Adding another hot prospect to this promising nucleus seems
crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to pinpoint one exact need,'' Ford said, ``but
we definitely want players who are going to compete on a nightly
basis. We want guys who want to be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
