<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD-WORKING CIENFUEGOS IS TRYING TO GET GALAXY FIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Long after training ends and while most are
finishing their showers, it's not unusual to find 31-year-old
midfielder Mauricio Cienfuegos taking extra shots or finishing an
extra set of sit-ups.
</P>
<P>
   As the Los Angeles Galaxy playmaker enters the latter stages of
his career, fitness for the 5-foot-4 set-up man becomes extremely
important.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a big-time professional, his work ethic is first rate,''
Galaxy coach Sigi Schmid said. ``Sometimes you say at his age he
needs to do a little less, but more is what he feels comfortable
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Usually, Cienfuegos snags one of the younger players to help him
with his extra drills _ and he doesn't plan on slowing down now
that he's getting older.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've grown accustomed to it,'' Cienfuegos said. ``I may not be
the last one off the field all the time, but usually I am. Maybe
I'm wrong, but the older you get the more time you need to put in
to train.''
</P>
<P>
   The El Salvadoran has struggled recently, as has the Galaxy, but
he's hoping to help change all that this afternoon when Los Angeles
plays host to New England at the Rose Bowl at 4:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe his teammates should be out there a little longer with
him. Following last week's 1-0 loss to Tampa Bay, the Galaxy fell
to 4-5. The team has struggled offensively, netting only five goals
in nine games.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, who arrived to training camp late because of a
contract dispute with Major League Soccer, says the difference
between last year's team and this one is fitness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come to the conclusion that last year we had a great
preseason and we were very well prepared physically heading in,''
Cienfuegos said. ``This year that didn't happen and now we're
paying the price.''
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos may be paying the biggest price. He admits his timing
has been off, limiting his ability to feed the ball to the
necessary space for strikers Welton and Cobi Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been off in terms of rhythm and timing of my distance
(passes),'' Cienfuegos said. ``Once I get that going, we'll start
getting Cobi and Welton the ball in a timely manner.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the bulk of the offense flowed through Cienfuegos.
This season, he's had to work a lot harder to get touches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's seeing some of the ball, but he can see a lot more of
it,'' said Schmid. ``Especially if we can take a lead. If that
happens, he'll see more of the ball because teams will come at us a
lot more, creating opportunities for us to play the ball through
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the lack of scoring this season isn't for lack of
chances. As Schmid has maintained the past two weeks, Cienfuegos
said the Galaxy misses a physical presence up front.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was our Achilles' heel last week,'' Cienfuegos said. ``We
had some crosses by the bunches and if we had a central striker
like (Carlos) Hermosillo, he would have probably knocked three of
those goals in. We've had the opportunities, but we do miss that
presence in the middle.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo is closer to returning. His Mexican team faces
elimination this weekend. If they should fall, he would need a
week's vacation prior to joining the Galaxy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
