<SLUG> BC-GEN-SOFTBALL-REGIONAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHRIDGE FALLS, UCLA WINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ And so it goes with Cal State Northridge softball:
impressive sometimes but not impressive enough times.
</P>
<P>
   That pattern marked the Matadors during the Big West Conference
season, preventing them from sweeping opponents and defending their
title. And it marked them Saturday in the NCAA regional at UCLA
when second-seeded Missouri eliminated them with a 3-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   That's the same Missouri team that had never beaten fifth-seeded
Northridge (30-24) in six previous meetings, including Thursday's,
when the Matadors rocked Stephanie Falk's offspeed pitches for six
runs in the second inning en route to a 7-3 win.
</P>
<P>
   This time, CSUN collected seven hits but couldn't hit Falk
enough to sustain a rally. Although coach Janet Sherman said her
team adjusted to Falk's throwing outside (she threw inside
Thursday), Northridge left runners on third twice and scored its
lone run on a throwing error in the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``She threw the same as our first game,'' Missouri coach Jay
Miller said, ``but she had better command of her pitches today.
When she is on, no one else is better in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Northridge had its chances. Katrina Nolletti doubled in
the fifth but stayed on second. So did Summer Richardson after she
pinch-doubled in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Pierce doubled to lead off the seventh and pinch
runner Michelle Wintermute reached third with two outs, but Jessica
Creith looked at strike three.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to be in that type of situation. That's what (the
game) is about,'' she said. ``Not being able to come through, it's
frustrating, but that's the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Once again, one run wasn't enough for pitcher Tara Glaister,
just as it wasn't enough Friday against Minnesota. Glaister pitched
well enough to win, giving up five hits and striking out two, but
Missouri (40-20) rallied for three runs in the bottom of the sixth
on a hit batter, two singles and two sacrifice flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have my best stuff all day,'' Glaister said. ``The
pops weren't there. It wasn't moving.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, we hit the ball hard and did what we needed to do,''
Missouri coach Jay Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA 5, Minnesota 0: Stacey Nuveman hit two home runs and drove
in four to lead the top-seeded Bruins (58-6) to today's 1 p.m.
regional final against Missouri (41-20), which beat Northridge and
Minnesota Saturday. The winner advances to the College World Series
beginning Thursday in Oklahoma City, but Missouri needs to win
twice.
</P>
<P>
   Nuveman's two round-trippers, a solo shot against Steph Klaviter
(23-10) in the third and a three-run homer in the fifth off
Michelle Harrison, gave her 30 for the season, the first time a
UCLA player has reached that plateau and only the second time any
college player has done so. Arizona's Laura Espinoza hit 30 in 1994
and 37 the next year. Nuveman now has a nation-leading 89 RBI this
season, placing her eighth all-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been struggling a bit as of late,'' Nuveman said. ``It
felt good to bust out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She took a pitch that was really low and outside and hit it
out,'' Minnesota co-coach Lisa Bernstein said of the second home
run. ``It would not have ever been called a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyndsey Klein celebrated her 21st birthday with three hits,
including the game-winning solo home run in the third inning, her
fifth of the season. She also doubled and singled.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney Dale (30-1) became the fourth UCLA pitcher to win 30
games in a season with a two-hit shutout with eight strikeouts and
one walk. Dale had a no-hitter and faced the minimum through six
innings before giving up two singles to start the seventh. UCLA is
the only team in the nation not to have given up a run in a
regional.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 2307EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
