A7675 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-NEWYEAR-2ndTAKE-LA     05-22 0304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-NEWYEAR-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: all other parties.
</P>
<P>
   The site of the Crenshaw District party is still being planned,
but the Alameda Street party will run from Olvera Street to Union
Station, the Harbor event will be beneath the Vincent Thomas Bridge
_ which will be lighted for the first time by $400,000 in private
money _ and the Grand Avenue celebration downtown will be in front
of the Museum of Contemporary Art.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the community festivals will feature puppet shows,
carnival rides, storytelling, sports and hobby activities, stunt
demonstrations, yacht or classic car parades, dance lessons and
international crafts.
</P>
<P>
   Children's groups will perform, as will collections of 2,000
mariachis, 2,000 swing dancers, 2,000 tenors, 2,000 tuba and
trombone players and 2,000 jazz musicians in a millennial jam
session, among other groups.
</P>
<P>
   Four times during the day, the Opus 21 _ Festival of Sacred
Sounds will feature simultaneous sounding of bells, horns and
choirs from churches, temples and mosques throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
   This joyful noise will erupt at noon to open the city's
celebration; at 4 p.m., to recognize midnight Greenwich Mean Time,
the benchmark for time-keeping worldwide; at 9 p.m., when it will
be midnight on the East Coast and the United States enters 2000;
and at midnight local time.
</P>
<P>
   Bands and dancing for adults will start at 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:45 p.m., six locations will join in a count to midnight.
That will culminate in a ``sky show'' with simultaneous fireworks,
lasers, sky writing and other effects, Nodal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to try to animate the sky over L.A.,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, if you look up, you see buildings,'' he said. But
in Los Angeles, the sky overhead is ``the one thing we have in
common.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
