<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-NEWYEAR-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOS ANGELES PROMISES DEC. 31 PARTY TO END ALL PARTIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Promising a New Year's Eve that ``makes Times
Square look like bush league,'' organizers of the official Los
Angeles millennium celebration seem to have more bravado than time.
</P>
<P>
   With only seven months remaining until the cosmic odometer flips
to 2000, city officials still are lining up all the entertainers
and corporate donors.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, they promise a world-class, once-in-a-millennium
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have nothing against New York, but Los Angeles is where
it's happening. L.A. rocks,'' said Mark Kroeker, picked by Mayor
Richard Riordan to coordinate the city's bash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time for something spectacular for the people of Los
Angeles _ something that really makes L.A. shine. We want to unify
our city,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the clock is ticking.
</P>
<P>
   London is building a $418 million ``Millennium Dome,'' and
Paris, Rome, Chicago and other cities have been planning their
soirees for years. And New York City _ well, the Big Apple seems to
think it's the place to be, even though officials there are still
hammering out their plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``With it being New York City and New Year's Eve and the
millennium _ people for the most part are coming to us. They want
to be a part of NYC 2000 events,'' said Germaine Febles, deputy
director of New York's celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Kroeker is not impressed. His advice for Angelenos: ``Don't
leave Los Angeles. You'll be sorry you did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll put together something that makes Times Square look like
bush league. L.A. is going to be the place to be on New Year's Eve.
It's going to be phenomenal,'' said the former Los Angeles Police
Department deputy chief.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he noted that Los Angeles is under pressure to present a
good show because it will be the last large city in the nation to
ring out 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bring the curtain down here,'' Kroeker said. ``We want to
make sure Los Angeles is ready to do a curtain call.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan is confident Los Angeles can grab the spotlight and hang
onto it during its daylong celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to do something to show we're the entertainment
capital of the world,'' Riordan said. ``When it's midnight in New
York, it's 9 o'clock here and we want to get some attention.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the plan is for five simultaneous festivals throughout
the city, including one somewhere in the San Fernando Valley,
perhaps at Van Nuys Airport, Balboa Park or the Van Nuys government
center.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the city will be throwing a major celebration
in Hollywood featuring an aerial light show worthy of Tinseltown's
special-effects artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to blow out every other celebration in the
country,'' said Adolfo V. Nodal, general manager of the city's
Cultural Affairs Department. ``We have so much talent here. The
cultural resources are amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, officials are cagey about who will perform where,
promising they'll have everything nailed down within a month.
</P>
<P>
   The five admission-free, alcohol-free, family festivals around
the city will last from noon to midnight and host 50,000 to 100,000
people.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Kroeker said the city is planning ``something that
leaves a legacy for our children.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what legacy Kroeker promises is unclear _ a secret, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't just a park or a scholarship fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be based on the survival needs of young people for the
next millennium,'' he said. ``We want to do something that leaves
more than an empty champagne bottle in the street.''
</P>
<P>
   The City Council approved $1.2 million for the festivals, and
Kroeker said he's working to amass far more in corporate and
private donations to augment that cash. He declined to reveal who
has contributed so far.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say the city already is spending too much.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be some value in what those folks want to do,'' said
Kris Vosburgh, executive director of the Howard Jarvis Taxpayers
Association.
</P>
<P>
   But if that's the case, then participants should be willing to
pay a small admission charge, or companies should be interested
enough to foot the entire bill, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's galling because they're constantly coming forward saying
they need more money for essential services,'' he said of city
officials. ``Then at budget time they always find money for bells
and whistles. The attitude is, it's only $1.2million. But these
amounts add up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may sound like a Puritan here, but it's our money,''
Vosburgh said.
</P>
<P>
   The party planners insist any money spent is an investment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tying the whole city together. We're trying to do
something wonderful for the people of L.A.,'' Nodal said.
</P>
<P>
   Each location of the festival will have large television screens
linking it with all other parties.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-22-99 2326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
