r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN     05-22 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERSIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS SPREAD THE WEALTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Tim Duncan was the best player on the floor
(again), and in a relieved locker room San Antonio paid proper
homage to their quiet prodigy (again).
</P>
<P>
   But Duncan's masterful 37-point, 14-rebound performance Saturday
at the Forum did not dominate the postgame discussion, not even
close. Instead, the Spurs distributed the credit as selflessly as
they distributed the ball in a devastating 103-91 victory over the
Los Angeles Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the topics ranged from point guard Avery Johnson's
fourth-quarter jumpers to reserve Jaren Jackson's season-high 22
points to the Spurs' overwhelming fourth quarter _ when they scored
36 points and shot 63 percent while the Lakers scored 25 points and
shot 35 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers had too much youth and athleticism for Houston, but
their flimsy fundamentals collapsed against the best the Spurs had
to offer in the closing minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say anything about the Lakers, but I will
talk about what we do in the fourth quarter,'' Johnson said. ``We
tend to execute really well. We make our free throws, and we don't
have any breakdowns on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs have executed the same end-game principles with the
same personnel and the same coach for the entire season. They know
what to do and how to do it, and that cohesion was crucial in the
final minutes of Games 2 and 3. Meanwhile, the Lakers were in chaos
throughout the season and failed to create a foundation that would
withstand postseason pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``You build to a certain point, and we've been doing it for the
last 2{ months,'' Spurs center David Robinson said. ``A lot of it
is chemistry, and that's one thing we've been fortunate enough to
develop. That's the strength of our team. In terms of talent, we
aren't the most overwhelming team, but we work well together, and
that's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 3 was also about the Spurs' resourcefulness, about someone
other than Duncan _ and the foul-plagued Robinson, for that matter
_ making critical shots in the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan carried San Antonio in the first half with 24 points, but
when the Lakers applied double-team tactics in the closing minutes,
Johnson and Jackson calmly countered with perimeter jumpers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When teams have guys who step up, that's usually who's going
to win games, especially the close ones,'' Lakers guard Derek
Harper said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's performance was shocking, considering he was averaging
five points in the playoffs and made two baskets combined in Games
1 and 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was my turn to do something off the bench,''
Jackson said. ``Malik (Rose) was good in the last game (13 points).
We've been solid off the bench through the year. I just wanted to
make sure I did my share.''
</P>
<P>
   On the rare occasions the Lakers double-teamed Duncan and
contained Jackson, the crafty Johnson popped open to make two
19-foot jumpers in the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not leaving me open as much (as in recent years),''
Johnson said. ``But in the end, they decided to and fortunately ...
I was able to make the shots that really put a dagger in them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
