<SLUG> BC-POW-PARADE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREED POW GETS HERO'S WELCOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN ROUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE, Texas _ Many residents in this small, all-American
town first met Army Spc. Steven Gonzales when he appeared on their
TV screens _ a bruised and bewildered soldier held captive in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Their hearts went out to Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez and Staff
Sgt. Christopher Stone, two more soldiers captured by Serbian
forces. But there was a special tie to Gonzales: His parents, Rosie
and Gilbert Gonzales, live and work in Huntsville.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier on the TV screen immediately became the city's
``adopted son.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, in a downtown parade and ceremony befitting a hero,
hundreds of proud, flag-waving residents embraced a
different-looking Gonzales: a fresh-faced kid with a charming
smile, dark eyebrows and his father's gentle disposition.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, who was freed May 2, rode through downtown Huntsville
in the back of a white 1963 Rolls Royce convertible. Looking
healthy and seemimg unruffled by the swarm of news media, he
grinned and gave a thumbs-up to the throngs shouting, ``Welcome
home, Steven.''
</P>
<P>
   The celebration included a birthday party at a mall for
Gonzales, who turned 22 while in captivity, as well as a ceremony
at Sam Houston State University, where local, state and national
officials praised Gonzales and his family. The parade also honored
prisoners of war and those missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   Parade-goers with miniature American flags tucked in their hats,
hair, pockets and shirts praised Gonzales for remaining a loyal
soldier during 32 days' captivity. And they thanked God for his
release.
</P>
<P>
   But most said their greatest feeling of pride came from watching
Gonzales conduct himself respectfully and modestly at a time when
youths are portrayed so negatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's so young, and has come through this with such maturity,''
said Jim Montgomery, 73, a Navy veteran. ``You hear so much about
young people today.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales behaved in a manner reminiscent of ``the 20-year-olds
that went off to World War II,'' Montgomery said. ``He just seems
to be a good, all-around, nice young man.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, who said he survived with help from prayers and hymns
memorized at church camp, responded emotionally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to thank our great Lord. He was my strength and my
refuge and so much more to me during my captivity,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He thanked the crowd for supporting him and his family, but said
that more significant are ``our service members ... who have walked
before me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Without them, I would not have had the opportunity to uphold
these ideals,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also thanked those still in military service, adding that he
hopes they will receive such a welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales and his family stopped once along the parade route, at
the front lawn of the Walker County Courthouse. There, Steven
Gonzales cut the yellow ribbon that his mother had placed around a
sprawling tree the day after he was taken hostage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very emotional moment. It meant the world to be able
to take it down,'' Rosie Gonzales said, holding the ribbon.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, Ramirez and Stone were part of a U.N. peacekeeping
force when they were captured by Yugoslav forces March 31 as they
patrolled the Macedonian border.
</P>
<P>
   An American religious delegation led by the Rev. Jesse Jackson
negotiated their release.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
