<HEADLINE>
LEAPIN' LOCALS OUTJUMP FURRIN FROGS AT TEXAS FESTIVAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LINDA P. CAMPBELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Texas _ In a ribbitting display of froggery, Jacob
King's local leaper legged it out of the taped-down circle quicker
than Amanda Bentley's ``foreign'' frog for first place in the
junior high division Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for an unnamed novice still wet behind the tympani,
recruited as he was just the night before the 16th annual Lake
Worth Bullfrog Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Although jumpy festival organizers flew in seven New York frogs
to make sure they had enough contestants for the frog-jumping
contest, King and other locals popped in at race time with a horde
of home-grown hoppers that proved to be a leap above the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught him last night at my tank,'' said King, an Azle
Junior High student whose family lives on 368 acres in Northwest
Tarrant County.
</P>
<P>
   ``One time, we caught over 28 one night. We only caught nine
last night, because we were only out about 30 minutes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also catch them and eat 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Mottled green thighs pumped and webbed feet flew as the frogs _
well, some of them _ hopped hurriedly from inside a small circle to
the outskirts of a 5-foot sphere taped on a wooden stage.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Covin and his sons Trevor, 9, and Cody, 7, of Lake Worth
took home a first place and a participant's ribbon with their
slimers, captured Friday night at Lake Benbrook.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just sit there and be quiet, and they'll honk,'' Covin
advised.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the biggest and best bullfrogs we've had for the
races,'' said Northwest Chamber of Commerce Executive Director Judy
Haas, whose daughter has been tending the out-of-state amphibians.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the competitors were slipped back into buckets
and coolers after strutting their stuff, others sat in their
keepers' hands, clasped tightly but being gently rubbed on their
smooth, slimy backs.
</P>
<P>
   Haas said the New Yorkers will go to a local pond or the Fort
Worth Nature Center &AMP; Refuge.
</P>
<P>
   King and his buddy Micah Collier, 13, who took a third place,
said they will probably hang on to theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll keep them to make them bigger for next year,'' Collier
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
