<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ORIOLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZALEZ'S LATE HOMER LIFTS RANGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
BALTIMORE _ The Rangers played seven games short-handed while right
fielder Juan Gonzalez nursed the strain in his right hamstring.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet, the Rangers never considered placing Gonzalez on the 15-day
disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's ninth inning at Oriole Park in Camden Yards _ where
Gonzalez's three-run homer off Baltimore's Ricky Bones propelled
the Rangers to an 8-7 victory _ revealed their reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers expect their two-time American League most valuable
player will contribute more during the eight games in which he
plays than any replacement from Triple-A Oklahoma would during the
span of 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was willing to trade seven days for eight,'' Rangers manager
Johnny Oates said. ``That's a profit of one. You don't want to lose
him for 15 days. You might even be willing to trade 10 days for
five with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who went hitless during his first eight at-bats since
returning to the lineup Friday, nullified Rangers rookie reliever
Jeff Zimmerman's first failure this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles scored the go-ahead runs with Zimmerman on the mound
in the seventh and eighth innings only to witness closer Mike
Timlin fail to convert a save for the fourth time in 10
opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Timlin, who recorded the final two outs of the eighth inning,
surrendered a leadoff double to center fielder Roberto Kelly and
issued a four-pitch walk to second baseman Mark McLemore to begin
the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Timlin then induced a weak ground ball to the mound from Rusty
Greer. Timlin fielded it cleanly, but his throw to third baseman
Cal Ripken sailed wide of the bag and deflected off the infielder's
glove and into shallow left field.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first thought was, `Wow! Lead runner,' '' Timlin said.
``Had I thrown it, I would have hit him in the chest. I just babied
it over there, though, and threw it away.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly scored from second, and McLemore raced to third. Orioles
manager Ray Miller summoned Bones from the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, who acknowledged his timing at the plate being amiss
from the injury, stepped to the plate hitting .125 (3-for-24) for
his career against Bones. The right-hander threw a first-pitch
curveball that missed the strike zone, and Gonzalez fouled a 1-0
slider down the right-field line.
</P>
<P>
   That foul ball would be an encouraging sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good things happen when you stay behind the ball,'' Oates
said. ``He was going to make sure he got that run in. It was good
to see him do that against a guy he hasn't had much success
against.''
</P>
<P>
   Bones threw a second consecutive slider, and Gonzalez drove it
down the right-field line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just looking for a long fly ball to drive in that run,''
said Gonzalez, whose home runs rarely travel to right field.
</P>
<P>
   The ball cleared Camden Yards' 25-foot-high scoreboard, and
closer John Wetteland _ despite allowing a solo home run to Delino
DeShields _ converted his 13th save in 14 opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's never thrown me anything close to the middle of the plate
that I could hit out of the park,'' Gonzalez said of Bones. ``It
was my turn today.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles appeared well on their way to victory after
eighth-inning, run-scoring singles by right fielder Rich Amaral
(3-for-4) and first baseman Jeff Conine, who went 4-for-5 with
three runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty much a cryin' shame to battle that hard all day
and have tremendous days from Conine and Amaral and a key hit from
Ripken,'' Miller said. ``Then, two of our veteran relievers came
in.''
</P>
<P>
   Timlin and left-hander Jesse Orosco, who failed to retire a
batter, issued three walks during the eighth and ninth innings.
That ensured Gonzalez of one more plate appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I've said before, you can't walk people at the bottom of
the lineup,'' Miller said, ``because sooner or later the big boy
ends up there at the plate doing just like Gonzalez did.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Rangers never placed Gonzalez on the disabled
list. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
