<HEADLINE>
KRAFT TIES COURSE RECORD WITH 61, SHARES LEAD AT COLONIAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Greg Kraft should be glad he makes his
living by playing professional golf, not predicting its outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft wrapped up a third-round effort of 61 Saturday at the
MasterCard Colonial, tying the course record. After a clinical
dissection of his 10 birdies and lone bogey, Kraft explained why
the effort left him pleased but far from exuberant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I won't be leading going into the last round,'' said
Kraft, whose record-tying round moved him to 7 under par for the
tournament. ``Somebody's going to get to 12 or 13 under, with the
way the course is playing. I'll probably be five shots back and
have to post another number.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprise!
</P>
<P>
   Despite his meager expectations, Kraft heads into today's final
round as one of three players with a share of the lead. He is
joined by Scott Verplank and Billy Mayfair, who fashioned rounds of
66 and 68, respectively, while playing under more adverse
conditions during the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   As the day progressed, Colonial's greens dried out under sunny,
cloudless skies, causing difficulties with approach shots for
players with afternoon tee times. Kraft experienced no such
problems with a 9:19 a.m. start, climbing 51 spots on the leader
board by matching the course record held by Keith Clearwater and
Lee Janzen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit it close all day,'' said Kraft, who had only two birdie
putts longer than six feet, along with a 60-foot chip-in at No. 18.
``The greens were really soft and receptive.''
</P>
<P>
   Those were not the words used by Phil Mickelson (5 under), who
played in the next-to-last group and said he hit a 4-iron shot at
No. 4 that stopped ``quicker than any of the sand wedges I hit on
the back nine.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the golf course played totally different in the
morning than in the afternoon,'' said Mickelson, who wondered aloud
if Colonial's greens had been watered before the start of the third
round, giving an edge to morning starters. ``They were very soft
for the first half of the players, and it got very firm for the
second half. I'm a big advocate of firm greens, but I advocate firm
greens for everyone. It's important that the course plays the same
way for everyone, whether it's hard or soft.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Russell, PGA Tour tournament official, said whatever
difference occurred in Saturday's scoring conditions resulted from
Mother Nature, not a early-hours irrigation project. Russell said
the Colonial greens have been hand-watered at the conclusion of
play each day but no water has been added in the mornings before
the start of rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the same every day,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, Kraft capitalized on his early start better
than anyone else in the field, taking birdies on his first three
holes to begin the day and his final four to conclude it. He joins
Verplank and Mayfair atop a final-round leader board that shows 31
golfers within five strokes of the lead and 44 within seven shots.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how many players remained in contention in the well-packed
field, Verplank said: ``About 40. Maybe 50.''
</P>
<P>
   Verplank added his name to the list with an effort that included
his second consecutive eagle at No. 11, a 599-yard par-5. Verplank
made a 35-foot eagle putt Saturday, moving him to 5 under par at
No. 11 and 2 under for his remaining 51 holes during the 1999
Colonial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played as good as I can play,'' said Verplank, who had two
bogeys during a round of 66 that marked the best effort by an
afternoon starter in the third round. ``These greens were hard and
bouncy. To shoot a 61 out here ... that's pretty awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayfair turned in his third consecutive sub-par effort, joining
Fred Funk (5 under overall) and Tim Herron (4 under) as the only
players to break par in each round. Although he joined Verplank in
heaping praise upon Kraft for his course record, Mayfair suggested
another 61 is unlikely to be uncorked by any of today's
front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the wind keeps blowing and it stays sunny, it's going to be
hard on the leaders,'' Mayfair said. ``If someone goes off (early)
and posts a 63 or 64, they have a great chance of winning.''
</P>
<P>
   The post-and-wait method worked Saturday for Kraft, even though
it caught him off-guard. If someone follows his lead today, they
could be wearing a plaid jacket. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
