<SLUG> BC-GLF-COLONIAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES TO COURSE AFFECT BROOKS' GAME
</HEADLINE>
 NOTES-TEX (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN, J. DOUGLAS FOSTER, TROY PHILLIPS AND KEVIN LYONS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Mark Brooks hasn't exactly experienced home
cooking on his hometown golf course. The Fort Worth native carded
an even-par 70 Saturday to finish where he started the day, at 2
over.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks said the setup of the Colonial course, as dictated during
tournament week by PGA Tour officials, is much different than what
he's used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give you an example,'' Brooks said. ``The 12th hole, a
dogleg left into the wind, you normally cannot drive it into the
right bunker off the tee, at all. And it's really in play; 290
yards into the wind and you can knock it into the bunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sit out here and watch the guys play 18, they're using a sand
wedge. I use an occasional wedge in there, but it's usually more an
8-, 9-iron shot. It's pretty pitiful. You can step out there and
watch two or three groups and you see them, they're rolling 80
yards. I'm used to the ball rolling 20 or 30 yards. It makes a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as my game, I just haven't made enough putts to really
get going.'' MICKELSON TO MISS OPEN?
</P>
<P>
   Phil Mickelson said that there is a chance he could miss this
year's U.S. Open, scheduled for June 17-20 at Pinehurst No. 2 in
North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   With his wife, Amy, eight months pregnant, Mickelson said the
arrival of the couple's first child could be very near the Open
dates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I'm going to be able to play that this year to
be honest,'' Mickelson said. ``I'll have to play it by ear.'' STILL
A RACE
</P>
<P>
   By no means is the MasterCard Colonial a three-man battle.
Co-leader Greg Kraft knows that.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft entered the third round 9 strokes behind the leaders
before shooting a 61 early in the day. Entering the final round,
there are 53 players within 9 strokes of leaders Kraft, Scott
Verplank and Billy Mayfair. SURGING WATSON
</P>
<P>
   As defending champion Tom Watson came strolling up No. 18 at
around 11:20 a.m. Saturday, he met a pleasantly surprised throng.
</P>
<P>
   Having barely survived the cut with a two-day 144 (4 over),
Watson regained his 1998 form to shoot a 66 for an even-par 210
after three rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was better than Saturday and a lot better than the day
before,'' said Watson, who had no bogeys after carding a combined
eight in the first two rounds. ``It looked like I was going to miss
the cut, and I made it right into the money. I had nothing to lose
today, so I played with abandon.''
</P>
<P>
   Since opening with a 74, Watson's swing has been in ``adjustment
mode.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My caddy, Bruce Edwards, and I ended up in a much better frame
of mind after today's round,'' Watson said. ``It was kind of a
scruffy round on the back side, and the 66 just happened.''
LEHMAN'S HOT ROUND
</P>
<P>
   When he bogeyed two of the first four holes, Tom Lehman must
have thought Saturday's third round would be a long one. But Lehman
rebounded to make six birdies and an eagle on No. 11 to card a
6-under-par 64.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times when you have great rounds like that you get
off to a good start,'' said Lehman, who knocked in 30-foot putts on
Nos. 11 and 12. ``I had some early bogeys, but, if you will, they
were good bogeys. I hit some good shots they just didn't fall. I
kept playing with confidence and the shots started falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehman, the 1996 British Open Champion who is ``85 percent''
after shoulder surgery in November, is at 4-under-par 206 through
the first three rounds of the tournament. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
