<HEADLINE>
ZIMMERMAN SETS TEAM RECORD THEN FALTERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
BALTIMORE _ Right-hander Jeff Zimmerman established a Rangers
record for a reliever yesterday by retiring his 24th and 25th
consecutive batters.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The two batters: Baltimore's B.J. Surhoff and Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman then tasted failure for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old rookie surrendered three consecutive two-out
singles in the seventh inning, and the Orioles took a 4-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers tied the score in the eighth inning when
pinch-runner Luis Alicea scored on a one-out ground ball by first
baseman Lee Stevens, but Zimmerman again surrendered the lead by
allowing a run-scoring single to right fielder Rich Amaral in the
bottom half of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball has a great way of bringing you back down to earth
and planting you six feet under,'' Zimmerman said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman entered the day with the best earned-run average
(0.61) and lowest opponents' batting average (.084) of any
major-league reliever, but yesterday proved he is human.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew he was before today,'' Rangers manager Johnny Oates
said. ``A nice run? That's putting it mildly.''
</P>
<P>
   How will Zimmerman respond?
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have much concern about that,'' pitching coach
Dick Bosman said. ``He's a hard-nosed kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Zimmerman: ``I'm not going to try and do anything
different.'' \Nsubheds:Quality results With the 8-7 victory against
the Orioles, the Rangers have won 10 of the 11 games this season in
which they got a quality start, defined as a start in which the
pitcher lasts six or more innings and surrenders three or fewer
runs. Date Pitcher Opponent IP R Result April 6 Sele Tigers 7 0 W,
