\Nshirt:Briefly _ First baseman Lee Stevens, who entered
yesterday's game leading the American League in intentional walks,
drew his seventh with two out and Rafael Palmeiro on second base in
the sixth inning. Stevens' intentional walks can be attributed to
his performance _ a .315 batting average and nine home runs _ and
the lack of production by the Rangers' No. 9 hitters batting behind
him. _ Catcher Ivan Rodriguez's fourth-inning home run extended his
hitting streak to 12 games, the best by a Rangers player this
season. _ The ninth-inning home run by Baltimore's Delino DeShields
was the third homer surrendered by closer John Wetteland in his
past three appearances. _ Orioles first baseman Will Clark
(fracture, left thumb) returned to Baltimore yesterday, but don't
expect him to be reinstated from the 15-day disabled list before
tonight's game. Clark, the Rangers' first baseman from 1994-98,
went 3-for-6 with three walks while playing in the Orioles'
extended spring-training program yesterday morning in Sarasota,
Fla. The Orioles, though, appear to be targeting Clark's return for
Tuesday at Anaheim. _ Orioles left fielder B.J. Surhoff extended
his hitting streak to 13 games with his second-inning, run-scoring
single. Surhoff enters tonight's game hitting .370 (10-for-27) in
six games against the Rangers this season.
