<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7688 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LENO-PACING-2TAKES-LA     05-22 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENO-PACING-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAY LENO ISN'T WORRIED ABOUT PACING INDY 500
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PHIL DAVIS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jay Leno isn't worried about pacing the Indy 500
next week. Taking Indy's deadly curves at 125 mph in a brand-new
Chevy Monte Carlo is nothing compared with cruising Mulholland
Drive in one of his shakier vintage cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have cars that necessarily go fast,'' he said of his
collection of 54 cars and 53 motorcycles. ``I have the kind of cars
that people are amazed you are physically able to get to your
destination.''
</P>
<P>
   Take his two-cylinder, three-wheel Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty loud, it's pow, pow, pow,'' Leno said. ``I'm on
Mulholland Drive one day and I come sliding around this corner and
I see a cop there with his radar gun and I think, `Ah, I'm
screwed,' and then I go by and he goes, `Hi Jay, how are you
doing?' And I realize I'm only going 33mph. But it's so frightening
in this thing. It's the kind of car where you're scared to death,
you're holding on for dear life and girls are passing you putting
on their lipstick in Honda Civics.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say the ``Tonight Show'' host doesn't expect major
thrills when he leads the pack in front of more than 300,000 fans
at the 83rd running of the Indianapolis 500 on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   It's a rare honor _ even for America's top comedian.
</P>
<P>
   Most Indy pacers are racing greats like Parnelli Jones, who took
first in the 1963 Indianapolis. But Leno's well-known passion for
cars put him among the elite ranks of Indy 500 VIPs such as U.S.
Air Force Gen. Chuck Yeager, the test pilot who set a speed record
in 1947 when he broke the sound barrier, and actor James Garner,
whose starring role in the 1966 movie ``Grand Prix'' kicked his
love of racing into high gear. Yeager paced Indy in 1986; Garner in
1975, 1977 and 1985.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite an honor,'' Garner said. ``Driving the pace car is
about keeping your concentration _ ignoring 300,000 fans and 33
high-performance cars raring to go right behind you.''
</P>
<P>
   Garner, who has faithfully attended the Indy 500 almost every
year since 1958 and counts dozens of drivers among his friends,
said pacing Indy is a unique thrill topped only by his experiences
racing on courses from Daytona to Baja.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get in a race head to head with someone, there's
nothing better,'' Garner said. ``At Indy, you're just pacing. But
it is the biggest race in the world. And at least I led for a
little while.''
</P>
<P>
   As this year's official pace car driver, Leno is responsible for
making sure 33 of the best drivers in the world get off to a good,
fast start. He will take the fire-engine red Monte Carlo pace car
up to 125 mph in several laps around the 2{-mile oval before diving
into pit row as the racers blast off at speeds that reach 236 mph.
Crashes and other track mishaps slow average race speeds down to a
still-dizzying 145 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Leno was trained on the course by Indy champ Jones, who paced
last year's race. ``Indianapolis is a very complicated track to
drive,'' Leno said. ``When we were practicing with the pace car,
Parnelli would take the wheel and we'd be going 100 mph and we're
just touching the wall with the mirror. It's measured in inches.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why both Leno and Garner hold the Indy racers in the
highest regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting,'' Leno said. ``To me, race car drivers like
Mario Andretti, Phil Hill and Dan Gurney are just as much athletes
as Michael Jordan or Mickey Mantle or whoever. It's just a
different kind of sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Joseph Haraszti, a Pasadena psychiatrist with close ties to
the racing community, said it's not surprising ``Type AAA
personality'' overachievers like Leno, Garner and actor Paul Newman
are drawn to the thrill of fast machines.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are people who are highly successful, highly driven,''
he said. ``They have this need to push themselves to the limit and
conquer new worlds.''
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing new about America's passion for cars, he added,
and the only difference between celebrities and regular guys is
what they can afford.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Garner and Newman, Leno's love of driving has rarely led
him to the racetrack. He has done a few celebrity races, but other
than that, the closest he's come to breaking a speed record was the
one time he was suspended from Andover High School in Massachusetts
for burning rubber in his '65 Buick Gransport.
</P>
<P>
   That was the beginning of a lifelong love of anything with
wheels and a motor. After rising through the stand-up comedy ranks
and inheriting the ``Tonight Show'' throne from Johnny Carson in
1992, Leno put his considerable wealth into a car collection that
has grown exponentially with his increasing fame. (His collection
totaled 16 motorcycles and roughly half a dozen cars back in 1987,
when he first starting filling in for Carson on a regular basis.)
Leno's collection now includes 107 vehicles, among them eccentric
rides like the three-wheel Morgan and more mainstream autos like a
Jaguar XJ-8 and a Dodge Viper.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: and a Dodge Viper.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' Mavis Leno, the comedian's wife, says of his
love for cars. ``I don't understand people who don't have a passion
for something.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a few things he does that make me a little nervous,
like when he drives his old steam-powered cars, which are a little
dangerous,'' she continued. ``He drives a lot of very old cars and
motorcycles where the technology was better on speed than it was on
brakes. But he's always 100percent alert and he has a very good
reaction time, so I count on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay Leno is a regular at classic car shows around Los Angeles.
And, of course, every night millions of Americans see him whiz by
NBC studios in Burbank during the ``Tonight Show's'' opening
sequence.
</P>
<P>
   But, Leno insists, his obsession with restoring and driving cars
and motorcycles doesn't put him in the same class as Indy drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Driving is like sex,'' he said. ``A lot of guys think they're
pretty good at it. Everyone knows how to drive, for the most part,
so they think race car driving is like regular driving _ only
faster. And, of course, it isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Leno shudders at the thought of being a grinning rich guy who
haunts racetracks in flame-retardant Nomex jumpsuits, pretending he
has the skills and know-how to race professionally. He has too much
respect for racing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's sort of the more-money-than-brains club,'' he said.
``Racing is not something you can really do part time. I don't even
pretend to put myself in the same category with those guys. But to
just go around the track at high speed and get a sense of what they
do every day is very exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
