<DOCNO> NYT19990522.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-22 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7714 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     05-22 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV30-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 30)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; DESPERATE CHARACTERS &LR;  By Paula Fox. Norton, $12. In this trim,
intensely focused 1970 novel, an upper-middle-class New York woman
is bitten on the hand by a stray cat, setting off a chain of events
that mirror the confusion and bitterness in her loveless marriage.
The New York Times reviewer Peter Rowley praised ``the skillful
insistency with which Fox probes her characters' lives'' and ``her
acute sense of individual and social psychology.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A SOLDIER'S STORY &LR;  By Omar N. Bradley. Modern Library, $17.95.
As the commander of more soldiers in the field than any other
officer in American history, General of the Army Omar Bradley was
uniquely placed to assess the ups and downs of the European
campaign in World War II. ``The highest service'' of his candid,
balanced memoir, Hanson W. Baldwin wrote in 1951, ``is to provide a
gallery of military portraits, a background of personalities,
against which the war in North Africa, Sicily, France and Germany
was fought.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; ECLIPSE &LR; , by Alan Moorehead (Soho, $13), a British war
correspondent recalls his experiences covering the Allied offensive
and the grunts and officers he encountered along the way. Reviewing
this ``fine narrative'' in 1946, Charles Poore said, ``You have an
eerie feeling ... that he wandered untrammeled from one end of the
war to the other.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIVE US THIS DAY &LR; , by Sidney Stewart (Norton, $13.95), is a
harrowing narrative of the Pacific war by an American enlisted man
who survived the Bataan Death March and three years in Japanese
captivity. ``Through its immense picture of human courage in the
face of suffering, it reinforces our faith in the ultimate triumph
of man's spirit,'' David Dempsey wrote in 1957. ``It is
unforgettable.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE TREATMENT &LR;  By Daniel Menaker. Washington Square/Pocket
Books, $14. Jake Singer is motherless, aimless and lonely, but his
biggest challenge may be coping with his ferocious Cuban Catholic
analyst, who sees himself as ``the last Freudian.'' Last year the
reviewer Jim Shepard called this first novel ``an ethically
instructive comedy'' that is ``admirable for both its craft and its
humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BEACH: THE HISTORY OF PARADISE ON EARTH &LR;  By Lena Lencek and
Gideon Bosker. Penguin, $13.95. This eccentric chronicle of beach
culture from the Romans to the Californians includes a bibliography
with 335 entries and the authors' picks of the world's top 80
resorts. The result is an ``entertaining, handsomely illustrated
book'' that manages to be both ``scholarly and briskly
good-humored,'' Alexander Frater wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHILISTINES AT THE HEDGEROW: PASSION AND PROPERTY IN THE
HAMPTONS &LR; , by Steven Gaines (Back Bay/Little, Brown, $14.95),
explores life on the eastern tip of Long Island, N.Y., and the
parade of artists, charmers, socialites and celebrities who have
walked its beaches. In 1998 the reviewer Jennifer Steinhauer found
the book to be overstuffed with gossip but said it featured
``engaging ... tales of the social, ethnic and architectural
history of one of the most exclusive summer resort areas in
America.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IN SEARCH OF LOVE AND BEAUTY &LR;  By Ruth Prawer Jhabvala.
Counterpoint, $14. The author's first work of fiction set in
America focuses on a charismatic European refugee who becomes a
guru in New York, and the circle of uprooted ladies to whose bodies
and souls he ministers. In 1983 Robert Towers called this ``a
macabre comedy of impulsive, thwarted lives'' and said ``Jhabvala
renders a little world of emotional, greedy refugees with much
shrewdness of insight.''
</P>
<P>
   The same publisher has also reissued  &UR; HEAT AND DUST &LR;  ($14), an
earlier novel by Jhabvala that revolves around a restless young
British woman who moves to India with her husband in the 1920s and
quickly goes native, falling under the sway of a charming Indian
prince. In 1976 the reviewer Pearl K. Bell said the author depicts
``the barriers of incomprehension and futility that persist between
English and Indians with witty precision.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JANE AUSTEN: A LIFE &LR;  By Claire Tomalin. Vintage, $14. The
latest take on the British novelist holds that her life was more
exciting, traumatic and adventurous than previous biographies have
allowed. In 1997 the reviewer Kevin Barry said that while the
approach is overly speculative, ``it is Tomalin's overt intention
to present us with a Jane Austen living on the edge of a mobile
world.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GAFF TOPSAILS &LR;  By Patrick Kavanagh. Penguin, $13.95. The ghost
of ``Ulysses'' hovers over this first novel, which traces a day in
the life of several people _ among them a bitter priest and a
dreamy teen-age girl _ who inhabit an Irish Catholic parish on the
coast of Newfoundland in 1948. ``The narrative swoops down, like a
sea gull, on each character,'' Courtney Weaver wrote last year.
``Like Joyce, Kavanagh uses language as a metaphor for the division
of souls and of countries.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FREE LIVE FREE &LR;  By Gene Wolfe. Orb/Tom Doherty, $15.95. This
science-fiction tale centers on a detective, a prostitute, a
salesman and a witch who are lured by a mysterious man to a Chicago
house slated to be demolished. ``The plot ... is full of surprises
that I can't even hint at without ruining the pleasure of discovery
that awaits those who enter the worlds that Wolfe creates,'' Gerald
Jonas wrote in 1985.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
