<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-ASU-PARK-PRO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASU'S PARK TO TURN PRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TULSA _ Apparently there is no saving Grace for the Arizona
State women's golf program, which had its attempt at a record
seventh NCAA Championship washed away by a thunderstorm on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Park, who capped her brilliant amateur career with
individual honors at the weather-plagued tournament at Tulsa
Country Club, plans to join the professional ranks following her
appearance at the upcoming U.S. Women's Open, ``The Republic'' has
learned.
</P>
<P>
   Park did not want to confirm such an announcement in the
aftermath of the NCAA competition, which left her and teammates in
a state of shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Later,'' said the ASU sophomore, who conceded that her mind
was made up before she added the NCAA crown to the other 54 titles
she has captured in 118 junior/amateur tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan to play as an amateur in the Open, and after that, I
have no plans. I will make an announcement sometime this summer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Park's father, Soo Nam Park, a wealthy restaurateur from
Seoul, South Korea, said a plan is in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still Grace's call. She is the one that must make the
final decision,'' Soo Nam Park said. ``But it looks like she'll
(turn professional).
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, school has become boring for her. She will
probably announce her decision either on Saturday or Sunday at the
U.S. Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Park said his 20-year-old daughter plans to play the Futures
Tour, which is the equivalent of the men's Nike Tour. She would
then attempt to qualify for the LPGA in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is limited to four exemptions each year (by the LPGA),''
Park said. ``Since she already has played in (the Standard Register
PING) and the Dinah Shore, she can only play in two more (LPGA)
events the rest of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Futures will be challenging and raise her competitive
level. That's really what she needs now. She can't get that in
college.''
</P>
<P>
   Park's appearance at the Open does not count against her because
she is the reigning U.S. Amateur champ, who always is invited to
the national championship. This year's tournament is June 3-6 at
West Point, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of her advisers, which include ASU Coach Linda
Vollstedt and her instructor, Mike LaBauve, have given the move
their blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her game is so good; she's ready,'' Vollstedt said of the
two-time All-American. ``But I can't confirm anything. You'll have
to get that from Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   LaBauve said that he would never advise one of his pupils to
skip the final two years of college.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Grace is ready,'' he said. ``Is college golf piquing her
interest? No.
</P>
<P>
   LaBauve said Park is eager to take her game to the professional
level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she's hungry for the (LPGA) tour,'' he said. ``Just
like everybody else, I think she wants to see what she can do if
she focuses her life strictly on golf. Right now, it's tough to
juggle school, her social life and her golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Park, who has made the cut in eight of the 12 LPGA tournaments
she has played as an amateur, does have all the components to play
professionally. For instance, she captured the NCAA pre-tournament
long drive championship on Tuesday with a wind-aided blast of 342
yards. But she frequently drives the ball over 300 yards since she
switched to the new PING titanium driver, and her irons also carry
farther than those of her peers.
</P>
<P>
   According to Vollstedt, ``Grace has the best short game I've
ever seen in college golf.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is saying something, considering Vollstedt has coached 14
LPGA players.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a weakness, it is her putting. But since LaBauve
switched her to the cross-handed style, or ``low hand left,'' as
the pros refer to it, her putting has improved.
</P>
<P>
   According to agent Tim McNulty, the director of player
management for women's golf at Cornerstone Sports in Dallas,
``Grace is the total package.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She is head and shoulder above anyone (in the college ranks)
in terms of marketability,'' McNulty said. ``She's possibly the
best woman to come along in golf in the past 10 years, because
she's photogenic, feminine and has a golf game that is all-world,
especially her length off the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornerstone is not the only agency that has been hovering around
Park this week at the NCAA tournament. International Management
Group's Jay Burton, who represents LPGA superstars Karrie Webb and
Se Ri Pak, has been present, as has Steven SungYong Kil, a South
Korean-based agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she doesn't need me,'' said SungYong, who originally
represented Park. ``Grace is totally Americanized, and my strength
is in translation.''
</P>
<P>
   Soo Nam Park said that deciding who will represent his daughter
is the last piece of the puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been having discussions with her legal guardian in
Phoenix (Charlie Parker) and our good friend Kerry Graham about
that subject,'' Park said. ``But until we determine who that is,
I'll travel with her this summer when she plays on the Futures.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
