<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOTTERY-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALENTED SUN, OR LUCKY SON? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Father and son can be a dangerous combination in
sports. An irresistible temptation and the fastest way to last
place.
</P>
<P>
   For every Scott Layden, there is a Joey Meyer, surfing on
daddy's coattails and riding an athletic franchise into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   For every Andy MacPhail, there is a Bill Bidwill Jr., proof that
management by genetics can be a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   And now the spotlight shines on Bryan Colangelo, a general
manager who must justify the title, prove he is more than just a
last name. A man who must exhibit more than the knack of fleecing
the Dallas Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the NBA held its annual fix, er, lottery, and the
Suns couldn't beat the odds. And while the big-market Bulls
suspiciously ended up with the No. 1 pick, treating you to the
sight of Jerry Krause and his bouncing chins, reminding you of the
Patrick Ewing conspiracy theory in 1985, the Suns are left in no
man's land.
</P>
<P>
   There are eight solid choices in a quirky class: Lamar Odom,
once accused of cheating on an entrance exam to UNLV. Steve
Francis, an Allen Iverson clone who has attended six schools in six
years. The talent-laden Corey Maggette, who didn't even start for
Duke last season. A group rounded out by Elton Brand, Wally
Szczerbiak, Richard Hamilton, Baron Davis and Andre Miller.
Naturally, the Suns pick ninth.
</P>
<P>
   So will it be Jonathan Bender, a 6-11 prep star from
Mississippi? A kid that weighs all of 195 pounds?
</P>
<P>
   Or 7-foot-3 Aleksandr Radojevic, who played at a community
college in Kansas?
</P>
<P>
   Or will the Suns hold off on their draft debt to the Bulls, keep
their No. 16 pick and peddle both selections to move up in the
draft?
</P>
<P>
   The options clearly outweigh the saviors.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, it is a trying time for the younger Colangelo, who has
run hot and cold. His heist of Jason Kidd was visionary. Cliff
Robinson was a bold stroke. George McCloud was a solid acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, the results were a bit different.
</P>
<P>
   The good: The trade of Steve Nash reaped 36 lottery balls and
Pat Garrity.
</P>
<P>
   The debatable: A six-year extension for Rex Chapman. A lengthy,
lucrative contract for Luc Longley. The failed risk of Antonio
McDyess and all those all wasted draft picks.
</P>
<P>
   The unquestioned: The Suns are slow, soft and light-years from
an NBA title.
</P>
<P>
   They also are falling out of favor in the Valley, a team that
couldn't sell out its only home playoff game of 1999. A team that
soon may long for the kind of cult following cheering for the
Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   So it is up to the younger Colangelo to fill in the cracks
before the walls crumble. He has to re-sign Robinson. He has to
find an impact performer with the $2 million exception, and a
strong complementary player with the $1 million exception.
</P>
<P>
   He has to bulk up the interior with size and skill, allowing the
passive Longley to roam the perimeter and turning Tom Gugliotta
into what he always has been: the third option on offense.
</P>
<P>
   And he has zero margin for error.
</P>
<P>
   As much as Danny Ainge has shown a nice touch in the coach's
seat, he did little to help the future of the Suns. Only Garrity's
uncanny self-confidence allowed him to succeed in limited minutes.
And in this desperate search for athleticism, wouldn't it be nice
to know whether Toby Bailey has a future in the NBA?
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to rebuild while focusing on continuity and
meaningless playoff berths. But that is the path the Suns have
chosen, and the burden now facing the younger Colangelo.
</P>
<P>
   Brand could be the physical specimen sorely needed. Maggette is
the kind of athlete who comes around once every decade. Either
would be a celebrated pick, but neither will be available without
serious posturing. Colangelo must decide by Monday whether to hang
on to the No. 16 pick, and even if he does, there is no guarantee
of moving up.
</P>
<P>
   Which is the nature of the business, one dominated by general
mangers with vision. And soon, we'll know whether the younger
Colangelo is the real deal or just another fortunate son. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
