<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-ROCKIES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAAL HELPS OUT D-BACKS STAFF IN WIN OVER ROCKIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ With the Diamondbacks ship beginning to take on water
in the pitchers' quarters, left-hander Omar Daal grabbed a large
bucket and bailed them out Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   He gave the relief corps a badly needed day of rest to allow
soreness to dissipate and minds to recuperate. Daal threw a
complete game and scattered 11 hits, only one over the final four
innings, as Arizona ended a three-game losing streak with an 8-3
victory over the Colorado Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   A sellout crowd of 48,594 at Coors Field saw the Diamondbacks
raise their record to 24-20 and remain 1{ games behind San
Francisco in the National League West Division. Colorado fell to
17-22.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona pitchers had given up eight runs in each of the team's
previous three losses. The team lost right-handed starter Todd
Stottlemyre because of a partially torn rotator cuff earlier in the
week, and relievers Gregg Olson (pulled lower abdominal muscle) and
Darren Holmes (stiffness in lower back) were slowed considerably
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody had to tell me about that (relief situation),'' said
Daal, who threw 125 pitches, walked two and struck out two while
evening his record at 4-4.
</P>
<P>
   It was his first complete game of the season and fourth of his
career, and the team's first this season other than the three by
left-hander Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told myself that I was going to have to go as long as I can,
pitch a good game,'' Daal said. ``The last three innings, I was
feeling good. I wanted to try to keep the ball down and get the
groundouts.''
</P>
<P>
   He accomplished his objective.
</P>
<P>
   He got five groundouts in the final three innings, including
double play balls in the eighth and ninth innings.
</P>
<P>
   The second double play ended the game, when Daal had a chance to
field a grounder by pinch-hitter Angel Echevarria but decided to
let it go. Second baseman Jay Bell snared it, stepped on second
base to force Chris Sexton and threw to first to get Echevarria.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great field presence,'' said Bell, whose three-run
homer was the highlight of a five-run sixth inning that allowed the
Diamondbacks to take control. ``He knows what to do and what not to
do. It's fun to play behind a pitcher like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Catcher Damian Miller said he didn't think Daal had his best
stuff, ``but the way he pitches . . . he's a battler. He mixed up
his pitches and has a good idea of what he wants to do out there. I
love catching him.
</P>
<P>
   ``His fastball wasn't working that well early, but then he got
it up to 87, 88 later in the game and started spotting it.''
</P>
<P>
   Daal's combination plate gave Rockies right fielder Larry Walker
a case of indigestion. Walker was hitless in four at-bats and saw
his hitting streak come to an end at 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Omar had him frustrated, going after balls out of the
strike zone,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   Angry was a better description.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has been steamed at Daal since a game at Coors Field last
season when he hit a tapper back to Daal and Daal held the ball,
forcing him to run to first base and throwing him out at the last
minute. Walker tapped the ball back to Daal again Saturday in his
first at-bat to begin a double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He shouldn't beat us,'' said Walker, who beat the Diamondbacks
on Friday night with a homer in the bottom of the 11th inning.
``Not here. Not at our house because we're better than him. It's no
hidden secret that he's not a friend of mine. He throws at me all
the time (Daal hit Walker with a pitch in a game at Bank One
Ballpark last Sunday). I don't play those show-me-up games.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado took a 1-0 lead in the first inning on an RBI single by
Dante Bichette. Arizona countered with two in the third on a
leadoff homer by Tony Batista and a single by Luis Gonzalez that
scored Daal, who had singled.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies moved back in front, 3-2, in the fourth on a one-out
solo homer by Vinny Castilla and an RBI single by Sexton.
</P>
<P>
   Three singles off left-hander Bobby Jones, a walk to Batista and
an error by Jones got the Diamondbacks going in the sixth. Bell
greeted right-hander David Lee with a three-run homer, his 14th of
the season. It was Lee's major league debut after being called up
from Double-A on Thursday. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
